<html> 
<head><title>Discriminatory Intent Cannot Be Inferred By Proximity of Termination to FMLA Leave</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/person/time/timehead.gif" alt="Family and Medical Leave Handbook">
<P>
<h2>Discriminatory Intent Cannot Be Inferred By Proximity of Termination to FMLA Leave</h2>

An employer's intent to discriminate based on an employee's assertion of rights under the Family and
Medical Leave Act (FMLA) cannot be inferred from the length of time between an employee's return from
leave and his or her termination, the U.S. District Court for Southern Texas recently ruled.<P>

Bettye Garcia claimed that her employer, Fulbright &amp; Jaworski L.L.P., retaliated against her in
response to her using medical leave under the FMLA, when the company fired her a month after her return
from leave. The law firm responded that Garcia had been terminated for poor performance and the
proximity of its termination decision to the employee's medical leave was irrelevant.<P>

Garcia was employed by the firm as a section clerk, performing filing and word processing under the
supervision of Brenda Pittman, the secretarial coordinator. A 1992 performance evaluation indicated that
Garcia needed to improve in several areas. Pittman counseled Garcia and stated that the employee would
have three months to improve her performance and would be reviewed again at the end of that time. If
Garcia failed to improve her performance, Pittman implied that there might not be a section clerk position
for her with the firm. The three-month review showed some improvement in Garcia's performance, but her
evaluations later in the year indicated that her job performance was deteriorating.<P>

During this time, the employee requested and was granted a medical leave of absence for eye surgery and
then foot surgery. She returned to work two months later, her physicians providing a return to work
authorization with no restrictions. Approximately one month after returning from leave, Pittman met with
and informed Garcia that the company had decided to terminate her due to "continuing failure to meet
minimum job requirements."<P>

Citing the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals' holding in <I>Oswalt v. Sara Lee Corp.</I>, 74 F.3d 91 (1996), the
Texas district court stated that establishing a prima facie case under the FMLA was similar to establishing
such a case under Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964. The court held that Garcia must demonstrate she
met certain criteria outlined in <I>Oswalt</I> to establish a prima facie case under the federal leave law, including
that:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>(1) she was protected under the FMLA;<P>

(2) she suffered an adverse employment decision; and<P>

(3) she was treated less favorably than an employee who had not requested leave under the FMLA or that
the adverse decision was made because of her request for leave.<P></BLOCKQUOTE>

The employer argued that Garcia failed to establish a prima facie case because she had not produced
evidence that her termination resulted from the medical leave. The firm stated that "her poor performance
reviews and probation predated her FMLA leave period and reflect that she did not do her job adequately
before or after her return from leave."<P>

The firm also maintained that because Garcia's job performance was well-documented and consistently
poor, she could not demonstrate that the company's reasoning for her discharge was pretextual. The firm
also argued that the employee could not show that she was treated differently from similarly situated
employees in light of its termination for poor performance of three other section clerks who had not taken
leave under the FMLA.<P>

Garcia argued that her performance reports cited her absences for medical reasons as one reason for her
work problems. She also stated that she twice tried to talk to Pittman about her medical condition and
resulting absences, but was refused by the supervisor.<P>

The court granted the employer's motion for summary judgment, stating that Garcia's physicians'
certification of her ability to return to work without restrictions supported the fact that her medical
condition did not hinder her job performance. Also, the court noted that she had failed to demonstrate the
requisite intent to discriminate on the part of her employer. "Her conclusory allegation that Pittman
intentionally twice refused her request for time to discuss her medical condition . . . is insufficient to show
intent to discriminate," the court said, adding that Garcia's statement that her evaluations had mentioned
her absences as resulting in performance problems was also insufficient to establish discriminatory intent.
"Plaintiff has failed to demonstrate that poor work performance was not the cause of her termination," the
court said.<P>

The court found that Garcia had offered only "conclusory allegations" as proof that she was terminated in
retaliation for asserting her rights under the FMLA, and had presented no evidence or authority to back her
claims. "Discriminatory intent cannot be inferred merely from the time an employee is terminated after
returning from the FMLA leave," the court ruled, citing <I>Day v. Excel Corp.</I>, No. 94-1439-JTM (D. Kan.
1996). (<I>Garcia v. Fulbright &amp; Jaworski L.L.P.</I>, S.D. Texas, Civil Action No. H-95-0053, Aug. 15,
1996) <P>

<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/person/time/time.html"><img src="/tpg/person/time/smalltime.gif" alt="Return to Family
and Medical Leave Handbook Home Page"></a> <a href="/tpg/prices/personnelprices.html"><img
src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ] "></a>
</pre>
</center>
