<head>
<title>New Pension Law: A Provision-by-Provision Analysis</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/plan/planhead.gif" alt="The 401(k) Handbook"></center>
<P>
<h2>New Pension Law: A Provision-by-Provision Analysis</h2>

<P>
President Clinton signed landmark pension reform legislation on Aug. 20, and sweeping changes to a wide range of pension administration rules and regulations will go into effect over the next several years.
</P>

<P>
The new law, the Small Business Job Protection Act of 1996 (P.L. 104-188), offers alternative means for satisfying the nondiscrimination tests for 401(k) plans, changes the definition of a highly compensated employee (HCE) and streamlines certain plan distribution rules. 
</P>

<P>
It also simplifies the definition of compensation limits and repeals the family aggregation rule and the combined plan limit.
</P>

<P>
This special report highlights the pension-related provisions in the new law. For each provision that will affect the administration of defined contribution or defined benefit pension plans, or both, the report summarizes the current law, the change, and the new provision's effective date. 
</P>

<P>
In addition, the report also contains analyses of some of the more significant changes. This commentary was provided by Joseph Hessenthaler, a principal at Towers Perrin and contributing editor of the <I>401(k) Handbook</I>. It is aimed at guiding you through the legal language and into its "real world" implications.
</P>

<P>
The following provision-by-provision analysis of the new pension law is organized by topic: simplified distribution rules; increased access to retirement plans; nondiscrimination testing changes; and miscellaneous provisions. The first sidebar shows when each provision takes effect; the second sidebar lists related provisions in the law that have less relevance to 401(k) plans.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT><I>Simplified Distribution Rules</I></H3>
</P>

<P>
<B>Repeal of five-year averaging for lump-sum distributions</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> Plan participants may use five-year forward income averaging for calculating the tax on lump-sum distributions. This allows the taxpayer to pay a separate tax on the lump-sum distribution that approximates the tax due if the distribution were made in equal installments over a five-year period. The taxpayer may deduct the lump-sum distribution from gross income. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> This five-year averaging option will be eliminated, and the separate tax on the lump-sum distribution and the income deduction will be repealed.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 2000. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> Lump-sum distribution treatment will still apply to 401(k) plans for the net unrealized appreciation of the distribution of employer securities. Similarly, the current lump-sum distribution treatment will be available for the separate tax treatment of excess distributions. 
</P>

<P>
Plan administrators should update employee communications to reflect this change when it takes effect, including the required notice on rollover rights.
</P>

<P>
<B>Exclusion for death benefits</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> When a plan participant dies, the plan beneficiary may exclude $5,000 in employer-provided benefits from gross income. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> The exclusion will be repealed.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> For plan participants who die after Aug. 20, 1996.
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> With no exclusion, the determination of taxable income on a distribution is now simpler. 
</P>

<P>
Given the effective date, employers must adjust their reporting procedures promptly. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Simplified rules for taxing annuity distributions</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> For annuity benefits under a qualified plan, the return on investment in the annuity contract is not considered income for tax purposes. The amount of nontaxable return on investment ("return of basis") may be determined by dividing an employee's total investment by the total expected payments over the annuity's term. The IRS, however, also offers a simplified method for determining the taxable portions of annuity benefits.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> The new law calculates taxable annuity benefits using a method similar to the IRS' simplified method. To use this method, the total investment would be divided by the number of anticipated payments, as illustrated below.
</P>


<TABLE BORDER="1" CELLPADDING="5" CELLSPACING="1">

<TR ALIGN=CENTER>
<TH ALIGN=CENTER>Age distribution begins</TH><TH ALIGN=CENTER>Number of payments</TH>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>No older than 55</TD>	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>360</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>56-60</TD>	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>310</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>61-65</TD>	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>260</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>66-70</TD>	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>210</TD>
</TR>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER>
	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>Over 70</TD>	<TD ALIGN=CENTER>160</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>


<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Applies to annuities with starting dates after Nov. 18, 1996.
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> This change simplifies the calculation, but the new method is less generous because it takes longer to recover the nontaxable amount. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Required distributions at age 70 1/2</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> For participants in qualified plans, distributions must begin by April 1 of the calendar year following the calendar year in which the participant turns 70 1/2.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> For participants who are still working, the distribution must begin by April 1 of the calendar year following the calendar year in which the participant retires.
</P>

<P>
Moreover, the accrued benefit of participants who retire after 70 1/2 will be "actuarially increased" to take into account the time period after the attainment of age 70 1/2 in which benefits increased in value. Thus, the accrued benefit must reflect the value of benefits the participant would have received if he or she had retired at 70 1/2 and had begun receiving benefits at that time. The actuarial adjustment is not required for defined contribution plans.
</P>

<P>
The change does not apply to IRAs, or to plan participants who are 5-percent owners.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 1997.
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> For participants currently receiving required minimum distributions, the legislative intent appears to be that a plan may, but is not required to, allow such participants the right to stop the distributions. The plan, however, cannot stop the distributions without the participant's consent.
</P>

<P>
Besides changing employee communications, employers must create a procedure for adjusting the pension benefits of participants who work and who will begin receiving benefits after age 70 1/2.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT><I>Increased Access to Retirement Plans</I></H3>
</P>

<P>
<B>Establishment of SIMPLE retirement plans for small businesses</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> SIMPLE (Savings Incentive Match Plan for Employers) plans do not exist under current law. A somewhat similar plan -- a salary reduction simplified employee pension (SARSEP) -- can now be maintained by employers with 25 or fewer employees. SARSEPs are not qualified plans; they function like IRAs, in which employees and employers make contributions similar to a 401(k) arrangement. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> Small businesses (100 or fewer employees who earn at least $5,000 per year) that do not offer other retirement plans can offer SIMPLE plans. A SIMPLE plan could function as either an IRA for each employee or as a 401(k) plan. It will not be subject to nondiscrimination or top-heavy rules, and will have simplified reporting requirements. Moreover, ERISA will be amended so that employers are not subject to fiduciary liability regarding employees' control over their SIMPLE accounts. 
</P>

<P>
SIMPLE plan sponsors must fulfill either a matching or nonelective contribution formula. Under the matching arrangement, in any five-year period an employer must make a 100-percent matching contribution for the first 3 percent of an employee's salary for at least three years. For the remaining two years, an employer must make a 100-percent matching contribution for the first 1 percent of an employee's salary.
</P>

<P>
Under the nonelective option, the employer must make a guaranteed contribution equivalent to 2 percent of an employee's salary for every employee earning more than $5,000 per year. 
</P>

<P>
Contributions to the SIMPLE plan cannot exceed $6,000 per year (indexed for inflation) and must be fully vested. SIMPLE accounts may be rolled over into an IRA two years after an employee enters the plan. 
</P>

<P>
Withdrawals of contributions during the first two years of participation will be subject to a 25-percent excise tax. Withdrawals after two years will be subject to a 10-percent excise tax. Employer matching or nonelective contributions are not treated as wages for employment purposes. 
</P>

<P>
Companies with SIMPLE plans that grow beyond 100 employees have two years to dismantle their plans. 
</P>

<P>
New SARSEPs cannot be set up, but SARSEPs currently operating will be allowed to continue.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> The SIMPLE provisions go into effect Jan. 1, 1997. 
</P>

<P>
New SARSEPs cannot be created after Jan. 1, 1997. SARSEPs established before that date will be allowed to continue, and new employees hired after that date will still be allowed to make contributions.
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> With the enactment of SIMPLE, Congress intends to encourage the adoption of 401(k)-type plans by small businesses. It remains to be seen whether the required level of minimum employer contribution under SIMPLE will dampen the enthusiasm for establishing these new plans. However, several vendor groups appear to be geared up to market this concept, and this may help the spread of these programs.
</P>

<P>
<B>Tax-exempt organizations eligible for 401(k) plans</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> Tax-exempt organizations cannot offer 401(k) plans, unless the plan was established before July 2, 1986.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> The law is repealed for tax-exempt organizations, including Indian tribal groups; state and local governments are excluded.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> The provision is effective for plan years beginning after Jan. 1, 1997.
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> With this change, all nonprofit organizations may now maintain elective tax-deferred plans. However, nonprofits eligible to maintain a 403(b) plan will need to consider the advantages and disadvantages of implementing a 401(k) plan, given its ADP testing requirements.
</P>

<P>
<B>IRAs for spouses</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> In general, the annual deductible contribution limit for IRAs is the lesser of $2,000 or 100 percent of compensation. For married individuals whose spouses do not work for compensation, the limit is $2,250.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> Deductible IRA contributions of up to $2,000 can be made for each spouse, even if the spouse does not work, as long as the combined compensation of both spouses is at least equal to the contributed amount. But the current rules that phase out deductible IRA contributions for adjusted gross income above certain levels still apply.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 1997.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT><I>Nondiscrimination Testing Changes</I></H3>
</P>

<P>
<B>Simplified definition of highly compensated employee</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> An employee is considered a highly compensated employee (HCE) if during the preceding year one of the following conditions apply: he or she was a 5-percent owner of the company; earned more than $100,000 in 1996 from the employer; earned more than $66,000 and was in the top 20 percent of the company's earners; or was an officer of the employer who earned more than $60,000. If no officer earned more than $60,000, the highest-paid officer is considered an HCE.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> An employee will be considered an HCE if during the preceding year he or she was a 5-percent owner of the company or earned more than $80,000.
</P>

<P>
A plan could choose a definition that would not consider employees earning over $80,000 as HCEs if they were not in the top 20 percent of the company's earners, unless the employee was a 5-percent owner.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 1997. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> For the 1997 plan year, employers must use the $80,000 limit when reviewing employee compensation for 1996. 
</P>

<P>
In general, this change should decrease the number of HCEs, and will enable their identification in the beginning of the year. This change should also help many plans pass the nondiscrimination tests, and should eliminate cuts in distributions for many middle managers.
</P>

<P>
<B>Repeal of the family aggregation rule</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> If an employee is a 5-percent owner or is one of the company's top 10 earners, then the compensation and benefits paid to the employee is aggregated with family members who are also employees when conducting the nondiscrimination tests and calculating compensation limits under 401(a)(17).
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> The rule will be repealed.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 1997.
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> For small plans, this change could make a difference in passing the nondiscrimination tests. This would also help in Section 415 testing, because employees will not have to be aggregated when determining compensation limits, thus decreasing the chances of exceeding the 25-percent-of-pay limitation.
</P>

<P>
<B>Modification of additional participation requirements</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> Qualified plans must cover at least 50 employees or 40 percent of the company's workers, whichever is less. The rule may be applied separately to an employer's different lines of business, but each line of business must have at least 50 employees. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> The requirement will apply only to defined benefit plans. A plan will not satisfy the requirement unless it benefits the lesser of: (1) 50 employees; or (2) the greater of 40 percent of all employees or two employees (one employee if there is only one).
</P>

<P>
In addition, lines of business would not need 50 employees to qualify as separate lines of business for these requirements.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 1997.
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> This change should encourage more employers to start defined contribution plans, especially when employers have small divisions or separate ventures that need different plans.
</P>

<P>
<B>Prior year testing</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> For qualified cash or deferred arrangements, the nondiscrimination test is satisfied if the actual deferral percentage (ADP) or actual contribution percentage (ACP) for highly compensated employees, <I>for the same plan year</I>, is equal to or less than: (1) 125 percent of the ADP of all eligible nonhighly compensated employees; or (2) the lesser of either (a) 200 percent of the ADP of all eligible nonhighly compensated employees or (b) 200 percent of the ADP plus 2 percentage points.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> In nondiscrimination testing, the ADP or ACP for nonhighly compensated employees for the current year will be compared with their prior year's ADP or ACP, unless an employer elects to use the current year ADP or ACP. If the employer uses the current year, that election could only be changed by following specific IRS procedures.
</P>

<P>
New plans could use a straight 3-percent assumption or the plan could elect to use current year data for nonhighly compensated employees.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 1997.
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> The employer will still have to do a full test for HCEs and non-HCEs. However, the non-HCEs' ADP and ACP for the current year will be computed or deferred based on their prior year's contributions and pay. 
</P>

<P>
In addition, the change raises several questions, such as how the ADP and ACP will be calculated for current year non-HCEs who made no contributions in the prior year, particularly in cases where they were ineligible to do so. The applicable statutory language may not be consistent with congressional intent. Therefore, clarification from the IRS, or a technical correction from Congress, may be forthcoming. 
</P>

<P>
<B>ADP safe harbor for cash or deferred arrangements</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> For qualified cash or deferred arrangements, the nondiscrimination test is satisfied if the ADP for highly compensated employees, <I>for the same plan year</I>, is equal to or less than: (1) 125 percent of the ADP of all eligible nonhighly compensated employees; or (2) the lesser of either (a) 200 percent of the ADP of all eligible nonhighly compensated employees or (b) 200 percent of the ADP plus 2 percentage points.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> The nondiscrimination tests for cash or deferred arrangements will be satisfied if the plan fulfills one of two contribution requirements and a notice requirement.
</P>

<P>
For the contribution requirement, the employer must, on behalf of all eligible nonhighly compensated employees: (1) make a nonelective contribution to a defined contribution plan of at least 3 percent of salary for every eligible nonhighly compensated employee; or (2) make a matching contribution equal to (a) 100 percent of the employee's elective contributions for the first 3 percent of salary and (b) 50 percent of elective contributions from 3 percent to 5 percent of salary. 
</P>

<P>
In addition, the rate of match for highly compensated employees cannot be greater than the rate of match for nonhighly compensated employees. This rule also applies to the following alternative.
</P>

<P>
As an alternative to the second option above, the employer will satisfy the matching requirement if the employer's matching contribution does not increase as an employee's rate of elective contribution increases, and the aggregate amount of matching contributions at any rate of elective contributions is as great as it would have been if the percentages in the first option above were satisfied.
</P>

<P>
The notice requirement will be fulfilled if each eligible employee is given advance written notice of his or her rights and obligations under the arrangement.
</P>

<P>
Matches must be offered as soon as the employee is eligible to contribute. The contributions must be 100-percent vested, and cannot be withdrawn until the employee reaches age 59 1/2.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 1999.
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> Under this change, a plan that offers a 100-percent match for the first 4 percent of salary would fulfill the safe harbor requirements. 
</P>

<P>
A plan that offers a 50-percent match on the first 2 percent of salary and a 200-percent match on the next 1 percent of salary would not fulfill the safe harbor requirements, since it offers less than the safe harbor minimum on the 1-percent and 2-percent elective contributions and then increases as the rate of elective contributions increases. A plan with a service-weighted matching contribution would fulfill the safe harbor requirement that the rate for any HCE cannot exceed the rate for any non-HCE whenever at least one HCE receives the highest matching contribution and at least one non-HCE receives the lowest matching contribution. 
</P>

<P>
<B>ACP safe harbor for defined contribution plans</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> Employer matching contributions and after-tax employee contributions under qualified defined contribution plans are subject to special actual contribution percentage (ACP) nondiscrimination tests similar to the ADP tests. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> A plan would satisfy the ACP test if it meets the contribution and notice requirements under the ADP safe harbor, and if it follows a limitation on matching contributions.
</P>

<P>
To fulfill the matching contribution limitation, the plan must limit employer matching contributions to the first 6 percent of compensation deferred by the employee. The rate of the employer's matching contribution cannot increase as the employee's rate of deferral increases. Also, the rate of match for highly compensated employees cannot be greater than that for nonhighly compensated employees.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 1999.
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> After-tax contributions still must be tested. If a plan sponsor is making safe harbor matching contributions, it seems that the contributions could not be used in after-tax testing unless the contributions exceed the safe harbor. Furthermore, the new law does not clarify if the safe harbor is available for plans with matching contributions only or on after-tax contributions or pretax contributions to a 403(b) plan. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Alternative nondiscrimination rules for early participation</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> A plan can prohibit employees from participating if they are not 21 years old or have less than one year of service. 
</P>

<P>
For the ADP and ACP tests, the employer may separately test eligible employees who otherwise could have been excluded (those under 21 years old or with less than one year's service). If as a group they fulfill the Section 410(b) coverage rules, the employer may exclude them when conducting the ADP or ACP tests for eligible employees.
</P>

<P>
The employer has the option to ease the eligibility requirements -- for example, lowering the age to 18 and eliminating the one-year service requirement.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> Instead of separate testing, the plan would be able to conduct one ADP test in which the ADP for all highly compensated employees eligible to make contributions (including those who only satisfy the "lessened" requirements) is compared with the ADP for eligible nonhighly compensated employees who are over 21 and have completed one year of service. Separate testing for Section 410(b) coverage is still required.
</P>

<P>
A similar rule applies to the ACP test.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 1999.
</P>

<P>
<B>Distribution of excess contributions</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> Qualified cash or deferred arrangement plans that fail nondiscrimination testing may distribute excess contributions to employees. In determining the amount of excess contributions and the employees to whom they are allocated, the contributions of highly compensated employees are reduced in the order of their actual deferral percentage, beginning with those highly compensated employees with the highest actual deferral percentages. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> Distribution of excess contributions will be required to be made on the amount of the contribution by each highly compensated employee, rather than on the actual deferral percentage. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 1997.
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> The highest paid employees will likely receive excess distributions. Therefore, some employers may feel pressure to maintain a nonqualified 401(k) makeup arrangement.
</P>

<P>
<B>Definition of compensation for contribution limits</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> The definition of compensation does not include employee contributions to certain plans.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> Employee contributions to Section 401(k), Section 403(b), Section 457 and Section 125 plans will be included as compensation when determining Section 415 contribution and benefit limits.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 1998.
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> This provision should relieve some of the pressure of the Section 415 limitations on lower-paid employees who contribute the maximum amounts to their dependent care and medical flexible spending accounts and to their 401(k) plans. 
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT><I>Miscellaneous Provisions</I></H3>
</P>

<P>
<B>Change in uniform retirement age</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> The uniform retirement age, when used for nondiscrimination testing, is 65.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> The Social Security retirement age will be treated as a uniform retirement age for purposes of the general nondiscrimination rules. The Social Security retirement age is currently 65, but is scheduled to increase gradually.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 1997.
</P>

<P>
<B>Contributions for employees with disabilities</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> Employers may elect to continue contributing to the defined contribution plan of employees who are permanently and totally disabled, but not if they were owners, officers or highly compensated employees before becoming disabled. For the limits on annual additions, the compensation of a disabled employee is equal to his or her annual compensation before the disability.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> If the plan provides for the continuation of employer contributions for disabled employees, the employer would not need a special election to do so. Employers may also provide for disabled highly compensated employees.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 1997.
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> This change eliminates one of the main reasons employers do not currently provide contributions to disabled employees under 401(k) or other defined contribution plans -- the special election.
</P>

<P>
<B>Waiver of minimum waiting period for annuity distributions</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> With qualified joint and survivor annuities, participants must receive a written explanation of benefits no less than 30 days and no more than 90 days before the annuity starting date. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> The 30-day minimum period will not apply if waived by the participant and the participant's spouse (if necessary). The payments could be made immediately once the participant completes the waiver, and payments could be retroactive.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 1997.
</P>

<P>
<B>Correction of interest and mortality rate provisions</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> Under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT), when adjusting a nonannuity benefit or the dollar limitations on benefits that begin before age 62, the interest rate used cannot be less than either the rate specified in the plan or a 5-percent rate, whichever is greater.
</P>

<P>
If the benefit is subject to Section 417(e)(3) requirements, the interest rate on 30-year Treasury securities is substituted for the 5-percent rate. In addition, the mortality table from the Secretary of the Treasury must be used. 
</P>

<P>
Similar rules apply to the interest rate and mortality assumptions used in calculating the value of lump-sum distributions for involuntary dispositions of certain accrued benefits. For plans adopted before Dec. 8, 1995, those rules do not apply before the earlier of the date a plan amendment that applies the assumption is adopted or goes into effect (whichever is later), or the first day of the first plan year beginning after Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> For benefits subject to Section 417(e)(3) requirements, a plan can no longer substitute the 30-year Treasury securities interest rate for the 5-percent option when calculating reductions on dollar limits under Section 415. 
</P>

<P>
In addition, for plans in effect before GATT (Dec. 8, 1994), the effective date of the interest rate and the mortality assumptions used to calculate benefit and contribution limits will conform with the provisions on calculating lump-sum distributions. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Retroactive to Dec. 8, 1994.
</P>

<P>
<B>Repeal of combined plan limit</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> Annual contributions to defined contribution plans are generally limited to the lesser of $30,000 or 25 percent of compensation. For defined benefit plans, the annual benefit is generally limited to the lesser of $120,000 or 100 percent of the participant's average compensation for the highest three years. There is a combined limit if the employee participates in both types of plans.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> The combined limit will be repealed.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 2000. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> Many employers will be able to contribute more to higher-paid employees in defined benefit plans. In addition, employers will not need to maintain or retrieve cumbersome historical data on their defined contribution plans. Finally, this change also enhances opportunities to provide more benefit for highly compensated employees in a defined benefit plan.
</P>

<P>
<B>Suspension of excess distribution tax</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> Annual distributions from qualified plans that exceed $150,000 (or $750,000 for a lump-sum distribution) are subject to a 15-percent excise tax. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> For distributions received in 1997, 1998 and 1999, until the repeal of the combined plan limit goes into effect, the excise tax will be suspended.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> For distributions received in 1997 through 1999.
</P>

<P>
<B>Increase in prohibited transaction tax</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> An excise tax is now imposed on prohibited transactions, equal to 5 percent of the amount of the transaction. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> The tax will increase to 10 percent.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Transactions occuring after Aug. 20, 1996.
</P>

<P>
<B>Changes in treatment of leased employees</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> A leased employee is treated as an employee for benefits purposes if the individual has performed services on a substantially full-time basis for at least a year, and the services are typical of those "historically performed" in the employer's business.
</P>

<P>
If more than 20 percent of an employer's nonhighly compensated workforce is leased, all leased individuals are to be treated as employees for employee benefits eligibility.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> In determining a leased employee's eligibility for benefits, the "historically performed" services criteria will be replaced by a new "primary control" test. Under this test, a leased employee will be treated as an employee if he or she is under the primary direction or control of the organization for which the employee performs the services. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 1997.
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> This change moves the status determination closer to the reality of the relationship between leased employees and the organizations for which they perform services.  
</P>

<P>
<B>Penalties for pension reporting requirements</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> There is a two-tiered penalty system for sponsors who fail to file information reports to the IRS on time: a penalty for each failure and a separate flat amount for each failure to file with the IRS or to notify payees.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> A single system will replace the two-tiered system. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 1997.
</P>

<P>
<B>New language for spousal consent forms</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> Benefits from a plan subject to survivor benefit rules may be paid in a form other than a qualified joint and survivor annuity (QJSA) or a qualified preretirement survivor annuity (QPSA) if the participant signs a waiver and satisfies the relevant requirements.
</P>

<P>
In addition, benefits may be paid to a former spouse according to a qualified domestic relations order (QDRO).
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> By Jan. 1, 1997, the Secretary of the Treasury must develop new language for the spousal consent form and QDRO that discloses whether the QJSA or QPSA waiver is irrevocable and whether it could be revoked by a QDRO.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Jan. 1, 1997.
</P>

<P>
<B>Waiver of excise tax on liquidity shortfalls</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> Certain underfunded defined benefit plans that will have liquidity shortfalls must make quarterly payments to maintain their liquid assets. If these payments are not made, the plan sponsor is subject to an excise tax equal to 10 percent of the outstanding liquidity shortfall.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> The Secretary of the Treasury may waive the excise tax for failing to make a liquidity shortfall payment if the plan sponsor establishes that the shortfall was due to reasonable cause and reasonable steps have been taken to remedy it.
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Aug. 20, 1996.
</P>

<P>
<B>Adoption of plan amendments</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> In general, plan amendments for complying with rule changes must be made by the income tax return deadline for the taxable year in which the change occurs.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> Plan amendments or annuity changes made to reflect these new pension simplification provisions will not be required before the first plan year on or after Jan. 1, 1998. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Aug. 20, 1996.
</P>

<P>
<B>Comments:</B> The provision's language does not clarify whether the amendments will have to be made by the end of the 1998 plan year or at a later date.
</P>

<P>
<B>Veteran's bill technical corrections</B>
</P>

<P>
<B>Current law:</B> The Uniformed Services Employment and Reemployment Rights Act of 1994 (USERRA) did not clarify how makeup plan contributions made by veterans returning from military duty would affect plan qualification or plan loan requirements.
</P>

<P>
<B>Change:</B> Makeup contributions made by veterans who were away on military duty will not be subject to Section 404 and 415 limitations for the year that the contributions are made. 
</P>

<P>
<B>Effective:</B> Retroactive to Dec. 12, 1994. 
</P>

<HR>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>What Happens When?</H4>

<FONT SIZE="2"><P>
Here are the major pension-related provisions in the new law, listed by their effective dates:
</P>

<B>Effective Aug. 20, 1996:</B>

<UL>
	<LI>Exclusion for death benefits (for participants dying after 8/20/96)
	<LI>Correction of interest and mortality rate provisions
	<LI>Increase in prohibited transaction tax 
	<LI>Waiver of excise tax on liquidity shortfalls
	<LI>Veteran's bill technical corrections (retroactive to 12/12/94)
</UL>

<B>Effective Jan. 1, 1997:</B>

<UL>
	<LI>Simplified rules for taxing annuity distributions (for annuities with starting dates after 11/18/96)
	<LI>Required distributions at age 70 1/2
	<LI>Establishment of SIMPLE plans for small businesses
	<LI>Tax-exempt organizations eligible for 401(k) plans
	<LI>Spousal IRAs
	<LI>Simplified definition of HCE
	<LI>Repeal of family aggregation rule
	<LI>Modification of additional participation requirements
	<LI>Prior year testing
	<LI>Distribution of excess contributions
	<LI>Change in uniform retirement age
	<LI>Contributions for disabled employees
	<LI>Waiver of minimum waiting period for annuity distributions
	<LI>Suspension of excess distribution tax (effective for distributions received in 1997 through 1999) 
	<LI>Changes in treatment of leased employees
	<LI>Penalties for pension reporting requirements
	<LI>New language for spousal consent forms
</UL>

<B>Effective Jan. 1, 1998:</B>

<UL>
	<LI>Definition of compensation for contribution limits
</UL>

<B>Effective Jan. 1, 1999:</B>

<UL>
	<LI>ADP safe harbor
	<LI>ACP safe harbor
	<LI>Alternative testing for early participation
	<LI>Repeal of combined plan limit
	<LI>Adoption of plan amendments (amendments not required before 1/1/98)
</UL>

<B>Effective Jan. 1, 2000:</B>

<UL>
	<LI>Repeal of five-year averaging for lump-sum distributions
</UL></FONT>

<HR>

<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Other Pension-Related Provisions In the New Law</H4> 

<FONT SIZE="2">Elimination of aggregation rules for self-employed plans<BR>
Elimination of special vesting rule for multiemployer plans<BR>
Expanded distributions under rural cooperative plans<BR>
Section 415 limit changes for governmental plans<BR>
Administrative changes to Section 457 plans<BR>
Trust requirements for Section 457 plans maintained by state and local governments<BR>
Salary reduction agreements in Section 403(b) plans<BR>
Section 403(b) plans for Indian tribal governments<BR>
Application of elective deferral limits to 403(b) plans<BR>
Retirement benefits for ministers<BR>
Length of service awards for Section 457 plans<BR>
Church pension plan simplification<BR>
Increase in guaranteed benefits for multiemployer plans<BR>
Lump-sum credits for federal spouses<BR>
Liability under ERISA for insurance companies<BR>
</FONT>
