<head>
<title> Court Declines to Assess Notice Penalties and Attorney's Fees</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/heal/healhead.gif" alt="Mandated Health Benefits&#151;The COBRA Guide"></center>

<h2>Court Declines to Assess Notice Penalties and Attorney's Fees, Noting Ex-employee Tried to Exploit "Inadvertent Error"</h2>

An employer and insurer were not liable for notice penalties and attorney's fees because they took
"immediate remedial steps" once they realized an election notice was not sent on a timely basis, and the
aggrieved qualified beneficiary did not incur any damages, a federal district court in Kansas ruled. In <I>Kost
v. United Parcel Service, Inc.,</I> 1996 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 11832 (D. Kan. 1996), the court also took the
qualified beneficiary to task, noting that she tried to exploit the defendants' "inadvertent error" to collect a
"windfall award."  <P>

<H3>Facts of the Case</H3><P>

Shanda Kost was an employee of United Parcel Service, Inc. (UPS). Kost was covered under the company's
group health plan, of which UPS was the plan administrator and Aetna Life Insurance Co., was the claims
administrator. When someone incurred a qualifying event, it was UPS' practice to notify Aetna of any
employment terminations and rely upon Aetna to send written COBRA election notices. (See Practice
Pointer.)<P>

In September 1993, Kost terminated her employment. However, she did not receive a COBRA notice on a
timely basis. Possibly due to a computer error by either UPS or Aetna, her employee separation form was
not entered into the UPS computer system until December 1993--three months after she resigned. The
court could not determine precisely what happened because computer tapes were only kept for 13 weeks;
therefore, when the case went to trial in July 1996, the December 1993 tapes were no longer available for
review.<P>

Fifteen months after Kost terminated employment, her attorney notified UPS and Aetna in a Dec. 10, 1994,
letter that she had not received a COBRA notice. UPS then agreed to provide retroactive coverage and
waive the COBRA premium for the 17-month period between October 1993 and February 1995. Kost
rejected that offer. <P>

Kost sued UPS and Aetna for COBRA notice violations, and sought attorney's fees and penalties of up to
$100 a day from her termination of employment. (A plan administrator that fails to notify qualified
beneficiaries of their COBRA election rights within 14 days of being notified of the qualifying event may be
liable for statutory penalties of up to $100 per day from the date of failure under ERISA. See &#182;1317
and 1520.) <P>

Kost contended that: (1) in addition to the computer tape error, UPS erred in failing to input her separation
information into the computer promptly after the separation; (2) a UPS supervisor forged her signature on
the company's employee separation form; and (3) had she received a COBRA notice on a timely basis and
elected COBRA coverage, she would have had to pay a monthly premium of about $240. However, Kost did
not claim that she or any dependents incurred any uninsured medical expenses during the 18-month period
in which she could have received COBRA coverage. <P>

<H3>Court Said Kost Not Injured in Any Way</H3><P>

In reaching its decision in favor of UPS and Aetna, the court indicated that whether to assess a penalty for
failing to provide a COBRA notice rested solely within its discretion. The court noted that in making such a
determination, it could consider factors such as the magnitude of prejudice or injuries incurred by the
plaintiff and whether the plan administrator's action showed bad faith.<P>

To that end, the court pointed out that Kost did not claim to have been prejudiced or injured by not being
informed of her COBRA rights. "In fact, there appear to be no damages whatsoever," the court stated.<P>

The court also determined that there was no bad faith attributable either to UPS or Aetna. The court noted
that UPS's failure to input Kost's separation information into the computer in a timely fashion did not "rise
to the level of bad faith; it merely demonstrates bureaucratic bungling of the papers."<P>

Furthermore, the court noted that Kost's allegation that her signature was forged on the separation
form--which is translated into computer tape and sent to Aetna for COBRA notification purposes--"has no
bearing" on why she never received a COBRA notice. In fact, the court indicated that the "forgery would
actually have advanced COBRA notification, not hindered it." Although the forgery may have been
committed for "some other nefarious purpose," the court determined that it did not show that UPS acted in
bad faith. <P>

UPS's system for COBRA notifications did fail, according to the court. Basically, Kost's COBRA notice
appeared to have fallen through the cracks in the UPS system. However, the court emphasized that UPS
took immediate remedial steps to correct its mistakes by offering to provide retroactive coverage and to
pay 17 months of COBRA premiums. Moreover, Kost did not suffer any injuries and was not prejudiced by
the lack of timely notice. <P>

The court agreed with UPS and Aetna that Kost's claim was "an unabashed effort to exploit [their]
inadvertent error into a windfall award of discretionary penalties and costs," and that it would not "be a
party to such an unscrupulous cause." <P>

<HR>

<CENTER><H4>Practice Pointer</H4><P>
</CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="2">In the <I>Kost</I> case, Aetna, which was the claims administrator, provided the written COBRA election notices. However, note that under COBRA, an employer has 30 days to notify the plan administrator of a qualifying event, who in turn then has 14 days to provide the qualified beneficiary with a COBRA election notice. Therefore, UPS--as the technical plan administrator--had the ultimate responsibility to ensure that COBRA notices were sent on a timely basis. (See &#182;1311 and &#182;1313 of the <I>Handbook</I>.) <P>
</FONT><HR>

<CENTER><H4>Practice Pointer</H4></CENTER><P>

<FONT SIZE="2">The <I>Kost</I> case demonstrates out how important it is for employers to make sure that they have established comprehensive COBRA notification systems. Given the possibilities of human error, mistakes will happen in COBRA administration. But if an employer has an adequate COBRA notification system in place and a notice falls through the cracks, this case points out that courts will give an administrator the benefit of the doubt.<P>

However, administrators should not forget that other courts have not been so kind. In fact, in other COBRA cases courts assessed COBRA notice penalties against plan administrators even though the qualified beneficiary did not want or need COBRA coverage. (See &#182;1520.) In these cases, the administrative system was either deficient or non-existent, and the court determined that it would be appropriate to penalize the administrator to emphasize the importance of compliance with COBRA's requirements. <P> 
</FONT>

<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/pen_ben/heal/heal.html"><img src="/tpg/pen_ben/heal/smallheal.gif"  alt="Return to Mandated Health Benefits&#151;The COBRA Guide Home Page"></a> <a href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ] "></a>
</pre>
</center>
