<html> 
<head>
<title>Federal District Courts Base FLSA Rulings Against State Employees
on Supreme Court Seminole Decision</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/person/fair/fairhead.gif"></center>
<P>
<h2>Federal District Courts Base FLSA Rulings Against State Employees on Supreme
Court Seminole Decision </h2>

Two district courts recently dismissed claims filed by state employees against
their employers under the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA), ruling that the
Supreme Court's decision in <I>Seminole Tribe of Florida v. Florida</I> (116 S. Ct. 1114
(1996)) protected states from private actions by state employees brought in
federal court. (See <I>Current Developments,</I> September 1996, page 7.)<P>

In <I>Seminole,</I> a five-justice majority of the Supreme Court struck down a provision
of the Indian Gaming Regulatory Act (IGRA) (25 U.S.C. &#167;2710(d)(7)), which
was passed by Congress under the Indian Commerce Clause of the Constitution. The
provision required states to negotiate in good faith with Native American tribes
to enter into tribal-state compacts governing conduct of gaming activities on
Indian reservations. The provision also gave federal courts jurisdiction over
causes of action brought by Native American tribes to enforce the states'
obligation to negotiate such compacts.<P>

Pursuant to the provision, the Seminole tribe sued the state of Florida and its
governor for injunctive relief to force the governor and the state to enter into
negotiations for a tribal-state compact on gaming. However, the Supreme Court
ruled that Florida and its governor were immune from such a suit pursuant to the
11th Amendment.<P>

<H3>Highway Patrol Employees</H3>

In <I>Whitesell v. Moore,</I> No. 5:96-CV-292-BR2 (E.D.N.C. Aug. 14, 1996), Robert
Whitesell, an employee of the North Carolina State Highway Patrol, filed charges
against the state and the state's secretary of crime control and public safety,
claiming he was misclassified as exempt under the FLSA and was owed compensation
for overtime hours worked for the department. Citing several court rulings, the
department asked the court to dismiss Whitesell's claims, arguing that the 11th
Amendment barred FLSA claims against a state government. <P>

In <I>Edelman v. Jordan</I> (415 U.S. 651, 662-63 (1974)), one case cited by the
defendants, the Supreme Court ruled that a state's own citizens or the citizens
of another state may not file suit against the state for money damages under the
11th Amendment. The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals extended this protection to
state officers acting in their official capacity, ruling that such a claim
against a state official was essentially a claim against the state (<I>Gray v. Laws,</I>
51 F.3d 426, 430 (1995)). Further, in <I>Seminole,</I> the Supreme Court held that
states "may not be sued in federal court unless they consent to it in unequivocal
terms or unless Congress, pursuant to a valid exercise of power, unequivocally
expresses its intent to abrogate the immunity."<P>

The district court in <I>Whitesell</I> noted that Congress passed the FLSA under its
authority granted in the Interstate Commerce Clause of the Constitution. However,
the Supreme Court in <I>Seminole</I> "overruled prior case law and held that 'Article I
[the Interstate Commerce Clause] cannot be used to circumvent the constitutional
limitation placed upon federal jurisdiction,'" the district court stated.<P>

Moreover, because the FLSA was established under Congress' Interstate Commerce
Clause authority, the law cannot dismiss the state's 11th Amendment immunity.
"Plaintiff cannot raise his claim against defendants, a state and its officer
acting in his official capacity, in this court," the district court ruled.<P>

The plaintiff acknowledged that <I>Seminole</I> prevented "Congress from granting him a
right to sue defendants." However, he argued that the state and its official
"implicitly" relinquished their immunity under the 11th Amendment "by choosing to
comply with FLSA and causing its employees to legitimately rely on that
compliance."<P>

To decide the question, the district court again turned to the <I>Seminole</I> decision.
The Supreme Court in <I>Seminole</I> held that to determine whether Congress properly
has abrogated the states' sovereign immunity, two questions must be asked:<P>

<OL TYPE="1" START="1">
	<LI>has Congress unequivocally expressed its intent to abrogate the immunity; and
	<LI>has Congress acted pursuant to a valid exercise of power?<P>
</OL>

Using this standard, the court concluded that the state's compliance with the
FLSA was not voluntary, but required by Congress. The district court therefore
found that "defendants have not 'unequivocally' waived their 11th Amendment
immunity."<P>

<H3>New York State Employees</H3>

In the second case, <I>Close v. State of New York,</I> No. 94-CV-0906, 1996 U.S. Dist.
LEXIS 12330 (Aug. 19, 1996), 404 employees of the state alleged they were not
paid for overtime hours worked under the FLSA. They sought compensation for the
overtime, liquidated damages and attorneys' fees.<P>

In February 1996 the U.S. District Court for Northern New York issued a
memorandum decision and order holding that the state had violated the FLSA for
not properly compensating its employees for overtime hours worked. However, the
state recently filed a motion to dismiss the case and vacate the previous ruling
under the Supreme Court's Seminole finding, claiming the district court did not
have jurisdiction to hear the case. <P>

The state employees argued that the <I>Seminole</I> decision did not change a state's
responsibilities under the Interstate Commerce Clause; <I>Seminole</I> only dismissed
state's 11th Amendment immunity under the Indian Commerce Clause, the plaintiffs
said. However, the court stated that "the Indian Commerce Clause is a greater
transfer of power from the states to the federal government than is the
Interstate Commerce Clause," and dismissed that portion of the employees'
argument.<P>

Responding to the employees' second claim that the state had relinquished its
immunity by consenting to the suit, the court responded that "judicial
recognition of constructive waiver has been extremely rare." Only when Congress
clearly indicates its intent to make states responsible in federal court for
certain actions, and the state "voluntarily chooses" to undertake such actions,
can states waive their 11th Amendment immunity, the court noted. "This is not a
situation where a state knew beforehand that an inevitable cost of engaging in an
activity and deriving its benefits was consent to be sued," the court ruled.<P>

The plaintiffs also claimed that the United States Code allowed actions under the
FLSA "against an employer (including a public agency) in any federal or state
court of competent jurisdiction" (29 U.S.C. &#167;216(b)), calling into question
the constitutionality of the FLSA as it applies to states. Therefore, according
to plaintiffs, the U.S. Attorney General must certify the FLSA constitutionality
issue before the court can proceed. The district court responded that "because
the constitutional issue is so clear in this case following the Supreme Court's
ruling in <I>Seminole Tribe,</I> however, there is no reason for the court to await the
outcome of the certification."<P>

The district court followed the <I>Seminole</I> ruling, stating that it "no longer [had]
subject-matter jurisdiction over the state's violation of the Fair Labor
Standards Act," and vacated its memorandum decision against the state.  <P>




<hr>
<center>
