<html>
<head>
<TITLE>'One Plan' Guidance to Help Consolidate Response Plans</TITLE> 
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/enviro/blst/blsthead.gif" alt="Risk Management Program
Handbook"><h4> <i>Accidental Release Prevention Under the 1990 Clean Air Act
</i></h4></center><hr>
 
<h2>'One Plan' Guidance to Help Consolidate Response Plans</h2>

<P>
New emergency planning guidance, known informally as the "one plan," is now available from the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) to help facilities consolidate multiple emergency response plans into one functional "integrated contingency plan" (ICP) (61 FR 28642, June 5).
</P>

<P>
"The National Response Team's Integrated Contingency Planning Guidance" is designed to assist facilities with creating a single plan that demonstrates compliance with federal emergency planning requirements under nine existing regulatory programs (administered by five federal agencies).
</P>

<P>
EPA, in its role as chair of the National Response Team (NRT), coordinated preparation of the guidance, which was spurred by EPA's 1994 report to Congress, <I>A Review of Federal Authorities for Hazardous Materials Accident Safety</I> (see <I>Risk Management Program</I> newsletter, April 1994, p. 1). 
</P>

<P>
That report recommended, among other things, that the NRT examine "the different federal requirements for facility contingency planning to determine the desirability of a federal baseline standard to which additional, and necessary component features could be added."
</P>

<P>
In the guidance, EPA points out that the "one plan" does not change existing regulatory requirements and does not impose any new ones. Rather, "it provides a format for organizing and presenting material currently required by the regulations," EPA states. Also, facilities are not required to adhere to the guidance and may continue to maintain multiple plans, although the integrated plan is a "preferable alternative." 
</P>

<P>
The organization of an ICP, as recommended in the nonmandatory guidance, consists of: an introductory section that addresses the plan's scope and provides facility identification information; a core plan section that describes a facility's essential emergency response procedures, functions and management system; and a series of annexes that contain more details on specific topics such as emergency response training, a facility's incident command system, data on existing hazards at a facility and incident documentation.
</P>

<P>
"The use of a single emergency response plan per facility will eliminate confusion for facility first responders who often must decide which of their plans is applicable to a particular emergency," EPA states in the guidance. "The ICP concept should also allow coordination of facility plans with plans that are maintained by local emergency planning committees, area committees [pursuant to the Oil Pollution Act of 1990], cooperatives and mutual aid organizations."
</P>

<P>
According to NRT and the five federal agencies that administer emergency response planning rules, "one plans" prepared in the guidance's format "will be acceptable and be the federally preferred method of response planning."
</P>

<P>
Included as part of the guidance is an outline of a model ICP, with descriptions of the types of information that should be incorporated into each element of a plan.
</P>

<P>
Also, because facilities that utilize the ICP approach still must cross-reference elements of their "one plan" with existing regulatory requirements (so that reviewers can verify compliance), the guidance provides two matrices to help with this process. One of the matrices aligns current regulations with each ICP element, allowing plan drafters to refer to the matrix to identify specific regulatory requirements that apply to each element.
</P>

<P>
In constructing an ICP, the guidance notes that facility planners "need to find the right balance between the amount of information contained in the core plan versus the response critical annexes." Facilities with fewer hazards may choose to place most of its information in the core plan, while facilities with multiple hazards likely will include more information in the annexes.
</P>

<P>
According to the guidance, the core plan should include the essential steps necessary to initiate, conduct and terminate an emergency response action. It also "should provide information that is time critical in the earliest stages of a response and a framework to guide responders through key steps necessary to mount an effective response." The use of checklists and flowcharts is recommended to best convey the information, the guidance states.
</P>

<P>
The annexes to an ICP should augment, rather than duplicate, core plan information, according to the guidance. In addition to sections on detailed notification and response procedures, the annexes "should also address issues related to post-accident investigation, incident history, written follow-up reports, training and exercises, plan critique and modification process, prevention, and regulatory compliance, as appropriate."
</P>

<P>
For copies of the ICP guidance, call the Emergency Planning and Community Right-to-Know hotline at (800) 424-9346. The guidance also is available electronically from the Internet home page of EPA's Chemical Emergency Preparedness and Prevention Office. The address is: <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov/swercepp/">http://www.epa.gov/swercepp/</A>. 
</P>



