<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Consent Order Effective Tool for Coordinating Corrective Action Programs</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/tpg/enviro/fixx/fixxhead.gif" ALIGN=top></center>

<BODY>

<H2>Consent Order Effective Tool for Coordinating Corrective Action Programs</h2>
<P>

At many facilities subject to RCRA corrective action 
requirements, implementation of a corrective action 
program must be coordinated with the requirements of 
other environmental regulatory programs. For example, 
a RCRA permit may require the implementation of an 
Interim Corrective Measure (ICM) for groundwater. While 
the RCRA permit requires and governs the implementation 
of the ICM, it does not, in many instances, deal specifically 
with the treatment and discharge or disposal of the 
groundwater. The RCRA permit can, therefore, create 
a domino type effect, impacting the facility's wastewater 
treatment requirements, impacting the permit requirements 
of the facility, and perhaps leading to significant 
compliance issues. These non-compliance issues can 
manifest themselves in agency enforcement actions or 
citizen suits.<P>

Facilities should not have to &quot;choose their poison&quot;; 
that is, a facility should not be put into a position 
of risking non-compliance under one regulatory program 
as a consequence of complying with another. A mechanism, 
such as a Consent Order, that facilitates coordination 
among relevant regulatory programs can be useful in 
this regard.<P>

<h3>Consent Order Specifics</h3><P>

Consent Orders, which involve multiple regulatory programs, 
can be used to address these concerns to the satisfaction 
of facility owners and regulators. For example, such 
a comprehensive consent order can be used to coordinate 
short- and long-term implementation of a ground water 
ICM with upgrades to a wastewater treatment plant. 
If implementation of the ICM is a priority, the order 
can allow non-compliance with a C Permit, while upgrades 
are implemented that allow for discharges that will 
comply with the facility's permit.<P>

A Comprehensive Order also can provide a basis for coordinating 
a cross-media remediation program. In a sense, such 
an Order allows the agency to prioritize the issues 
to be addressed, recognizing that significant corrective 
action programs often impact other regulatory programs, 
such as air and water. In particular, the Order can 
allow the agency to look at a facility as a whole, 
and not just from a RCRA perspective, to determine 
which concerns pose the greatest risk and to ensure 
that the facility addresses those concerns and regulatory 
issues first.<P>

There may be significant benefits to coordinating compliance 
under an umbrella consent order. For example, while 
permits usually do not include a force majeure provision 
excusing non-compliance for reason beyond the permitee's 
control, these provisions are common in consent orders. 
With proper structuring of a Comprehensive Order, non-compliance 
with a permit may be subject to a force majeure provision 
of the Order. Additionally, since most Consent Orders 
are considered enforcement-type activity, they may 
insulate a facility owner from a citizen suit for past 
or prospective compliance matters that are subject 
to the Order.<P>

There are, of course, costs associated with a Comprehensive 
Order as well. Such an order can require the facility 
owner to commit to a very broad compliance program. 
In addition, the ability of a facility owner to negotiate 
matters covered by the Order can be very limited once 
the Order becomes effective. Consequently, unless there 
is a sufficient degree of specificity in the Order, 
in fulfilling its all of its specifications, a facility 
owner may suffer unexpected expenses.<P>
</BODY>
<foot>

<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/enviro/fixx/fixx.html"><img src="/tpg/enviro/fixx/smallfixx.gif"></a> <a href="/tpg/prices/enviroprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ] "></a>
</pre>
</center>
