<html>
<head>
<title>IRS Releases Expedited Claims Procedures for Educational Assistance Tax Refunds</title>
</head>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/disc/dischead.gif" alt="Employer's Handbook:
Complying with IRS Employee Benefits Rules"></center>

<h2>IRS Releases Expedited Claims Procedures for Educational Assistance Tax Refunds</h2>

<P>
<B><I>W-2c Filing Requirement Disappoints Employers</I></B>
</P>

<P>
The IRS has published guidance on how to claim refunds for federal income taxes withheld on educational assistance benefits received during the temporary lapse of Code Section 127 in 1995 and 1996.
</P>

<P>
The guidance, released Aug. 23, 1996 (in IRS News Release 96-36), includes general information on correction procedures and refund claims. It is similar to guidance published after the exclusion's last reinstatement in 1993 (see &#182;704 of the <I>Handbook</I>).
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Employers Wanted Simple Procedures</H3>
</P>

<P>
The Section 127 exclusion expired on Dec. 31, 1994. The Small Business Job Protection Act of 1996 (P.L. 104-188) retroactively reinstated the exclusion from Jan. 1, 1995, through June 30, 1997.
</P>

<P>
Before this recent guidance, many employers had hoped the IRS would issue special procedures for simplifying the correction process for 1995 and 1996 reporting and withholding errors involving educational assistance benefits. And in fact, lawmakers did recognize the need for such procedures. For the first time in the exclusion's expiration-extension cycle, Congress included language in the statute urging the IRS to do so.
</P>

<P>
The IRS, however, didn't relax the current correction procedures, but instead is requiring employers to prepare W-2c forms.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Tax Refund Procedures for Employees</H3>
</P>

<P>
Eligible employees must apply for refunds of federal, state and local income taxes previously withheld on their 1995 educational assistance benefits. The IRS will not automatically refund these taxes.
</P>

<P>
To get a refund, an employee must file a 1995 W-2c form (the Statement of Corrected Income and Tax Amounts) and a 1040X form (the Amended U.S. Individual Income Tax Return).
</P>

<P>
Employers should use the W-2c to show taxable wages after excluding any educational assistance benefits received in 1995 (up to $5,250).
</P>

<P>
For example, Sam, an employee at XYZ Co., earned $25,000 in 1995. That same year, Sam also received $3,000 in educational assistance benefits.
</P>

<P>
XYZ's original W-2 form issued to Sam would have shown total taxable wages of $28,000 ($25,000 plus $3,000). The revised W-2c, however, would show corrected total taxable wages of only $25,000.
</P>

<P>
Ordinarily, when filing a 1040X, an employee must answer all questions on corrections to the original tax return. To streamline and expedite the refund process, the IRS has simplified the required information. Now, an employee need only:
</P>

<UL>
	<LI>include name, address and Social Security number;
	<LI>write "1995 Tax Year" on the 1040X;
	<LI>sign the form; and
	<LI>attach a W-2c.
</UL>
<P>
In addition, an employee should write "IRC 127" in the top margin of the 1040X.
</P>

<P>
In some cases, refund claims for taxes withheld on educational assistance benefits could involve several other steps. For example, if an employee's 1995 income drops below $26,672 after subtracting educational assistance benefits from total taxable wages, the employee could be eligible for the Earned Income Credit.
</P>

<P>
Refunds of Social Security and Medicare taxes will depend in part on how an employer handles these situations.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Tax Refund Procedures for Employers</H3>
</P>

<P>
The IRS did not change existing procedures employers must follow to claim refunds and credits for tax overpayments. IRS publication <I>Circular E</I> (the <I>Employers Tax Guide</I>) summarizes these procedures.
</P>

<P>
To get a refund, employers should use Form 843 to claim refunds of Social Security and Medicare taxes paid on educational assistance benefits and Form 941 to claim credits for these overpaid taxes.
</P>

<P>
Both the refund and credit procedures have advantages and drawbacks. Employers seeking refunds will receive interest on overpaid taxes. But, because employers already must file the Form 941 with the IRS each quarter, recording the additional information required for an educational assistance tax credit should be simpler than filing the additional Form 843.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Filing Assistance</H3>
</P>

<P>
Call the IRS at 1-800-829-1040 to learn more about procedures for claiming educational assistance refunds. To request forms, such as the 1040X, call 1-800-TAX-FORM.
</P>

<P>
For a complete explanation of refund and credit procedures for taxes paid on educational assistance benefits, see this month's updates to &#182;704 and Appendix C of the <I>Handbook</I>. 
</P>

<HR>

<H4 ALIGN=LEFT>Resolving Conflicting Expiration Dates</H4>

<FONT SIZE="2"><P>
How does Congress rectify a legislative discrepancy such as the educational assistance exclusion's two expiration dates? It usually enacts a technical correction.
</P>

<P>
Technical corrections resolve legislative "errors" -- that is, statutes that clearly conflict with what Congress intended. Legislative errors have many causes. Congressional staff preparing a bill for the president's signature sometimes make typographical or transcription mistakes. Given the breakneck speed at which they worked in August to prepare several major bills, errors are understandable, and surprisingly few and far between.
</P>

<P>
Unfortunately, the exclusion's competing expiration dates is one of these errors. Although the statute provides two expiration dates -- May 31, 1997, and June 30, 1997 -- the conference report to the statute, which outlines congressional intent, clearly establishes only one expiration date -- May 31, 1997.
</P>

<P>
Will the 104th Congress enact a technical correction resolving the exclusion's conflicting expiration dates? Probably not. House and Senate leaders have indicated that they will not work on any major legislation before adjourning in late September. The new 105th Congress, which will convene in January 1997, could introduce a technical correction, but any bill that the correction becomes attached to likely will not come up for a vote for several months.
</P>

<P>
Until Congress resolves the issue, educational assistance plan administrators are permitted to follow the expiration date provided in the bill signed into law by the president -- June 30, 1997.
</P>
</FONT>
<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/pen_ben/disc/disc.html"><img src="/tpg/pen_ben/disc/smalldisc.gif"
alt="Return to Employer's Handbook: Complying with IRS Employee Benefits Rules
Home Page"></a> <a href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img
src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ] "></a>
</pre>
</center>
<hr>
<center><h6>&#169; 1996 Thompson Publishing Group / <a 
href="mailto:webmaster@thompson.com">webmaster@thompson.com</a></h6></center>


</body> 
