<html>
<head>
<TITLE>EPA's Ashland Audit Highlights PSM, Emergency Planning</TITLE> 
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/enviro/blst/blsthead.gif" alt="Risk Management Program Handbook"><h4> <i>Accidental Release Prevention Under the 1990 Clean Air Act </i></h4></center><hr> 

<h2>EPA, OSHA Make Progress On Joint Investigation Plans</h2>

<P>
The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and the U.S. Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) are progressing with plans to share chemical accident investigation duties, and EPA officials recently unveiled blueprints for investigation protocol, training and development of products to guide accident investigators.
</P>

<P>
EPA and OSHA last year were charged with taking over many of the duties of the Chemical Safety and Hazard Investigation Board, which the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990 authorized, but the Clinton Administration has declined to fund (see <I>Risk Management Program</I> newsletter, February 1995, p. 1). The board is authorized by law to investigate major chemical accidents at stationary sources and issue reports and recommendations.
</P>

<P>
According to David Speights, associate director of EPA's Chemical Emergency Preparedness and Prevention Office, the agency had been building up its investigation capabilities over the past several years in anticipation of working with the board on cases and providing technical support. For example, EPA has gained experience from its ongoing chemical safety audit program, which consists of agency audits of prevention programs and emergency response planning at facilities that have experienced chemical releases.
</P>

<P>
OSHA, on the other hand, has been investigating major chemical incidents for a number of years, and since 1992 has been applying the process safety management standard as an enforcement tool in its investigations. However, these investigations, which typically require three to four months of onsite work, are resource-intensive and can require extensive testing, use of expert analysis and storage space for evidence, said Mike Marshall, incident investigation team leader with OSHA.
EPA's investigation tools
</P>

<P>
To further build its expertise and catch up with OSHA, Speights said that over the past couple of years, EPA has been conducting several "pilot" investigations to learn the intricacies of reviewing major chemical accidents. Also, the agency has been working to put together several tools to help with investigations, including:
</P>

<UL>
<P>
	<LI>a legal authority handbook that pieces together from various statutes the parameters of EPA's investigation authority (EPA does not have the same explicit authority granted to the board);
</P>
<P>
	<LI>guidances used in specific industries to support accident history and background research;
</P>
<P>
	<LI>a list of analysis and testing facilities to use during investigations; 
</P>
<P>
	<LI>technical assistance subcontracts with technical experts that have chemical industry, refinery and fire prevention backgrounds; and
</P>
<P>
	<LI>an in-house legal and technical assistance team.
</P>
</UL>

<P>
Currently, EPA has the resources to participate in approximately five major chemical incident investigations per year and has informed Clinton Administration officials that it could gear up to participate in 20 investigations annually, Speights said.
</P>

<P>
EPA's first full investigation involved the Dec. 13, 1994, incident at the Terra Industries Inc. plant in Port Neal, Iowa. An initial investigation report was released by EPA in January (see <I>Risk Management Program</I> newsletter, February 1996, p. 2) and Speights said it currently is being reviewed by an outside, five-member expert review panel. "EPA anticipates using these types of panels for all its chemical incident investigations," he said.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Pool resources, work on protocol</H3>
</P>

<P>
One of the goals of both EPA and OSHA is to effectively pool resources and conduct joint investigations of major chemical accidents at facilities across the country. For example, in response to the April 21, 1995, explosion and fire at the Napp Technologies plant in Lodi, N.J., EPA and OSHA informally coordinated a joint investigation and plan to issue a joint report this fall. 
</P>

<P>
However, the experience highlighted the need for more formal procedures to address investigation logistics. As a result, the two agencies currently are working on a protocol to outline the tasks of each agency during a joint investigation, as well as determine which other agencies can be involved, Speights said. For example, EPA would like to involve state agencies as members of a single, joint investigation of each incident, but some states have preferred not to participate, he said.
</P>

<P>
In addition to working on the protocol, EPA and OSHA plan to define a "large catastrophic event," which may act as the "trigger" that will require or allow a joint investigation. Also, the two agencies have completed an initial draft of a formal memorandum of understanding on joint investigations, OSHA's Marshall said.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Cooperative approach</H3>
</P>

<P>
One problem that the two federal agencies will be struggling with as they perform joint investigations is that, by law, OSHA is required to issue any citations within six months of an inspection, Speights said. Thus, companies have an interest in forcing OSHA to complete investigations within six months. 
</P>

<P>
However, EPA is looking at taking a more cooperative approach with companies as it plans investigations, he said. For example, EPA may consider asking a company to waive the six-month requirement so that OSHA and EPA can jointly investigate for root causes and basically put the enforcement approach on hold. But EPA does not yet know whether companies will buy into this, EPA's Speights said.
</P>

<P>
To help improve cooperation among parties to an accident investigation, the University of Pennsylvania's Center for Decision Sciences held a roundtable discussion in June with the many stakeholders in chemical accident investigations--EPA, OSHA, labor unions, insurance companies and the chemical industry--to circulate ideas related to finding the cause of accidents, learning from investigations and sharing results with stakeholders. The roundtable also addressed two conflicting goals of accident investigation: developing evidence to support litigation versus finding the actual cause and freely sharing investigation results.
</P>

<P>
Finally, EPA and OSHA are planning several "information products" that will be developed from the lessons learned in investigations, including: alerts that focus on what happened and the steps that others can take to reduce risks; full reports on each incident investigated; and other guidance. "Findings from investigations likely will make their way into EPA's guidance documents under the RMP rule, revisions to model RMP plans and, if necessary, through rulemaking," Speights said. 
</P>



<hr> <center> <pre> <a href="/tpg/enviro/blst/blst.html"><img src="/tpg/enviro/blst/smallblst.gif" alt="Return to Risk Management Program
Handbook Home Page"></a> <a href="/tpg/prices/enviroprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt="
