<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>DOL Finalizes Plan Asset Regulations</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/mend/mendhead.gif" alt="Pension Plan Fix-It Handbook"></center> <P>
<h2>DOL Finalizes Plan Asset Regulations </h2>
 
<P><B><I>Pension Payback Program Also Expanded</I></B></P>

<P>Last month, the Department of Labor (DOL) issued the final rule that defines when employers should deposit plan assets, and expanded its Pension Payback Program to encourage more employers to "pay back" missed employee pension plan contributions without incurring civil penalties or federal criminal prosecution.</P>

<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Final Plan Asset Regulations</H3>

<P>Under the final plan asset regulations issued Aug. 2, employers must deposit employee
contributions to defined contribution plans within 15 business days following the last day of the month in which the contributions are withheld from pay or received by the employers.</P>

<P>The final regulations amend the current rules, which required employers to deposit the
contributions as soon as possible, but no later than 90 days after they are made by plan participants.
</P>

<P>The change will take effect on Feb. 3, 1997. The final rule, published in the Aug. 7 <I>Federal Register</I>, applies to all types of pension plans covered by ERISA, including 401(k) plans and profit-sharing plans. In a change from the proposed rules, the final version will not apply to ERISA health plans.</P>

<P>According to Labor Secretary Robert Reich, the change is being made because some employers have been using contributions as an "interest-free revolving loan fund" during the 90-day period. Shortening the waiting period, he added, "takes away the temptation to divert the money."</P>

<P>"As the [401(k)] system grows so quickly," Reich said, "it's not surprising that there's going to be some rotten apples."</P>

<P>The final regulation provides that participant contributions become plan assets on the earliest date that they can be reasonably segregated from the employer's general assets (as under the current rules), but in no event later than the 15th business day of the month following the month in which the participant contributions are withheld or received by the employer. This is significantly shorter than the current 90-day limit, but more generous than the DOL's proposed rule. That proposed rule was based on IRS payroll withholding rules, and would have required participant contributions to be segregated and placed in trust within just a few days in certain instances. (For an analysis of the proposed rules, see the February 1996 issue of <I>Current Developments</I>, p. 1.)</P>

<P>According to the final rules, an employer may obtain a 10-day extension of the deadline with respect to participant contributions received or withheld in a single month.</P>

<P>The final rules also do not affect the ability of cafeteria plan sponsors to rely on a 1992 DOL technical release that specifies that DOL will not enforce ERISA's requirement that plan assets must be placed in trust in cases involving cafeteria plans.</P>

<P><H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Employer Concerns About Deposit Time</H3></P>

<P>After the proposed rule was issued in December 1995, more than 500 employers sent comments to the DOL criticizing the proposal. Common complaints included:</P>

<UL TYPE=DISC>

<LI>The proposed contribution process will be too complex to conduct weekly or
biweekly, because segregating and allocating employee contributions require coordination among many different parties and administrative systems.<P>

<LI>The change will be costly for employees in the long run, as the costs of implementing the changes
would be borne by the employees, who would then contribute less to their benefit plans.<P>

<LI>The change will be too radical for a problem that is not widespread, and it will penalize plans that are now in compliance by saddling them with new implementation costs.<P></UL>

<P>Olena Berg, assistant secretary of labor for pension and welfare benefits, estimated that 94 percent of employers should be able to comply immediately with the rule.</P>

<P>The 180-day waiting period before implementation should give the other 6 percent of employers enough time to make the necessary adjustments, she added.</P>

<P>Moreover, Reich said that according to the DOL's own "conservative" estimate, employees as a group would gain $75 million in interest on contributions in 1997 under the new rule, since employers would be depositing the money in accounts sooner.</P>

<P>The final rule was released as this supplement to the <I>Handbook</I> went to print. More detailed coverage of the rule will be provided in next month's issue of <I>Current Developments</I>.</P>

<P><H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Extended Pension Payback Program</H3></P>

<P>The DOL has also published a class exemption that would extend the time frame and amend other aspects of the Pension Payback Program, the department's recent amnesty program for employers who miss pension plan contributions.</P>

<P>Under the program, employers who restore delinquent participant contributions plus lost earnings on these delinquent contributions to pension plans will not incur criminal penalties under ERISA for failing to deposit employee contributions, and will not be subject to penalties assessed by the IRS for participating in prohibited transactions. The U.S. Justice Department has lent its support to this program.</P>

<P>In the earlier program, the amnesty "window" extended from March 7, 1996, to Sept. 7, 1996. The amendment published Aug. 2 opens this window even more -- back to Nov. 28, 1995. Restored payments must relate to amounts paid by participants or withheld from their wages for contributions to pension plans no later than April 6, 1996. The previous program applied only to pension plan contributions paid by participants or withheld by an employer from participants' wages on or before April 5, 1996. (See the April 1996 issue of <I>Current Developments</I>, p. 1, for a more detailed description of the program.)</P>

<P>To accommodate this recent expansion, the DOL has announced that for restorations that occurred between Nov. 28, 1995, but before March 7, 1996, the total outstanding delinquent participant contributions on the Nov. 28 date, excluding earnings, must not have exceeded the aggregate participant contributions received or withheld from the employees' wages for the 12 calendar months immediately preceding November 1995.</P>

<P>Employers wishing to participate in this payback program must notify, in writing, the DOL's Pension and Welfare Benefits Administration, in Washington, D.C., no later than Sept. 7, 1996. This notification must include certain documentation.</P>

<P>For more information, contact Jeffrey Monhart, pension investigator, Pension and Welfare Benefits Administration, U.S. Department of Labor, Washington, DC; 202/219-4377.</P>


