<html>
<head>
<Title> Proposed placement of autistic boy in self-contained classroom violates
IDEA, court rules<P></Title>
</head>

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif"> 
<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/fed_gts/hand/handhead.gif" alt="Section 504 Compliance
  Handbook"></center><P>

<h2>Proposed placement of autistic boy in self-contained classroom violates IDEA,
court rules<P></h2>
A Virginia school system has been ordered by the U.S. District Court for the
Eastern District of Virginia to educate an autistic boy in regular education
classrooms because its proposed special education placement would deny him a
free, appropriate public education.<P>
The Loudoun County, Va., board of education proposed placing Mark Hartmann, an
11-year-old boy, in special education after a year of including him in one of its
regular classrooms. Hartmann challenged the decision, alleging that it violated
section 504 and the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA). However,
a hearing officer determined that the district's proposed placement did not
violate its obligation to educate him, to the maximum extent appropriate, with
nondisabled children.<P>
The court reversed, finding that the board's efforts to include Mark were
inadequate. Although the board hired a full-time, personal aide to assist
Hartmann, the court held that it failed to follow the advice of qualified experts
who favored Hartmann's continued inclusion. <P>
Instead, it placed on his individualized education program team staff persons
"who had inadequate training and experience" about educating autistic children in
an inclusive setting, "thereby dooming their inclusion efforts to failure."<P>
Hartmann could receive significant educational benefits in a regular education as
long as he has the help of an aide and properly adapted curriculum, the court
determined. It noted that at least two school systems had successfully
"mainstreamed" Hartmann, citing evidence that he could do simple addition and
subtraction by the end of fourth grade. He also could point correctly to pictures
of the appropriate coins when asked to give his aide 35 cents.<P>
The district argued that special education was appropriate because Hartmann was
not working at his age level. The court disagreed, saying, "Mark is learning in
the inclusive setting and he has more chance of fulfilling his unknown potential
in such a setting than in the less enriched one of the self-contained class."<P>
Although he had some behavioral problems while attending a Loudoun district
school, the court found that, without heeding the advice of experts, the district
was unable to provide successful behavior modification strategies. Hartmann's
behavior improved greatly after he left Loudoun's school and was mainstreamed in
another district, the court also found.<P>
The court cautioned that its holding was limited to what was in Hartmann's best
interest and did not sanction inclusive education for all autistic children. The
court analyzed the case primarily under the IDEA, but concluded it would enjoin
"further violations of the IDEA and the Rehabilitation Act." This case is
<i>Hartmann v. Loudoun County Board of Education,</i> Appendix IV:617. 
<P>
<hr> <center> <pre> 
<a href="/tpg/fed_gts/hand/hand.html"><img
src="/tpg/fed_gts/hand/smallhand.gif" alt="Return to Section 504 Compliance
 Handbook Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/grantprices.html"><img
src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt="
[ ORDER ] "></a> </pre> </center> <hr> <center><h6>(c) 1996 Thompson Publishing
