<html> 
<head>
<title>EMS Personnel Do Not Qualify for 207(k) Exemption, District Court Rules</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/person/fair/fairhead.gif"></center>
<P>
<h2>EMS Personnel Do Not Qualify for 207(k) Exemption, District Court Rules</h2>

Emergency medical service (EMS) personnel working for a county 	do not qualify for the partial
overtime exemption under 207(k) of 	the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA) because they failed to meet
the applicable regulatory test, the U.S. District Court for South Carolina ruled May 13 (<I>Roy v. County of
Lexington</I>, Case Number: 3:93-2292-19, 1996 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 7718). The court also found that the
employees' meal periods and sleep time were noncompensable under the act.<P>

The EMS staff is one of five departments within the Lexington County's public safety division. The county
was subdivided into nine response areas, with a staff of EMS personnel assigned to each specific substation.
Although some EMS units were jointly housed with firefighting units, the two units were physically
separated by a wall. Each substation was staffed by two EMS employees on duty throughout each 24-hour
period. These EMS employees responded to calls forwarded by the county's 911 service.<P>

"The EMS teams were dispatched to fires, crime scenes, and automobile accidents whenever there was a
report of an injury, the likelihood of an injury or the dispatcher had no reliable information upon which to
determine whether an injury had occurred," the district court noted. Each team was expected to respond
within two minutes to any call within its service area. If an ambulance was already on call, however, a
neighboring EMS substation would be contacted to respond to the call.<P>

The county placed EMS employees under a 207(k) plan, paying them time and one-half for every hour
worked over 43 in a work period. The EMS employees worked on three recurring shifts of 24 1/2 hours,
which constituted a "one day on and two days off" schedule. The shift contained three meal periods, during
which employees were not to be interrupted except in the event of an emergency call. If interrupted during
a meal period, they were paid for the entire hour. They also were paid if their sleep time was interrupted,
including a full hour of compensation when even one minute of sleep was disturbed for an emergency call. If
they could not get five consecutive hours of sleep, the entire eight-hour period was compensated.<P>

EMS employees received an annual salary paid in biweekly installments. Since their schedules fluctuated
over time, they were paid one-half of their regular hourly rate for each overtime hour worked in the work
period. Because they were paid by salary rather than on an hourly basis, their regular rate of pay was
calculated by dividing the total number of compensable hours worked in the two-week pay period by their
biweekly salary.<P>

The FLSA (29 U.S.C. &#167;207(k), Appendix I, page 18) provides a partial overtime exemption for public
employees engaged in law enforcement and firefighting activities. For EMS personnel who work for an
agency independent of law enforcement or fire protection to qualify for the exemption, the employer must
meet the "substantially related" test (29 C.F.R. &#167;553. 215, Appendix II, page 86.4) and the "80/20"
rule (29 C.F.R. &#167;553.212, Appendix II, page 86.4) under the regulations, the court noted.<P>

The "substantially related" regulatory test requires an employer to prove that EMS personnel "have
received training in the rescue of fire, crime and accident victims" and "are regularly dispatched to fires,
crime scenes, riots, natural disasters and accidents." The county satisfied the first prong of the test
regarding EMS training, the court found. <P>

The county argued that it also met the second prong of the test because it dispatched EMS employees to
fires, crime scenes and automobile accidents on a regular basis. The district court did not agree. "In order
for this standard to be satisfied, logic dictates that there be some comparison of the total number of calls
of this type with the number of times that an ambulance responds to them," the court said. "Otherwise, the
word 'regularly' would add nothing to the test."<P>

Using a standard for evaluating regularity adopted by the U.S. Court of Appeals for the 6th Circuit in
<I>Justice v. Metropolitan Gov't of Nashville </I>(4 F.3d 1387), the court found that about 31 percent of total
calls responded to by the county's EMS personnel were made concurrently with law enforcement and
firefighting agencies, with the remainder of calls being of a strictly medical nature with no law
enforcement or fire response. The court also noted that only 10 percent of the total number of EMS working
hours were spent on law enforcement and fire calls. The district court, therefore, concluded that the
county did not meet the "substantially related" test under the regulations.<P>

The court then turned its attention to the "80/20" rule, which requires that EMS employees spend no more
than 20 percent of their time on nonexempt activities -- that is, activities not related to law enforcement
and fire protection (i.e., medical calls). The county calculated that for a two-month period EMS employees
spent less than 16 percent of their time on medical calls. The district court accepted the formula that the
county used in its calculation, but said the county should have expanded its analysis to the six-month period
in question. Using this longer time period, the court found that the county's EMS employees spent 23
percent of their time on medical calls.<P>

The district court also questioned whether the county's estimate of time spent by EMS employees on
medical calls -- 50 minutes -- was too conservative. Rather, the court found that the average call lasted
70 minutes, which resulted in EMS personnel spending more than 20 percent of their time on strictly
medical calls. The court, therefore, concluded that the county did not meet the "80/20" rule under the
regulations. As such, the county's EMS personnel did not qualify for payment under a 207(k) plan.<P>

<H3>EMS Employees' Meal Period and Sleep Time Is Noncompensable</H3>

The regulations (29 C.F.R. &#167;785.19, Appendix II, page 132) provide that employees must be
"completely relieved from duty" during their meal periods for the time to be considered noncompensable
under the FLSA. The county's EMS employees argued that to be completely relieved from duty, employees
should not be on call. However, most courts reject this strict interpretation because "it is inconsistent with
the prevailing Supreme Court precedent which interprets the FLSA ... or because it is inconsistent with the
intent of the regulations," the district court said. The 6th Circuit adopted a more flexible approach in <I>Hill v.
United States</I> (751 F.2d 810, 814 (6th Cir. 1984),<I> cert. denied</I>, 474 U.S. 817 (1985)), ruling that an
employee is not entitled to be paid for meal time "as long as the employee can pursue his or her mealtime
adequately or comfortably, is not engaged in the performance of any substantial duties, and does not spend
time predominantly for the employee's benefit."	<P>

Applying this "predominant benefit" test, the district court concluded that the EMS workers were not
primarily engaged in work-related activities during meal periods, noting that "these employees had no
official responsibilities during this period of time other than to respond to an emergency call if called upon."
The only restriction placed on EMS employees during meal periods was that they remain within their
service area. The court concluded that the county's EMS employees "were not acting primarily for the
benefit of their employer during their meal periods," therefore, the time was noncompensable under the
act.<P>

Concerning the compensability of sleep time, the regulations (29 C.F.R. &#167;785.22, Appendix II, page
132) state that if an employee is required to be on duty 24 hours or more, the employer and the employee
may agree to exclude sleep time from hours worked. Further, if the sleep time is interrupted by a call to
duty, that time is considered hours worked. If the employee cannot get a reasonable night's sleep, the time
is compensable. For enforcement purposes, the Department of Labor (DOL) has determined that if an
employee cannot get five hours of uninterrupted sleep, the time is compensable.<P>

The employees argued that the entire period that has been designated for sleep purposes -- eight hours --
must be uninterrupted a majority of the time for the regulation to apply. The court noted that, if this
interpretation is correct, the regulation does not apply to the employees because evidence at trial
established that their sleep time was interrupted by emergency calls at least 60 percent of the time. The
county, however, argued that a reasonable night's sleep is five hours of uninterrupted sleep and that during
two of the months at issue, approximately 75 percent of the sleep periods were without interruption for
the entire eight hours or for at least five hours. The court, accepting this standard, found that the EMS
employees had "at least five hours of uninterrupted sleep during a majority of the time allocated for this
purpose."<P>

The district court also noted that although EMS personnel did not have a written agreement with the county
to exclude sleep hours from compensable hours of work, they did not challenge the county's policy through
the established grievance process nor did they complain to their supervisors about it. The district court
found that "the affected employee's failure to contest the policy within a reasonable period of time
constitutes implied consent to the sleep period exemptions." The court, therefore, ruled that the EMS
employees' sleep time was noncompensable under the act.<P>

<H3>Payment on a Fluctuating Workweek Basis</H3>

The county's EMS employees argued that they should not have been paid on the basis of a fluctuating
workweek. The court agreed, finding that there was no agreement between the employees and the employer
to pay overtime compensation at the half-time rate.<P>

The regulations (29 C.F.R. &#167;778.114, Appendix II, pages 100-101) provide that "a salaried
employee whose hours fluctuate from week to week may reach a mutual understanding with his employer
that he receive a fixed amount as straight-time pay for whatever hours he is called to work in a workweek,
whether few or many, and that he will be compensated for his overtime work at a rate of fifty percent of
his regular hourly rate." Even though the employer is not required to explain the method of half-time
calculation, "at a minimum, the employer must provide its employees with a reasonably clear and accurate
explanation of their compensation," the district court noted.<P>

When the county established its overtime policy in 1985, it circulated a memorandum, indicating that
employees would be paid overtime at time and one-half their regular rates. Although the memo was
incorrect, the error was never corrected, the court pointed out. In addition, the employee handbook
"contained arguably contradictory language about whether the EMS employees would be paid on a fluctuating
work week schedule," according to the court.<P>

EMS personnel and the county did not have a mutual understanding that overtime hours worked would be
calculated on a half-time basis, the court concluded. The county, therefore, violated the FLSA when it
compensated EMS personnel on a fluctuating workweek basis, and the employees are entitled to overtime
payment at time and one-half their regular rates for all hours worked over 40 in a workweek.<P>

The court determined that the EMS employees are entitled to overtime back wages for a period of two
years immediately prior to the filing of this action as well as prejudgment interest, attorneys fees and
costs. <P>


<hr>
<center>
