<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Clinton Pushes for Improved Consumer Protections</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/bene/benehead.gif" alt="Employer's Health Benefits Bulletin"></center>
<P>
<h2>Clinton Pushes for Improved Consumer Protections</h2>

<P>
With the ink of his signature on the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996 barely dry, President Clinton recently seized upon the increased visibility of health care issues to propose or support measures that would improve consumer protections.
</P>

<P>
During a Sept. 5 speech in Florida before a group of senior citizens--a constituency with a long-standing concern about health care issues--Clinton noted that the millions of Americans affected by changes in the health care system "ought to feel comfortable about the health care they receive."
</P>

<P>
To that end, he told the group that he has asked Secretary of Health and Human Services Donna Shalala and Labor Secretary Robert Reich to form the Advisory Commission on Consumer Protection and Quality in the Health Care Industry. According to Clinton, the national commission will meet on a "bipartisan basis ... to evaluate the ways that health plans can best serve their customers over the long run so that we can have a health care system we can afford and one we can be proud of."
</P>

<P>
That same day, Clinton issued an executive order which provided more details on the commission.
</P>

<UL>
<P>
	<LI>It will be composed of a maximum 20 members appointed by the president. The members will be consumers, institutional health care providers, heath care professionals, other health care workers, insurers, purchasers, state and local government representatives and experts in health care quality, financing and administration. The Labor and HHS secretaries will serve as co-chairs and report to Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
	<LI>The commission shall advise the president on changes in the health care system and recommend any measures necessary to promote and assure health care quality and value, and protect consumers and workers in the health care system by: (1) reviewing data on consumer information and protection; (2) reviewing existing and planned work that defines, measures and promotes health care quality of health care; and (3) collecting and evaluating data on changes in availability of treatment and services.
</P>
<P>
	<LI>The commission will make a preliminary report to the president by Sept. 30, 1997. A final report will be submitted 18 months after the commission's first meeting. 
</P>
</UL>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Could Lightning Strike Twice?</H3>
</P>

<P>
Clinton, who helped revive action on the then-languishing portability bill in his State of the Union speech last January, threw his support behind another stalled measure--the Patient Right to Know Act of 1996 (H.R. 2976)--during his Florida speech.
</P>

<P>
The legislation was introduced last February and approved by the House Commerce Committee on June 27. It was also referred to three House committees--Ways and Mean, Economic and Educational Opportunities and Government Reform and Oversight. Thus far, those committees have taken no action on the bill.
</P>

<P>
Under the bill, any entity--including third-party administrators of ERISA plans--that offers a public or private health plan could not: (1) as part of any contract or agreement with a health care provider, restrict or interfere with any medical communication; or (2) on the basis of a medical communication, take any of the following actions against a provider--refuse to contract with, terminate or refuse to renew a contract, prohibit referrals to the provider, refuse to compensate for covered services, or any other retaliatory action. Any entity violating the provisions would be subject to a civil penalty of up to $25,000 for each violation and up to $100,000 if it is determined that a "pattern of violations" exists.
</P>

<P>
The legislation was introduced by Rep. Greg Ganske, R.-Iowa, to curb the use of alleged "gag clauses" by some managed care plans, in which plan providers are prohibited from telling patients about all treatment options in an effort to curb expenditures. 
</P>

<P>
In supporting the bipartisan legislation, Clinton emphasized that he is "convinced that the right kind of managed care can really be the best of all worlds--can give more choices to consumers, can give people more chances to make decisions that are right for them, can keep the costs of health care down and still maintain very high quality." 
</P>

<P>
However, he cautioned that "some bad things can happen" that could lead to a decline in the quality of health care, such as "gagging" providers, which he said has to stop.
</P>

<P>
"Doctors just must not face discrimination when they uphold their oath to give patients the best care," said Clinton. "Patients should feel safe in the knowledge that they have been given the full story of what all their treatment options are and what are best for them. They should be told about the best treatment, whether it's the cheapest or not ..."
</P>

<P>
However, some employer groups believe that the legislation could negatively affect group health plans. At a July 30 hearing of the Ways and Means Health subcommittee, a representative from the National Business Coalition on Health noted the following employer concerns.
</P>

<OL>

	<LI>The bill fails to ensure uniformity by granting states authority to impose their separate and mutually inconsistent standards.
</P>
<P>
	<LI>The bill's "overly broad prohibitions" on oral as well as written communications would create "ambiguities" that will lead to increased litigation.
</P>
<P>
	<LI>Managed care would be eroded because, as employers lose the ability to use performance guarantees and information requirements, they would have no incentive to continue managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
	<LI>Administrative expenses would rise as plans review or renegotiate contracts, written statements and oral communications. 
</P>
</OL>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Push for Subsidies </H3>
</P>

<P>
President Clinton also expressed his support for mandatory maternity stay legislation during his Florida speech, and mentioned a health insurance subsidy proposal that appeared in his defunct balanced budget plan last year. First Lady Hillary Clinton also discussed the proposal in her Aug. 27 speech at the Democratic National Convention in Chicago. Under the plan, the federal government would provide sliding scale subsidies for up to six months to help workers and their families who are between jobs. 
</P>





<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/pen_ben/bene/bene.html"><img
src="/tpg/pen_ben/bene/smallbene.gif"  alt="Return to Employer's Health Benefits Bulletin 
Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ]
"></a>
</pre>
</center>
