<html> 
<head>
<title>Medicare Secondary Payer Law Trumps State Insurance Law, Federal
Appeals Court Rules</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/cobs/cobshead.gif" alt="Coordination of Benefits
 Handbook"></center>
<P>
<h2>Medicare Secondary Payer Law Trumps State Insurance Law, Federal Appeals
Court Rules</h2>

State insurance laws are generally permitted by the McCarran-Ferguson Act to
remain effective when federal laws of broad application--which are often written
in expansive, sweeping terms--might otherwise inadvertently interfere with those
laws. However, one exception is when Congress has specifically chosen to deal
with state insurance law. Under the McCarran-Ferguson Act, federal law will
preempt even state insurance law if the federal law "specifically relates to the
business of insurance." <P>

That was the rationale of the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in <i>United
States v. Rhode Island Insurers' Insolvency Fund</i>, 1996 U.S. App. LEXIS 6574
(April 5, 1996). The court determined that the Medicare Secondary Payer (MSP) law
does specifically relate to the insurance business, and therefore preempts a
Rhode Island state law that would have made Medicare the primary payer of $14,000
in medical claims. Moreover, according to the court, the state law and the MSP
law contain contradictory terms on the order of payment responsibility.
Therefore, the federal MSP law preempts the state law under a standard preemption
analysis. <P>

Because the state refused to voluntarily accept Medicare's status as secondary,
the award was for double damages based on provisions of the MSP law. <P>

The 1st Circuit consists of Maine, New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Rhode Island and
Puerto Rico. The decision is binding in those states and may be cited as legal
precendent by courts in other U.S. Circuits. <P>

<h3>Rhode Island Law Versus Federal Law</h3><P>

The Rhode Island Insurers' Insolvency Fund Act (RIIIFA) creates a fund to help
pay claims filed against insolvent insurers. RIIIFA provides that when an insurer
becomes insolvent, the fund is "deemed to be the insurer to the extent of the
obligations" covered under the insurer's policies. RIIIFA also contains a
nonduplication clause that requires fund claimants to first exhaust any right of
recovery under a governmental insurance plan and allows the fund to refuse to pay
amounts that are recoverable.<P>

The MSP program, enacted to lower federal Medicare payments, requires Medicare
beneficiaries to exhaust available private insurance coverage before resorting to
Medicare coverage. (See Tab 500 of the <i>Handbook.</i>) The MSP law provides
that "Medicare benefits are secondary to benefits payable by a third party payer
even if the State law . . . states that its benefits are secondary to
Medicare."<P>

The case involved three Medicare beneficiaries who were involved in automobile
accidents and received approximately $14,000 in medical benefits from Medicare.
The three filed claims against the fund because their automobile insurance
carrier was insolvent. The fund paid the claims--with the exception of the
$14,000 that had been disbursed by Medicare. When the fund refused to pay that
amount, the United States sued it in a federal district court for $28,000. The
district court found for the United States, and the fund appealed that decision
to the 1st Circuit.<P>

<h3>McCarran-Ferguson Act</h3><P>

The McCarran-Ferguson Act generally preserves for the states the ability to
regulate the business of insurance, and provides that federal law should not be
interpreted to supersede a state insurance law "unless such Act specifically
relates to the business of insurance." (See &#182;223.)<P>

After examining both the "specifically relate" and the "business of insurance"
portions of the test, the appeals court agreed with the district court that the
McCarran-Ferguson Act in this case failed to prevent the preemption of the Rhode
Island law. Noting that while the McCarran-Ferguson Act does not usually allow
for the preemption of state insurance laws, the court said that federal law may
nonetheless trump state insurance law when it is clear that Congress intended to
"inject itself into the area of state insurance law." <P>

The MSP law, the court found, does "specifically relate" to insurance because it
does not concern a rule of general application that might encompass both insurers
and non-insurers, but rather deals directly with payments under an automobile or
liability insurance policy. Moreover, the MSP law involves the "business of
insurance," because it affects the core relationship between the insurer and its
insured, the court said. Some of the core matters included in the business of
insurance, the court noted, are the type of policy that may be issued and its
reliability, interpretation and enforcement. The MSP provision prohibits private
insurers from enforcing terms which make Medicare primary, and thereby affects
the business of insurance, the court said.<P>

<h3>Same Result Under Conventional Preemption Analysis</h3><P>

The fund argued that the MSP law and the RIIIFA are compatible and therefore
federal law should not supersede state law under a standard preemption analysis.
According to the fund, MSP provides for Medicare reimbursement only if it is
reasonable to expect reimbursement to be made, and it is not reasonable to expect
the fund to pay because of its provision requiring exhaustion of governmental
insurance. The court rejected this argument, finding that if state law is
preempted, it would be reasonable to anticipate that payment would be made to
Medicare.<P>

Finally, the court rejected the fund's argument that it is government agency
rather than a policy or plan of insurance as defined under the MSP rules. By its
own terms, the court said, the RFIIIA deemed the fund to be the insurer, and
therefore the fund is considered a primary plan under the MSP provisions and
regulations. <P>

<hr>
