<head>
<Title> OUST, ASTM To Develop Standard for Tiered Third-party UST Inspection Program</Title>
</head>

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">
<IMG SRC = "/tpg/enviro/ustt/ustthead.gif" alt="Underground Storage Tank Guide"><P>

<h2> OUST, ASTM To Develop Standard for Tiered Third-party UST Inspection Program</h2><P>

As part of its private sector initiative, the U.S. Environmental Protection

Agency's (EPA) Office of Underground Storage Tanks (OUST) is working with the

American Society for Testing and Materials (ASTM) to develop a standard for a

third-party inspection program in which private inspectors would grant

underground storage tank (UST) owners certificates documenting their tank

management practices.<p>

The goal of the program, which has the working title "Alice," is to incorporate

good UST management into common business practices, said OUST's Sammy Ng, who is

in charge of developing the concept for the agency. Some entities already

require tank owners to provide assessments of their UST maintenance as a

transaction condition. For example, bank regulating agencies such as the Federal

Deposit Insurance Corp. and the Federal and National Mortgage Association

instruct banks to require environmental assessments, he said. But the types of

assessments vary.<p>

The purpose of the inspection program would be to create a standardized document

describing a facility's past UST maintenance that would be universally accepted

by lenders, members of the real estate and insurance industries, state

regulatory agencies, EPA and the consulting community, said OUST Acting Director

Lisa Lund. The document would give these entities a certain level of assurance

about the quality of tank management at a facility, Lund said. For instance, it

would help lenders assess the financial risk of loaning money to a tank owner or

speed property transfers, she said.<p>

The idea is for real estate, banking and insurance regulatory agencies to

instruct businesses to require the document as part of their national guidelines

on environmental issues, Ng said. This would help them evaluate the risk posed

by USTs and make transactions easier, he said. <p>

OUST has approached lenders and members of the real estate and insurance

industries about ways to create market incentives for proper tank management, Ng

said. These groups are realizing that they too have an interest in managing USTs

on commercial properties, EPA said. Properly maintained, USTs "have been and

continue to be an asset to a property. There are safe and accepted ways to

operate tanks so that they remain assets ... and it will be mutually beneficial

for EPA, states and interested private industries to join forces in ensuring

good tank management." The Alice concept was suggested by members of the real

estate industry who need a standardized method for documenting UST maintenance

to simplify transactions at closure, Ng noted. <p>

The inspection program would contain different tiers or levels of analysis--to be

determined by ASTM--for meeting different end-users' needs, Ng said. For example,

an Alice 1 could be a rudimentary assessment of tanks that might be required

annually under the terms of a loan agreement, he said. An Alice 3 could be a

full-blown site assessment involving installation of probes that might be

required by banks for major mortgages or facility upgrades, he said.<p>

The concept is akin to Pennsylvania's third-party service provider program in

which private consultants perform legally required inspections paid for by the

tank owner, Lund said. The twist is that OUST is asking ASTM to develop training

materials and train consultants on how to perform the inspections, she said.

ASTM would not license or certify the consultants, however. OUST is considering

working with the Air and Waste Management Association to certify or license the

inspectors, Ng said.<p>

States may consider using Alice as part of their enforcement programs, Ng said.

For instance, they could give certain benefits to certificate-holding tank

owners and focus inspection efforts on facilities that have not been inspected,

he said.<p>

The first meeting of the ASTM task group for the standard is June 17, Ng said.

OUST would like to have a standard adopted by the middle of next year and does

not anticipate a lengthy licensing or certification process for inspectors, he

said. The agency hopes that having a standardized "proof-of-compliance" document

will facilitate the loan process for tank upgrades to meet the 1998 deadline, he

said.<p>

For more information on OUST's private sector initiative, contact one 

of the following OUST personnel. For insurance issues, contact Sammy 

Ng at (703) 603-7166, or ng.sammy@epamail.epa.gov. For banking issues, 

contact Mark Barolo at (703) 603-7141, or barolo.mark@epamail.epa.gov. 

For real estate issues, contact Peggy Flaherty at (703) 603-7152, or

flaherty.margaret@epamail.epa.gov.<p>

