<Title> Welfare Reform Creates New Assistance Block Grant</Title><P>

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif> 
<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/fed_gts/gran/granhead.gif" alt="Federal Grants Management
 Handbook"></center></IMG><P>

<h2> Welfare Reform Creates New Assistance Block Grant</h2>

<body>
<i>Food Stamps, Medicaid Remain Entitlements</i><P>

The new welfare reform bill (H.R. 3734), expected to be signed into law at press
time by President Clinton as the Personal Responsibility and Work Opportunity
Reconciliation Act of 1996, will dramatically change the welfare system and hand
states a greater amount of administrative control. Most provisions of the law
will take effect July 1, 1997.<P>

The act eliminates Aid to Families with Dependent Children (AFDC) as an
entitlement, replacing it with block grants to states known as Temporary
Assistance to Needy Families (TANF). The legislation generally gives states more
flexibility in designing programs and deciding eligibility requirements. <P>

However, states must meet minimum requirements for getting recipients into jobs
and have to report more information to the federal government than under current
welfare programs. TANF will be oriented toward performance by giving bonus grants
to states that exceed certain goals and reducing allocations for states failing
to meet specified requirements. States that are penalized through reduced funding
must replace those federal funds with states funds, in effect doubling the amount
of any penalty.<P>

Several proposed block grants were left out of the legislation. Some members of
Congress had wanted to create block grants for foster care and adoption
assistance, child and family services, Medicaid and food stamps. The new statute
makes some changes to these programs and consolidates several child care and
commodity assistance programs.<P>

<h3><i>Temporary Assistance for Needy Families (TANF)</i></h3><P>


Under the new TANF provisions, states will have to submit a plan outlining how
they would conduct the program to meet its goals, including getting recipients
into work. TANF funds can be used to: provide assistance to needy families; end
dependence on government benefits by promoting job preparation, work and
marriage; prevent out-of-wedlock pregnancies; and encourage the formation and
maintenance of two-parent families.<P>

States also will be able to receive supplemental grants for work programs and
cash welfare payments. In the case of the latter, a state would qualify if its
average federal welfare spending per person was less than the national average
and its population growth exceeded the average of all the states.<P>

A contingency fund will be established to help states with rising welfare
caseloads. Eligible states could receive additional funds of up to 20 percent of
their annual TANF allotment. States could qualify if unemployment is higher than
in previous years or if food stamp participation has increased 10 percent. The
same rules for using regular TANF grant funds apply to the supplemental and
contingency funds.<P>

TANF funds can be spent on state-designed job training programs, and the use of
vouchers that allow recipients more choice in where to get employment services is
permissible. Not only do individuals receiving assistance have to meet certain
work requirements, but states are held more accountable for finding recipients
jobs. Under TANF, 50 percent of single-parent families receiving assistance must
be participating in work activities by 2002, and for two-parent families, 90
percent must be working by 1999. States failing to achieve these goals could be
penalized through a 5 percent to 21 percent reduction in their allotments.<P>

"Work activities" that count toward the minimum percentage is strictly defined.
For example, no more than 12 months of vocational education training can count as
a work activity. States must not displace existing workers when finding
recipients jobs and must have grievance procedures to resolve complaints from
workers who claim to have been displaced.<P>

The legislation sets relatively broad parameters for eligible uses of TANF funds.
States will be able to transfer up to 30 percent of their TANF allotment to the
Child Care and Development (CCDBG) or the Social Services block grant programs.
The new law also will allow states to provide family assistance services through
contracts with religious organizations "on the same basis as any other private
organization." Current regulations restrict the use of sectarian organizations in
such programs.<P>

Under TANF, states will have some discretion in establishing eligibility for
benefits but will have to comply with certain limitations on who can receive
assistance and for how long. The law establishes a lifetime limit on benefits of
five years, though states can have a shorter limit and give "hardship exemptions"
to 20 percent of families on their monthly caseload. <P>

States are prohibited from providing TANF assistance to certain populations.
These include most unmarried parents under age 18 who do not live with a parent
or other adult or who refuse to attend high school or an equivalent training
program. Legal immigrants are denied welfare benefits their first five years in
the United States; states can decide their eligibility after that time. The
so-called "family cap" requirement was dropped, though states have the option of
imposing a cap if they choose, which denies benefits for any new children born to
a family receiving TANF. States can also deny aid to those convicted of a drug
felony.<P>

While the welfare legislation imposes penalties on states that fail to meet its
requirements, the legislation offers financial incentives to states to achieve
the goals of welfare reform, such as reducing out-of-wedlock births, and will
reward "high performance" states with bonus grants of up to 5 percent of their
state family assistance grant. State performance will be measured through a
formula developed by the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services (HHS), the
National Governors Association and the American Public Welfare Association.  <P>

<h3><i>Grant Administration, Reporting Requirements</i></h3><P>

Under TANF, states will be required to continue spending at least 75 percent of
their past state expenditures on specified welfare and social service programs.
States that fail to meet the work participation requirements will be required to
maintain 80 percent of their spending. In contrast, AFDC has no
maintenance-of-effort requirement; it matches state dollars at a designated rate
(between 50 percent and 83 percent). Although the law contains some restrictions
on what can count toward a state's maintenance-of-effort, it does permit states
to apply expenditures for families that are ineligible for federal benefits under
welfare reform -- including families that have exceeded their five-year benefit
limit.<P>

Also, administrative costs for states under TANF are capped at 15 percent.
Because the legislation requires states to collect, track and analyze much more
data about assistance recipients, many states will need to expand their computer
systems or purchase new systems. Therefore, "information technology and
computerization" related to TANF requirements will not count toward the 15
percent cap. However, administrative costs that states count toward their
maintenance-of-effort are subject to that limit.<P>

Under the new reporting requirements, states must collect data on each family
receiving assistance and report to HHS on a quarterly basis. That information,
which can be reported through a scientifically acceptable sampling method
approved by HHS, must include such factors as:<P>
<UL>
<LI>the number of family members and each member's relationship to the youngest
child;<P>
<LI>the race and educational status" and "citizenship" of each adult and child;
and<P>
<LI>the number of hours per week that adults participate in education,
employment, job search, job training and other activities.<P>
</UL>

States must also report on the percentage of TANF funds they used for
administrative purposes; the total amount expended on programs that quarter; the
number of noncustodial parents in work activities; and the amount spent on
transitional services for families moving from welfare to work. States failing to
submit required reports would have their grants reduced by 4 percent. <P>

States that have received waivers to experiment under AFDC (as approved by HHS
under Section 1115 of the Social Security Act) will be allowed to continue
administering welfare programs according to the terms of the waivers until they
expire. Those terms will take precedence over any provisions in the welfare law
that are inconsistent with the waiver, but states will receive block grant
allotments in place of other payments provided for in the waiver. If a state
submitted a waiver request before the enactment of the legislation, the waiver
can still be approved by HHS on or before July 1, 1997. <P>

<h3><i>Expanded CCDBG</i></h3><P>

The title IV-A AFDC Child Care, Transitional Child Care and At-Risk Child Care
programs are folded into the CCDBG program under the new welfare law. States will
receive a single child care block grant to provide assistance to low-income
families. <P>

Under the new CCDBG program, states are subject to a 5 percent cap on
administrative costs, but the conference report on the welfare reform legislation
lists numerous exceptions to what counts toward that cap. For example,
eligibility determinations, participation in judicial hearings, recruitment and
inspections of child care placements, and maintenance of computerized child care
information "are an integral part of service delivery and should not be
considered administrative costs."<P>

The legislation removes the current requirement that states spend 25 percent of
CCDBG funds for activities that improve the quality and increase the availability
of child care. However, a new set-aside is created: states will be required to
use at least 4 percent of all funds for "comprehensive consumer education" for
parents. As under TANF, states must report quarterly to HHS on each family
receiving assistance. In addition, states must report twice a year on other
program information, including "the manner in which consumer education
information was provided and the number of parents who received it."<P>

<h3><i>Child Support Enforcement</i></h3><P>

The new statute broadens states' obligations for enforcing child support payments
and tracking parents who owe child support. The enhanced federal matching rate of
90 percent for automated data systems will decrease to 80 percent for fiscal
years 1996 through 2001. No performance-based system for funding is established,
but the legislation requires HHS to develop a proposal that would give states
"incentive payments."<P>

By Oct. 1, 1997, states must operate a "directory of new hires." Employers and
labor organizations must report to the state the name, address and social
security number of each newly hired employee. The state child support agency is
expected to use the information to help establish paternity for TANF and other
assistance programs, and to locate individuals who owe child support.<P>

A 5-percent reduction in TANF funding will be the penalty for states failing to
comply with the child support and paternity enforcement provisions. States can
reduce benefits to individuals who refuse to cooperate with states in
establishing paternity.<P>

<h3><i>Other Assistance Programs Affected</i></h3><P>

The Food Stamp Program was not turned into a block grant, as proposed, but
various eligibility and income determination provisions were revised. For
example, childless adults aged 18-50 will be eligible to receive food stamps for
three months in any three-year period. If those recipients become unemployed,
they may apply for three more months of benefits. States are given greater
latitude in implementing employment and job training requirements for food stamp
recipients. The legislation broadens the U.S. Department of Agriculture's
authority to waive food stamp requirements. <P>

In a major administrative change, the new law requires states to implement
electronic benefit transfer (EBT) systems for the Food Stamp Program within six
years. Under EBT, it is envisioned that food stamp recipients will be issued
debit cards that will be used to electronically deduct benefit allotments as food
is purchased in stores. USDA can waive the deadline if a state "faces unusual
barriers" to implementing EBT.<P>

Previously, states had been encouraged but not required to implement EBT. States
have been wary, however, because the Federal Reserve Board has ruled that states
are subject to "Regulation E," which limits cardholder liability if cards are
lost or stolen and in turn could increase state costs. However, the new law
provides that Regulation E will not apply to any EBT system administered by state
or local governments distributing means-tested benefits. <P>

Other food assistance programs will undergo changes. Reimbursement levels are
lowered for meals provided under the Summer Food Service Program for Children and
Child Care Food Program. The legislation also melds soup kitchen and food bank
commodities programs into the Emergency Food Assistance Program (TEFAP).
Technical changes are made to the school lunch and breakfast programs.<P>

Medicaid coverage will continue as an entitlement, rather than the block grant
proposed earlier this year. Individuals who stop receiving TANF benefits and go
to work will continue to be covered by Medicaid for one year.<P>

Congress also had proposed turning disability assistance for children under the
Supplemental Security Income Program into a block grant, but that idea was not
adopted. However, the legislation tightens the definition of "disability" for
purposes of determining eligibility for individuals under age 18. The revised
definition includes impairments leading to "marked and severe functional
limitations and which can be expected to result in death or last at least a
continuous period of not less than 12 months."<P>

The new law makes several changes to the eligibility of legal immigrants for
receiving various benefits. Under some programs, such as the Food Stamp Program,
non-citizens legally in the United States are generally ineligible. Under other
programs, such as TANF, Medicaid and title XX (the Social Services Block Grant
Program), states have the option of prohibiting legal immigrants from receiving
benefits. The legislation provides exceptions for emergency assistance. 
</body> <foot>

