<html> <title> Secondary Payer's Discounted  Rate Accepted as Full
Payment</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/cobs/cobshead.gif" alt="Coordination of Benefits Handbook"></center>
<P>
<h2> Secondary Payer's Discounted  Rate Accepted as Full Payment</h2>
<body>
<P>

<b><i>Provider Can't Later Bill Primary Payer for Regular Rate, Appeals Court
Rules</b></i><P>

A primary insurer that might have paid a hospital bill at an undiscounted cost of
$654,227 was not required to pay the hospital at all because the secondary
insurer paid the bill first, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals has found.
Because the hospital unconditionally accepted the secondary insurer's discounted
amount of $177,219 as payment in full on behalf of the participant, the
participant was no longer legally obligated to pay further medical expenses, and
had no further right to claim indemnification from the primary insurer. As
assignee of the participant's right to payment from the primary plan, the
hospital in the case, <i>Cedars-Sinai Medical Center v. Massachusetts Mutual Life
Ins. Co.</i>, 1995 U.S. App. LEXIS 27693 (9th Cir. Sept. 21, 1995), stood in no
better position than the participant, and was similarly not entitled to any
further payment from the primary insurer. <P>

<h3>Facts of the Case</h3><P>

John Gambardella obtained dependent coverage through his employer plan, insured
by MassMutual. The terms of the plan required medical care to be provided by a
member of MassMutual's  exclusive provider network except in an emergency, in
which case notification to a network member was required within 48 hours. John's
wife Jane was pregnant when the coverage became effective, and the coverage
extended to medical expenses of the newborn as a dependent from the moment of
birth.<P>

Jane's health coverage, provided to her employer by CIGNA, included coverage for
both her pregnancy and care of the newborn. Under Jane's plan, she was required
to receive medical care from the Cedars-Sinai Medical Center. Cedars did not
participate in the MassMutual plan.<P>

Both plans contained a coordination of benefits provision that incorporated the
birthday rule to determine which insurer would be primarily responsible for
medical costs incurred by the newborn. Because John's birthday fell first in the
year, MassMutual was the primary insurer. <P>

Jane gave birth prematurely at Cedars. Upon Jane's admission, John assigned to
Cedars all the medical insurance benefits that would otherwise be payable to him.
The newborn remained hospitalized at Cedars for five months, but John did not
provide the notification required by MassMutual until after the baby was released
from the hospital.<P>

Cedars sought payment of $654,227 from MassMutual for medical expenses incurred
by the baby. MassMutual denied the claim because no notice was provided within 48
hours. Cedars then accepted CIGNA's payment of $177,219 as full payment for the
baby's medical expenses pursuant to a previously negotiated discount rate. Cedars
agreed that this payment discharged the Gambardellas' debt to Cedars.<P>

Cedars subsequently attempted to collect payment from MassMutual, contending that
as the baby's primary insurer, MassMutual was obligated to pay for her care at an
undiscounted rate of $654,227.<P>

<h3>Assignee "Stands in the Shoes" of the Insured, Appeals Court Determines</h3><P>

The district court in California found that John's failure to comply with the
48-hour notice requirement did not prejudice MassMutual, and that under
California law, the claim should not have been denied on that basis. However, the
court found that the Gambardellas' debt to Cedars had been fully discharged by
CIGNA's payment, and because there was no further indebtedness, Cedars, as John's
assignee, could not recover any additional payment. <P>

The 9th Circuit affirmed the district court's ruling that MassMutual was not
responsible for any further payment to Cedars. According to the court, Cedars had
no legitimate claim against MassMutual because Cedars, as John's assignee, merely
"stands in the shoes" of John, (that is, takes his place) with respect to
recovery of insurance proceeds, and CIGNA's payment had discharged John's debt in
full. Because John did not legally owe any further payment to Cedars, John was
not entitled to claim further recovery from MassMutual; consequently, Cedars had
no further right of recovery. <P>

Finding that MassMutual did not owe Cedars any further payment, the 9th Circuit
did not consider MassMutual's argument that the district court erred in applying
the state law regarding prejudice.<P>

It is interesting that Cedars forfeited its right to claim the undiscounted rate
of payment despite its initial application to MassMutual for payment of medical
expenses which, it could be argued, were denied improperly. Note that the case
involved the claim of Cedars against MassMutual and did not discuss the
settlement of the primary versus secondary issue between the two private
insurers. <P>

The 9th Circuit includes Alaska, Arizona, California, Hawaii, Idaho, Montana,
Nevada, Oregon, Washington and Guam. <P>

</body> 

<foot>

