<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Adding Value to Your Benefits Program Through Flexibility</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/bene/benehead.gif" alt="Employer's Health Benefits Bulletin"></center>

<h2>Adding Value to Your Benefits Program Through Flexibility</h2>

<P>
<B><I>By Richard D. Quinn, Contributing Editor<BR>
President, Personnel Research Associates</I></B>
</P>

<P>
For many benefit professionals, the first question asked in plan design is: "Is it legal?" Legal compliance is essential. However, the driving force in plan design should be choice and flexibility.
</P>

<P>
Choice comes in many forms. Health benefits may offer HMOs and/or indemnity plans with varying deductibles and out-of-pocket costs. Cafeteria plans offer many options, including life insurance and disability coverage. Progressive employers allow employees the choice of non-traditional benefits such as group legal, group auto and universal life insurance.  
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>The 401(k) Plan--The Ultimate in Choice </H3>
</P>

<P>
But even with all these options, the most critical choice for employees is retirement income. With the decline in defined benefit plans, the uncertain future of Social Security and the increasing age limit for full retirement benefits, employees' reliance on retirement planning is even more crucial.
</P>

<P>
As the trend continues to move toward 401(k) defined contribution plans, many employers still design their plans primarily to pass the tax code's discrimination tests. As a result, employers tend to constrain employee contribution choices--allowing only pre-tax contributions and restricting changes to once each month or quarter. In addition, many plans severely limit withdrawals, do not permit loans, restrict fund allocation among available investments and otherwise force employees into plans that are very limited, have little flexibility and fail to accommodate life events that occur prior to retirement.
</P>

<P>
Between the start of a career and retirement, most people will marry, purchase a home and send their children to college. They may also face unforeseen financial emergencies. Conventional wisdom says that 401(k) plans should be for retirement only, and other methods should be used to save for such events. However, most Americans lack the discipline to save for long-term goals. 
</P>

<P>
The best way most people save money is through payroll deduction. Therefore, rather than restricting 401(k) plans to retirement savings only--making it more difficult to squirrel away funds for a home and college education--why encourage all types of savings within a qualified retirement plan?  
</P>

<P>
This might raise participation and savings rates, and generate good will within the work force. When employees have little access to their funds and are slapped with tax penalties for making an emergency withdrawal, they are inclined to save only the smallest amount they can spare. However, if employees have more flexibility to manage these funds, they are more likely to maximize their savings.
</P>

<P>
It is possible to design such a plan in today's environment. Following is an outline of a user-friendly thrift plan which has been in place since 1981 and has never failed a discrimination test. 
</P>

<UL>
	<LI>Contributions--both pre-tax and after-tax--are permitted in any combination up to 25 percent of pay (limited to the current 401(k) contribution cap). Employees can send in "make-up" contributions by check at any time during the plan year.
</P>
<P>
	<LI>The employer matches 50 percent of employee contributions up to 6 percent of salary, on a pre-tax and/or after-tax basis.
</P>
<P>
	<LI>Employees are eligible to contribute immediately upon hire; the company match begins after six months. Rollover contributions are accepted, and employees can allocate rollovers into eight funds.  
</P>
<P>
	<LI>There is daily valuation of accounts. Employees can make investment changes and other transactions and request a complete account statement on a daily basis through a telephone voice response system. Paper forms have been eliminated.
</P>
<P>
	<LI>Two loans--each allowing up to 60 months to repay--are permitted at one time. Employees can model loan payments by length of a loan or by the monthly payment amount through the voice response system. Employees may also write checks to make extra principal payments on an outstanding loan.
</P>
<P>
	<LI>Hardship withdrawals are permitted for all allowable reasons under the IRS safe harbor rules. 
</P>
<P>
	<LI>In-service withdrawals are permitted at any time. Employees who have after-tax money in the plan can determine how much of a total distribution is required to receive a specified amount on an after-tax basis. They can then elect a rollover for the taxable portion and receive a check for the balance. This avoids a taxable distribution, avoids the need for a hardship withdrawal and minimizes the total withdrawal amount. However, company contributions can be suspended if money is withdrawn too soon after the employee places it in the plan--this is an IRS rule you can't avoid.
</P>
<P>
	<LI>Investment allocations and transfers among funds can be made in 1-percent increments.
</P>
</UL>

<P>
Sound attractive? That's the whole idea. This plan is consistent with a total flexible benefits strategy, in which employee choice and flexibility are the name of the game. The plan is in full IRS compliance, but IRS rules did not drive the plan design. Rather, someone came up with an idea and everything possible was done to implement it <I>and</I> comply with the regulations.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Fitting Into an Overall Strategy</H3>
</P>

<P>
A defined contribution plan is not an isolated tool to be used for retirement income only. Rather, it lends itself to other uses. 
</P>

<P>
For example, if an employer seeks to reduce or eliminate its obligation for retiree medical benefits, allowing employees to fund such an obligation over a longer period of time is essential, especially with today's trend toward mid-career hiring. First, employers can provide group medical benefits to assure the availability of such coverage. Second, they can provide vehicles--such as a thrift plan or a 501(c)(9) trust with or without employer contributions--in which employees can accumulate funds to pay health premiums. One employer has established a retiree health account in which employees can place money on an after-tax basis. The earnings accumulate and can be used tax-free for eligible medical expenses. Contributions can be as low as $5 per week. In the future, the employer will place $75 per year into the account once an employee attains 25 years of service.  
</P>

<P>
Retirees can also have more flexibility in retiree benefits if employers offer a choice of options such as multiple indemnity plans, HMOs and PPOs. Retirees who contribute to such coverage can assume more responsibility by enrolling in a higher deductible plan if they are ineligible for or do not want a managed care option. This also helps hold the employer's costs down.  
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>A "Total Benefit Needs" Approach</H3>
</P>

<P>
401(k) plans and other employee benefit programs must be considered within an overall benefits strategy that reflects the needs of both employees and the employer. This is not as difficult as it may sound. The basis for such a strategy is understanding four things: (1) the available resources that can provide employee benefits; (2) employees' goals and concerns; (3) any likely future changes; and (4) the nature of the work force. For example, a long-term stable work force from which most people retire is vastly different than a work force from which employees will not retire or will retire with relatively few years of service. 
</P>

<P>
Today, the realities of the global marketplace affect workers at all levels. Stability is an extinct concept--individual responsibility and accountability are today's buzzwords. But for the average employee, the reality of those words in terms of financial security--where survival now depends on  adequate savings and prudent choices--are not fully understood. Benefit plan design can provide an invaluable service to the work force of the future by helping employees make the decisions necessary for lifelong financial security. Employers that offer such benefits will ultimately have an edge in attracting the best employees. But to seize this opportunity, employers must look beyond the question, "how do I comply with the law?" and begin asking themselves, "how can a design a benefits program that can be a valuable tool in employee recruiting and retention?"
</P>

<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/pen_ben/bene/bene.html"><img
src="/tpg/pen_ben/bene/smallbene.gif"  alt="Return to Employer's Health Benefits Bulletin 
Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ]
"></a>
</pre>
</center>
