<html>
<head>
<Title> Property Owners Near Leaking USTs Sue Marketers in Nationwide Class Action Suit</Title>
</head>

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">
<IMG SRC = "/tpg/enviro/ustt/ustthead.gif" alt="Underground Storage Tank Guide"><P>


<h2>Property Owners Near Leaking USTs Sue Marketers in Nationwide Class Action Suit</h2><P>

Acting with unprecedented speed, an Alabama county judge May 8 certified a nationwide class of people who own property near leaking underground storage tanks (USTs) one day after plaintiffs filed a lawsuit seeking damages for property devaluation caused by the alleged "willful and outrageous" conduct of many of the nation's oil companies (<I>Peters v. Brants Grocery</I>, No. CV-96-29 (Ala.
Cir. Ct. Coosa Cnty.)). <p>

The 48-page complaint seeks an unspecified amount of compensatory and punitive damages for common law claims of negligence, nuisance, trespass and fraud. According to plaintiffs' class counsel Kenneth Ingram Jr., potential liability likely will be in the tens of billions of dollars. "Plaintiffs will prove that this widespread environmental calamity need never have happened. The oil company defendants were well aware more than thirty years ago of this problem and largely chose to ignore or conceal, or minimize it until forced to respond," the 
complaint states. <p>

Defendants in the case include the major oil producers Amoco Oil Co., British Petroleum Exploration &amp; Oil Inc., Chevron USA Inc., Exxon Corp., Shell Oil Co. and Texaco Refining and Marketing Inc. <p>

The suit alleges that defendants who upgraded selected facilities by replacing old UST systems took the action "more for economic, marketing and public relations objectives than for environmental protection" and left to leak many tank systems that needed repair. In addition, it alleges that defendants failed to investigate contamination or to warn adjacent property owners.<p>

Petroleum-marketer attorney Jeffrey Leiter of Collier, Shannon, Rill and Scott said the plaintiffs likely will have a problem proving that leaking tanks have caused a diminution in their property value. State trust fund and insurance data indicate that most tank leaks do not spread to adjacent properties, he said. <p>

Judge John Rochester approved the class, saying a class action is "the fairest

and most efficient means" of adjudicating the case. The class includes U.S.

property owners who have had or will have their properties "affected by soil,

sediments, groundwater and/or surface water contamination from a site containing

an underground storage tank system," according to the four-page certification

order. Specifically, 10 percent or more of the property must be located within

250 feet of a former retail petroleum-marketing facility where a leak was

reported in the last three years, the order states.<p>

The case qualified as a class action because it would be impracticable to join a

large number of separate plaintiffs in a single lawsuit; there is a well-defined

common interest among the parties in the questions of law and fact; and the

plaintiff will adequately protect the interests of the class, the order states.

Leiter said he is investigating the validity of the order. <p>

Property owners who meet the definition of the class are considered to be class

members unless they remove themselves by filing an opt-out notice with the court.

Thus, settling this case would give oil companies an opportunity to resolve much

of their future liability, but it is not clear for how long, Leiter said. Also,

it may be less expensive to defend this lawsuit and handle future claims

individually, he said. <p>

Personal injury and existing claims are excluded from the class, according to the

order. Also excluded are claims by government agencies or entities, such as state

or local highway departments; common carriers, such as railroads; easement

holders, such as utilities or pipeline companies; oil companies; defendants; and

U.S. or Alabama justices, judges and magistrate judges.<p>

The order requires defendants to "search their records and provide the

plaintiffs' attorneys with a list ... of all potential members of the plaintiff

class and their addresses" within 30 or 45 days, depending on applicable state

law. <p>

Other defendants named in the action are Brants Grocery, Conoco Oil &amp; Gas

Associates, CTE Environmental Inc., Ecology and Environment Inc., Eutaw Bait

Shop, Hamilton Texaco Service Station, Mapco Petroleum Inc., Star Enterprises and

Tenneco Inc. The suit does not name all of the nation's oil producers, but the

complaint may be amended after discovery to add additional companies, Ingram

said.<p>

Ingram is with the law firm of Morris, Haynes, Ingram &amp; Hornsby in Alexander

City, Ala. Also representing the plaintiffs are Joe Whatley Jr. and Peter Burke

of Cooper, Mitch, Crawford, Kuykendall &amp; Whatley in Birmingham, Ala.  



