<html> <title>Cafeteria Plans With Cash Opt-Out Provisions May Violate Medicare
Secondary Payer Law</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/flex/flexhead.gif" alt="Flex Plan 
Handbook"></center>
<P>
<h2> Cafeteria Plans With Cash Opt-Out Provisions May Violate Medicare Secondary
Payer
Law</h2>
<body>

A recent technical correction to the Medicare secondary payer law may affect
cafeteria plans that provide employees with cash if they waive medical coverage.
<P>

The Medicare law contains a provision which states that an employer cannot offer
financial incentives to employees over age 65 to waive coverage under the
employer's plan in favor of Medicare. The intent of the law is to discourage
employers from giving cash to employees over age 65 in order to shift costs to
Medicare. If this rule is violated, the Health Care Financing Administration
(HCFA) can levy fines of $5,000 per occurrence.<P>

The original version of the Medicare law provided that a financial incentive was
permissible, <i>provided it was offered to all employees who were covered under
the
plan</i>. In other words, under the prior version of the law, a cafeteria plan
which
provided cash to employees who waive coverage was permissible, provided all
employees were provided with the cash option (not just those over age 65).<P>

Unfortunately, amendments to the Social Security law which were enacted in 1994
changed the wording of the law by dropping the phrase, <i>"unless the incentive
is
offered to all employees who were covered under the plan."</i> In other words,
based
on the current wording of the law, offering a cash opt-out to employees over age
65 would violate the law, even if the opt-out is offered to all other employees.
<P>

The change in the law raises some concerns for cafeteria plan sponsors that offer
cash to employees who waive coverage. The conservative approach would be to not
offer the cash option to active employees over age 65. However, by doing so, an
employer could violate the nondiscrimination rules that apply to cafeteria plans,
depending on the composition of the over-age-65 employee group. As a practical
matter, HCFA is not currently enforcing this issue, and has announced no
immediate plans to do so.<P>


</body> 

<foot>

<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/pen_ben/flex/flex.html"><img
src="/tpg/pen_ben/flex/smallflex.gif"  alt="Return to Flex Plan Handbook 
Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER
]
"></a>
</pre>
