<html><title>Final IRS Regulations Clarify Deductions for Reimbursement and
Expense Allowances</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/perk/perkhead.gif" alt=" Employer's Guide to 
Fringe Benefit Rules"></center>
<P>
<h2> Final IRS Regulations Clarify Deductions for Reimbursement and Expense
Allowances</h2>
<body>

<b><i>No Significant Differences From Proposed Regulations</i></b><P>

The IRS has issued final regulations clarifying deductions for employer-provided
club dues, spousal travel and business meal and entertainment expenses.<P>

The Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1993 enacted a 100-percent deduction
disallowance for employer-provided club dues and for spousal travel and increased
the deduction disallowance for business meal and entertainment expenses from 20
percent to 50 percent. The final regulations guide employers in applying these
statutory changes to their fringe benefits policies.<P>

The final regulations became effective when they were published in the May 30
<i>Federal Register</i> (61 <i>Fed. Reg.</i> 27005). They do not differ significantly from the
proposed regulations, but include additional information that should help
benefits administrators apply the deductions correctly.<P>

<h3>Choice Allowed Between Exclusion and Deduction</h3><P>

Employers can choose how to treat expenses for employees' business use of clubs
or spousal travel. If an employer provides either of these two fringe benefits
for a bona fide business purpose, the employee can exclude the benefit from gross
income as a Code Section 132 working condition fringe benefit. (See Tab 400 of
the <i>Guide</i> for a discussion of working condition fringes.) If the employee is
allowed to exclude the benefit, the employer cannot also deduct the benefit as an
otherwise "ordinary and necessary" business expense.<P>

The employer can deduct the benefit's cost as a compensation expense if it treats
the value of the club's business use or spousal travel as compensation, and
includes that amount in the employee's income.<P>

Independent contractors and tax-exempt organizations also can choose between
excluding or deducting these two fringe benefits.<P>

<h3>No Usage Threshold for Club Dues</h3><P>

Employees must be taxed only on their personal use of clubs, even if their
personal use is more than their business use. Previously, an employee was taxed
on 100 percent of the club's use if that use was primarily personal.<P>

The rules for taxing a club's personal use do not affect an employer's choice
between excluding or deducting the club's business use.  (See &#182;410 of the
<i>Guide</i>.)<P>

<h3>Other Individual Defined</h3><P>

The proposed regulations directed that the spousal travel rules apply to spouses,
dependents and "other individuals." The final regulations clarify that "other
individuals" do not include business associates traveling with an employee, such
as customers, clients, suppliers, other employees, agents, partners or
professional advisors. (See &#182;420 of the <i>Guide</i>.)<P>

<h3>Get It Right the First Time</h3><P>

An employer's option to deduct or exclude a fringe benefit expense is attractive.
But in either situation, the club dues or spousal travel expense must be for bona
fide business purposes. The final regulations emphasize that a benefit must be
treated correctly on all tax forms when they are filed. If the employer treats
the benefit as compensation, taxes must be withheld.<P>

If the IRS decides during an audit that an employee's club use or spousal travel
was not for a bona fide business purpose, the benefit would be included in the
employee's gross income as compensation and would be subject to payroll
withholding and income taxes.<P>

If the IRS is auditing the employer, the employer will be liable for any
additional taxes on the employee's benefit and for any penalties. In addition,
the IRS will not permit the employer to deduct the recharacterized compensation.
Once an employer forgoes a deduction, it cannot file a refund claim to get it
back.<P>

<h3>Errors Could Trigger Nonaccountable Plan Penalties</h3><P>

The final regulations confirm that the IRS will not consider an employer's
reimbursement plan "nonaccountable" merely because an employer reimburses an
employee for nondeductible club dues or spousal travel. This provision, however,
does not apply if the spousal travel benefit is for a purpose other than bona
fide business.<P>

Under the Code Section 62 accountable plan rules, an employee must return any
advance that isn't used for substantiated business expenses. Not returning the
excess jeopardizes the arrangement's accountable status and could make all
benefits provided under the plan taxable -- even reimbursements for
business-related expenses. (See &#182;741-&#182;743 of the <i>Guide</i> for a discussion
of the accountable plan rules.)<P>

Here's an example of a penalty: Using a $700 travel advance, an employee buys two
$200 airline tickets for business travel, one for herself and one for her
husband. She also spends and substantiates $300 for business meals. If her
husband traveled with her for a bona fide business purpose, she then spent the
entire $700 on bona fide business expenses. But if her husband didn't travel for
that purpose, his $200 ticket would become an excess advance that the employee
failed to return. This failure would trigger the nonaccountable plan penalties
and the employee would be taxed on the entire $700 advance, not on just her
husband's $200 ticket.<P>

<h3>Unchanged Expenses</h3><P>

The IRS didn't modify the proposed regulations for business meal and
entertainment expenses. Employees may continue to exclude 100 percent of their
business meal and entertainment expenses from income. Employers, however, may
deduct only 50 percent of these expenses as "ordinary and necessary" business
expenses. <P>

<h3>Guidance Missing on Other Deductions</h3><P>

Although the final regulations reassure employees that they will not necessarily
be taxed on the nondeductible 50 percent of their business meal and entertainment
expenses or on any business-related club dues or spousal travel expenses, the
final regulations do not provide similar reassurances for eight other Code
Section 274 deduction limitations. Employees could be taxed on these fringe
benefits even if they substantiate their business expenses. The deduction
limitations cover gifts, foreign travel, tickets to sporting events, sky boxes,
non-North American conventions and cruises, lavish meals, educational travel and
luxury water transportation. (See &#182;400, &#182;701 and &#182;720 of the <i>Guide</i>
for a discussion of these deduction limitations.)<P>

On-premises athletic clubs might or might not be excludable as a fringe benefit.
The final regulations don't confirm whether this benefit is affected.<P>

<h3>Valuation Issues Remain Ambiguous</h3><P>

The final regulations do not offer guidelines for determining the disallowed
deduction amount for club dues or spousal travel when the costs of those benefits
differ from their "deemed" value, as is often the case with flights on company
planes. Other regulations permit an employer to deduct the cost of a company
flight for an employee's personal use, even though the flight's Standard Industry
Fare Level value is significantly less than the employer's actual cost. But the
regulations do not address what deduction the employer should record if there are
no additional expenses for providing a spousal travel benefit or if the
employer's incremental costs are zero, such as when both employee and spouse
travel on the company plane or when both stay in a double-occupancy hotel room.
<P>


</body> 

