<html>
<head>
<Title> Student with heart condition lawfully barred from playing college ball,
7th Circuit rules<P><P></Title>
</head>

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif"> 
<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/fed_gts/hand/handhead.gif" alt="Section 504 Compliance
  Handbook"></center><P>

<h2> Student with heart condition lawfully barred from playing college ball, 7th
Circuit rules<P></h2>
A permanent injunction ordering Northwestern University to allow a
student-athlete with a heart condition to play college ball has been vacated by
the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.<P>
Nicholas Knapp's heart stopped after a game in his high school gym in the fall of
1994. After being hospitalized, Knapp resumed playing basketball for his high
school team. When he signed an athletic scholarship to play basketball for
Northwestern University, Northwestern knew of his heart condition. <P>
However, after Knapp enrolled, the team physician determined he was not medically
eligible to participate in intercollegiate basketball. Knapp continued to receive
his scholarship and was kept on the team, but was barred from practicing or
competing.<P>
Knapp sued, claiming that Northwestern violated section 504. The U.S. District
Court for the Northern District of Illinois agreed and ordered Northwestern to
let Knapp play collegiate basketball (November 1996 Monthly Bulletin, p. 4). <P>
The 7th Circuit reversed, determining that Knapp was not substantially limited in
a major life activity and not qualified to play college ball. Barring Knapp from
playing intercollegiate basketball does not substantially limit him in the major
life activity of learning, the appellate court held.<P>
"Numerous college students graduate each year having neither participated in nor
attended an intercollegiate sporting event. ... Not playing intercollegiate
sports does not mean they have not learned. Playing or enjoying intercollegiate
sports therefore cannot be held out as a necessary part of learning for all
students," the 7th Circuit stated.<P>
Knapp was not qualified to play intercollegiate basketball because Northwestern
rationally determined that, if he competed, there was a reasonable probability of
his personal physical injury (possibly even death), the appellate court also
determined. <P>
"In regard to cases involving risk of future injury, a school's perception of the
threat of such injury cannot be based on unfounded fears or stereotypes; it must
be based on objective evidence. ... But here, where Northwestern acted rationally
and reasonably rather than paternalistically, no Rehabilitation Act violation has
occurred," the 7th Circuit said.<P>
This case is <i>Knapp v. Northwestern University,</i> Appendix IV:614. 
<P>
<hr> <center> <pre> 
<a href="/tpg/fed_gts/hand/hand.html"><img
src="/tpg/fed_gts/hand/smallhand.gif" alt="Return to Section 504 Compliance
 Handbook Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/grantprices.html"><img
src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt="
[ ORDER ] "></a> </pre> </center> <hr> <center><h6>(c) 1996 Thompson Publishing
 Group / <a
href="mailto:webmaster@thompson.com">webmaster@thompson.com</a></h6></center>

</body>
