<html>
<head>
<Title>OMB Readies A-133 Changes; AICPA Plans New Reporting Guidance</Title>
</head> <P>

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif"> 
<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/fed_gts/sass/sasshead.gif" alt="Single Audit Information Service"></center><P>
<I>Implementing the 1996 Amendments</I>

<h2>OMB Readies A-133 Changes; AICPA Plans New Reporting Guidance </h2>

<P>
The Single Audit Act Amendments have set off a new round of changes to federal policy and industry guidance, the first of which will likely be proposed revisions to Office of Management and Budget (OMB) Circular A-133, <I>Audits of Institutions of Higher Education and Other Non-Profit Institutions</I>. The A-133 proposal may be issued later this month, according to OMB officials.
</P>

<P>
Within the next several months, the audit community also can expect drafts of a new compliance supplement (see story, below), revised AICPA reporting guidance and a machine-readable certification form to be submitted with an A-133 audit. All of these components are needed for audits to be performed under the new statutory and regulatory single audit requirements, which apply to audits of fiscal years beginning on or after July 1, 1996.
</P>

<P>
The first move will be another proposal to revise Circular A-133, which will include plans to rescind Circular A-128, <I>Audits of State and Local Governments</I>. Coupled with the Circular A-133 revisions issued last April, the proposed revision would fully implement the recent amendments to the Single Audit Act, OMB officials told attendees of AICPA's National Governmental Accounting and Auditing Update Conference in August.
</P>

<P>
The Single Audit Act Amendments (P.L. 104-156) brought all non-federal entities under the same audit requirements. To implement the statutory changes, OMB plans to apply Circular A-133 to state and local governments. Several other changes are needed for A-133 to adhere to the statute, including:
</P>

<UL>
<P>
	<LI>adding a two-year grace period before the new report submission deadline takes effect (i.e., nine months after the end of the period audited, beginning with audits of fiscal years beginning on or after July 1, 1998); and
</P>	
<P>
	<LI>providing for biennial audits. The Single Audit Act Amendments permit non-profits that had biennial audits for all periods ending between July 1, 1992, and Jan. 1, 1995, to continue to have biennial audits. Likewise, state and local governments can continue to have biennial audits if they have been required by state constitutions or laws in effect on Jan. 1, 1987, to undergo audits less frequently than annually. 
</P>
</UL>

<P>
Although the A-133 proposal will focus on new statutory requirements that OMB has little discretion in implementing, other revisions are possible, said Sheila Conley, an OMB policy analyst in the Office of Federal Financial Management, in remarks to AICPA conference participants. In particular, OMB may revisit the issue of who should be responsible for completing the new certificate that must be filed with the audit report under the revised Circular A-133.
</P>

<P>
The April revision added a new reporting requirement for grantees by requiring the management of the audited entity to complete the certificate. The certificate affirms that the auditee engaged the auditor to perform an A-133 audit, contains a series of "yes or no" statements about the audit report and any audit findings, and certifies that the summarized information "accurately and completely reflects the results of this audit."
</P>

<P>
"We would like to get some feedback as to whether or not it would make sense for the auditor to prepare the certification form," Conley said. "Much of the information that will be captured will come directly from the auditor's report." Therefore it may be more efficient for the auditor, rather than the auditee, to prepare the part of the form summarizing the audit report results, while the auditee would still be responsible for signing the certification, she said.
</P>

<P>
The proposal is expected to have a 60-day comment period. The status of the Circular A-133 proposal is available on Thompson Publishing Group's Internet homepage, <A HREF="/tpg/fed_gts/sass/sassnews.html">"Status of OMB Policies"</A>. When issued, the proposed revisions also will be posted on the Thompson Publishing Group site.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>AICPA Will Revise Reporting Guidance</H3>
</P>

<P>
To help auditors perform the new single audits, AICPA plans to issue in early 1997 new guidance for the form and content of single audit reports to correspond with OMB's revised reporting requirements, said Mary Foelster, technical manager of the AICPA Professional Standards and Services Division. The guidance will likely be a revised Statement of Position (SOP) 92-9, <I>Audits of Not-for-Profit Organizations Receiving Federal Awards</I>. The updated SOP will supersede all single audit guidance in the existing SOP 92-9 and the <I>Audit and Accounting Guide for State and Local Governments</I>, Foelster told conference participants.
</P>

<P>
Foelster said that an AICPA task force had developed some ideas for streamlining the reporting package and may recommend reducing the number of required audit reports to three. "There would be a report on the general purpose financial statements or the statements for not-for-profits, a report that would cover the Yellow Book requirements for internal controls and compliance, and a third report that would cover single audit matters, internal controls and compliance for major programs," she said.
</P>

<P>
Illustrative reports also will be included in the revised guidance. "We will provide examples of clean reports and reports that are not as clean," Foelster said. "I expect that we'll have that guidance out in time for auditors to use in planning engagements." 
</P>

<P>
George Rippey, director of technical and non-federal audit staff at the U.S. Department of Education's Office of Inspector General and a member of the AICPA task force working to simplify the reports, elaborated on the upcoming changes. "Through the revisions to the Single Audit Act as well as the proposed changes to the compliance supplement, two reports are going to drop out: the report on non-major programs and the report on compliance with general requirements," Rippey said. In addition, the report on compliance will be at an opinion level rather than having statements of positive or negative assurance, he said.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Impact on Auditors' Work</H3>
</P>

<P>
Speaking at the AICPA conference, federal audit officials discussed how changes to the Single Audit Act and Circular A-133 could impact auditors' work. OMB's Conley said auditors who will no longer be auditing subrecipients expending less than $300,000 a year in federal awards may be in a good position to do other monitoring work for clients that make subawards.
</P>

<P>
Because pass-through entities will not be able to receive federal reimbursement under the revised A-133 for single audits of subrecipients under the threshold, pass-through entities will need to "figure out a different way to exercise that [monitoring] responsibility," Conley said. Those entities can use program and financial reports already being submitted to them, on-site monitoring, financial statement audits and agreed-upon procedures that target specific compliance requirements. Which monitoring tools an entity elects to use will probably depend on how much of its federal awards it is passing through to subrecipients, she said.
</P>

<P>
In the audit engagement and planning process, auditors also will need to estimate the amount of work they will have to do under the revised Circular A-133, particularly in respect to determining major programs through a risk-based approach, planning internal control testing and reporting on compliance.
</P>

<P>
"You as the auditor need to judge the amount, the nature, timing and extent of the work that you do in order to support an opinion on compliance with regard to major programs," Conley said, adding that a new compliance supplement should help auditors in making that assessment. The revised circular also requires auditors to plan to achieve a low assessed level of control risk. Auditors will need to decide how this impacts the rest of their audit work, since they cannot  "just test one or two items," she said.
</P>

<P>
Auditors had been particularly concerned about how the risk-based audit approach to determining major programs would affect their audit work, said Terry Ramsey, a technical and nonfederal audit staff member at the U.S. Department of Education's Office of Inspector General. In revising A-133, OMB tried to address those concerns in several ways, he said.
</P>

<P>
First, the circular caps the number of programs that must be audited under the risk-based approach. Second, the threshold at which a program must undergo a risk assessment is a sliding scale (instead of being fixed at $100,000, as was originally proposed) so auditors of states and other very large entities would not be as burdened. Third, auditors usually will not have to use a risk-based approach when auditing entities for the first time under the new requirements. Ramsey added that, in most cases, a risk assessment can be carried forward from year to year, so an auditor does not need to conduct an assessment every year on the same programs. 
</P>

<P>
The auditor is required to document risk assessments in its work papers, but as long as assessments are conducted in accordance with the circular, federal agencies cannot "second guess" the auditor's judgment, Ramsey said. If an agency wants to provide advice on a program's risk, the auditor can consider that in future audits but does not have to go back to previous audits or make changes to a current audit.
</P>






