<html> 
<head>
<title>Pension Simplification Measure Signed Into Law</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/sign/signhead.gif" alt="Guide to Assigning &amp; Loaning Benefit Plan Money"></center>
<P>
<h2>Pension Simplification Measure Signed Into Law</h2>

<h3><i>Changes Include QDRO Model Language, Prohibited Transaction Excise
Tax</i></h3>

<P>
On Aug. 20, 1996, President Clinton signed the Small Business Job Protection Act
of 1996 (P.L. 104-188), raising the minimum wage and enacting numerous tax
simplification rules--many of which affect qualified pension and profit sharing
plans. 
</P>

<P>
The new law will change the rules that apply to several compliance requirements
described in the <i>Guide:</i>
</P>

<UL>
<LI> model language for qualified domestic relations orders (QDROs);
<LI> the excise tax on prohibited transactions;
<LI> five-year foward averaging; and 
<LI> plan loan made to reemployed veterans.</UL>

<P>
In addition, the new welfare reform law signed by President Clinton last month
includes a provision affecting qualified medical child support orders (QMEDs).
</P>

<P>
Following is a description of each of these changes.
</P>

<h3>Model QDRO Language</h3>

<P>
Section 1457 of the Act requires the Secretary of the Treasury to develop "sample
language for inclusion in a form for a qualified domestic relations order" that
will meet the requirements for QDROs. 
</P>

<P>
This language must "focus attention" on the need to consider any lump sum payment
options as well as the joint and survivor annuity requirements applicable under
the plan in question. The statutorily mandated form language must be issued by
Jan. 1, 1997, and must be publicized by the Secretary of the Treasury through
"pension outreach efforts" undertaken by the Treasury Department.
</P>

<P>
The Secretary of the Treasury is also supposed to develop sample language for
inclusion in a form for spousal consent required under the tax code and ERISA.
The language must be written in a manner calculated to be understood by the
average participant. It must disclose whether a waiver to which a spouse consents
is irrevocable and whether a waiver may be revoked by a QDRO. 
</P>

<P>
This mandate for model QDRO language is unusual because the Secretary of the
Treasury does not have regulatory jurisdiction over the substantive QDRO
requirements. Instead, it is the Department of Labor that is supposed to develop
regulations in consultation with the Secretary of the Treasury. Therefore, it is
not clear what type of language will be developed by Jan. 1, 1997.
</P>

<h3>Prohibited Transaction Excise Tax</h3>

<P>
The new law increases the prohibited transaction excise tax (see &#182;422 of the
<i>Guide</i>) from 5 percent to 10 percent effective for prohibited transactions
occurring after Aug. 20, 1996, the date of enactment. 
</P>

<P>
It is not entirely clear how this new excise tax applies in the context of
continuing prohibited transactions, such as plan loans. The prohibited
transaction tax for plan loans "pyramids" so that new plan loans are deemed to be
made for each plan year until the loan is corrected (see &#182;422 of the
<i>Guide</i>). It is not clear whether the 10 percent excise tax is supposed to
apply to all "deemed" loans occurring after the date of enactment or whether the
new tax applies only to actual prohibited loans made after that date. 
</P>

<h3>Repeal of Forward Averaging </h3>

<P>
The new law repeals 5-year forward averaging for distributions made after Dec.
31, 1999. However, 10-year forward averaging, which was preserved through changes
made in the Tax Reform Act of 1986, continues to be available for eligible
individuals. (See &#182;515 of the <i>Guide</i> for a discussion of 5-year
forward averaging.)
</P>

<P>
The new law also repeals the excise tax for excess distributions, but only for
distributions in 1997, 1998 and 1999. The tax will apply to distributions made in
later years. (See &#182;514 of the <I>Guide</I> for a discussion of the excess
distribution tax.)
</P>

<h3>Special Plan Loan Rules for Reemployed Veterans</h3> 

<P>
The new law establishes special rules designed to help ease the transition back
into qualified plans for reemployed veterans. These rules provide for special
plan loan repayments by these reemployed veterans. 
</P>

<P>
Under the special loan rules, if a plan suspends the requirement for loan
repayments during an employee's period of qualifying military service, the
suspension period will not be taken into account for any of the plan loan or plan
qualification requirements. Presumably, this means that a plan could simply
disregard the period that the participant was in qualifying military service in
determining whether the plan loan rules are met. (See &#182;430, &#182;433 and
&#182;434 of the Guide for a discussion of the tax code's loan repayment rules.) 
</P>

<P>
For example, suppose a participant is called to active military duty at a time
when he has two years left on a five-year plan loan. Suppose the plan suspends
the required loan repayments for any period of such active duty. If he is in
service for one year, then on his return, the new provision would allow the plan
to disregard the one year of no repayments. Presumably, this means that upon the
participant's reemployment, the participant will be treated as if his loan still
had two years left during which it has to be repaid. 
</P>

<P>
This clarifying provision is effective retroactively to Dec. 12, 1994, the date
that the veteran's reemployment rights act was most recently amended. 
</P>

<P>
The legislative language for these rules is not as precise as it could be. For
example, it is not clear whether interest that accrues during the loan suspension
period must continue to accrue or whether it is ignored for purposes of the loan
suspension. Nevertheless, having some legislative language on which to rely will
be helpful to plans trying to develop a policy for dealing with outstanding plan
loans.
</P>

<h3>QMED Change in Welfare Reform Bill</h3>

<P>
Additionally, the new welfare reform legislation signed by President Clinton on
Aug. 22 clarifies the definition of a qualified medical child support order
(QMED). 
</P>

<P>
Before this new law, qualified orders under ERISA generally had to be issued by a
court (see &#182;625 of the <i>Guide</i>). This led to a good deal of confusion,
as many state administrative agencies had the authority to issue support orders
that were binding for purposes of state law, but not for the ERISA rules
governing QMEDs. According to the new rule, qualified orders will now include a
judgment, decree or order issued through a legally binding administrative process
under state law. This new change reflects a liberalization of the rules governing
qualified medical child support orders. 
</P>


<hr>
<center>
