<html> <title> NAIC Revises Model Coordination of Benefits Regulation </title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/cobs/cobshead.gif" alt="Coordination of Benefits
Handbook"></center>
<P>
<h2>NAIC Revises Model Coordination of Benefits Regulation<P></h2>
<body>

The National Association of Insurance Commissioners (NAIC) has rewritten its
model rule on coordination of health benefits to clarify its wording, as well as
to address a number of technical issues. Although the NAIC rule is not law, the
model is used by the various states as a framework upon which they may base their
own coordination rules. Many states adopt the model as drafted by the NAIC;
others choose to adopt it with specified modifications. (See &#182;900 of the
<i>Handbook</i>.) <P>

Some of the changes adopted by the NAIC in its 1996 revision are noted below.<P>

<UL>
<LI><i>Conflicting COB</i> -- Under the revised NAIC model, if two plans cannot
agree on the order of benefit payment within 30 days after the plans have
received all of the information needed to pay the claim, the plans must
immediately pay the claims in equal shares. After payment is made, the plans are
to resolve their relative liabilities. No plan, however, is required to pay more
than it would have to pay if it were primary.<P>

<LI><i>COB for Dependent Children</i> -- The prior version of the model
determined the order of benefit payment for dependent children in instances in
which a child's parents were divorced or separated. Under the revised rule, the
NAIC has redrafted the rules so that they address the order of benefit payment
for dependent children of unmarried parents. <P>

</UL> 
Essentially, the rule looks to the custodial relationship between the parent and
the child, rather than to the marital status of the parents. An additional
determining factor is court-assigned financial responsibility for health care
coverage of the dependent child; if the parent with financial responsibility
provides that coverage by virtue of a spouse's plan, then the spouse's plan would
be primary to the plan of a parent without financial responsibility.<P>

<UL>
<LI><i>Definition of Custodial Parent</i> -- Under the revised rules, a new
definition is added to explain that the custodial parent is the individual
awarded custody by a court decree. If there is no court decree, the parent with
whom the child resides for more than one-half the year is deemed to be the
custodial parent. <P>

<LI><i>Definition of Allowable Expense</i> -- Deductibles, coinsurance, and
copayments are now specifically included in the definition of the term "Allowable
Expense." The definition additionally clarifies that a primary plan's reduction
of benefits because of failure to utilize the services of a preferred provider is
an exclusion from the Allowable Expense. <P>
</UL>

The section providing examples of expenses that are not allowable has been
expanded. Expenses above the highest usual and customary fee (where both plans
use that method to compute benefits), or the highest negotiated fee (where both
plans negotiate fees) are not allowable. If one plan uses usual and customary
fees and the other plan negotiates fees, the Allowable Expense will not exceed
the primary plan's payment arrangement. <P>

The NAIC believes that COB should not be used to increase a provider payment in a
case where the provider has agreed to accept a negotiated rate, and encourages
plans to include provisions in their provider contracts to account for payments
under coordination of benefits.<P>

<UL>
<LI><i>Definition of "Closed Panel Plan"</i> -- The revised rule contains a new
definition to describe a plan that covers participants by providing services
through a panel of providers that contract with or are employed by the plan; this
definition applies to HMOs, PPOs, and EPOs among other types of plans. In
describing the use of the model COB rule, the NAIC notes that in most instances,
COB does not occur if a covered person is enrolled in two or more closed panel
plans and obtains services from a provider in one of the plans because the other
plan (whose providers were not used) has no liability.<P>

<LI><i>Order of Benefit Determination</i> -- In the event that none of the rules
governing the order of benefit determination applies to a particular situation, a
default provision has been added that would require the plans pay the allowable
expenses in equal shares.<P>

<LI><i>"Plain English" Description of COB</i> -- The NAIC has issued a new
appendix to the model regulation, entitled the <i>Consumer Explanatory
Booklet</i> which describes the operation of COB, including a section which
discuses the operation of a "benefits bank" or "benefits reserve" under COB (that
is, a reserve established in instances when a plan "saves" by properly paying
benefits on a secondary basis). <P>

</UL>
The revised 1996 NAIC model regulation is included with this issue's supplement
to the <i>Handbook</i>, to be inserted at Appendix I. <P>


</body> 

<foot>

<hr>
<center>
<pre>
