<html> 
<head>
<title>DOL Plan Asset Rules Will Affect Plan Loan Programs</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/sign/signhead.gif" alt="Guide to Assigning &amp; Loaning Benefit Plan Money"></center>

<h2>DOL Plan Asset Rules Will Affect Plan Loan Programs</h2>

The Department of Labor issued final regulations last month governing the timing
of when participant contributions are to be treated as "plan assets" that must be
placed in trust. These final regulations, which generally go into effect Feb. 3,
1997, require that participant contributions be treated as plan assets as soon as
they can reasonably be segregated from the employer's assets, but not later than
15 business days after the end of the month in which the participant
contributions are withheld or received by the employer.<P>

The final regulations were published at 61 <i>Fed. Reg</i>. 41220 (Aug. 7,
1996).<P>

<h3>Repayment via Payroll Deduction</h3><P>

The new regulations were aimed at plans, such as 401(k) plans, that allow for
participant contributions through pre-tax salary reduction agreements as well as
after-tax payroll deductions. However, they will also affect plan loan programs.
When participants obtain plan loans, they typically agree to payroll deductions
for the repayment of the loans. Sometimes, though, payroll deduction might not be
available. Plan loans must be made available to all participants who are
employees of the employer, even those for whom payroll deduction is not
available. (See &#182;413 of the <i>Guide.</i>) Further, a plan loan might be
repaid outside of payroll if the participant is on a leave of absence.<P>

In the context of the final plan asset regulations, plan loan repayments are
treated as all other participant contributions. Therefore, they must be
transmitted to a plan's trust no later than the 15th day of the month after the
month in which the funds are withheld or received by the employer. This is the
rule regardless of whether or not payroll deduction is available. Of course, if
there is payroll deduction available, as is true in many loan situations, the
plan asset regulation's timing rule should be met through the same system that
remits other participant contributions to the trust made via payroll
deduction.<P>

<h3>Other Repayment Options</h3><P>

A more difficult situation arises where a participant is repaying a loan outside
of the regular payroll deduction mechanism. In such a case, plan administrators
need to consider administrative designs to assure that participant repayments
will be transferred to the plan's trust as soon as possible after they are
received by the plan administrator.<P>

Some employers that commented on the proposed rule (issued last December) had
asked the DOL for a special provision to liberalize the time within which
non-payroll deduction loan repayments had to be transferred to a trust. However,
the DOL indicated in the preamble to the final regulation that such a rule was
beyond the scope of the regulation and that there was not enough evidence upon
which the DOL could base an exception.<P>

<h3>Review Administrative Procedures</h3><P>

In the preamble to the final regulations, the DOL indicated its view that "[a]n
employer's failure to transmit loan payments within a reasonable time after
withholding or receiving them could subject the employer to liability for
violations of the same provisions of ERISA and criminal law that are violated
when an employer is delinquent in forwarding participant contributions to plans."
Thus, plan loan administrators should review their procedures to assure
compliance with the plan asset regulations. In particular, administrators should
examine the following three questions. <P>

<i>Are plan loan repayments remitted to the plan's trust as soon as possible
after they are received by the plan administrator? </i><P>

If a plan administrator is holding on to plan loan repayments for an unduly long
period of time, the administrator may be subjecting itself to fiduciary
liability. This may require the fiduciary to make the plan participant whole for
any lost interest.<P>

<i>Is the plan administrator holding on to plan loan repayments when there is a
change in recordkeeper? </i><P>

If so, there could be a violation. The DOL does not recognize an exception from
the plan asset regulations merely because an employer is changing recordkeepers
or trustees. According to the DOL, "a change in recordkeepers or other service
providers to a plan should not affect the maximum allowable period before
participant contributions become plan assets."<P>

<i>Are plan loan repayments handled through a different payroll deduction
mechanism than participant pre-tax or after-tax contributions? </i><P>

If so, the systems should be coordinated to avoid any violations of the plan
asset requirements. <P>


<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/pen_ben/sign/sign.html"><img
src="/tpg/pen_ben/sign/smallsign.gif"  alt="Return to Guide to Assigning &amp; 
 Loaning Benefit Plan Money Home Page"></a> <a
href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER
] "></a>
</pre>
</center>
