<Title> OMB Plans to Combine Three Cost Principles</Title> <P>

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif> 
<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/fed_gts/gran/granhead.gif" alt="Federal Grants Management
 Handbook"></center></IMG><P>

<h2> OMB Plans to Combine Three Cost Principles</h2>

<body><i>Officials Discuss Changes to Circulars A-21 and A-122</i><P>

The Office of Management and Budget (OMB) recently announced long-term plans to
merge its cost principles so that one document would govern how costs are treated
for almost all types of federal funding recipients. OMB officials said they hope
to start working on a proposal, which would consolidate Circulars A-87, A-21 and
A-122, in late 1997. <P>

"One of our goals at OMB is to bring symmetry among the cost principle circulars,
and we're going to be looking very carefully over the next year at merging all
cost principle circulars so that non-profits, states and universities are treated
alike," said Norwood Jackson Jr., deputy controller in OMB's Office of Federal
Financial Management. Hospitals would remain subject to cost regulations of the
U.S. Department of Health and Human Services (HHS).<P>

OMB officials discussed recent and proposed revisions to the circulars in
speeches at the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants Not-for-Profit
Industry conference in Washington, D.C., in June. In particular, officials said
they hoped to issue revisions to Circular A-122, <i>Cost Principles for Non-Profit
Organizations</i>, by the end of the year, but indicated that certain proposed
changes may be postponed or dropped altogether.<P>

OMB proposed in October 1995 to cap at 26 percent the administrative cost rate of
non-profit organizations receiving $10 million in federal awards. Circular A-21,
<i>Cost Principles for Educational Institutions</i>, includes such a cap for all
colleges and universities. Applying the same cap to non-profits would be
consistent, but OMB has little data for selecting an administrative cost limit
appropriate for non-profit organizations, officials said.<P>

OMB is now rethinking the proposal. Many federal agencies and non-profit
organizations oppose the provision (see July 1996 <i>Current Developments</i>, Page 1).
"There are those who feel very strongly that we should cap the administrative
portion of indirect costs, much as we have with regard to colleges and
universities. But there are those who are arguing, and I think they may well be
right, that non-profits are not just like colleges and universities," Jackson
said.<P>

It is possible that advice to drop the cap will be heeded when revisions to the
circular are finalized, said OMB Policy Analyst Gil Tran, in remarks at the AICPA
conference. Tran recommends that OMB delete for now the proposal from the final
revisions, and instead ask the non-profit community for more input on the
proposed cap. "If they're serious about capping, I think it's probably worthwhile
for us to take a look at and collect some data, and [then] propose a cap," Tran
said.<P>

Delaying implementation of an administrative cost cap pending further study would
be agreeable to HHS, said Charles Gale, director of grants policy and oversight
at HHS, in a separate response. Gale and other federal agency representatives had
written OMB to oppose the 26 percent cap.<P>

Non-profit organizations have been slow to supply OMB with the data it needs to
develop a suitable limit on administrative costs. In particular, OMB is
requesting non-profits receiving more than $10 million in federal awards to try
to develop a university-style indirect cost model that would show what their
indirect cost rate would be. "No one gave us that, and what bothers me about it,
it puts me in a very difficult situation," Jackson said. "Because if your
indirect cost rate relative to administrative costs should legitimately be
greater than 26 percent, nobody has given me a case to support that statement.
And so that makes it very difficult for OMB to defend you if you in fact should
get a higher rate."<P>

In fact, National Institutes of Health (NIH) data appear to show that 26 percent
would be a relatively generous administrative rate for non-profit research
institutions, Tran said. For non-profits included in the statistics, their
general and administrative cost rate average was 19 percent. However, the NIH
survey produced somewhat flawed results, because non-profits do not have a
standard way of calculating their rate based on modified total direct costs, he
said. "Also, some non-profit organizations ... are single function, and therefore
they use the direct allocation method and direct charge their administrative
costs. That's why the administrative [portion] is so low."<P>

Tran told conference attendees that, if implemented, the 26 percent cap would
include all administrative costs, not just general and administrative. That means
that facilities-related costs, such as building use allowance, depreciation, and
operations and maintenance, would be allocated to administrative functions using
that portion of the facilities. Those additional costs "would be counted against
the 26 percent cap," Tran said.<P>

Under OMB's proposal, non-profits receiving more than $10 million in direct and
indirect costs also would be required to use a multiple allocation base method
patterned after that required of universities receiving more than $10 million in
direct costs. "It's going to make the development of the indirect cost rate
proposals or recovery methods a bit more difficult," but would "treat large
non-profits in a manner similar to colleges and universities," Jackson said.<P>

Non-profits wrote OMB to express concern about other proposed revisions to
Circular A-122. OMB proposed to not allow malpractice insurance as an indirect
cost, as is the case under Circular A-21. "Some organizations have come up to us
and said they're whole function is to provide health care, so malpractice
insurance is critical. In those cases, they have a point," Tran said. But those
non-profit organizations would be able to claim malpractice insurance as a <i>direct</i>
cost, he emphasized. "It will always be allowable as a direct cost to the special
projects that require human subjects."<P>

Tran acknowledged the unpopularity of another provision borrowed from A-21: a
proposal to not allow the cost of trustees' travel. He is recommending that OMB
abandon this proposal.<P>

Upon the urging of the U.S. Agency for International Development, OMB also is
re-examining its proposal to disallow excess severance and foreign nationals'
severance pay. "If we're going to employ a foreign national, is it reasonable for
us to disallow what is comparable salary for that country?" OMB is talking with
officials at USAID to find a way of dealing with the issue.<P>

Included in the A-122 proposal is a provision to raise the equipment
capitalization level to $5,000, which is parallel with the definition of
equipment in Circular A-110, <i>Uniform Administrative Requirements for Grants and
Agreements With Institutions of Higher Education, Hospitals and Other Non-Profit
Organizations</i>. OMB also told federal agencies a year ago that they could
implement a $5,000 threshold for university and non-profit recipients.<P>

While the higher threshold is not controversial, it may be difficult for some
organizations to implement, Tran said. First, a non-profit will have to use
whatever equipment capitalization level is specified in its financial statement
if that level is less than $5,000. Also, when converting from a lower (e.g.,
$500) to a higher (e.g., $2,500) threshold for capitalizing equipment, "there's a
bunch of equipment in there [between the two levels] that you have not fully
depreciated or recovered the full cost," Tran said.<P>

Organizations can use one of two methods to recover those costs. They can
continue to claim use allowance or depreciation on the equipment that now falls
under the capitalization threshold, but they must continue to keep records on
that equipment. "Basically you have to prove that this equipment is still usable
and is being used for the benefit of federal programs," Tran said, "so that's the
drawback."<P>

Alternatively, an organization can make arrangements with its federal cost
negotiator to amortize the amount to be written off over several years. "In most
cases, [cost negotiators] would not allow you to take the whole amount in one
year, because I don't think you can just retire all the equipment in one year,"
Tran said. <P>

<h3><i>Final Revisions to Circulars A-21, A-122</I></h3><P>

OMB officials discussed the inclusion of certain Cost Accounting Standards Board
(CASB) requirements in the May 8 revisions to Circular A-21. "We felt that the
standards were mom and apple pie' standards, and they should be extended to all
sponsored agreements to the university community, because in some cases they
didn't do anything that wasn't already accomplished by A-21," Jackson said. To
avoid any confusion over having two entities making cost accounting rules, OMB
arranged for the Office of Federal Financial Management, rather than CASB, to
answer universities' questions about the standards.<P>

Many colleges and universities had not wanted the cost accounting standards
applied to them. OMB officials acknowledged that Cost Accounting Standard 502,
<i>Consistency in Allocating Costs Incurred for the Same Purpose by Educational
Institutions</i>, was particularly controversial. For example, some universities were
concerned that the standard would prohibit them from directly charging clerical
salaries and wages, even when administrative staff work solely on federally
funded projects.<P>

"If you read the cost accounting standards verbatim, it seems to disallow it
[direct charging of administrative salaries and wages], but we have an
interpretation in A-21 that allows those types of costs ... for major projects,"
Tran said. "I don't anticipate any problem with that." OMB is working with HHS
and the Defense Contract Audit Agency to ensure that federal agencies and
auditors understand what kinds of allocation methods are allowable under the cost
accounting standard.<P>

Extending CASB's disclosure statement (Form DS-2) to colleges and universities
receiving $25 million or more in federal awards also was unpopular, as many
institutions thought the submission would be overly burdensome, Jackson said. "I
understand where people are coming from there, but we felt that if organizations
received over $25 million in federal funds, they should, as part of their normal
business behavior, be prepared to disclose their cost accounting practices to
federal cost negotiation agencies." <P>

The A-21 revision also raised the equipment capitalization level to the lesser of
$5,000 or the threshold used in the institution's financial statements. Tran
noted that colleges and universities could encounter the same kinds of problems
when converting the equipment threshold as would non-profits. In that case,
institutions would have the same two options for recovering costs: (1) continuing
to claim depreciation or use allowance, or (2) amortization.<P>

OMB also added a provision to Circular A-21 to require a fixed facilities and
administrative cost rate to be used for the life of the federal award. Tran
predicted that federal awarding agencies may choose to extend this requirement to
non-profit organizations in rate negotiations. "We've issued this guideline to
federal agencies to use a fixed rate throughout the project, period," he said, so
agencies have the option of applying it to non-profit awards. <P>

Tran also addressed some questions that had been raised about OMB's Oct. 6, 1995,
revision to Circular A-122. He emphasized that the Sept. 29, 1995, effective date
for allowing interest on facilities acquisitions applies to the date the building
becomes occupied. The needs justification requirement (which applies to
facilities costing more than $10 million and where the federal government's
reimbursement will be at least 40 percent of the facility's cost) must be met for
both the interest and any use allowance or depreciation on that building to be
allowable. Also, interest on equipment is allowable for new acquisitions only. A
grantee cannot terminate a lease on a piece of equipment and then buy the same
piece of equipment, Tran said. <P>
</body> <foot>

