<head>
<Title> Updated Compliance Supplement Taking Shape</Title>
</head> <P>

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif"> 
<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/fed_gts/sass/sasshead.gif" alt="Single Audit Information Service"></center><P>

<h2> Updated Compliance Supplement Taking Shape</h2>

<P>
<I><B>OMB Hopes to Release Initial Draft This Month</B></I>
</P>

<P>
A description of the audit process, definitions of types of compliance requirements and detailed guidance on internal controls will be among the new features of a combined and revised compliance supplement that the Office of Management and Budget (OMB) hopes to finalize in early 1997.
</P>

<P>
OMB officials and members of a federal task force revising the compliance supplement announced their plans in August at the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants (AICPA) National Governmental Accounting and Auditing Update Conference in Washington, D.C. OMB may send out early drafts for comment this month or early October to federal agencies, the AICPA, the National State Auditors Association and other interested groups. 
</P>

<P>
A new supplement is crucial to ensure that auditors can follow the requirements of the Single Audit Act Amendments of 1996 and revised OMB Circular A-133, <I>Audits of Institutions of Higher Education and Other Non-Profit Institutions</I>, both of which apply to audits of fiscal years beginning on or after July 1, 1996, officials told conference attendees. 
</P>

<P>
"Now the pressure is on us to get the compliance supplement out," said Dennis Duquette, deputy inspector general for management and policy at the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, and chair of OMB's inter-agency task force revising the document. "We'll probably be moving into a major review of the whole compliance supplement later in the year, the October or November time frame, if everything goes according to schedule," he added.
</P>

<P>
Because the supplement must be issued in time for audits under the revised A-133, drafts of the supplement will probably be issued piecemeal. The federal task force is aiming to complete work on the larger programs first, so different federal agencies' sections of the compliance supplement may be released at different times. A less formal feedback process is being used in place of a <I>Federal Register</I> notice because of the tight deadline and the fact that the document is not mandatory guidance, officials said. Also, OMB hopes to put the revised compliance supplement on its homepage on the Internet. By making the document available electronically, Duquette said, "we can literally update the information and add programs to it as we go along."
</P>

<P>
In 1990, OMB issued the <I>Compliance Supplement for Single Audits of State and Local Governments</I>, and followed suit in 1991 with the <I>Compliance Supplement for Audits of Institutions of Higher Learning and Other Non-Profit Institutions</I>. The programs' compliance requirements cited in both documents are out-of-date, said Terry Ramsey, technical and non-federal audit staff for the U.S. Department of Education and a member of the compliance supplement task force.
</P>

<P>
Auditors want the compliance supplement to be a safe harbor, and "we're working towards that," Ramsey said. The task force is hoping to revise the supplement annually, he said. However, auditors will have to remain alert to changes in compliance requirements not reflected in the supplement and adjust their audit procedures accordingly. 
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Broader Scope, Different Format</H3>
</P>

<P>
Rather than merely updating the requirements listed for federal programs, the task force is trying to address other problems with the current compliance supplements. For example, the existing documents are not kept up-to-date and standard audit procedures for compliance requirements are inconsistent, Ramsey told participants at AICPA's conference. 
</P>

<P>
"You'll be testing the same thing, and one time it will tell you to do 'A' and another time it will tell you to do 'B,'" making it hard to use those standard audit procedures for audits of programs not included in the compliance supplement, Ramsey said. He listed other perceived weaknesses with the existing documents that OMB hopes to fix: the types of program-specific compliance requirements -- such as allowable services and eligibility -- are not defined or explained; the special tests and provisions listed for a program may include requirements that are also listed in the general requirements section of the supplements; and the documents give no guidance on internal control testing.
</P>

<P>
The new compliance supplement will have a different format from OMB's two existing supplements. Ramsey said the new compliance supplement will likely include:
</P>

<UL>
<P>
	<LI>an introduction that gives an overview of the audit process;
</P>
<P>
	<LI>a matrix listing all the federal programs included in the compliance supplement and indicating what types of compliance requirements apply to each program; 
</P>	
<P>
	<LI>a discussion of common requirements;
</P>
<P>
	<LI>a discussion of federal programs and their specific requirements;
</P>
<P>
	<LI>a discussion of generic audit procedures that can be followed for each type of compliance requirement (e.g., testing compliance with a matching requirement);
</P>
<P>
	<LI>a discussion of internal controls over compliance; and
</P>
<P>
	<LI>a separate supplement for housing authorities.
</P>
</UL>
<P>
The introduction will give auditors guidance on the single audit process, highlighting recent changes. "One thing auditors are going to have to start looking for now is to see if any compliance requirements have been waived," Ramsey said. Since waivers are permitted under many federal programs, the first step for the auditor will be to determine whether any waivers have been granted to a federal award recipient. "The auditors are going to have to use some judgment on asking for some documentation to support the waiver," he said.
</P>

<P>
The current general requirements section will be renamed the "common" compliance requirements, Ramsey said. Under the revised Circular A-133, the auditor will have to give an opinion on a recipient's compliance with both common and specific requirements (in contrast to the auditor reporting on the general requirements and rendering an opinion only on the specific requirements). The federal task force is rewriting the section to ensure it's compatible with the revised circular. "We'll only put things in there auditors can give an opinion on," he said. For example, Drug-Free Workplace Act requirements will not be included. Each common requirement will be followed by a succinct audit objective -- "to help guide the auditor in what their work is supposed to be focused on" -- and then suggested audit procedures, Ramsey said. 
</P>

<P>
The specific requirements section will give the auditor program-specific information (program objectives, procedures and compliance requirements). As with the existing supplements, program requirements will be grouped into categories: types of services allowed; eligibility; matching, level-of-effort and/or earmarking; special reporting; and special tests and provisions. However, the new supplement will not include suggested audit procedures for each program, Ramsey said. Instead, audit procedures will be based on each category of requirements -- termed "types of compliance requirements."
</P>

<P>
To develop an audit procedure for a certain type of requirement, auditors would refer to a section in the compliance supplement containing generic audit procedures, Ramsey said. This section would define, give an audit objective and suggest audit procedures for testing compliance with each type of requirement. The discussion for a particular type of requirement, such as eligibility, would be generic and not in reference to any particular program. 
</P>

<P>
By grouping program requirements into "types," the compliance supplement will be consistent with the revised Circular A-133, Ramsey said. Under the new circular, "when you're reporting audit findings, your audit finding will be material for a type of compliance requirement or the audit objective in the compliance supplement," he said. Therefore, the types of requirements identified in an audit report will match the types of requirements listed in the compliance supplement. Categorizing requirements into generic "types" may make it easier for auditors to use the document as a guide for auditing programs not included in it, he added. The new compliance supplement is expected to cover about 150 programs, so it will not contain many of the smaller federal programs. 
</P>

<P>
The exception to using generic audit procedures will be for any special tests and provisions of a program, Ramsey said. If a program has statutory or regulatory requirements that do not easily fit into a standard type of requirement (allowable services; eligibility; matching, level-of-effort and earmarking; and special reporting), the audit objective and suggested audit procedures will tailored to those requirements. 
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT>New Audit Tools to Be Included</H3>
</P>

<P>
The matrix concept is aimed at giving auditors an at-a-glance summary of which types of compliance requirements apply to each program, Ramsey said. For example, in the matrix, an auditor would be able to see that a particular program has rules on allowable activities but no matching requirements. The auditor would also be able to assess whether any general requirements do not apply to a particular program.
</P>

<P>
A new section on internal controls will be helpful for auditors who are testing controls over major programs and provide illustrations for federal award recipients about what kinds of controls they should have in place, Ramsey said.
</P>

<P>
To get up-to-date information on the status of the compliance supplement, go to Thompson Publishing Group's Page on the subject: "<A HREF="/tpg/fed_gts/sass/sassnews.html">Status of OMB Policies</A>."
</P>

<HR>

<P>
<H4 ALIGN=LEFT>What Are 'Generic Audit Procedures'?</H4>
</P>

<P>
<FONT SIZE="2">The federal task force working on the new compliance supplement envisions a process where auditors will use generic audit procedures for each type of compliance requirement to test for a recipient's compliance with specific program requirements. Participants at AICPA's conference were given examples of what this generic approach might look like. The example of one type of compliance requirement (eligibility) that follows is only illustrative and is not official guidance from OMB.
</P>

<UL>
<P>
	<LI><I>Definition of Eligibility</I>: This type of compliance includes requirements that the award be limited to certain individuals, groups of individuals or subrecipients.
</P>

<P>
	<LI><I>Audit Objective</I>: To determine whether (a) the individuals or groups of individuals who received benefits from the federal program were eligible to receive the benefits, (b) the subawards were made only to eligible subrecipients, and (c) the amounts provided to eligibles were calculated correctly.
</P>	

<P>
	<LI><I>Generic Audit Procedures for Testing Eligibility of Individuals</I>: Select a representative sample of transactions and perform tests to determine whether the eligibility compliance requirements have been met for specific transactions. This testing should address whether the individual receiving benefits was eligible and that the amount paid to the individual was correctly calculated. The auditor should be alert to whether any benefits were for individuals or groups of individuals which are specifically classified in the compliance requirements as ineligible.</P>
</UL>


<P>
Separate procedures would be suggested for testing eligibility for areas of service delivery and eligibility for subrecipients.
</P></FONT>





<hr> <center> <pre> 
<a href="/tpg/fed_gts/sass/sass.html"><img src="/tpg/fed_gts/sass/smallsass.gif" alt="Return to Single Audit Information Service Home Page"></a> <a href="/tpg/prices/grantprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ] "></a> </pre> </center> <hr> <center><h6>&#169; 1996 Thompson Publishing Group / <a href="mailto:webmaster@thompson.com">webmaster@thompson.com</a></h6></center>

</body>
