<html>

<Title> OMB Issues Final Revisions to Circular A-133</Title> <P>

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif> 
<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/fed_gts/gran/granhead.gif" alt="Federal Grants Management
Handbook"></center></IMG><P>

<h2> OMB Issues Final Revisions to Circular A-133</h2>

<body>

<i>Many Changes Parallel Single Audit Legislation </i><P>

The Office of Management and Budget (OMB) issued on April 30 a revised Circular
A-133, <i>Audits of Institutions of Higher Education and Other Non-Profit
Institutions</i>. The changes raise the audit threshold to $300,000, establish a
risk-based approach to determining which programs to audit, and expand the
responsibilities and requirements of grantees undergoing audits. In addition, the
revisions to Circular A-133 affect what has to be included in the audit report
and when the report must be submitted. Some grantees also will see a change in
who they can select to perform their audits and what responsibilities they have
over subrecipients.<P>

The new A-133 applies to non-profit entities expending (rather than receiving)
$300,000 or more of federal awards in a fiscal year. Non-U.S. based recipients
and subrecipients are excluded from the scope of the circular. The circular still
focuses its audit coverage on "major programs," but now requires auditors to
consider the "risk" of a program.<P>

Proposed restrictions on selecting auditors who have prepared an entity's cost
allocation plan or indirect cost proposal were modified in the final revision so
they affect only relatively large organizations. Other ideas, such as allowing
triennial audits for low-risk auditees and requiring management letters to be
included in the audit report, were not adopted.<P>

OMB shortened the deadline for submitting audit reports from 13 months to nine.
The circular now makes it easier for organizations to be eligible to have
program-specific audits by allowing a group of similar programs to be treated as
a single program. Most provisions of the new A-133 are effective for fiscal years
ending on or after June 30, 1997.<P>

The revised circular in many ways parallels proposed legislation to amend the
Single Audit Act. "Provisions were made to easily adapt Circular A-133 to include
state and local governments if the Single Audit Act is amended," OMB said in the
preamble to the revision.<P>

<h3>Determining Major Programs, Audit Coverage</h3><P>

To determine major programs, auditors will follow a series of steps using both
dollar thresholds and risk-based criteria. "Type A" programs will be those
exceeding:<P>

<UL>
<LI>$300,000 or 3 percent of federal expenditures when all federal expenditures
total $100 million or less;<P>

<LI>$3 million or .3 percent of federal expenditures when all such expenditures
are more than $100 million but are less than or equal to $10 billion; or<P>

<LI>$30 million or .15 percent of federal expenditures when all such
expenditures are greater than $10 billion. </UL><P>

Programs under these dollar thresholds will be called "Type B" programs. Type A
programs that are deemed to be low-risk will not have to be audited unless needed
to ensure that 50 percent of the entity's total federal expenditures are covered
by the audit. A program could qualify as low risk if it has been audited as a
major program at least once during the past two audit periods under the new
circular and had no findings in the most recent audit period. However, OMB gives
auditors discretion in deciding whether findings from questioned costs, fraud and
follow-up from prior audit findings "do not preclude the Type A program from
being low-risk." <P>

Type B programs will have to be audited only if they are identified as high-risk,
or if necessary to comply with the 50 percent rule. Auditors are expected to use
"professional judgment" in assessing a program's or entity's risk. OMB lists
numerous factors that can affect risk and notes that some factors should weigh
more heavily than others. Potential indications of a high risk program include
findings from previous audits, weak internal controls, weak systems for
monitoring subrecipients, new or recently modified computer systems, grantor
agencies' discovery of problems, new programs or new program rules, or the entity
is a new federal grantee. <P>

Two general rules apply in deciding how many programs must be audited. No more
high-risk Type B programs must be audited than the number of low-risk Type A
programs identified by the auditor. In other words, the number of programs
audited under a risk-based approach may be no more than the number of programs
audited under the dollar thresholds. However, the 50 percent rule overrides this
cap on the number of programs audited. The required coverage of federal
expenditures must be met regardless of the number of high-risk Type B or low-risk
Type A programs identified. If the auditee as a whole is assessed as low-risk,
then the mandatory coverage is lowered to 25 percent.<P>

 An auditee may be deemed as low-risk, and be eligible for 25 percent coverage of
federal expenditures, if they meet other criteria, such as receiving unqualified
opinions on their financial statements and schedule of expenditures of federal
awards, and having no material weaknesses in internal controls.<P>

 In addition, a federal agency or pass-through grantee can request that a program
be audited as major and pay the full incremental cost of covering that program.
Auditors can defer implementing a risk-based approach for first-year audits
(including the first year an entity is audited under the revised circular).<P>

<h3>Grantee Responsibilities Under Circular A-133</h3><P>

Grantees, whether they are primary recipients (called pass-through entities in
the circular) or subrecipients, will have new responsibilities in the audit
process. While many requirements articulated by OMB in the revised circular are
already standard practice, such as preparing financial statements and schedules
of federal awards, the circular gives new details on the type of information that
must be included.<P>

For example, the schedule of expenditures of federal awards should "include notes
that describe the significant accounting policies used in preparing the schedule"
and state the dollar threshold used in identifying Type A and Type B programs.
Pass-through entities are asked to identify, to the extent practical, in their
schedule how much of their federal awards is passed through to subrecipients from
each program that is audited as major.<P>

In addition, auditees now must prepare a certification about the audit results
and a summary schedule of prior audit findings. The audited entity's management
must certify certain basic information about the audit, including whether there
are any findings and the amount of questioned costs under each federal program.
Subrecipients must submit their certification not only to the Federal Audit
Clearinghouse, but also to pass-through entities. However, the full report must
be sent to pass-throughs only when findings or prior audit findings relate to
federal awards provided by the pass-through entity. Management letters do not
have to be included in the reporting package, OMB decided, but must be available
to federal agencies or pass-through entities if requested.<P>

The revised circular spells out OMB's expectations for pass-through entities'
monitoring of subrecipients, but does not add as many new requirements as had
been proposed. The March 1995 proposal would have allowed federal agencies to
require pass-through entities to arrange for audits of subrecipients receiving
less than $300,000 in federal awards. After many commenters objected, OMB elected
not to include this idea in the revision. However, OMB stated in the preamble
that "both the pass-through entity and the pass-through entity's auditors have
responsibilities for these funds even when an audit of the subrecipient is not
required."<P>

Primary recipients may need to do additional monitoring, and their auditors "will
need to consider obtaining compliance assurances by reviewing the pass-through
entity's records and monitoring procedures, performing additional procedures to
determine compliance, such as testing the subrecipient's records, or a
combination of procedures," OMB said. The pass-through entity's auditor also must
determine whether that entity's system for monitoring subrecipients is adequate,
and whether the pass-through entity's records should be adjusted due to
subrecipient noncompliance, OMB continued.<P>

<h3>Restrictions on Auditor Selection</h3><P>

In response to federal agency concerns about auditors' independence, OMB had
considered restricting auditors (and their accounting firms) who prepare cost
allocation plans, indirect cost proposals or disclosure statements required by
Circular A-21 for a entity from performing an A-133 audit for the same entity. As
proposed, the restriction would have applied when indirect costs charged were
greater than 5 percent of any Type A program's expenditures or greater than 5
percent of expenditures for all federal programs.<P>

Since many grantees and auditors opposed this proposal, the final version aims to
restrict auditor selection only for the largest grantees. Instead of setting the
threshold as a percentage of expenditures, grantees will have to comply with the
provision if they recovered more than $1 million in indirect costs during the
year prior to the year to be audited. An OMB official said that around 200
colleges and universities and 150 non-profit organizations would be affected by
the rule.<P>

When a grantee has a multi-year indirect cost proposal or cost allocation plan,
the restriction applies to the base year used in the preparation of those
documents and any years after in which the resulting indirect cost agreement or
allocation plan is used to recover costs. "We want the auditor to be independent
of the base year and the years where that [agreement] is used," the official
said.<P>

The restriction will not apply to auditors who prepare a university's disclosure
statements required under Circular A-21 (see story, page 1). The provision
applies to fiscal years ending on or after June 30, 1999. OMB said the effective
date is delayed two years to give auditees time to switch auditors if needed.<P>

<h3>Other Changes in Audit Requirements</h3><P>

The revised Circular A-133 offers more flexibility to permit program-specific
audits. A program-specific audit is allowed when a grantee spends federal awards
under only one program and the recipient is not otherwise required to have a
financial statement audit. However, "federal program" is redefined so that all
federal awards made from one agency for the same purpose should be considered one
program. Likewise, states can combine funding for similar federal programs in
making awards to subrecipients. Therefore, an entity expending funds under
programs with the same compliance requirements may be eligible to have a
program-specific audit.<P>

In addition, institutions receiving research and development awards can have a
program-specific audit if those awards are from the same federal agency (and
pass-through entity, if applicable) and a program-specific audit is approved in
advance.<P>

Although OMB had floated the idea of triennial audits for low-risk auditees, that
idea was not adopted. Audits must be performed annually for all recipients.
However, federal or pass-through agencies can allow recipients having
program-specific audits to undergo audits every two years, with the audit
covering both years.<P>

OMB added more specific guidance for auditors on reporting audit findings and set
a $10,000 threshold for reporting questioned costs. However, OMB dropped a
proposal to require a management assertion and auditor attestation for internal
control or compliance.<P>

The deadline for submitting audit reports was shortened from 13 months to nine
months after the end of the period audited. Even if the reports are completed
before then, they should be submitted to the clearinghouse 30 days after the
auditor issues the report to the grantee. Auditees must make copies of the report
available for public inspection, unless any law or regulation prohibits it. 
<P>
</body> <foot>

