<html><head> <Title>New Circular A-133 Marks Broad Changes to Audit
Requirements</Title></head> <P> <body> <body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif>
<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/fed_gts/sass/sasshead.gif" alt="Single Audit Information
Service"></center></IMG><P>

<h2>New Circular A-133 Marks Broad Changes to Audit Requirements</h2> The Office
of Management and Budget (OMB) has revised its Circular A-133, <i>Audits of
Institutions of Higher Education and Other Non-Profit Institutions</i>. The new
circular emphasizes targeting audit resources to areas of greater risk, getting
better information from the audit process and freeing up some federal funds to be
used for program purposes. <P>

To accomplish this, OMB made numerous changes to the circular. The audit
threshold was raised to $300,000, a risk-based approach was established for
determining which programs to audit, and more specific guidance was added to
permit program-specific audits. In addition, the revisions to Circular A-133
address what elements to include in the audit report and when the report must be
submitted. <P>

The new A-133 applies to non-profit entities expending (rather than receiving)
$300,000 or more of federal awards in a fiscal year. Non-U.S. based recipients
and subrecipients are excluded from the scope of the circular. The circular still
focuses its audit coverage on "major programs," but now requires auditors to
consider the "risk" of a program.<P>

Proposed restrictions on selecting auditors who have prepared an entity's cost
allocation plan or indirect cost proposal were modified in the final revision so
they affect only relatively large organizations. Other ideas, such as allowing
triennial audits for low-risk auditees and requiring management letters to be
included in the audit report, were not adopted. OMB shortened the deadline for
submitting audit reports from 13 months to nine. Most provisions of the new A-133
are effective for fiscal years ending on or after June 30, 1997.<P>

The revised circular in many ways parallels proposed legislation to amend the
Single Audit Act. "Provisions were made to easily adapt Circular A-133 to include
state and local governments if the Single Audit Act is amended," OMB said in the
preamble to the revision. Once those amendments are enacted, OMB will rescind
Circular A-128 and revise certain A-133 terminology to reflect that it will apply
to all non-federal entities spending federal funds, said Norwood Jackson Jr.,
deputy controller of OMB's Office of Federal Financial Management, speaking at
the 11th Biennial Forum for Governmental Auditors held in Seattle last month.<P>

<h3>Determining Major Programs, Audit Coverage</h3><P>

To determine major programs, auditors will follow a series of steps using both
dollar thresholds and risk-based criteria (see chart below). "Type A" programs
will be those exceeding:<P>

<UL> <LI>$300,000 or 3 percent of federal expenditures when all federal
expenditures total $100 million or less;<P>

<LI>$3 million or .3 percent of federal expenditures when all such expenditures
are more than $100 million but are less than or equal to $10 billion; or<P>

<LI>$30 million or .15 percent of federal expenditures when all such expenditures
are greater than $10 billion.</UL><P>

Programs under these dollar thresholds will be called "Type B" programs. Type A
programs that are deemed to be low-risk will not have to be audited unless needed
to ensure that 50 percent of the entity's total federal expenditures are covered
by the audit. A program could qualify as low-risk if it has been audited as a
major program at least once during the past two audit periods under the new
circular and had no findings in the most recent audit period. However, OMB gives
auditors discretion in deciding whether findings from questioned costs, fraud and
follow-up from prior audit findings "do not preclude the Type A program from
being low-risk." <P>

Type B programs will only have to be audited if they are identified as high-risk,
or if necessary to comply with the 50 percent rule. Auditors are expected to use
"professional judgment" in assessing a program's or entity's risk. Circular A-133
lists numerous factors that can affect risk and notes that some factors should
weigh more heavily than others. Potential indications of a high-risk program
include findings from previous audits, weak internal controls, weak systems for
monitoring subrecipients, new or recently modified computer systems, grantor
agencies' discovery of problems, new programs or new program rules, or the entity
is a new federal grantee. <P>

Two general rules apply in deciding how many programs must be audited. No more
high-risk Type B programs must be audited than the number of low-risk Type A
programs identified by the auditor. In other words, the number of programs
audited under a risk-based approach may be no more than the number of programs
audited under the dollar thresholds. However, the 50 percent rule overrides this
cap on the number of programs audited. The required coverage of federal
expenditures must be met regardless of the number of high-risk Type B or low-risk
Type A programs identified. If the auditee as a whole is assessed as low-risk,
then the mandatory coverage is lowered to 25 percent.<P>

An auditee may be deemed as low-risk, and be eligible for 25 percent coverage of
federal expenditures, if they meet other criteria, such as receiving unqualified
opinions on their financial statements and schedule of expenditures of federal
awards, and having no material weaknesses in internal controls.<P>

In addition, a federal agency or pass-through grantee can request that a program
be audited as major and pay the full incremental cost of covering that program.
Auditors can defer implementing a risk-based approach the first year an entity is
audited under the revised circular. The one-year grace period also applies to the
first year an auditor audits a particular entity, but an auditee that changes
auditors frequently cannot use the deferment more than once every three years.<P>

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/fed_gts/sass/sassjune1a.gif" alt="This chart is entitled Deciding Which
Federal Programs Must Be Audited As Major Programs Under the Revised
A-133"></center></IMG><P>

<h3>Changes to Audit Procedures, Requirements</h3><P>

The new Circular A-133 impacts how much testing is required, how many
expenditures are covered, and how auditors must report questioned costs and
compliance issues. The reporting package must include:<P>

<UL> <LI>a certification by the auditee that includes summary information on the
types of reports and opinions issued, the auditee's federal programs and
expenditures amounts, and yes or no statements on the kinds of findings and
questioned costs reported;<P>

<LI>financial statements and a schedule of expenditures of federal awards
(re-termed from schedule of federal awards);<P>

<LI>a summary schedule of prior audit findings;<P>

<LI>auditor's reports that include an opinion on financial statements and
schedule of expenditures of federal awards, a report on internal controls, a
report on compliance, and a schedule of findings and questioned costs that
includes a summary of the auditor's results; and<P>

<LI>a corrective action plan.</UL><P>

As is currently the case, the audit report must be sent to the Federal Audit
Clearinghouse. The report must be sent to federal agencies or pass-through
entities only when findings or prior audit findings relate to federal awards
provided by that agency or entity. Management letters do not have to be included
in the reporting package, but must be available to federal agencies or
pass-through entities if requested.<P>

The reporting package includes some new elements, such as the audit report
summary and auditee certification. Additionally, the schedule of expenditures of
federal awards should "include notes that describe the significant accounting
policies used in preparing the schedule" and state the dollar threshold used in
identifying Type A and Type B programs.<P>

In addition, the report on compliance must include an opinion on whether the
auditee complied with "laws, regulations and the provisions of contracts or grant
agreements which could have a direct and material effect on each major program."
Audit guidance currently in effect requires only a positive or negative assurance
on compliance. Jackson said that auditors will not have to give an opinion on
compliance with drug-free workplace and other general requirements that do not
have a direct and material effect on major programs. The new requirement instead
will focus auditors' testing on "the stuff that if you don't comply with it, it's
serious business ... whether it be eligibility or allowability of costs," he
said.<P>

As noted above, the 50 percent rule is codified in the new circular. Whereas
AICPA and OMB guidance had applied the rule to testing controls over federal
financial assistance programs, the new A-133 extends the required 50 percent
coverage to everything in the audit, including compliance testing. Auditors are
required to "audit as major programs federal programs with expenditures that, in
the aggregate, encompass at least 50 percent of total federal expenditures," the
circular states. <P>

The circular requires auditors to plan the testing of internal controls over
major programs to achieve a low assessed level of control risk. "All CPA
commenters and over half of the state auditor commenters opposed the proposed
requirement," saying that "it increases the amount of audit work, limits [the]
auditors' judgment and is arbitrary," according to OMB. In its preamble, OMB
emphasized that the new requirement only applies to the planning of testing; if
an auditor finds control exceptions, he or she does not have to continue testing
until a low level of risk is achieved. Instead, inadequate internal controls
should be reported as a reportable condition or material weakness, and the
related control risk should be assessed at the maximum level.<P>

The purpose of the requirement is to ensure that more than just one or two
transactions are tested, Jackson told conference attendees. Under the Single
Audit Act, "it was never intended to have such a <i>de minimis</i> level of
testing involved in meeting the requirements of the law," he said.<P>

OMB added more specific guidance for auditors on reporting audit findings and set
a $10,000 threshold for reporting questioned costs. "This business of every
little thing having to be reported is going down the tubes," Jackson said.
Auditors also are required to report known questioned costs that are $10,000 or
less when likely questioned costs are projected to be greater than $10,000 for a
type of compliance requirement for a major program. The circular tells auditors
to provide information to help report readers judge "the prevalence and
consequences of the questioned costs."<P>

<h3>Program-Specific Audits</h3><P>

The revised A-133 offers more flexibility to permit program-specific audits. A
program-specific audit is allowed when a grantee spends federal awards under only
one program and the recipient is not otherwise required to have a financial
statement audit. However, "federal program" is redefined so that all federal
awards made from one agency for the same purpose should be considered one
program. Likewise, states can combine funding for similar federal programs in
making awards to subrecipients. Therefore, an entity expending funds under
programs with the same compliance requirements may be eligible to have a
program-specific audit.<P>

In addition, institutions receiving research and development awards can have a
program-specific audit if those awards are from the same federal agency (and
pass-through entity, if applicable) and a program-specific audit is approved in
advance. <P>

<h3>Audits of Subrecipients</h3><P>

The revised circular spells out OMB's expectations for pass-through entities'
monitoring of subrecipients. OMB stated in the preamble that "both the
pass-through entity and the pass-through entity's auditors have responsibilities
for these funds even when an audit of the subrecipient is not required." Primary
recipients may need to do additional monitoring, and their auditors "will need to
consider obtaining compliance assurances by reviewing the pass-through entity's
records and monitoring procedures, performing additional procedures to determine
compliance, such as testing the subrecipient's records, or a combination of
procedures," OMB said. <P>

All entities spending less than $300,000 in federal funds are exempt from A-133's
audit requirements. At the audit conference, Jackson emphasized that any
pass-through agency imposing a single audit on subrecipients under that threshold
would not have those audit costs reimbursed by the federal government unless a
single audit was required by state law. "You can't expect to bill the federal
government for something the federal government didn't impose," he said.<P>

Instead, OMB hopes that pass-through entities will use a "surgical audit
approach" to monitoring small grantees. "The way you do that, instead of having a
full-blown single audit that might cost you $10,000 or $15,000, is to arrange
[with a CPA firm or state auditor] for agreed-upon procedures to be performed ...
to ensure that certain critical compliance requirements are being adhered to," he
said. <P>

Under agreed-upon procedures, the grantor agency can still disallow costs and
collect those funds from the grantee, Jackson said. And because the arrangement
would constitute program monitoring, the costs of having agreed-upon procedures
performed would be reimbursable under federal grants and contracts, he added.
Neither Circular A-133 nor the Single Audit Act amendments proposed specify
agreed-upon procedures as a required monitoring tool. <P>

<h3>Restrictions on Auditor Selection</h3><P>

In response to federal agency concerns about auditors' independence, OMB Circular
A-133 now restricts auditors (and their accounting firms) who prepare cost
allocation plans, indirect cost proposals or disclosure statements required by
Circular A-21 for an entity from performing an A-133 audit for the same entity.
Since many grantees and auditors opposed the proposal, the final version aims to
restrict auditor selection only for the largest grantees.<P>

Instead of setting the threshold as a percentage of expenditures, as was
proposed, grantees have to comply with the provision if they recovered more than
$1 million in indirect costs during the year prior to the year to be audited. An
OMB official said about 200 colleges and universities and 150 non-profits would
be affected by the rule. <P>

When a grantee has a multi-year indirect cost proposal or cost allocation plan,
the restriction applies to the base year used in the preparation of those
documents and any years after in which the resulting indirect cost agreement or
allocation plan is used to recover costs. "We want the auditor to be independent
of the base year and the years where that [agreement] is used," the official
said.<P>

The restriction will not apply to auditors who prepare a university's disclosure
statements required under Circular A-21 (see story, page 1). The provision
applies to fiscal years ending on or after June 30, 1999. OMB said the effective
date is delayed two years to give auditees time to switch auditors if needed.<P>

<h3>Other Provisions of A-133</h3><P>

The deadline for submitting audit reports was shortened from 13 months to nine
months after the end of the period audited. Even if the reports are completed
before then, they should be submitted to the clearinghouse 30 days after the
auditor issues the report to the grantee. The deadline can be extended if agreed
to in advance by the federal cognizant or oversight agency for audit.<P>

Although OMB had floated the idea of triennial audits for low-risk auditees, that
idea was not adopted. Audits must be performed annually for all recipients.
However, federal or pass-through agencies can allow recipients having
program-specific audits to undergo audits every two years, with the audit
covering both years. OMB also had suggested requiring a management assertion and
auditor attestation for internal controls or compliance. The proposal was
dropped, as the majority of commenters felt "it would impose additional
requirements on entity management and increase audit costs," OMB said. The
revised circular is included in this month's supplement and can be electronically
accessed at <b>http://www.whitehouse.gov/WH/EOP/omb</b>.<P>

