<html>
<head>
<title>CONUS Per Diem Rates Increase for 1997</title>
</head>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/pen_ben/disc/dischead.gif" alt="Employer's Handbook:
 Complying with IRS Employee Benefits Rules"></center>

<h2> CONUS Per Diem Rates Increase for 1997</h2>
<h2><i>Both Standard Lodging and M&amp;IE Rates Revised Upward</h2></i><P>
The General Services Administration (GSA) has significantly increased the federal
per diem rates for travel in the continental United States (CONUS).<P>
For the first time since 1993, the four CONUS meal and incidental expense
(M&amp;IE) rates have increased across the board -- from $26, $30, $32 and $38 in
1996, to $30, $32, $38 and $42 in 1997.<P>
The GSA also has increased the standard CONUS lodging rate, from $40 in 1996, to
$50 in 1997.<P>
The CONUS per diem rates became effective for employee travel as of Jan. 1, 1997.
The complete rate schedule appeared in the Nov. 21, 1996, Federal Register.<P>
<h3>Tax Treatment of Employee Travel Allowances</h3><P>
The federal per diem rates serve as reference points for determining the maximum
excludable per diem allowance an employer may provide to an employee or
independent contractor traveling to a particular location. An employer is not
required to report as compensation any per diem allowance equal to or less than
the federal per diem rate set for that location. An employer, however, must
report as compensation the portion of any per diem allowance exceeding the
proscribed federal rate. The employer also must withhold payroll taxes, including
income, FICA and FUTA taxes, on any excess allowances.<P>
Although the higher 1997 CONUS rates increase the per diem amounts employees may
exclude from income, employers' corresponding deductions for business travel
expenses will not increase as substantially. Code Section 274(n) disallows
employers from deducting 50 percent of the M&amp;IE portion of any per diem
allowance. <P>
Consequently, the payroll tax savings that employers will realize from the
increased rates sometimes will not completely offset the associated reduction to
the corporate income tax deduction stemming from the 50-percent disallowance.<P>
Some employers have challenged the disallowance of the incidental expense portion
of the M&amp;IE rate, especially when such incidental expenses, as defined under
the Federal Travel Regulations, do not encompass meal or entertainment expenses
-- two types of expenses Section 274(n) explicitly governs. The IRS, however, has
not yet modified the disallowance's application to CONUS per diem allowances.<P>
<h3>Reading the Rates</h3><P>
The 1997 CONUS per diem rate schedule lists 500 locations in the continental
United States, down from 667 locations in 1996. For each location, the rate
schedule provides one of the four M&amp;IE rates ($30, $32, $38 or $42), and a
lodging rate ranging from $50 to $189. <P>
The 1997 M&amp;IE rates for many previously listed locations shifted upward due
to the across-the-board $4 M&amp;IE rate increase and $10 lodging rate increase,
as well as to annual cost fluctuations. This year's rate schedule breaks down
into the following groups:<P>
<UL>
<LI>There are now 37 locations assigned the $42 M&amp;IE rate. Because this rate
did not exist before this year, no locations were assigned the $42 rate in
1996.<P>
<LI>There are now 79 locations assigned the $38 M&amp;IE rate, up from the 52
locations in 1996.<P>
<LI>There are now 154 locations assigned the $34 M&amp;IE rate, down from 238
locations in 1996.<P>
<LI>There are now 230 locations assigned the $30 M&amp;IE rate, down from 275
locations in 1996.<P>
<LI>Because the GSA eliminated the $26 rate, no locations were assigned this rate
for 1997.<P></UL>
Like the 230 locations assigned the $30 rate for 1997, all locations not listed
on the CONUS schedule have a $30 M&amp;IE rate; the locations actually specified
in the $30 category appear in the schedule because their lodging rates exceed the
$50 minimum rate.<P>
For the first time, the rate schedule includes New Orleans among the highest-rate
cities; it still does not include Philadelphia, however, which now is assigned
the $38 rate, up from $34 in 1996. Both Dallas/Fort Worth and Miami, after
shifting into the highest rate category last year ($38), remain in the
highest-rate category for 1997 ($42).<P>
<h3>Varying Lodging Costs</h3><P>
The CONUS rate schedule also provides per diem rates combining the lodging and
M&amp;IE rates for all 500 locations. The GSA developed these "combined rates"
because of the significant variances in lodging costs around the country.<P>
All locations in the continental United States not listed in the CONUS per diem
rate schedule are assigned an $80 combined rate, reflecting a $50 lodging
allowance and a $30 M&amp;IE allowance.<P>
For 1997, the combined rates covering lodging and M&amp;IE expenses for all
listed locations range from $80 for many locations, to $195 for New York City
($42 for M&amp;IE expenses and $153 for lodging). In 1996, the combined rates
ranged from $67 to $180.<P>
For 1997, the combined rates for certain seasonal locations range from the same
low of $80 to $223. In 1996, the combined seasonal rates ranged from $67 to
$204.<P>
<h3>Seasonal Price Hikes</h3><P>
Since 1994, the CONUS rate schedule has included both in-season and off-season
rates for some locations. These different seasonal rates apply during
GSA-designated periods only, and generally follow locations' popularity with
vacationers. Only the lodging allowances and, in turn, the combined rates of the
seasonal rates fluctuate. The M&amp;IE rates for these locations, however, remain
constant throughout the year.<P>
For example, for Vail, Colo., the lodging rate is $181 from Nov. 1 through March
31, and $89 from April 1 through Oct. 31. Its M&amp;IE rate, however, is $42
during both periods. Vail is assigned the highest lodging rate in the continental
United States during its in-season period; Martha's Vineyard/Nantucket has the
second highest in-season lodging rate at $179.<P>
<h3>IRS High-Low Rates Not Yet Available</h3><P>
Each year, the IRS issues a schedule of high-low per diem rates that employers
may use instead of the CONUS per diem rates. The high-low rates can simplify
determining the combined per diem rates for CONUS locations, and in some cases,
allow employers to provide higher per diem allowances than allowed under the
CONUS schedule.<P>
The IRS, however, had not yet issued its high-low rates at the time this issue of
Current Developments went to print in late December.
<P>
</P>

</FONT>
<hr>
<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/pen_ben/disc/disc.html"><img src="/tpg/pen_ben/disc/smalldisc.gif"
alt="Return to Employer's Handbook: Complying with IRS Employee Benefits Rules
Home Page"></a> <a href="/tpg/prices/benefitprices.html"><img
src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ] "></a>
</pre>
</center>
