<Title> Revised Circular A-21 Includes Cost Accounting Standards</Title> <P>

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif> 
<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/fed_gts/gran/granhead.gif" alt="Federal Grants Management
Handbook"></center></IMG><P>

<h2> Revised Circular A-21 Includes Cost Accounting Standards</h2>

<body>
The Office of Management and Budget (OMB) has issued final revisions to Circular
A-21, <i>Cost Principles for Educational Institutions </i>, that apply certain cost
accounting standards to universities and modify requirements for
facilities-related costs. <P>

The revision, published in the May 8 <i>Federal Register </i>, implements most of the
provisions proposed by OMB in February 1995, but ideas floated for benchmarking
facilities and utilities costs were not included in the final circular. OMB plans
to issue a formal proposal for handling facilities-related costs in the coming
year.<P>

The most significant changes to the circular include: <P>
<UL>
<LI>Extending certain cost accounting standards (CAS) to educational
institutions and requiring institutions receiving more than $25 million in
federal awards to file a disclosure statement of their accounting practices;<P>

<LI>Requiring the same indirect cost rates (which the circular now calls
facilities and administrative cost rates) to be used throughout the life of a
sponsored agreement;<P>

<LI>Establishing the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) and the
Office of Naval Research (ONR) as the only two cost cognizant agencies;<P>

<LI>Prohibiting as of July 1, 1998, the use of special cost studies to allocate
utility, library and student services costs;<P>

<LI>Reversing the allowability of dependent tuition benefits;<P>

<LI>Adding requirements and restrictions for allowing interest costs;<P>

<LI>Revising how institutions change from a use allowance to depreciation
methodology; and<P>

<LI>Raising the equipment threshold to $5,000. </UL><P>

Most provisions took effect May 8. However, the effective date for applying the
new cost accounting standards and required disclosure varies. Also, the ban on
using special studies for cost allocation is delayed for two years.<P>

<h3>Applying Cost Accounting Standards to Grants</h3><P>

After nearly unanimous opposition by university commenters, OMB decided to apply
certain standards issued by the Cost Accounting Standards Board (CASB) to all
sponsored agreements with institutions of higher education. CASB already has
applied some standards to contracts with colleges and universities, but the
changes to A-21 extend these standards to all types of awards.<P>

The standards reiterate many principles -- such as consistency in accounting
practices and treatment of direct and indirect costs -- that are already
articulated in Circular A-21. However, the requirements give more detail,
including examples of applying the standards, than A-21 previously provided. The
circular applies the standards to universities' fiscal years beginning on or
after May 8, 1996. <P>

The four CAS being incorporated into Circular A-21 are:<P>

<UL>
<LI>CAS 9905.501 -- Consistency in estimating, accumulating and reporting costs
by educational institutions;<P>

<LI>CAS 9905.502 -- Consistency in allocating costs incurred for the same
purpose by educational institutions;<P>

<LI>CAS 9905.505 -- Accounting for unallowable costs -- educational
institutions; and<P>

<LI>CAS 9905.506 -- Cost accounting period -- educational institutions.</UL><P>

All colleges and universities will be subject to these CAS. Institutions
receiving $25 million or more in sponsored agreements must disclose on form DS-2
how they account for all costs charged to federal awards and identify unallowable
costs in cost proposals and billings. The form is 20 pages long, but further
explanation that is requested for several types of answers would make the
submission significantly longer. For example, OMB asks educational institutions
for descriptions of systems for identifying and accounting for unallowable costs,
organizational structures, post-retirement benefit plans and costs, and other
practices. When institutions use more than one accounting method to handle a
certain type of cost, additional information also must be supplied. <P>

OMB had proposed staggered deadlines for submitting the disclosure, with
universities that received fewer funds having more time. The revised circular,
however, imposes the same time frame for all institutions. For entities not
already covered by CASB's regulations for contracts with institutions (which were
issued Nov. 8, 1994, and took effect Jan. 9, 1995), the form must be submitted
six months after the end of an institution's fiscal year beginning on or after
May 8, 1996. Cognizant agencies can grant extensions.<P>

College and university commenters felt that the additional standards were
duplicative of existing requirements in Circular A-21, and that the disclosure
statement would increase administrative burdens of universities that were already
subject to a cap in federal reimbursements for administrative costs. OMB said in
the preamble to the circular that "the four CAS are being incorporated since they
provide more explicit provisions and guidance regarding the consistent
application of cost accounting practices at educational institutions." Since
institutions already must comply with A-21 and document their financial
management practices in accordance with Circular A-110, administrative
requirements for completing form DS-2 will only be highly burdensome if "a
university does not currently have adequate written cost accounting
practices."<P>

The complete form must be submitted only once. Changes to cost accounting
practices must be disclosed through amendments to the original form. If the
change "is expected to have a material impact on the ... negotiated facilities
and administrative cost rates," the revised practice must be approved by the
cognizant agency.<P>

While no materiality thresholds were set for what changes would warrant amending
an institution's DS-2 form, an OMB official said insignificant accounting changes
or changes to a single award generally would not need to be reported on the form
unless an institution's cost rates were affected. "The determination of whether
an accounting change is significant and, therefore, requires an amendment to the
DS-2 and possibly a cost impact proposal is to be made by the cognizant agency,"
OMB stated in the preamble. OMB also tried to alleviate institutions' concerns
that CASB and OMB could give conflicting interpretations of the new requirements.
OMB's Office of Federal Financial Management, which has more experience than CASB
in dealing with colleges and universities, will address all federal agencies'
inquiries about the standards, an OMB official said. <P>

<h3>Cost Allocation and Negotiation Issues</h3><P>

OMB made several other changes to Circular A-21 that could affect rates used by
institutions. Notably, the circular now requires that facilities and
administrative cost rates in use at the time of the award of a sponsored
agreement be used throughout the life of that agreement. (The circular now uses
the term "facilities and administrative costs" rather than "indirect costs,"
although the cost accounting standards described above still use the term
"indirect costs.") The rationale for fixing the rate applied to an agreement, OMB
said, was that "it is only fair for the federal government to commit funding and
reimbursement based on the conditions as they are understood to exist at that
time" that an agreement is initially made.<P>

The provision defines the "life" of the sponsored agreement as each "competitive
segment," or the period of years set by the federal funding agency at the time
the award is made. In cases where an institution has a provisional rate pending
the establishment of a negotiated rate with the federal government, the
provisional rate will be adjusted once the negotiated rate is approved.<P>

Fixing the rates applied to specific awards could especially impact National
Science Foundation (NSF) grantees. Historically, NSF has capped the total funding
(including direct and indirect costs) for a specific project during the life of
the award. Therefore, an institution with rising facilities and administrative
cost rates could shift some funding from direct to indirect costs to cover the
increase. The new Circular A-21 requires NSF to change its policy so that the
rate freeze will apply only to the indirect costs of the project. <P>

OMB also reassigned cost cognizance to two agencies -- HHS and ONR. As of July 1,
1996, Circular A-88, <i>Indirect Cost Rates, Audits and Audit Follow-up at
Educational Institutions </i>, is rescinded. However, cognizant agency assignments
effective as of Dec. 31, 1995, will remain the same through the latter of
institutions' fiscal years ending during 1997, or the period covered by
negotiated agreements in effect on Dec. 31, 1995. After that time, cognizance
will revert to HHS or ONR, depending on which agency has awarded an institution
more funds for the past three years. If a school receives funding from neither
agency, HHS will have cost cognizance.<P>

Cognizant agency assignments will stay the same for a five-year period. The
circular also spells out that negotiated rates must be accepted by all federal
agencies unless "special circumstances, when required by law or regulation,"
compel an agency to use a different rate for a class of sponsored agreements or a
single agreement.<P>

<h3>Tuition Benefits, Special Cost Studies</h3><P>

Dependent tuition benefits will no longer be an allowable cost under the revised
circular. This provision takes effect for fiscal years starting on or after Sept.
30, 1998. OMB said in the preamble to the revisions that this change was made to
bring the circular more in line with cost principles for state and local
governments, non-profits organizations and the Federal Acquisition Regulations,
which do not allow these costs. Many institutions had opposed this change,
arguing that dependent tuition benefits helped schools compete with commercial
firms in recruiting personnel.<P>

The costs associated with using special studies to determine utility, library and
student services cost allocations will be disallowed for indirect (administrative
and facilities) rates negotiated on or after July 1, 1998. By then, OMB plans to
have an alternative method in place to determine these rates (see March 1996
<i>Current Developments </i>, page 1). <P>

OMB expects to issue a proposal addressing alternatives by July 1, 1997. If an
institution's rate agreement in effect on May 8, 1996, extends beyond 1998, the
ban on using special cost studies will start at the end of that rate agreement
period.<P>

<h3>Facilities and Equipment Costs</h3><P>

As it did with revisions to Circular A-87, <i>Cost Principles for State, Local and
Indian Tribal Governments </i>, OMB added a provision to require institutions
converting from the use allowance to the depreciation method for cost recovery of
assets to make the conversion "as if the depreciation method had been used over
the entire life of the asset." (See July 1995 <i>Current Developments </i>, page 1, for
information about this provision in Circular A-87.)<P>

The circular further clarifies that a combination of use allowance and
depreciation may not be used, in like circumstances, for a single class of
assets. "This provision prevents an educational institution from both using
depreciation to recover the cost of assets with useful lives that are shorter
than the average lives reflected in the use allowance rates (50 years for
buildings and 15 years for equipment) and using allowance for the recovery of
assets with longer useful lives," OMB said.<P>

<h3>Interest Allowability </h3><P>

In another move to promote conformity among the cost principles, OMB adopted a
provision included in Circular A-122, <i>Cost Principles for Non-Profit
Organizations</i>, that requires preparation of a lease purchase analysis for
facilities costing more than $500,000. The analysis, which is a comparison of the
costs associated with purchasing a facility versus leasing it, must be done in
accordance with OMB Circular A-110. <P>

Regardless of which option an institution chooses, interest reimbursement will be
limited to the least expensive arrangement, OMB stated. "These requirements are
needed to protect the federal government against abusive financing arrangements
(such as 'balloon financing method' where the entire principal amount is [paid]
at the end of the finance term)."<P>

The circular also requires universities to prepare a cash-flow analysis for debt
arrangements over $1 million, unless the educational institution makes an initial
equity contribution to the asset purchase of 25 percent or more, OMB said. If the
equity contribution is less, the institution must "reduce claims for interest
cost by an amount equal to imputed interest earnings on excess cash flow."
Additionally, the circular requires that cognizant agencies be notified of any
substantial relocation from a federally funded building.<P>

Probably the least controversial change to the circular is the revised definition
of "equipment". As such, the circular defines "equipment" as "an article of
nonexpendable, tangible personal property having a useful life of more than one
year and an acquisition cost which equals or exceeds the lesser of the
capitalization level established by the organization for financial statement
purposes or $5,000." OMB already had been allowing cognizant agencies to waive
the previous $500 threshold.<P>

The revised circular is included in this month's supplement (Appendix I). 
<P>
</body> <foot>

