<Title> 14.181 Supportive Housing for Persons with Disabilities (811)</Title> <P>

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif> 
<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/fed_gts/cope/copehead.gif" alt="Resource Guide to Federal Program Compliance Audits"></center></IMG><P>

<h2> 14.181 Supportive Housing for Persons with Disabilities (811)</h2>

<body>
<h3>FEDERAL AGENCY:</h3>
HOUSING, DEPARTMENT OF HOUSING AND URBAN DEVELOPMENT<P>

<h3>AUTHORIZATION:</h3>
National Affordable Housing Act, Public Law 101-625, 42 U.S.C.
8013, 104 Stat. 4324, 4331.<P>

<h3>OBJECTIVES:</h3>
To provide for supportive housing and related facilities for persons
with disabilities.<P>

<h3>USES AND USE RESTRICTIONS:</h3>
Capital advances may be used to finance the
construction or rehabilitation of supportive housing for persons with
disabilities, including the purchase of buildings with or without rehabilitation
for use as group homes. Project rental assistance is used to cover any part of
the HUD-approved operating costs of the facility that is not met from project
income.<P>

*<i>As a general rule, only the costs that have been or will be paid in cash within
45 days after the date of final endorsement or closing or are escrowed with the
mortgagee can be included in the mortgagor's or contractor's certificate of
actual cost. For projects with insured mortgages, direct loans and capital
advances, the mortgagor determines the cut-off date for the actual cost of
interest, taxes and mortgage insurance premium. This date may, at the earliest,
be the same date as the final completion date or, at the mortgagor's option, any
date in between. The date chosen as the cut-off date and the date to which the
operating statement and balance sheet are computed must be the same. The final
completion date is the date on which the HUD representative signs the final HUD
representative's trip report (Form HUD-5379) showing substantial completion. This
form must be properly endorsed by the field chief architect. HUD notifies the
mortgagor/borrower, the general contractor and the mortgagee of the date of
completion in writing. This date is the basis for establishing the cut-off date
for insured projects, direct loan projects and capital advance projects (HUD
Project 4470.2, Chapter 1). Eligible costs are those costs of the project
construction and certain fees paid in cash or that will be paid in cash within 45
days of final endorsement. HUD Handbooks 4470.1 REV-2, 4450.1 REV and 4470.2,
Chapter 2, contain information on allowable costs that must be reported on Form
HUD-92330 and the ways in which costs can be adjusted for items considered to be
a recovery of costs.<P>

<b><i>SUGGESTED AUDIT PROCEDURES:</b></i><P>

<UL>
<LI>Review the trip report (Form HUD-5379) or similar notification to determine
the final completion date.<P>

<LI>Review charges for time-sensitive expenses, such as interest, taxes and
mortgage and property insurance premiums, to determine that none were incurred
after the cut-off date.<P>

<LI>Review other amounts claimed on Form HUD-92330 to determine whether they
were claims for expenses paid in cash within 45 days after final closing. All
amounts claimed should be net of any adjustments or recoveries of costs.</i><P>
</UL>

<h3>ELIGIBILITY REQUIREMENTS:</h3><P>

<b>Applicant Eligibility</b>: Nonprofit corporations.<P>

<b>Beneficiary Eligibility</b>: Beneficiaries of housing developed under this program
must be very low income physically disabled, developmentally disabled or
chronically mentally ill persons (18 years of age or older).<P>

*<i>Where tenants or projects are subsidized, the owner is responsible for
accepting applications, correctly calculating the tenant's contribution toward
rent and utilities and any subsidy, determining initial tenant eligibility,
completing annual recertification of tenant eligibility and rectifying improper
or inaccurate tenant information in accordance with the guidelines provided in
HUD Handbook 4350.3 and the applicable housing assistance payments contract.<P>

<b><i>SUGGESTED AUDIT PROCEDURES:</b></i><P>

<UL>
<LI>Compare the owner's procedures for accepting applications, determining
initial eligibility, total tenant payment and re-examining eligibility with
provisions in HUD Handbook 4350.3.<P>

<LI>Review a sample of tenant files to determine whether: (1) applications are
complete and signed by the applicant; (2) tenants meet the eligibility
requirements pertaining to their subsidized unit for annual income and family
composition; (3) the tenant payment was calculated correctly; and (4) the family
income was re-examined on an annual basis. Include in the sample some of the
oldest and some of the most recently admitted tenants.<P>

<LI>Review a sample of tenant files to determine if the owner noted any
improper or inaccurate information while determining tenant eligibility or
recertifying tenants. If such information is noted, determine that the owner
followed the guidance in HUD Handbook 4350.3 pertaining to overpayment of a
subsidy and followed up on suspected fraud.<P>

<LI>Review a sample of tenant files to determine that the tenant file contains
the following documents: (1) application; (2) required verifications of social
security numbers, disability status, waiting list preferences and allowances for
adjusted income; (3) lease/lease addenda in the form as required by HUD; (4)
certification and recertification forms (Form HUD-50059); and (5) move-in and
move-out inspections.</i><P>
</UL>

<h3>ASSISTANCE CONSIDERATIONS:</h3><P>

<b>Formula and Matching Requirements</b>: This program has maintenance of effort (MOE)
requirements; see funding agency for further details. Statistical factors used
for fund allocation include a measure of the number of non-institutionalized
persons age 16 or older with a work disability and a mobility or self-care
limitation, and the number of non-institutionalized persons age 16 or older
having a mobility or self-care limitation but having no work disability from the
Census. Statistical factors used for eligibility do not apply for this
program.<P>

<b>Length and Time Phasing of Assistance</b>: The capital advance is not repayable if
the project is available for very low income persons with disabilities for 40
years. Project Rental Assistance Contract payments may not exceed 20 years.
Projects are expected to start construction within 18 months of the date of the
fund reservation, with limited provision for extensions. Funds will be advanced
on a monthly basis during construction for work in place.<P>

<h3>REPORTING AND RECORDKEEPING REQUIREMENTS:</h3><P>

<b>Reports</b>: Any change in the owner during the 40-year period must be approved by
HUD. All owners will be required to submit an annual financial statement to
HUD.<P>

*<i>Projects participating in HUD-assisted activities are required to ensure that
financial status reports contain reliable financial data and are presented in
accordance with the terms of applicable agreements between the entity and HUD.
The individual agreements contain the specific reporting requirements that the
entity must follow. <P>

<b>SUGGESTED AUDIT PROCEDURES:</b><P>

<UL>
<LI>Identify all required financial reports by inquiry of the owner/manager.<P>

<LI>Obtain an understanding of the auditee's procedures for preparing and
reviewing the financial reports.<P>

<LI>Select a sample of financial reports (other than those included in the
audited financial statements) and determine whether the reports selected were
prepared in accordance with HUD instructions.<P>

<LI>For the sample, trace significant data to supporting documentation, (i.e.,
worksheets, ledgers, etc.). Report all material differences between financial
reports and project records.<P>

<LI>Review significant adjustments made to the general ledger accounts
affecting HUD-assisted activities and evaluate the propriety.<P>
</UL>

Mortgagors and contractors involved in projects that receive HUD-insured loans,
direct loans and capital advances must maintain adequate records for the purpose
of determining the eligible costs associated with the projects (HUD Handbook
4470.2, Chapter 3).<P>

<b>SUGGESTED AUDIT PROCEDURES:</b><P>

<UL>
<LI>Obtain an understanding of the mortgagor's and contractor's accounting
system for identifying actual costs associated with a given project. Test the
system to determine that it identifies the costs to be reported on the Form
HUD-92330 on an individual project basis.<P>

<LI>Review Form HUD-92330 to determine whether it is complete and supported by
the accounting records.<P>

<LI>Trace significant data from Form HUD-92330 to supporting documentation
(i.e. worksheets, ledgers, etc.). Report all material differences between the
amounts reported on Form HUD-92330 and the supporting documents.<P>
</UL></i>

<b>Records</b>: Regular financial reports are required. Owners must service and maintain
records in accordance with acceptable mortgage practices and HUD regulations.
Owners also must supply those records necessary to indicate compliance with the
project rental assistance contract.<P>

*<i><b>SPECIAL TESTS AND PROVISIONS:</b><P>

Identity of Interest<P>

HUD Handbooks 4430.1 REV-1, 4470.1 REV-2 and 4470.2, Chapter 3 describe several
situations that are considered an identity of interest involving a mortgagor, a
contractor, a subcontractor or a materials supplier. Where an identity of
interest exists, the contractor must also submit a certificate of actual cost or
the party involved in the identity of interest as required by 4470.2, Chapter 3.
The contractor must submit a certificate of actual cost if a cost plus
construction contract was used. <P>

<b>SUGGESTED AUDIT PROCEDURES:</b><P>

<UL>
<LI>Review mortgagor and project records such as contracts and vendor invoices
to determine if an identity of interest exists between any of the parties
involved in the project, from mortgagors to contractors, suppliers and equipment
lessors.<P>

<LI>Where an identity of interest exists, determine that the additional
reporting requirements of HUD Handbook 4470.2 have been met.<P>
</UL></i>

<h3>REGULATIONS, GUIDELINES, AND LITERATURE:</h3>
24 CFR, 890; HUD Handbooks 4571.2.<P>

<font size=-1>* <i>Consolidated Audit Guide for Audits of HUD Programs</i>, U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development, 1993. </font>

</body> <foot>

