<head>
<Title>Stormater Compliance Resources on the Internet</Title>
</head>

<body background="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">
<IMG SRC = "/tpg/enviro/strm/strmhead.gif" alt="Stormwater Permit Manual"><P>


<h2>Stormwater Compliance Resources on the Internet</h2><P>

The Internet can help stormwater permittees comply with federal regulations and answer questions about state requirements, associations, trade organizations, environmental groups, products and services.

This resource guide contains sections on: 

<UL>
	<LI><A HREF="#legislative">Legislative and Regulatory Information</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#state">State Agencies</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#association">Associations, Trade Organizations and Environmental Groups</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#bulletin">Bulletin Boards</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#products">Products and Services</A>
</UL>


<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT><A NAME="legislative">Legislative and Regulatory Information</A></H3>
</P>

<P>
To obtain the most comprehensive Clean Water Act (CWA) compliance information, users should check the Point Source Information Provision and Exchange System (PIPES) web site, which is sponsored by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and maintained by Science Applications International Corp. The site contains policy documents, guidance manuals, stormwater regulations, notice of intent and termination forms and more. The web site also allows users to telnet directly to the PIPES BBS. It is located at <A HREF="http://pipes.ehsg.saic.com/pipes.htm">http://pipes.ehsg.saic.com/pipes.htm</A>.
</P>

<P>
Other EPA water sites of interest include:
</P>

<P>
Nonpoint Source Pollution Control Program: <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov/OW/NPS">http://www.epa.gov/OW/NPS</A>;
</P>

<P>
Office of Wastewater Management (includes a link to PIPES): <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov/OW-OWM.html">http://www.epa.gov/OW-OWM.html</A>;
</P>

<P>
Office of Water: <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov/OW">http://www.epa.gov/OW</A>; and
</P>

<P>
Watershed Management Program: <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov/OW/watershed">http://www.epa.gov/OW/watershed</A>.
</P>

<P>
In addition, EPA regional offices have added web pages about their water-related programs to the Internet. Unless specifically noted, water-related web sites of EPA regional offices include:
</P>

<P>
Region 1: <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov/region01">http://www.epa.gov/region01</A> (main site);
</P>

<P>
Region 2: <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov/Region2/html/water.htm">http://www.epa.gov/Region2/html/water.htm</A>;
</P>

<P>
Region 3: <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov/reg3wapd/index.html">http://www.epa.gov/reg3wapd/index.html</A>;
</P>

<P>
Region 4: <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov/region4/waterpgs/wtr.html">http://www.epa.gov/region4/waterpgs/wtr.html</A> (under construction);
</P>

<P>
Region 5: <A HREF="http://water.r05.epa.gov">http://water.r05.epa.gov</A>;
</P>

<P>
Region 6: <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov/earth1r6/6wq.html">http://www.epa.gov/earth1r6/6wq.html</A>;
</P>

<P>
Region 7: <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov/region07/programs/wwpd/wwp.html">http://www.epa.gov/region07/programs/wwpd/wwp.html</A>;
</P>

<P>
Region 8: <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov/region08">http://www.epa.gov/region08</A> (main site, water site is under construction);
</P>

<P>
Region 9: <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov/region09/water/index.html">http://www.epa.gov/region09/water/index.html</A>; and
</P>

<P>
Region 10: <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov/region10/www/offices/water/ow.html">http://www.epa.gov/region10/www/offices/water/ow.html</A>.
</P>

<P>
Other useful federal information sources include:
</P>

<P>
<I>Federal Register</I> online, which can be accessed through the Government Printing Office: <A HREF="http://www.access.gpo.gov">http://www.access.gpo.gov</A>;
</P>

<P>
U.S. Department of Agriculture's Natural Resources Conservation Service: <A HREF="http://www.ncg.nrcs.usda.gov">http://www.ncg.nrcs.usda.gov</A>;
</P>

<P>
U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service: <A HREF="http://www.fws.gov">http://www.fws.gov</A>;
</P>

<P>
U.S. Geological Survey (coordinates the National Water Quality Assessment program): <A HREF="http://www.usgs.gov">http://www.usgs.gov</A>;
</P>

<P>
U.S. House of Representatives: <A HREF="http://www.house.gov">http://www.house.gov</A>;
</P>

<P>
Thomas, a site created by the 104th Congress to provide free federal legislative information, provides the text of bills before Congress, the status of each bill, text from the <I>Congressional Record</I> and floor actions for each bill: <A HREF="http://thomas.loc.gov">http://thomas.loc.gov</A>; and
</P>

<P>
U.S. Senate: <A HREF="http://www.senate.gov">http://www.senate.gov</A>.
</P>


<H3 ALIGN=LEFT><A NAME="state">State Agencies</A></H3>

<P>
States, like EPA, have started posting information on the Internet to assist facility compliance efforts and reduce the cost of outreach programs. Most state agency sites located on the Web contain information on current and upcoming regulatory requirements. In addition, many state sites have lists of frequently asked questions to help facilities with similar questions find answers quickly and easily.
</P>

<P>
New Jersey has added their stormwater permit requirements and a state newsletter, <I>New Jersey Discharger</I>, to its web site. The newsletter includes information on proposed stormwater permits, proposed fees for the program, seminars, meetings and other compliance information. The bureau's web site also allows users to comment on and subscribe to the newsletter online. The New Jersey Bureau of Stormwater Permitting is located at <A HREF="http://www.state.nj.us/dep/dwq/bswp.htm">http://www.state.nj.us/dep/dwq/bswp.htm</A>. 
</P>

<P>
The Pennsylvania DEP allows individuals to e-mail state officials or obtain state documents by e-mail request. Pennsylvania's web site is located at <A HREF="http://www.dep.state.pa.us">http://www.dep.state.pa.us</A>.
</P>

<P>
In addition to containing stormwater information, the Washington Department of Ecology has developed a site that contains watershed assessments, an index and abstracts of environmental investigations and laboratory services reports, permitting information, a list of accredited environmental labs and more. The site is located at <A HREF="http://www.wa.gov/ecology">http://www.wa.gov/ecology</A>.
</P>

<P>
Cities also have developed sites to address stormwater runoff. Tallahassee, for example, has developed a web site that includes information on floodplain management, stormwater-related educational information for utilities and others and a questionnaire on stormwater. Tallahassee's site is located at <A HREF="http://www.state.fl.us/citytlh/stormwater_man/main.html">http://www.state.fl.us/citytlh/stormwater_man/main.html</A>.
</P>

<P>
<A NAME="association"><H3 ALIGN=LEFT>Associations, Trade Organizations and Environmental Groups</H3></A>
</P>

<P>
Associations, trade organizations and environmental groups also have developed web sites that contain information that may be of use to stormwater permittees. In addition to containing information on the organizations, its activities and its members, many of the sites contain legislative activity reports, information on water programs and newsletters. Some sites of interest include:
</P>

<P>
American Farm Bureau Federation: <A HREF="http://www.fb.com">http://www.fb.com</A>;
</P>

<P>
Amercian Water Resources Association: <A HREF="http://www.uwin.siu.edu/%7Eawra">http://www.uwin.siu.edu/~awra</A>;
</P>

<P>
Association of State and Interstate Water Pollution Control Administrators: <A HREF="http://www.deq.state.la.us/asiwpca/welcome.htm">http://www.deq.state.la.us/asiwpca/welcome.htm</A>;
</P>

<P>
Automotive Service Association: <A HREF="http://www.asashop.org">http://www.asashop.org</A>;
</P>

<P>
Environmental Defense Fund: <A HREF="http://www.edf.org">http://www.edf.org</A>;
</P>

<P>
National Association of Counties: <A HREF="http://www.naco.org">http://www.naco.org</A>;
</P>

<P>
National Cattlemen's Beef Association: <A HREF="http://www.cowtown.org">http://www.cowtown.org</A>;
</P>

<P>
National League of Cities: <A HREF="http://www.cais.com/nlc/nlcmain.html">http://www.cais.com/nlc/nlcmain.html</A>;
</P>

<P>
National Water Resources Association: <A HREF="http://www.nwra.org">http://www.nwra.org</A>;
</P>

<P>
Natural Resources Defense Council: <A HREF="http://www.nrdc.org">http://www.nrdc.org</A>;
</P>

<P>
Professional Lawn Care Association of America: <A HREF="http://www.plcaa.org">http://www.plcaa.org</A>; and
</P>

<P>
Water Environment Federation: <A HREF="http://www.wef.org">http://www.wef.org</A>.
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT><A NAME="bulletin">Bulletin Boards</A></H3>
</P>

<P>
To obtain the most comprehensive Clean Water Act (CWA) compliance information, users should check the Point Source Information Provision and Exchange System (PIPES) web site and bulletin board system (BBS). The web site allows users to telnet directly to the PIPES BBS. On the BBS, users can exchange questions through public or private messages, obtain technical assistance and information, and download computer programs. The site is located at <A HREF="http://pipes.ehsg.saic.com/pipes.htm">http://pipes.ehsg.saic.com/pipes.htm</A>.
</P>

<P>
Web surfers can post stormwater-related questions on two different bulletin boards set up by the Ground Water Protection Council. Typically, when posting a question, the person leaves an e-mail address to which others perusing the bulletin board can reply if they have an appropriate answer. The sites are located at <A HREF="http://www.site.net/gwpc/forums/stormwater/forum.html">http://www.site.net/gwpc/forums/stormwater/forum.html</A> and <A HREF="http://traffic.jam.net/gwpc/forums/stormwater/forum.html">http://traffic.jam.net/gwpc/forums/stormwater/forum.html.</A>
</P>

<P>
<H3 ALIGN=LEFT><A NAME="products">Products and Services</A></H3>
</P>

<P>
Firms that offer stormwater permit compliance services or products also have developed web sites. Many engineering and landscape firms offer services to help facilities create stormwater pollution prevention plans, evaluate best management practices and choose best available technology and best conventional pollutant control technology. Other firms offer engineering and modeling software, dewatering equipment or other stormwater control materials. To quickly find information about products and services available, users should try using Yahoo! (<A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com">http://www.yahoo.com</A>) or one of the many other search engines available on the Web.
</P>

<center>
<pre>
<a href="/tpg/enviro/strm/strm.html"><img src="/tpg/enviro/strm/smallstrm.gif" alt="Return to Stormwater Permit Manual Home Page"></a> <a href="/tpg/prices/enviroprices.html"><img src="/tpg/orderbut.gif" alt=" [ ORDER ] "></a>
</pre>
</center>
