<html>
<head> 
<title>Synthroid: Notice of Violation</title>
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<IMG SRC="/tpg/food/sell/sellhead.gif" alt="FDA Advertising and Promotion Manual">
<P>

DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH &amp; HUMAN SERVICES	Public Health Services<BR>
Food and Drug Administration<BR>
Rockville, MD  20857<BR>

<P>
November 7, 1996
</P>

<P>
TRANSMITTED VIA FACSIMILE
</P>

Robert Ashwood, Ph.D.<BR>
Director, Regulatory Affairs<BR>
Knoll Pharmaceuticals<BR>
199 Cherry Hill Rd.<BR>
Parsippany, NJ 07054<BR>

<P>
RE: Synthroid<BR>
Macimis ID #2380
</P>

<P>
Dear Dr. Ashworth:
</P>

<P>
This letter concerns Knoll Pharmaceuticals' (Knoll) promotional use of an article,<A HREF="#1">1</A> the "Berg/Mayor article," in Knoll's promotion of Synthroid (levothyroxine sodium). The Division of Drug Marketing, Advertising and Communications (DDMAC) has concluded that Knoll has violated the Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act (the Act), 21 U.S.C. &#167;331(a) by misbranding Synthroid. Specifically, the reprints of the Berg/Mayor article, when disseminated by Knoll after Knoll received additional material information, were and are misleading labeling under 21 U.S.C. &#167;321(n) because the article fails to reveal facts that are material in light of other representations made or suggested by statement or word in the Berg/Mayor article.
</P>

<P>
The Berg/Mayor article reports a study designed to evaluate the pharmacokinetic comparability of Synthroid and a competing levothyroxine product. The endpoints evaluated were the rate and extent of absorption over a relatively short period of time (less than one half-life), following supra-therapeutic doses of levothyroxine sodium. The authors of the article concluded that the measured endpoints were different between Synthroid and its competitor, and therefore the clinical pharmacokinetic profiles of the products were likely to be different from each other. Although the authors believed they had shown differences between the products, they noted that to show similarity, "a more complex design involving chronic administration in a well-controlled, hypothyroid population with the measurement of several endpoints" would be required.<A HREF="#2">2</A> 
</P>

<P>
In fact, since at least December of 1994, Knoll has been in possession of the results of a study with just such a more complex design involving chronic administration of thyroid replacement products in a hypothyroid population with the measurement of several endpoints, including thyroid stimulating hormone. This study, the "Dong study," was conducted by Dr. Betty Dong at the request of Knoll, and a manuscript reporting the results of the completed Dong study was accepted for publication by the Journal of the American Medical Association. Under pressure from Knoll, however, Dr. Dong withdrew the manuscript from publication. On its face, the manuscript from the Dong study contradicts the results of the Berg/Mayor study.
</P>

<P>
DDMAC has reviewed the manuscript of the Dong study, in consultation with FDA's Division of Endocrine and Metabolic Drug Products. Although we are unable to fully evaluate the data supporting the manuscript, we have concluded that the information is, at the very least, a material piece of information in the evolving scientific dialogue about the pharmacokinetic comparability of levothyroxine products, and specifically, the two products tested in the Berg/Mayor article.
</P>

<P>
Knoll should immediately cease dissemination of the Berg/Mayor article. Furthermore, because the agency is deeply concerned with the circumstances surrounding this issue, we invite you to meet with us in the near future to discuss our concerns. Knoll should respond to Patrick O'Brien, Regulatory Counsel, Division of Drug Marketing, Advertising and Communications, HFD-40, 5600 Fishers Lane, Rockville, MD 20857, stating its intent to comply with our requests. Knoll's response should be submitted no later than November 22, 1996. In all future correspondence about this issue, please refer to MACMIS ID#2380.
</P>

<P>
Sincerely,
</P>

Minnie Baylor-Henry<BR>
Director<BR>
Division of Drug Marketing, Advertising and Communications<BR>

 
<P>
<A NAME="1">1</A>. Berg JA, Mayor GH. A study in normal human volunteers to compare the rate and extent of levothyroxine absorption from Synthroid and Levoxine. <U>J. Clin Pharmacol</U> 1993; 33:1135-1140.
</P>

<P>
<A NAME="2">2</A>. Berg/Mayor at p. 1139.
</P>
<hr>

