<html> <title> Do It By Design</title>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/xrayhead.gif" alt="Guide to Medical Device 
Regulation"></center>
<P>
<body>

<center>From: The Center for Devices and Radiological Health<P>

<h2> Do It By Design</h2>

<b>An Introduction to Human Factors in Medical Devices</b></center><P>

<b>Draft: March 1, 1996</b><P>

U.S. Department of Health and Human Services<br>

Public Health Service<br>

Food and Drug Administration<br>

Center for Devices and Radiological Health<P>

<center><h3>INTRODUCTION</h3></center><P>

The purpose of this primer is to improve the safety of medical devices by
minimizing the likelihood of user error by <i>systematic, careful design of the
<b>user interface</b>, the hardware and software features that define the
interaction between users and equipment</i>. To this end, the document contains
background information about human factors as a discipline; descriptions and
illustrations of device problems; and a discussion of human factors methods.
Recommendations for manufacturers and health facilities are also included.<P>

Because many designers, engineers, scientists, and health professionals may be
unfamiliar with human factors, the primer is written as a basic educational tool
and assumes little background knowledge in the subject matter. At the same time,
much of the content may serve as a resource for those individuals who have had
experience with human factors issues.<P>

The primer is directed to the following audiences:<P>

<b>Manufacturers</b><P>

<UL>
<LI>Hardware and software engineers and designers<P>
<LI>Product and quality assurance managers<P>
<LI>Documentation writers<P>
<LI>Regulatory Affairs Staff<P>
<LI>Other research and development (R&amp;D), marketing, production, and
managerial staff who may influence user interface design</UL><P>

<b>Food and Drug Administration (FDA)</b><P>

<UL>
<LI>Device reviewers<P>
<LI>Incident evaluators<P>
<LI>Field investigators<P>
<LI>Compliance staff</UL><P>

<b>Health Professionals</b><P>

<UL>
<LI>Risk managers<P>
<LI>Physicians and nurses<P>
<LI>Maintenance personnel<P>
<LI>Purchasing agents</UL><P>

Good user interface design is critical to the safe and effective equipment
operation, installation, and maintenance. This document has been developed, in
part, to convince the reader that systematic attention to human factors is
extremely important. The practice of good human factors means <i>systematic
analysis and testing throughout development stages</i>; it is <i>not</i> simply a
matter of "fine tuning." Thorough attention to design will result in safer, more
usable devices and, correspondingly, fewer accidents, reduced training costs,
fewer liability problems, and less trial-and-error during device development.
Also, the information will be useful in planning human factors programs that
involve testing, incident analysis, or staff training. In addition to providing
technical information, the booklet discusses various human factors resources.<P>

Finally, "<i>Do It By Design</i>" encourages all readers to think critically
about the impact of device design upon the ability of health professionals to
treat patients safely and effectively. Consider the primer a starting point. One
should supplement this information with more detailed data, principles, and
methodologies from guidelines, standards, texts, and articles, some of which are
referenced in this document. Also, those individuals using these materials in
conducting human factors analyses and tests should obtain human factors
training.<P>

<center><h3>HUMAN FACTORS: AN HISTORICAL PERSPECTIVE</h3></center><P>

Human Factors is a discipline that achieves human-equipment compatibility by
means of user-interface design methods, user training development, and the
development of job aids. The emphasis of this document is design. The adjacent
figure illustrates some of the kinds of confusing design factors that underly the
need for human factors applications to hardware and software. Although the terms
"human engineering", "usability engineering", and "ergonomics" are often used
interchangeably as the process used to achieve highly usable equipment, "human
factors engineering", generally is used in this document.<P>

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/design/xraydesign1.gif" alt="This graphic shows that some user
interface designs are very confusing and likely to induce errors."></center><P>

Historically, human factors can be traced to early efforts by industrial a
engineers, psychologists, and efficiency experts to streamline manufacturing
operations and equipment for better worker efficiency. In World War II emphasis
shifted from production to personnel safety. A special focus was aircraft cockpit
design. Poor control and display design often induced pilot errors, sometimes
leading to crashes. Military applications have continued since, and in recent
years the advent of complex technology and media coverage of user problems and
accidents has increased the recognition of human factors. Examples include the
role of poor user interface design in the three-Mile Island meltdown; the
advertising of  "ergonomically-designed" automobiles; and the development of
"user friendly" computer hardware and software. Today this important discipline
is widely recognized by various governments , agencies, the military development
community, the telecommunications industry, numerous consumer product companies,
and increasingly by medical device manufacturers. <P>

<center><h3>WHY HUMAN FACTORS IS lMPORTANT TO MEDlCAL DEVICE
DESlGN</h3></center><P>

<i>Design-induced errors</i> by medical device users can, and do, lead to patient
injury, and sometimes death. Users respond directly to the equipment they are
operating, and misleading, illogical user interfaces  overtaxes even the most
skilled health practitioner. A brief discussion of device users, operating
conditions, incidents, and design implications will shed some light on the need
for systematic human factors engineering during medical device design and
development.<P>

<b>The Interaction of User Characteristics, Device Design, and the Operating
Environment</b><P>

Health professionals vary greatly in their physical, sensory, and mental
abilities. Lay people, who represent an increasing proportion of medical device
users, further extend such variability. Medical devices are used in many
environments, including operating rooms, emergency rooms, patient units, critical
care facilities, clinics, and homes. Conditions often are  adverse due to noise,
poor lighting, glare-producing surfaces, heat, dirt, electrical interference, and
moisture. Inadequate procedures, insufficient replacement parts, stress, and
fatigue can also degrade performance. Compounding the situation is the wide array
of equipment that a health practitioner operates. Devices used by a single
individual often differ greatly in design and frequency of use.<P>

A medical device will be used safely and effectively only if the
<i>interaction</i> of the operating environment, user capabilities, and device
design is considered by the manufacturer. The following dimensions of human
capability are basic to an understanding of human factors.<P>

<b>Physical and Sensory Characteristics</b><P>

People's most basic capacities include visual acuity, hearing, tactile dexterity,
strength, and reach. A number of related design factors influence human
performance: the legibility and discriminability of displayed symbols; audibility
and distinctiveness of alarms; strength required to make connections requirements
for reaching controls and activating keys; and other such factors.<P>

<b>Perceptual and Cognitive Abilities</b><P>
Perception fundamentally is how people identify and organize sensory input.
People's perceptual characteristics are important in the design and arrangement
of controls, keypads, displays, information presentation, as well as alarms and
alerts. Cognition refers to higher level mental phenomena such as memory,
attaching meaning to objects and concepts, use of rules and strategies, formation
of hypotheses, and abstract reasoning. There are numerous applications related to
design. For example, the multiple, hierarchical pathways and unlimited
information often found in computerized devices can rapidly exceed users' memory
limits. Therefore, a designer might develop easy-to-use retrieval systems, taking
advantage of well-established semantic, symbolic, and mnemonic techniques for
screen and menu design. Understanding people's limitations and exploiting their
strengths in this area is critical.<P>

<b>Expectancies:</b> People are predisposed to react to new situations according
to established habits. When users operate a new device that has physical and
informational characteristics resembling that of a device model they've
previously used, they often revert to earlier, often incorrect, habits.
Therefore, control and display design, coding, layout, and the operating steps in
a new model ideally will be similar to those on any predicate models having a
similar configuration.<P>

<b>Mental Models:</b> Based on experience, people form abstract concepts about
how complex phenomena actually work. Anesthesiologists, for example, form mental
representations of patient status based on information about respiration, heart
rate, oxygen levels, and other bodily processes. Monitors should present such
information in a manner consistent with such "models." There is a significant
need for thorough assessment of how users conceptualize device operations in
patient treatment and monitoring. This is a complex issue, because people differ
in how they mentally integrate and conceptualize data that changes over time.<P>

<b>Home-use</b><P>

Lay people increasingly use medical devices, and by virtue of illness, age, poor
reading ability, inadequate facilities, insufficient assistance, and inexperience
this population represents a special design challenge. Decrements in vision,
hearing, strength, dexterity, and memory are to be expected due to age and
illness. Also, older patients often are <i>unfamiliar with automated devices and
often are afraid to use them</i>. For this reason, as well as lack of medical
training, lay users' use of highly complex devices is a great concern. Also, some
devices that even physicians and nurses may find difficult to operate find their
way into the home, where the above problems are compounded by power outages,
insufficient electrical outlets, electromagnetic interference, and insufficient
spare parts and accessories. Additionally, basic structural design of household
doors and bathrooms don't always accommodate device use. Home-use devices should
be designed to accommodate that environment, since the reverse may not be
feasible.<P>

<b>Design Implications</b>

Obviously, completely "designing out" all problems associated with human
limitations and environmental factors is impossible. Few devices are entirely
"fail safe." However, designing the user interface with careful attention to the
user will result to a device that:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Accommodates a wide range of users working under variable conditions.<P>
<LI>Users can operate with fewer errors and resulting accidents. <P>
<LI>Require's less user training.</UL><P>

It is impossible to fully compensate for bad design, and numerous incident and
recall reports received by the Center for Devices and Radiological Health (CDRH)
attest to this. <i>The cumulative and interactive effects of errors can be
serious, and even disastrous</i>. The remainder of this booklet describes user
interface design issues, the process of human factors engineering, and related
topics.<P>

<center><h3>THE USER INTERFACE -- ISSUES AND PROBLEMS</h3></center><P>

This section describes and discusses problems related to human factors. The
material should foster an appreciation of the impacts of considering or not
considering user-interface during design and provide the reader with the
<i>rationale</i> that underlies human factors, as well as an understanding of
basic
principles. This discussion is illustrated primarily by brief summaries of
serious incidents that have been documented in CDRH's incident reporting systems.
The summary principles found in the "Rules of Thumb" in each subsection are by no
means exhaustive. The primer contains no detailed data on control dimensions and
forces, body dimensions, audition, vision, menu and screen design. The reader is
encouraged to consult guidelines such as the AAMI <i>Human factors engineering
guidelines and preferred practices for the design of medical devices (1993)</i>,
as well as other human factors guidelines and textbooks.<P>

<b>CONTROL/DISPLAY ARRANGEMENT AND DESIGN</b><P>

Although today's technology is moving away from display panel layouts having
numerous controls and displays, they are still important. Many  devices have
large consoles with rows of mechanical controls and displays. The designer must
consider the ability of users to quickly and  properly identify controls,
switches, and displays; reach and accurately set controls; read displays
accurately; and associate controls with their related displays. Efficient
configuration and grouping are important, as are unambiguous labels and keys that
are easy to operate. Finally, with all medical devices control and display
arrangements, operations, and labels should be consistent with user
expectations.<P>

<i>Examples of Errors Related to Hardware Design</i><P>

Below are a few examples of problems abstracted from incident reports and device
recalls.<P>

<OL>
<LI>A physician treating a patient with liquid oxygen set the flow control knob
between 1 and 2 liters per minute, not understanding that the scale numbers
represented discrete, not continuous, settings. <i>There was no airflow between
the
settings</i>. The patient, an infant, became hypoxic before the error was
discovered.
The device should have employed a discrete rotary control - one which has
detentes to snap the control into a discrete setting.<P>

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/design/xraydesign2.gif" alt="This graphic talks about discontinuous
flow between settings."></center><P>


<LI>In numerous incidents and recalls associated with defibrillators, the paddles
were difficult to remove from the retaining wells during emergencies. In one
incident, in which the patient died, the attendants couldn't operate the device
because they failed to activate a crucial control. The associated label was not
near the control.<P>

<LI>There have been cases in which patients were seriously injured when a nurse
over infused a patient after reading the number "7" as a "1". Given the depth of
the flowrate readout recessed in the infusion pump display panel, the top of the
"7" was blocked from view at even modest vertical viewing angles. Also, there
have been other reports in which flowrates have been similarly misread when
viewed from lateral angles, for example, 355 ml read as 55 ml.</OL><P>

These few examples illustrate the fact that seemingly small design flaws can
result in serious problems. Below are a few suggested rules of thumb for
designing the user interface.<P>

<i>Rules of Thumb</i><P>

<UL>
<LI>Make all facets of design as consistent with user expectations as possible.
Both users' prior experience with medical devices and well-established
conventions, such as symbology, are important.<P>

<LI>Design workstations, controls, and displays around the basic capabilities of
users regarding such characteristics as strength, dexterity, memory, reach,
visual acuity, and hearing.<P>

<LI>Design well organized and uncluttered control and display arrangements. These
facilitate proper identification and reduce the user's memory load.<P>

<LI>Be sure that auditory signals are well within users' threshold values for
amplitude and frequency. Consider the effects of ambient noise. Likewise, the
brightness of visual signals must be sufficient to be perceived by users working
under various conditions of ambient illumination. Also, both brightness contrast
and color contrast must be adequate to optimize legibility.<P>

<LI>Be careful that labels and displayed information are easy to read from
typical viewing angles and distances. Symbol, size, contrast, color, and display
depth must be considered.<P>

<LI>Ensure that the abbreviations, symbols, text, and acronyms placed on, or
displayed by, the device are also used in the instructional manual.<P>

<LI>Design control knobs and switches to correspond with both general conventions
and any that are unique to the user population.<P>

<LI>Arrange and design knobs, switches, and data-entry key in a way that reduces
the likelihood of accidental activation.<P>

<LI>Use color and shape coding to facilitate the rapid identification and
discrimination of controls and displays. Colors and codes should correspond to
universal industry convention. <P>

<LI>Space keys, valves, and control knobs sufficiently apart for easy
manipulation. This will also reduce the likelihood of  accidental
activation.</UL><P>

<i>Summary</i><P>

In summary, the layout and design of controls and displays greatly affects the
ability of users to successfully exercise functions and extract information
during device operations. The next section discusses the logic of such
user-device interactions as determined by software design.<P>

<b>DEVICE LOGIC AND MICROPROCESSING</b><P>

Although both hardware and software design influence device use, with modern
automation the logical, temporal, and informational characteristics provided via
software are increasingly crucial and often are error-inducing. For instance,
large amounts of data presented imprecisely and in an ambiguous,
difficult-to-read way increases the likelihood of it's being misread. An example
might be a crowded CRT display with cryptic identifiers combined with a time lag
between user response and displayed feedback. Such design characteristics overtax
the user's memory and decision-making capability.<P>

<i>Characterizing the Shift to Increasing Software</i><P>

With the large numbers of controls and displays found in conventional equipment,
the user must identify and integrate spatially disparate information. Although
such designs, and related problems of proper control identification and
activation are still common, the trend is to assign more functions to software.
This / reduces the number of controls and displays, but can increase the burden
on the user in other ways. The use of software is particularly obvious with
infusion pumps, like that shown in the illustration, below. Although there are
few controls and displays, the large amounts of programmed information impose
heavy demands on the user's memory, since most information must be called up in
sequence, which precludes simultaneous viewing of related data. Users "become
lost" in the system if sufficient prompts and roadmaps are absent. Also, users
easily misinterpret displayed data and/or respond inappropriately if precise
feedback and indications of functional status are missing.<P>

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/design/xraydesign3.gif" alt="This graphic shows an infusion
pump."></center><P>

Product developers often incorporate a large number of functions into the device
in order to provide flexibility and to serve a wider community, but extensive
functional capability may well impose an unreasonable cognitive load on the user
unless considerable effort is devoted to the design of the user interface. Below
are problems that lead to errors and apply to many medical devices. <P>

<UL>
<LI>Illogical or cumbersome control sequences<P>
<LI>Unfamiliar language, symbols, or codes.<P>
<LI>Inconsistencies among formats for successive or co-located displays<P>
<LI>Conventions that contradict user expectations<P>
<LI>Uncertain or no feedback after input<P>
<LI>Missing or ambiguous prompts<P>
<LI>Unsignalled resets or defaults<P>
<LI>No status information<P>
<LI>Ambiguous symbols or icons<P>
<LI>Missing lock-outs or interlocks<P>
<LI>Complex mental calculations required<P>
</UL>

<i>Examples of Errors Related to Software Design</i><P>

Many user errors induced by software design are incorrectly attributed to other
factors because frequently little, if any, physical evidence remains after an
incident. Also, software-related errors can be subtle. For example users become
frustrated by cumbersome data entry steps and make errors not directly related to
those steps. Ambiguous acronyms or abbreviations used in the command structure or
on menus may also lead to serious errors. On the other hand, there are many
tangible software  examples gathered from incident files, recalls, and analyses,
and a few are cited below.<P>

<OL>
<LI>There have been incidents with radiation treatment devices due to the fact
that users failed to enter dosage levels. The device software does not prompt the
user for the data. However, if the user does not enter a dosage level, the device
automatically defaults to a given value without signaling this value.<P>

<LI>As the result of software errors, a cardiac output monitor alarm could be
disabled when the control buttons were pushed in a specific sequence.<P>

<LI>Because of a software error, a neonatal monitor displayed half of the actual
BPM when heart rate exceeded a specific value. In one case, the user treated the
halved value as the real one, and the patient became hypoxic.<P>

<LI>With infusion pumps, there have been numerous recalls of devices in which
slight deviations from prescribed operating sequences have disabled device
operation, in some cases without any feedback to the operator. Other serious
incidents and recalls have involved such deficiencies as poorly signaled
operating modes, cumbersome operating steps, and the presentation of
unanticipated warning data on a display normally reserved for other critical
information.</OL><P>

Only by thorough analysis, testing, and the judicious use of guidelines and 
standards can efficient software designs be achieved.<P>

<i>Rules of Thumb</i><P>

<UL>
<LI>Don't contradict users' expectations. Rather, exploit their prior experience
with computerized equipment, and consider conventions related to language and
symbology.<P>
<LI>Be consistent and unambiguous in the use and design of headings,
abbreviations, symbols, formats, etc.<P>
<LI>Keep users informed about current device status.<P>
<LI>Provide immediate and clear feedback following user entries.<P>
<LI>Design procedural steps that progress in a logical, straightforward
sequence.<P>
<LI>Use appropriate prompts, menus, etc. to cue the user regarding important
steps; don't "strand" him!<P>
<LI>Give users recourse in the case of an error. Be helpful and forgiving by
providing conspicuous correction mechanisms.<P>
<LI>Don't overload or confuse users with information that is unformatted, densely
packed, or of too short duration.<P>
<LI>Consider the use of accepted symbols, icons, colors, and abbreviations, to
convey a great deal of information reliably, economically, and quickly. <P>
<LI>When struggling over a software design issue, don't overlook hardware
solutions -- for example, a stand-alone push-button for a high priority
time-driven function.<P>
<LI>Consider the use of dedicated displays or display sectors for highly critical
information. In such cases, <i>do not display other data in these
locations</i>.</UL><P>

<i>Summary</i><P>

Microprocessing offers terrific capabilities -- ready data access, manipulation,
and computation; speedy accomplishment of functions; and much more. Technological
sophistication, however, can work to the ; users' disadvantage if software design
,is done without regard for user needs. Designers should utilize human computer
interface (HCI) guidelines, thorough analysis, and use testing in software
development. Designers must also coordinate their efforts closely with the
hardware design work.<P>

<b>COMPONENT INSTALLATION</b><P>

Among the most common errors reported to CDRH are improper installation of device
components. Such errors are relatively conspicuous because of the physical
evidence remaining following an incident, as well as the frequently serious
consequences of such errors. Proper installation usually is critical to device
operation, and the effects of installation errors often go unrecognized for a
long time.<P>

<i>Problems and Examples</i><P>

Some commonly reported errors are as follows: tubing connected to the wrong port
or disconnected by casual contact; electrical leads inserted into an improper
power source; batteries or bulbs inserted incorrectly; and valves or other
hardware installed backward or upside-down. These examples are illustrated
below:<P>

<OL>
<LI>A component of an oxygen machine was installed upside down, resulting in a
patient death because of impeded air flow.<P>
<LI>A ventilator was recalled after low-pressure alarms had shorted out on
several occasions; the failures were traced to misinstalled batteries resulting
from the design of the battery ports.<P>
<LI>Three deaths were reported due to the introduction of feeding solutions into
IV tubing from enteral feeding tubes via an adaptor intended for introducing
medication into the enteral feeding system.<P>
<LI>Injuries and deaths have resulted from infusion-pump users confusing similar
cassettes, inserting one intended for a different model. Due to the confusion,
the medication volumes were incorrect, although the pump displays did not reflect
this.<P>
<LI>Breathing tube disconnects due to tube and connector design have lead to
numerous injuries, deaths, and "near misses" with ventilators.</UL><P>

Existing problems are exacerbated by the fact that there may be many component
manufacturers selling a wide range of parts for a type of device. There are a
great variety of cables, leads, connectors, valves, and tubing on the market, as
shown in the adjacent illustration. Parts for different models are often similar
in appearance and/or difficult to install, leading to mis-installations and
disconnections. In some cases, insufficient industry conventions, such as
standardized coding, may contribute to accidents. However, such accidents can be
prevented through careful human factors design. It is crucial that device 
components be considered part of a system, not as isolated elements!<P>

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/design/xraydesign4.gif" alt="This graphic talks about improper
connections and mis-assembly."></center><P>

<i>Rules of Thumb</i><P>

These are general considerations for reducing the likelihood of confusion between
similar components and making improper connections.<P>

<UL>
<LI>Cables, tubing, connectors, leuers, connecting ports, and other hardware
should be designed for easy installation and connection; and "reversals",
substitutions, and other incorrect installations should be "designed out" if
possible.<P>
<LI>If the hazard cannot be eliminated via a design solution, color codes or
other markings will help to ensure proper connections and component
installation.<P>
<LI>Positive locking mechanisms are desirable whenever the integrity of
connections may be compromised by factors such as component durability.<P>
<LI>Protected contacts are necessary for body leads that can be inadvertently
introduced into electrical outlets, power cords, extension cords or other common
connectors. Exposed contacts should be avoided.</UL><P>

There is a tremendous variety of device attachments and accessories. Potential
hazards should be identified, and then appropriate design and coding techniques
used to prevent confusion and mis-installation.<P>

<b>ALARMS</b><P>

Alarms and related advisories are intended to alert device users about situations
and problems related to patient and device status. This seemingly straightforward
function often is complex. Alarms must attract the attention of someone working
intently on an often critical task unrelated to the alarming device. In some
environments, multiple alarms sounding simultaneously or intermittently on one or
more devices makes proper identification difficult. Staff become distracted, and
alarms may be considered a nuisance or, at best, part of the background. In
addition,  ambient noise and numerous visual displays can mask the output from 
auditory and visual displays. Interacting with all of the above problems are
malfunctions and false alarms due to electro-magnetic interference (EMI), static
electricity, or over-sensitivity.<P>

<i>Problems and Examples</i><P>

Errors related to alarm failures and design include the following: false alarms,
delayed alarm, too sensitive or insensitive alarms, alarms drowned out by noise,
ambiguous meanings, inappropriate silencing, and accidental disabling. Below are
two actual incidents.<P>

<OL>
<LI>A patient receiving oxygen died when a concentrator pressure hose loosened.
The alarm was not loud enough to  hear over the drone of the device.<P>

<LI>A patient on a ventilator died following accidental detachment of the
breathing tube from the humidifier. The alarm did not sound because the pressure
limit setting apparently was so low that it was effectively
non-functional.</OL><P>

Variations of these scenarios are common. Low alarm intensity, high ambient
noise, low battery conditions, alarm settings, and other factors combine to
create potentially dangerous situations.<P>

<i>Rules of Thumb</i><P>

<UL>
<LI>Consider a wide spectrum of environments in designing alarms.<P>
<LI>Be sure that visual and auditory alerts and critical alarms are included in
the device design requirements.<P>
<LI>Carefully consider the effects of over-sensitivity, electromagnetic
interference, or static electricity on alarm functioning.<P>
<LI>Design auditory alarms well within hearing thresholds for the typical user.
Likewise, the luminance of visual alarms should be above visual thresholds. Both
luminance contrast and color contrast must be sufficient for legibility under
variable lighting conditions.<P>
<LI>Use codes (e.g., color) that correspond to established conventions.<P>
<LI>Design alarms that are distinguishable from one another and, to the extent
possible, from alarms on other devices used in the same setting.<P>
<LI>Design alarms to activate immediately following the onset of a critical
problem, failure, etc. Alarms should identify the source of the problem.<P>
<LI>Consider prioritizing alarms, and remember that critical alarms ideally
provide redundant auditory and visual signals.<P>
<LI>Design alarms so that when they are disabled or silenced, they remain so only
temporarily; and visual indicators should indicate their status.</UL><P>

<b>OTHER IMPORTANT ISSUES</b><P>

<i>Dimensions, Forces, and Angles</i><P>

Workstations, seating, and consoles associated with or integral to medical
devices literally must fit the user population. Data on the body dimensions of
various populations is collected and published in a variety of documents, such
dimensions including arm length, body height, leg length, and numerous other
bodily specifications. Such data are important in designing equipment so that
controls are within reach and seating arrangements are comfortable.
Conventionally applied to the design of work consoles, these considerations also
apply to many home use devices, such as wheelchairs. With the latter, such issues
as portability and compatibility with doors are applicable.<P>

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/design/xraydesign5.gif" alt="This graphic questions whether a
wheelchair fits a wide range of users and environments."></center><P>


More elusive, but critical, are the <i>biomechanical characteristics</i> of tools
such as hammers, scalpels, control knobs, and other devices that require
substantial dexterity or strength and/or involve repetitive motions. Errors or
musculo-skeletal injuries to health professionals and patients associated with
these factors are difficult to document, but they are important. Other devices to
consider are keyboards, some of which require unnatural hand positions and
increase the likelihood of carpel  tunnel syndrome, and dental drills difficult
to manipulate because of improperly (or not) angled shafts.<P>

<i>Inter-Device Compatibility</i><P>

"Transfer-of-training" from one device to another is a an important concern.
Health professionals often are trained on different makes and models of devices
performing the same functions. If two models have very similar user interface
configurations but differ with respect to required operator actions, habits
established with one device can interfere with user performance on the other.
"Negative transfer" from the original device will greatly increase the likelihood
of errors on the second. For example, if on/off switch positions are reversed on
two very similar devices, a user transferring from one to the other could easily
revert to the switch operation habits learned with the earlier device. The same
concern applies to a device that is retrofitted or redesigned, as in the case of
a recalled or new-generation model.<P>

<i>Failure Mode Effects Analysis</i><P>

Failure mode effects analysis usually considers the impacts of electrical,
mechanical, or software failures upon device functioning. But the impacts on the
user interface should be considered, as well. For example, false alarms lead
users to disregard further alarms; alarm failures, of course, have obvious
implications for device safety. Electrical or mechanical device failure can
affect the user interface in a way that confuses or misleads users. Sometimes a
device failure has produced improper or cryptic data display without the device
alerting the user that it is no longer functional. The impact of device failure
upon the users should be assessed prior to production and marketing.<P>

<i>Device Maintainability</i><P>

Medical devices should be designed for simple maintenance, since device
reliability sets an upper limit on safe, reliable operation. Maintenance
personnel often encounter the following problems:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Poor component labeling or coding.<P>
<LI>Inadequate self-diagnostic capability.<P>
<LI>Parts that are hard to locate visually or by touch.<P>
<LI>Screws and parts that are difficult to reach or manipulate.<P>
<LI>Confusing component arrangements.<P>
<LI>Requirements for difficult-to-find tools.<P>
<LI>Inadequate design for easy cleaning.</UL><P>

The signs of inadequate human factors attention include improperly connected
wires, stripped threads, high unreliability, dirty displays, and sticking keys,
among other things. Devices that are difficult to maintain not only are out of
use for long periods of time, but maintenance personnel may make errors or modify
devices to compensate for deficiencies.<P>

<i>Device Packaging</i><P>

Medical device packaging sometimes affects device operation. For example, there
have been incidents from packaging materials located so that users failed to
detect and remove them; in some cases device function was impaired. With one
infusion pump, serious accidents occurred from residual packaging materials
increasing flow rates. On the other hand, sometimes package design can be used to
reduce the likelihood of error. For example, catheters and compatible guide wires
usually are packaged together. The same is true of needles and syringes, some
infusion pumps and dedicated administration sets, and various contact lens
accessories. A unique example is a customized container cover having an integral
spacer that separates tissue heart valve leaves. The earlier use of cotton to
accomplish this had induced the formation of massive clots, leading to several
deaths.<P>

<i>Summary</i><P>

The effects of biomechanical stresses, negative transfer, failure modes,
maintainability, and packaging often are subtle and hard to identify. But they
must not be overlooked. The following section on human factors engineering deals
with methods that are used to design devices that are reasonably free from the
various design problems discussed up to this point.<P>

<center><h3>HUMAN FACTORS ENGINEERING*</h3></center><P>

* Although this section "talks to" the designer, the information should be of
interest to FDA personnel and health practitioners, as well. The discussion
further explains the rationale for human factors and may help clarify
expectations about device design and safety.<P>

Human factors engineering is a systematic, iterative process that is critical to
the effective user-interface design. Although product developers sometimes
believe that market studies provide most of the necessary human factors
information, such views are misleading. Some preference data obtained in market
research may prove useful, but human factors engineering involves the exercise of
various methods and tools throughout the design cycle. The developers of
commercial products, such as computers, have adopted and sometimes refined such
methods, referring to their efforts as <i>usability engineering</i>. Of
particular note
is their emphasis on user studies and computerized prototypes for testing and
analysis.<P>

Human factors engineering must be integral to both hardware and
software development to be effective. The members of the design team should
coordinate their efforts to gather analytical and user performance data to
achieve a user interface design that lends itself to safe device assembly,
operation, installation, and maintenance.<P>

<b>Overview and Rationale</b><P>

A new product development project, of course, can begin in any number of ways.
The initial concept may emerge from research, brain-storming, analysis, or
interviews and observations involving device users, designers, market
researchers, managers, or some combination of the above. As shown in the figure
on the next page, the tools and resources  for the effort may include incident
reports, technical articles, predicate devices, data from the medical community,
and expert opinion. Articles on device research and concepts, as well as
published product evaluations, provide a wealth of information about user
problems that are  associated with either specific models or with device types.
Finally, human factors guidelines should be used.<P>

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/design/xraydesign6.gif" alt="This graphic shows the Human Factors
Engineering Process."></center><P>


The critical requirement for human factors engineering is access to individuals
from the user population and their participation throughout the developmental
stages. Users contribute essential interview and observation data, and -they are
necessary for prototype testing. Also, along with subject-matter-experts, users
are valuable for analyses, scenario development, and brainstorming. Generally,
the sequence of analyses, studies, and tests rarely proceeds precisely in the
manner depicted in flow diagrams. No two projects are the same The following
factors, among others, will influence the flow of a given project<P>

<UL>
<LI>Pre-existing data<P>
<LI>Experience with predicate devices<P>
<LI>Complexity a the device<P>
<LI>A product's similarity to an existing one<P>
<LI>Criticality of the device<P>
<LI>Resources and organizational culture<P>
<LI>Design practices<P>
<LI>Competitive market pressures</UL>
<P>

Although there is latitude with respect to the analyses, tests, and tools
utilized, the process should not be haphazard. The design team should carefully
<i>plan</i> the human factors effort. Despite substantial variability among
different development projects, the <i>rationale</i> for human factors
engineering is the
same. Remember, the process is iterative, and participants from the user
population
play an essential a role throughout the effort. There is some trial-and-error,
but the larger problems are detected and eliminated during the earlier stages,
before the design is "hardened." The remainder of this section describes the
methods used by human factors professionals in designing equipment
user-interfaces.<P>

<b>DOCUMENT REVIEWS</b><P>

Documents on human factors and related device issues are valuable early in
development. Such information usually is easy to obtain and is useful in
understanding general and device-specific user interface issues, as well as human
factors methods.<P>

<i>The Literature</i><P>

Human factors articles, technical reports, and textbooks offer substantial
information. Numerous journals, magazines, and newsletters report studies and
surveys on the combined effects of design, environment, and work conditions upon
medical device operation. Also of value are design case studies and product
evaluations. Research, design, and conceptual articles of value also can be found
in human factors publications, such as <i>Human Factors, Ergonomics, and
Ergonomics
in Design</i>. Textbooks offer a more broad-based view of human factors
principles,
the design process, environmental factors, and the human being as an operator.
One will find both general discussions of sensory, physical, and cognitive
characteristics, as well as sensory-perceptual data. Finally, technical reports,
standards, and guidelines from government and military agencies can be useful.<P>

<i>Incident Reports and Recall Data</i><P>

A company's own recall data will provide historical data that may lead to
important insights about potential problems and design solutions relevant to new
product development . Review of reports to the FDA Medical Device Reporting (MDR)
system on your own devices or related to problems uncovered across a device area
may be enlightening. Although the reporting protocol traditionally has treated
use errors and design as separate issues, one can glean substantial information
from this source via careful analysis. In fact, such information may flag
numerous problems during the feasibility phase, before a development project is
underway.<P>

<i>Guidelines</i><P>

Guidelines provide principles, data, and human factors engineering methods. An
example of a principle might be something such as "There should be feedback
displayed immediately following a user input via a control, key, switch, or other
input device." Data may be of various types: anthropometric, angles, dimensions,
visual or auditory limits, etc. Methodology and tools are discussed in this
section.<P>

The most widely recognized guideline in the medical device community is the AAMI
document, <i>Human factors engineering guidelines and preferred practices for the
design of medical devices</i>, published in 1993. There are other guidelines
published by government agencies, notably in military standards and guidelines.
In addition, some textbooks are written as guidelines.<P>

Guidelines should be used judiciously. They are <i>not intended as
"cookbooks,"</i> and
one should remember that the effectiveness of a guideline is in part determined
by the education and skill of the person using it. Understanding the
<i>rationale</i> 
behind any principle or methodology is critical.<P>

<i>Manuals</i><P>

Review of <i>User instruction manuals for existing devices</i> can yield
information
about pitfalls to avoid and possible features to include when considering the
development of a new product. For example, a warning like "be careful of
automatic flowrate defaults " indicates that such defaults may not be clearly
signaled or, possibly, may not be really desirable in the first place. Or, the
review and comparison of the written operating procedures and control panel
illustrations may point to a number of strengths or weaknesses in key layout,
operating logic, and other user interface concerns during new product
development.<P>

Once the user interface concept begins to take shape, work on <i>user instruction
manuals for the new device</i> should begin. If this is coordinated closely with
the
design effort, the very process of developing the new manual may uncover design
problems.<P>

<i>Summary</i><P>

Reviewing the types of documents discussed above will help provide a clearer
picture of the following:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Sensory, perceptual, physical and cognitive characteristics of people.<P>
<LI>Environmental interactions with human performance, especially as mediated by
user
interface design.<P>
<LI>Human factors principles and methods.<P>
<LI>Generic problems associated with medical device types.<P>
<LI>Strengths and weakness of both predicate devices and the concept for the
device
under development.</UL><P>

Document reviews help to ask the right questions, avoid pitfalls, and get product
design process off on the right track.<P>

<b>EXPLORATORY STUDIES</b><P>

Obtaining first-hand information from doctors, nurses, and lay-users is essential
in assessing the strengths and weaknesses of device designs. Other potential
participants to consider are risk managers, maintenance personnel, trainers, and
supervisors. Questionnaires, on-duty observations, interviews, and focus tests
are methods used to assess design concepts, mockups, or predicate devices.<P>

<i>Why Do Such Studies?</i><P>

Direct contact with the user population is absolutely essential for good human
factors work, and it should be initiated in the earliest conceptual stages of
product design. Observations and remarks about existing devices, desirable design
features, and working conditions will provide the following:<P>

<UL>
<LI>A snapshot of how health professionals use their devices, how operating
conditions (including the multi-device environment), affect use, and what
problems are encountered.<P>
<LI>A sampling of the user population with respect to individual differences.<P>
<LI>Design and engineering staff familiarization with the device use
environment.<P>
<LI>Ideas for new designs and reactions to design concepts.<P>
<LI>Information necessary for establishing performance test protocols and
performance criteria.</UL><P>

Early studies, along with document reviews and task analyses, will get the design
process off in the right direction. They engender creative thinking and reduce
the likelihood of major mistakes in the design process.<P>

<i>Study Methods</i><P>

Planning ahead is a "must". Carefully consider the logistics and costs associated
with access to facilities and personnel, project staff, and equipment. In
addition, pilot work involving observational and interviewing procedures is
highly desirable.<P>

Below is a brief discussion of some techniques frequently used in early studies.
They are not independent of one another, and techniques discussed elsewhere such
as task analysis, may also be integrated into these approaches.<P>

<b>Observation:</b> In a medical facility the operating rooms, emergency rooms,
and critical-care units are fertile areas for observational studies. These
include the observation of <i>ongoing operations</i> and the inspection of
devices
<i>following operation</i>, especially after prolonged use. There are
implications for
such areas as design for maintenance, cleaning, installation, and the effects of
environmental conditions upon the user interface. In the operating environment,
substances such as dirt, water, saline solutions, alcohol, blood, and coffee
often impede proper device use.<P>

Wherever studies are conducted, observations should be non-intrusive and as
systematic as possible. Observations can be recorded as narrative description
and/or as entries on data sheets formatted with predetermined data categories.
Demographic and device information also should be recorded. When videotaping a
session, the tapes should be indexed by critical events and times to avoid
extremely time-consuming review at a later time. Another issue is the sampling of
subjects and operating conditions. Within the scope of time and resources
available, observing different users under varying work conditions is desirable
to ensure generality of the observations made.<P>

<b>Interviews:</b> Interviewing is a very flexible way of obtaining such
information as
opinions about specific devices and problems, user preferences, and ideas about
improving user-interface design. Interviews also can be conducted quickly and in
conjunction with observations. Below are a few ideas about interviewing personnel
in medical facilities.<P>

<b><i>Interviewing Users:</i></b> Health practitioners often hold perceptions
about a device
that differ greatly from the designer's. Interviewers can obtain valuable data by
having doctors or nurses do the following:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Describe "critical incidents" involving a device.<P>
<LI>Walk through the operational steps.<P>
<LI>Compare relative strengths and weaknesses of different models.<P>
<LI>Recommend device changes.<P>
<LI>Assess a new device concept.</UL><P>

Whatever is done, remember that interviewees usually won't be able to visualize
design concepts in the abstract. They should react to existing devices (ideally
presented during the interview), mockups, or drawings of a device interface. In
the latter instance, the proposed operational logic should be clear. Allowing
people to react to tangible concepts and actual devices will provide a wealth of
ideas. Questions such as those in the adjacent blood glucose monitor
illustration, can help to target design problems.<P>

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/design/xraydesign7.gif" alt="This graphic discusses user reactions to
a blood glucose monitor."></center><P>


<b><i>Interviewing Supervisors, Trainers, and Risk Managers:</i></b> Most
supervisors have
fairly broad views of device strengths and weaknesses. They are aware of serious
incidents and device characteristics that have been substantial impediments to
productivity. The training staff will have a more detailed picture of the effects
of poor design on training time, as well as recommendations about the
instructional manuals. Risk managers document problems, including incidents, that
can shed light on specific design problems.<P>

<b><i>Maintenance Personnel and Technicians:</i></b> These parties may have a
unique
perspective on device problems. For example, poor design for installation and
possibly examples of misinstalled components may come to light. Also, users often
bring them "broken" devices that, in fact, are functional; they simply are
difficult to operate! Finally, since recalled devices often are modified on site
by company service representatives, they may know of both hardware and software
fixes related to the user interface.<P>

<b>Conducting Focus Groups:</b> Focus group sessions are group interviews with a
few
individuals (e.g., 8 -10) from a specified population conducted to obtain
opinions and ideas with regard to a product concept. A focus group would consist
of a few health practitioners, ideally people from different facilities. These
individuals would be prospective users of the new device under consideration.
Such sessions should be conducted by experienced moderators working from scripts
prepared in concert with the design team. Well-conducted sessions yield numerous
ideas about both user-interface design alternatives and user requirements.
However, since device users generally have limited knowledge of design
alternatives and principles, <i>subjective data must be weighed against known
interface characteristics, human factors expertise, and user performance
data.</i><P>

<b>Physical Measurements:</b> Measuring sound and light will help in the
assessment of
such design-moderated environmental factors as glare, contrast, and the masking
of auditory alarms by ambient noise. Samples from different facilities will
produce data useful for profiling typical work environments, and such profiles
may be useful during actual design.<P>

<i>Summary</i><P>

Modest studies such as those discussed in this section will pay handsome
dividends. The design team gains a better appreciation of the user population,
their working environment, problems with predicate devices, and viable
alternatives for new designs.<P>

<b>ANALYSIS</b><P>

Various analyses are important to good user interface design, and these  include
analyses of functions, tasks, and hazards. Such analyses will help shape the user
interface by providing information about the following:<P>

<UL>
<LI>User needs and characteristics.<P>
<LI>Potential performance bottlenecks and error-inducing factors.<P>
<LI>Device impacts upon user training.<P>
<LI>Device operating logic. <P>
<LI>Potential hazards.</UL><P>

Analyses are woven throughout the development process and merit careful
attention.<P>

<i>Functions and Tasks Defined</i><P>

Considering the device and user together as a system, their actions can be
considered <i>functions</i>. Primary functions are device installation,
maintenance, operation, and monitoring. In the human factors profession, the
user's functional contributions are referred to as tasks. For example, a number
of infusion pump functions are necessary for accomplishing its intended use, and
to some extent these functions are shared by the device and the user. As an
illustration, one user task is the entry of flowrate data, the device function
being the pump action in response to the user's input. Or, regarding monitoring,
the pump monitors pressure and rate and displays the estimated flowrate values,
which in turn the user monitors. In addition, if pressure exceeds or falls short
of specified limits, the device will alarm. Likewise, the user will "alarm" if he
notices out-of limit values.<P>

<i>Addressing Functional Issues</i><P>

Increasingly, devices are multi-functional in order to accommodate a wider range
of users and to increase the flexibility of device application. Such capability
can impede ease of device use unless the respective assignments of functions to
the device and the user are carefully weighed. Machines are good at functions
such as storage and retrieval of coded data, rapid computation, and timing, among
others. People outperform machines in sensory, judgmental, interpretative, and
creative tasks. Functional sophistication and the allocation of functions between
a device and its user have very important implications for the eventual user
interface, and the following hypothetical example is a case in point.<P>

Scenario<P>

<blockquote>An infusion pump designer decides to provide the user with the
capability to "stack" flow rates, i.e., programming a sequence of rates that will
apply to successive patient administrations. The rate-retrieval function is now
added to the conventional rate-input function. A number of questions arise:
Should retrieval and administration of rates be automatic or manual? What happens
if one of the queued flowrates is accidentally deleted, defaulting to the next
flowrate "in line"? How does the user identify and track the flowrates? How does
the user access and change given flowrates? How are other device functions
coordinated with the different rates?</blockquote><P>

These are questions to be addressed very early. The answers will help shape the
functional design, which, in turn will determine the user-interface
alternatives.<P>

Many functions-related issues are linked to the complicated interrelationships of
user characteristics, individual variability, operating conditions, and
criticality of various functions. For example, in a ventilator, illustrated
below, the degree to which alarm settings should be automated or under user
control depends upon the latitude required by the user. Such factors as user
expertise, other equipment alarms, and criticality of alarmed conditions must be
considered with respect to allowable user discretion in setting alarm limits and
silencing, disabling, and resetting alarms. Some functional questions are even
more difficult. In some cases excessive functions may overburden users no matter
what the interface solution is. The other extreme is the case in which automation
can simplify operation to the point that the operator becomes bored or "loses the
picture," and the flexibility to respond to an emergency is lost. Most functional
issues are not this difficult, but the appropriate tradeoffs must be considered
before the design concept evolves much further.<P>

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/design/xraydesign8.gif" alt="This graphic shows that alarms on
monitors and ventilators pose difficult questions about allocating
functions."></center><P>


<i>Analyzing Tasks</i><P>

At various points during development the design team should perform detailed
sequential analyses of those tasks that comprise such functions as assembly,
installation, operation, and maintenance. Task analysis is (critical to good
human factors engineering and is performed throughout the design process. In the
early conceptual stages critical tasks can be identified and described by
observing and/or questioning health professionals who use the type of device
being considered for development. When design concepts are initially formulated,
the analyses will be conducted as paper-and-pencil exercises. As development
progresses, analyses will be performed with the help of such tools as device
descriptions, drawings, predicate devices and prototypes.<P>

Regarding procedures, there are many methodological "variations on a theme", but
task analysis is straightforward. Depending upon scope and purpose, the analyst
will do some, or all, of the following:<P>

<UL>
<LI>List the major tasks, such as calibration, entering operating parameters, or
attaching the device to patient.<P>
<LI>For each task, describe the necessary information, user actions, required 
decisions, and related components.<P>
<LI>For each action, or step, describe the equipment response.<P>
<LI>Record observations and inferences about design factors potentially impacting
the user.<P>
<LI>List the effects of environmental conditions on the user interface and
performance, and the impact of the user interface on training
requirements.</UL><P>

A subject matter expert and individuals from the device user population should
participate in the initial analyses, when the design concept is starting to take
shape. A task analysis format is an organizing structure that permits the analyst
to record data in a form that facilitates coherent integration of behavioral and
device information.<P>

On the next page is a table with a few sample steps from an analysis of a
marketed infusion pump as part of a pilot research study at CDRH. The analysts
were "troubleshooting" the user interface design. Following the table is a brief
description of the analysis and related field work in a scenario form.<P>

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/design/xraychart.gif" alt="This chart is entitled Sample of a Few Task
Analysis Steps from Analysis of Actual Pump: Troubleshooting the User
Interface."></center><P>

<font size =-1><b>Note</b>: Double function PAUSE/STOP key works operates differently in different
modes, and it also "remembers" first activation across modes. User easily can
turn off device by accident.</font><P>

Discussion of Analysis<P>

<blockquote>The infusion pump seemed very "easy to use." The human factors team
traversed the initial setup steps with seemingly little difficulty. But shortly
into the exercise, problems arose. First we had been operating on the assumption
that the pump was plugged in when, in fact, it wasn't. The battery and AC power
icons were poorly located, small, and had little iconic value. The icons were so
small that they appeared as little "dots" at normal viewing distances and angles.
We also discovered that users could miss important status information and prompts
due to very brief displays of the data. Another problem was a flowrate default
mechanism that could mislead users. In addition, with fast-scrolling flowrate
values, the desired value could easily be exceeded (or lower than intended, upon
recycling); poorly correlated visual and auditory feedback contribute to this
potentially dangerous situation. Finally, inconsistencies in a double function
key operation can exacerbate other problems by confusing and frustrating the
user. The research team visited a hospital after performing this analysis, and,
by chance, this pump was used in the unit visited. The head nurse stated that she
had selected it because it seemed "user friendly." Unfortunately, the unit staff
found it so difficult to use that she now considers the pump not only an
inconvenience, and an impediment to safety and effectiveness.</blockquote><P>

During the development of the pump in this example, had task analyses been
performed, <i>a set of guiding principles for pump setup, such as the following,
might have emerged</i>. They night have looked something like the following:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Status indication and feedback should be precise and unambiguous.<P>
<LI>Displayed alerts should be attention-getting and in view until acted upon.<P>
<LI>Flow rate and volume entry mechanisms should be convenient for the user, but
without sacrificing accuracy (e.g., over-scrolling).<P>
<LI>Specific keys should operate in a consistent manner across modes.</UL><P>

The next section recommends that human factors be integrated into product
development procedures conventionally used to isolate potentially hazardous
device failures.<P>

<i>Hazard Analyses</i><P>

<i>Hazard analysis</i> usually is performed to assess the hazards associated with
electrical or mechanical failures. Considering users as components in fault tree
and failure mode criticality analyses is also important. In <i>Fault Tree
Analysis
(FTA)</i> one can consider catastrophic incidents as "fault"s, analytically
isolating
the failures, or potential errors causing them. Conversely, using <i>Failure Mode
Effects Analysis (FMCA)</i>, one could start with "failures", or user errors,
"faults". The utility of these approaches can be illustrated by reference to
infant insertion of patient leads into AC power cords by parents, siblings, and
health professionals. This is depicted in the accompanying illustration. By first
anticipating such hazards, an analyst could have deduced causal errors. Or, the
same end could be accomplished by first hypothesizing possible errors. Either
case represents a 'What-if" scenario for all intents and purposes. It is
important to note that <i>hazard analyses may pinpoint low-frequency errors not
discovered in prototype tests involving users.</i><P>

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/design/xraydesign9.gif" alt="This graphic discusses using hazard
analyses to identify hazards and solutions for them."></center><P>

<i>Other Analyses</i><P>

Finally, other human factors techniques are <i>time lines and workload
analysis</i>.
Time lines represent sequential and simultaneous responses required of the user
and graphed over time. Workload analysis can produce measures ranging from
estimated energy expenditures for physical tasks to subjective and performance
measures associated with task loading. Task loading refers to additional
performance requirements imposed on operators. Both of these methodologies are
especially useful in multi-task situations which often involve the use of more
than one device by the user or users.<P>

<i>Summary</i><P>

Thorough analysis is a powerful tool and is necessary throughout the design
process. Overall, the findings help shape alternative user interface designs,
elucidate design flaws, and provide focus for human factors tests.<P>

<b>USABILITY TESTING</b><P>

Although the literature, small studies, and analyses will continue to be valuable
following the early product development stages, performance testing becomes
increasingly important as the design concept is refined. The "proof of the
pudding" is the ability of users to operate, install, and maintain devices safely
and effectively, and this can be assured only via testing.<P>

<i>Rationale</i><P>

Testing must be understood in the context of iterative design, which includes
inputs such as observations, opinions, human factors principles, and research.
The expertise of designers, health professionals, human factors professionals,
and researchers all feed into the actual design. Design concepts must be
subjected to <i>dynamic</i> tests as they become increasingly refined. There is
no
better way than having users perform simulated tasks using prototypes that embody
the user-interface design concepts<P>

<i>Prototyping</i><P>

From the human factors perspective, prototypes are representations of the user
interface, as defined by both the hardware and software. As development
progresses, the prototypes increase in <i>fidelity</i>, the degree of resemblance
to a
working device. Examples include story boards, screen prints, interactive
computer models, mockups, simulators, and working models. In prototype testing,
there are two interrelated fidelity issues the physical components with which
users interact and the more abstract, <i>conceptual device characteristics</i>
that help
define such interactions. Their relative importance depends on the purpose of a
given test. If installation and control or display layout and size are of special
interest, for example, a mockup probably would be used for simulated tasks. But
if underlying machine logic and information presentation are of concern,
prototypes ranging from a progressive series of story boards or interactive
screen displays to a working model should be employed to evaluate user efficiency
in task accomplishment. To some extent the impact of machine logic on performance
is a function of the prototype capability to respond to data entry with
appropriate information display. But even low fidelity prototypes can be valuable
as long as the critical procedural and informational characteristics are conveyed
to the user.<P>

<b>Non-Interactive Prototypes</b>: Modest testing sometimes begins early in
development
and may be combined with the exploratory tests and analyses described earlier. An
early test might consist of a user, or users, completing simulated tasks by
performing data entry operations on a sequence of story boards by indicating the
correct key or control, verbally describing the actions. Each user input is
followed by the presentation of a new board showing the feedback, prompts, or
status change appropriate to that input. Both performance accuracy and comments
will point to potential bottlenecks, errors, and design improvements.<P>

<b>Interactive Prototypes</b>: These increasingly are used throughout
development, and
they engender more realism in task performance than do story boards, screen
prints, and other static representations. Key panels and controls can be
represented graphically on a computer, with limited functionality programmed in.
Thus, for example, a finger press on a specific "button", simulated on a touch
screen, could result in apparent button movement followed by displayed feedback.
The program then sets up the contingencies for the next operator response."
Horizontal" prototypes allow activation of a wide range of data inputs without
much operational depth; that is, hierarchical menu depth is minimal. 'Vertical"
approaches allow more in-depth operation of fewer functions; for example, one or
two menu hierarchies might be fully accessible. Also, a limited number of task
paths can be programmed, depending upon test focus. Of course, the most incisive
data will be obtained with working and production models.<P>

<i>Planning, Designing, and Conducting a Test</i><P>

Testing requires much deliberation and planning. Below is a discussion outlining
the test process.<P>

<b>Purpose of the Test:</b> Factors such as developmental stage, previous or
anticipated
problems, and design alternatives will determine the purpose and focus of a test.
Some tests are conducted largely to uncover user interface problems, while in
other cases the purpose may be to assess a new design concept versus another
manufacturer's product to provide benchmarks of user performance. Or, overall
efficiency, performance times, influence of environmental factors, or interactive
effects of other equipment may be of interest.<P>

<b>Requirements and Measures:</b> User requirements are based primarily on the
earlier
interviews, observations, and literature reviews. Some requirements are specific,
such as "Installation should take no more than 30 minutes." In other instances,
they may be broader, such as "Novice users should reach high levels of efficiency
after a few hours of training." A precise definition of efficiency in terms of
errors and time can be hard to determine precisely while the design concept is in
a state of flux, but at some point in development a clearer picture of expected
performance levels will emerge, and detailed performance criteria need to be
defined. If possible, they should be quantitative, and they should be linked to
safe use and any other goals important to the manufacturer and user
population.<P>

Various measures are used in testing. Errors may be recorded by direct
observation, videotaping, or electronic data logging. Speed of operation is based
on task completion times, and other objective measures may be utilized, such as
number of times the user must refer to the device manual. Verbal responses also
are important and can be obtained via interviews or by having users state the
rationale for their actions as they progress through task sequences. Also
important are subjective impressions of usability and potential safety
problems.<P>

<b>Facilities:</b> Depending upon resources and nature of the test, a very modest
usability laboratory may suffice. A "bare-bones" lab might consist of a room
containing a table, chairs, electrical outlets, and adequate lighting. An
increasingly elaborate setup would include a one-way mirror, observation room,
video camera(s), rheostatic lighting, tape player (for noise presentation), an
automated data-logging system, a microphone, and other medical equipment.
Finally, as discussed later, testing in medical facilities is another
possibility.<P>

<b>Test Subjects:</b> As with other human factors studies, subjects should be
representative of the user population. If the device is used by a fairly
homogenous population, data obtained with about 10 individuals from that
population <i>may</i> be sufficient to eliminate most usability problems. The
design
team must consider the extent to which additional problems are uncovered as more
subjects are added and/or as more tests are run. Also, with a more heterogenous
population, larger samples are desirable. A larger sample also is necessary if
comparisons between different device models are of concern. Finally, the test
team may want to maximally stress the user interface by utilizing subjects having
relatively little experience with the type of device being tested.<P>

The number of subjects also will depend on the stage of product development.
Iterative tests using story boards or early prototypes can be  accomplished with
few subjects, especially if the test focus is the assessment of a few design
changes. However, in thorough tests of high fidelity prototypes, such as working
and production models, a larger subject sample definitely is necessary.<P>

<b>Conducting the Test:</b> Written <i>scenarios</i> will provide the organizing
structure for
what the subjects actual  will be doing. A scenario generally is a written
description of what the subject is expected to accomplish, and the description
may be broad or narrowly-focused. In the former, the subject might be asked to
turn on an infusion pump, for example, and set it up for drug administration. The
subject would progress through all the necessary tasks. But given a narrower test
focus, subjects might be asked to complete only tasks of special concern, an
example being the following: "Key in the appropriate flowrate and
volume-to-be-infused parameters." Whether subjects are given broad, narrow,
short, or long scenarios, these should be clearly written down to help ensure
consistency across subjects and test conditions. Health professionals will be of
use in checking the scenarios for realism and accuracy, as well as helping to
create them.<P>

On the next page is an example of a scenario that might be used in the assessment
of an arrhythmia monitor user-interface design. It consists of an illustration of
a monitor followed by a narrative that requests the subjects to perform various
tasks. This will help the test team obtain data on errors, performance times, and
subjects' impressions of device design features. Analysis and evaluation of this
data will answer the kinds of questions listed under the monitor figure.<P>

Example Scenario<P>

<blockquote>First ready the monitor for use by checking the receiver and recorder
connections. After switching the power on, switch on the monitor and perform the
basic setup tasks, such as checking and adjusting the calibration, amplitude,
gain, and alarm limits. When prompted, retrieve waveforms and trend data as
specified. Report any visual alarms, such as disconnected lead wires or a low
battery.</blockquote><P>

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/design/xraydesign10.gif" alt="This graphic shows a monitor
interface."></center><P>


Generally the device users selected as the test subjects should be health
professionals who are not trained on the specific model. After a subject receives
brief familiarization with the monitor, there are different ways the test team
can proceed. It could permit the subject to run through the operations at his own
pace or, at any point, interrupt with questions about bottlenecks or apparent
problems. If certain issues are of special interest, the test might focus on
these, spending less time on others.<P>

When conducting tests, it often makes sense to really <i>stress the user
interface.</i>
This can be accomplished by giving the user minimum device familiarization and
limiting use of the instruction manual. Also, testing novice device users imposes
a greater burden on the interface.<P>

Possible performance measures in the example scenario could include set-up times;
number of errors; type of errors, failures to detect and discriminate alarms; and
any observations that indicate performance obstacles. In addition, if the subject
is asked to "think aloud" as he proceeds through the tasks, it is important to
develop a record of his remarks. Finally, pre- and post- test questionnaires or
interview comments, likes and dislikes about user interface elements,
preferences, as and other comments about overall device safety and usability
issues are valuable. One caveat, however, is that users generally are
inexperienced with design principles. Although user opinions generally are
valuable, their <i>preferences for various interface designs must be weighed
against
performance data and expert opinion</i>.<P>

<i>Testing in the "Real" Environment</i><P>

The user interface should be tested under conditions that are as realistic as
possible. The following section discusses levels of reality in human factors
testing.<P>

<b>Simulating Actual Conditions in the Lab</b>: Some aspects of actual use
conditions are reasonably easy to simulate. For example, adjustable lighting and
individual lamps of varying wattage and directionality will produce variable
levels of illumination and glare. Likewise, tape recordings from emergency rooms,
operating rooms, and critical care facilities will reproduce decibel and
frequency levels that challenge alarm audibility and the user's concentration.<P>

More difficult to simulate are patient and device status and the interactive
effects of multiple devices; but fairly good simulations are possible. In the
monitor example above, changes in patient and device status could be simulated by
programming in ECG changes and alarms. In multiple device scenarios, test
subjects can alternate between different devices they typically use on the job.
Variables might include conflicting user interface designs and problems
associated with device attachments.<P>

<b>Simulations in Health Facilities</b>: Even without patients involved,
performance testing in health facilities can add substantial realism. If on duty
doctors and nurses are tested on devices that effectively simulate device
interfaces and functions, the effects of stress and fatigue on device use can be
assessed. But obviously, testing in emergency rooms, operating rooms, or critical
care facilities is difficult, if not impossible. Because tests are obtrusive,
testing in many cases probably should be performed during breaks and be limited
to especially problematic design issues. The exception would be a full simulation
in which physicians, nurses, or medical team performs a lengthy, simulated,
procedure. The facility, such as an operating room, essentially becomes a
laboratory.<P>

<b>Clinical Trials</b>: Ideally, one could do full testing during clinical
trials. However, there are very definite limits. First, manipulating and
measuring health practitioners' behavior can endanger patients. Second, the user
interface design should be at least adequate <i>prior</i> to clinical trials. But
these
factors don't preclude some testing at this stage. Doctors and nurses can be
alerted to design issues of special interest and interviewed after the completion
of procedures. Finally, observations by a team consisting of designers and
clinically-trained individuals can be fruitful.<P>

<i>Summary</i><P>

Obtaining performance and subjective data from actual users is crucial. If test
subjects cannot safely and effectively use a device under test conditions, you
can be sure performance under actual conditions will not meet these criteria.
Thorough testing helps ensure that the final product meets the needs of health
professionals and patients.<P>

<center><h3>SPECIAL ISSUES FOR MANUFACTURERS AND HEALTH FACILITIES</h3></center>

<b>INITIATING A COMPANY HUMAN FACTORS PROGRAM</b><P>

<i>Personnel</i><P>

Just as no two product development projects are identical, the same can be said
of corporations. Size, organization, and culture vary from firm to firm, and all
of these will affect the implementation of a human factors program. Whether
relying primarily on consultants or on in-house staff having experience with
human factors engineering, integrating human factors personnel into project
design teams is crucial.<P>

Also, it behooves manufacturers to educate both technical and managerial staff
about human factors, and the target audience should include engineers, designers,
manual and training developers, risk managers, quality managers, and corporate
executives. At the most basic level, staff need to know what a human factors
program is and why it is important. One should consider having a human factors
consultant give a few seminars and maybe doing a demonstration test. Involving a
company's own designers and products will greatly increases the effectiveness of
such a demonstration. Case studies also are useful, and these can be developed
around hypothetical problems or successful applications of human factors.
Likewise, consultants' first-hand experience with development efforts design
principles, liability issues, the human factors literature and research, and
other subjects will make any such presentations tangible and interesting.
Finally, there are established professional short courses in human factors, and
many universities offer degree programs in this discipline. There is a caveat,
however. Casual "armchair" approaches do not work! Training and experience are
necessary.<P>

<i>How Much Human Factors Attention is Necessary?</i><P>

Although there is no formula for deciding how extensive a human factors effort
must be, consideration of some basic variables will facilitate decision making.
Consider the following:<P>

<UL>
<LI>The nature of the user-device interaction, the user population, and the use
environment.<P>
<LI>The likelihood and criticality of errors. <P>
<LI>The extent to which user interface alternatives are feasible. <P>
<LI>The likelihood that a well-designed user interface will reduce the chance of
errors and consequent injury.</UL>
<P>
For example, in the unlikely case where a device has virtually no user interface
or functional integrity precludes interface design options, a substantial human
engineering effort would not be warranted. However, most devices require
substantially user/device interaction, and the complexity of the interface
usually must be considered. Also, the greater the impact of errors upon the
health and safety of patients, the greater the need for thorough analysis and
testing.<P>

<i>Resources</i><P>

Some resources already have been discussed: the literature, guidelines, and
current staff expertise. Many firms may also need outside help in establishing a
human factors program. There are many highly qualified human factors consultants
and consulting firms available for such purposes. Human factors specialist apply
their expertise to areas ranging from military systems, air-traffic control, and
nuclear power plants to office equipment and, increasingly, medical devices; the
basic rationale and methodology is the same in all of these areas. The societies
listed below serve as clearing houses for human factors consultants. The
addresses were obtained from <i>Medical Device and Equipment Design: Usability
Engineering and Ergonomics</i>.<P>

<i>Addresses</i><P>

<menu>Ergonomics Society<BR>
Rod Graves, Secretary<BR>
University of Technology<BR>
Loughborough, LEIC LE11 3TU<BR>
England<P>

Human Factors and Ergonomics Society (HFES)<BR>
P.O. Box 1369<BR>
Santa Monica, CA 90406<P>

IEEE Systems, Man, and Cybernetics Society<BR>
345 East 47th Street<BR>
New York, NY 10017<P>

Industrial Designers Society of America<BR>
1142-E Walker Road<BR>
Great Falls, VA 22066<P>

Society for Information Display<BR>
8055 W. Manchester Avenue<BR>
Suite 615<BR>
Playa del Rey, CA 90293<P>

Society for Technical Communications (STC)<BR>
Suite 904<BR>
901 North Stuart Street<BR>
Arlington, VA 22203<P>

Special Interest Group on Computer and Human Interaction (SIGCHI)<BR>
Association for Computing Machinery<BR>
P.O. Box 12115<BR>
Church Street Station<BR>
New York, NY 10249<P>

Usability Professionals Association<BR>
Janice James, Chairperson<BR>
American Airlines/STIN<BR>
P.O. Box 619616 MD 4230<BR>
DFW Airport, TX 75261 -9616</menu><P>

<i>Quality Assurance</i><P>

Human factors requirements should be integral to your test and development plan.
As you progress through development, you should check off the major human factors
issues related to the effort. Appendix 1 shows an example of a number of key
questions to ask during the development program. It delineates broad questions,
first about the need  to do human factors human factors engineering, and then
about process and principles.<P>

<b>ADVICE TO HEALTH FACILITIES</b><P>

Recognizing human factors design problems with already purchased devices is
important. The selection of new equipment that staff can operate safely and
efficiently also is important. This section deals with these issues.<P>

<i>Recognizing Problems</i><P>

Health professionals are more likely to blame themselves for errors than they are
to blame the equipment. User interface flaws can be subtle, and doctors' and
nurses' attention is focused on the patient, not the device. Also, a sense of
professional responsibility often precludes "blaming" the device. But <i>while
user
interface problems don't negate one's responsibility for device training and
careful device operation, poor design can greatly increase the likelihood of
errors</i>, and such errors can have serious consequences.<P>

If there are serious design flaws with your equipment, patterns may emerge if you
look hard enough. Ask users about operational problems they've had with a given
device, and try to determine how widespread the problem is. Also, biomedical
engineers and other maintenance personnel constitute a valuable source of
information. In addition to individual interviews, you also could try a focus
group or questionnaire approach, discussed earlier under Exploratory Studies.<P>

<i>Evaluating Already-Purchased Devices</i><P>

Below are some indications of problems:<P>

<b>Observations:</b> Training has been slow and arduous. Only a few staff seem
able to
use the device. Staff tend to modify the equipment or take shortcuts.<P>

<b>Installation Problem:</b> Staff find installation of accessories difficult,
confusing, or overly time-consuming. Alarms and batteries often fail. Incorrect
accessories sometimes are installed. Parts often become detached.<P>

<b>Complaints:</b> Displays are difficult to read or understand. Controls are
poorly
located or labeled. Alarms are difficult to hear or distinguish. Device alarms
are very annoying. Device operation is illogical and confusing.<P>

<b>Incidents:</b> Accidents or "near misses" can be a real tip-off, especially if
there
are highly competent individuals involved. In questioning staff and examining
implicated devices, look for the kinds of problems mentioned above.<P>

Regarding incidents, above, the new coding manual for MedWatch Form 3500A
contains a number of codes having implications for user interface design. These
are found under the "Device-Related Terms", "Results of Evaluation Codes", and
"Conclusion Codes." These should be valuable not only for device-reporting
purposes but also for in-house human factors training and evaluation.<P>

<i>Evaluating Devices Before Purchase</i><P>

Prior to buying a new model, you should consider means of assessing its
usability, especially if it is life-sustaining or life-supporting. Among the
things you can do are the following:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Ask the manufacturer if he has done human factors/usability testing. <P>
<LI>Check with your own people, and possibly other facilities, about predecessor
models made by the manufacturer. Check with other facilities, that may also be
using the new model, as well.<P>
<LI>Check published evaluations of the new model.<P>
<LI>Request a trial period prior to the actual purchase of a new device.</UL><P>

<i>Analyze and Test the Model</i><P>

In doing analyses and tests, there are a few points to keep in mind. Be careful
of biasing the users. The staff should know that <i>it is the device, not the
users,
being tested</i>. If this isn't made clear, users quite likely may feel that
their
performance on devices will be discussed with their superiors,  and thus they
will not be forthcoming about errors and related interface design deficiencies.
Also, should a device be evaluated during actual use on patients, data should be
collected over a reasonable length of time, not just a day or two. In real world
settings, actual problems often emerge slowly and require repeated observations
for identification.<P>

<b>Final Comment:</b> You can do a lot to assess devices you already are using,
as well
as those you are considering for purchase. When you uncover things you
particularly like or dislike, let the manufacturer know. Companies not only are
responsive to their customers, but they <i>want</i> to market medical devices
that meet
your needs for functionality, safety, and effectiveness.<P>

<center><h3>APPENDIX</h3></center><P>

<b>LIST OF KEY HUMAN FACTORS ISSUES</b><P>

In considering the need for, and conduct of, human factors analysis and testing,
there are a number of issues and questions to ask.<P>

<OL>
<LI>Does the device require much user interaction with respect to operation,
maintenance, cleaning, or parts installation? If so, do the technology and device
functions permit different alternative user interface designs?<P>

<LI>Given the combination of user interface, user population, and operating
conditions, are errors likely?<P>

<LI>Could the consequences of error be serious for the patient or user?<P>

<LI>In doing actual testing:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Is someone integral to the design team focusing on the user-related
issues?<P>
<LI>Are users involved?<P>
<LI>Are your hardware and software designers coordinating
their efforts with respect to human factors?<P>
<LI>Have you developed a test plan?</UL><P>

<LI>Have you developed user requirements, and are you updating them? Have you
checked the literature and your own files for useful human factors
information?<P>

<LI>What studies, analyses, and test steps are you performing? Are you examining
all relevant issues related to the installation of accessories and to device
operation.<P>

<LI>Have you done testing in simulated environments; actual environments?<P>

<LI>Have your user requirements been met?<P>

<LI>Have you accounted for any possible interface changes introduced into
production models by manufacturing?</OL><P>

