<html> <title> DESIGN CONTROL GUIDANCE FOR MEDICAL DEVICE
MANUFACTURERS</title><body>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/tpg/gif/tpgpattern.gif">

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/xrayhead.gif" alt="Guide to Medical Device 
Regulation"></center>
<P>

<center> From: The Center for Devices and Radiological Health</center>

<h2>DESIGN CONTROL GUIDANCE FOR MEDICAL DEVICE MANUFACTURERS</h2>

<b>Draft: March 1, 1996</b><P>

This Guidance Relates To FDA 21 CFR 820.30 And Subclause 4.4 Of ISO 9001<P>

March 1996<P>

<center><h3>FOREWORD</h3></center><P>

This guidance is a primer on design controls. It is intended to provide readers
with an understanding of what is meant by "control" in the context of the
requirements. Medical device companies vary considerably in size and structure,
the types of devices produced, methods of design and development, and methods of
management. By providing readers with an understanding of what constitutes
control of a design process, readers can determine how to apply the concepts in a
way that is both consistent with the requirements and best suited for their
particular situation. For example, the scale of operation of a manufacturer can
have considerable impact on the manner in which design controls are implemented.
However, in order for the guidance to be complete, topics indirectly related to
the regulations such as product life cycle and concurrent engineering are
included. The following paragraphs describe additional concepts that should be
kept in mind while reading this guidance.<P>

First, three underlying concepts served as a foundation for development of this
guidance:<P>

<OL>
<LI>The nature of the application of design controls for any device should be
proportional to both the complexity of and the risks associated with that
device;<P>

<LI>The design process is a multifunctional one that involves other departments
beside design and development if it is to work properly. Consequently, senior
management should have an active role in creating an environment in which design
controls can be properly implemented; and,<P>

<LI>The product life cycle concept serves throughout this document as the
framework for introducing and describing the design control activities and
techniques.</OL><P>

Second, design control concepts are applicable to process development as well as
product development. The extent is dependent upon the nature of the product and
processes used to manufacture the product. For example, some in vitro
diagnostics, such as chemical entities, are totally dependent on new methods of
synthesis for their development. Another example is microchip manufacturing
technology that has made pacemakers possible.<P>

Third, the safety and performance of a new product is also dependent on an
intimate relationship between product design robustness and process capability.
Robustness is the ability of the product design to withstand manufacturing
variations and customer usage while still maintaining product quality. Process
capability is a statistical measure of functional stability. For example, a
sterilization process should be stable and capable of sterilizing a product, but
the product should also be designed to be sterilizable. For some product design
manufacturing method combinations, process capability might be proven and the
concern for robustness is minimal. In other combinations, either the design
should be made more robust, or the manufacturing process made more capable to
assure safety and performance.<P>

For completeness, it should be noted that processes can often be designed for
robustness as well. Such processes prevent defects in assemblies. For example, a
threaded fastener that depends upon a proper value of torque can be replaced by a
clip or snap joint, thus avoiding the need to control tolerances. Similarly, if
two wire connections are likely to be improperly connected, the choice of proper
lengths of wire can prevent connection to the wrong terminals.<P>

Finally, some tools and techniques are described in the guidance. Although
aspects of their utility are sometimes described, they are included in the
guidance for illustrative purposes only. Including them does not mean that they
are preferred. The literature contains an abundance of information on tools and
techniques. Such topics as project management, design review, process capability,
and many others referred to in this guidance are available in textbooks,
periodicals, and journals. As a manufacturer applies design controls to a
particular task, the appropriate tools and techniques used by competent personnel
should be applied to meet the needs of the unique product/process for that
task.<P>

<center><h3>1.0 GENERAL</h3></center><P>

Design controls are a set of interrelated techniques and activities that apply to
the design process to ensure that design process objectives are met. Concepts and
topics important to understanding design controls for medical devices and their
successful implementation are device quality, the device life cycle, sequential
versus concurrent engineering, risk management for safety, the role of senior
management, and quality systems.<P>

<b>1.1 DEVICE QUALITY</b><P>

The primary objective of the design process is the design of a quality device.
Describing device quality in technical terms, it is a measure of how closely
device performance matches intended performance over the expected range of
manufacturing variations and expected range of environmental conditions for the
intended use environment for the life of the device. However, device quality has
an even broader meaning. Quality means the totality of features and
characteristics that bear on the ability of a device to satisfy fitness-for-use,
including safety and performance (820.3 (s)). Therefore, a quality device is one
that meets user expectations, both stated and implied. Relating these concepts to
the design process, device quality is achieved by (1) developing design
requirements based on user expectations, and (2) designing a device that conforms
to those requirements, given the production capabilities of the manufacturer and
the expected range in variation of the process during device production.<P>

<b>1.2 DEVICE LIFE CYCLE</b><P>

The design and development of devices, particularly complex ones, is performed in
phases or stages. The phases are elements of a device life cycle model. A design
process that conforms to a life cycle model is preferred because the design
process proceeds in a systematic manner. A simplified diagram of the phases of a
waterfall life cycle model is shown in Figure 1. This particular model presents
the design process from the perspective of verification and validation
activities. A typical life cycle model might include those phases plus others for
production, installation, maintenance, repair, and disposal.<P>

This model represents a sequential design process. Each phase has defined inputs
and outputs. At the end of each phase, work products are completed. A design
review is conducted to assess work products, confirm conformance of outputs to
inputs, and determine if continued development of the device is warranted. If,
for this idealized process, the decision is to proceed, the outputs of a phase
then become the inputs to the next phase, ensuring input/output congruity with
preceding phases. The net effect is the transformation of design input
requirements into a product that conforms to those requirements.<P>

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/guide/xrayguide1.gif" alt="This flowchart is entitled Simplified Flow
Diagram of the Phases of the Waterfall Model Design Process"></center><P>

The phases and principal activities associated with each phase are the
following:<P>

<menu>REQUIREMENTS:  Design input requirements are established.<P>

SPECIFICATIONS:  Requirements are analyzed, and translated into
specifications.<P>

FUNCTIONAL:  Functions are established. The device functional architecture an,
lower-level functions are identified. Lower-level functions are translated into
design criteria.<P>

DESIGN/IMPLEMENTATION:  Product and process solutions are defined and analyzed. A
preferred set of solutions that satisfy functional requirements and define the
physical architecture of the device are selected. Detailed design is completed to
the extent required for implementation. The design is converted into hardware,
software, etc.<P>

TEST:  Testing occurs at the unit, integrated, and systems level to determine if
specifications are met.<P>

FIELD TEST:  Tests are conducted from a user-perspective to determine if user
expectations are met.</menu><P>

<b>1.3 CONCURRENT ENGINEERING</b><P>

Although the sequential design process serves as a useful method for introducing
the concept of conformance, the design process is dependent upon the completion
of one phase before beginning the next one. In practice, this can create
problems. For example, it may not be possible to complete the design input
requirements without acquiring information obtained through evaluation of a
prototype developed in a subsequent phase. Another example is the relationship
between the device design and the manufacturing process design. When constraints
are encountered during design of the manufacturing process that require
reconsideration of the device design, the manufacturing process designer may not
have sufficient knowledge of the device parameters to know which ones are
critical. Even with this knowledge, working with the device designers to make
changes in the device design may not be possible because of the advanced state of
development of the device.<P>

A design process that overcomes many of the problems associated with the
sequential design process is the concurrent engineering process. The goal of
concurrent engineering is the mutual optimization of the crucial characteristics
of a device and their related processes. To meet this goal, the device design,
manufacturing process design, and support process design occur concurrently. The
activities of these design teams is highly integrated including the exchange of
information and data. The teams attempt to mutually take into account all desired
downstream characteristics during the upstream design processes to produce a more
robust design that is tolerant of manufacturing and use variation. A
simplified representation of the upstream design processes is shown in Figure
2.<P>

In general, the concurrent engineering process is driven by scheduled events with
defined deliverables. Therefore, unlike the sequential design process, design
inputs will often initially include estimates so that the development process is
not delayed. The estimated values are replaced as information needed to establish
final values is acquired in the development process. As a result, care must be
taken to assure that design outputs continue to be traceable to the design input
requirements throughout the design process.<P>

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/guide/xrayguide2.gif" alt="This flowchart is entitled Simplified
Representation of Concurrent Engineering Upstream Design Processes"></center><P>

<b>1.4 Risk Management for Safety</b><P>

Risk management is the systematic application of management policies, procedures,
and practices to the tasks of identifying, analyzing, controlling, and monitoring
risk. It is intended to be a framework within which experience, insight, and
judgement are applied to successfully manage risk. Risk management encompasses
many different types of risk including technical, financial, contractual,
schedule, etc. Managing all relevant risks, regardless of type, should be an
integral part of the design process. However, because of the importance of
medical device user and patient safety, the description of risk management in
this guidance is directed to device safety. The principles and practices
described do apply to the management of other types of risk as well.<P>

Risk is the probable rate of occurrence of a hazard causing harm and the degree
of severity of the harm. A hazard is a potential source of harm. Harm, for the
purposes of this guidance, is physical injury and/or damage to health. Safety is
freedom from unacceptable risk of harm. Risk management activities include: (1)
program planning, (2) setting of risk criteria, (3) hazard identification, (4)
risk assessment, and (5) risk reduction and control.<P>

The risk management program is integrated with the design process and risk
management activities occur throughout the design process. Figure 3 is a
simplified flow-diagram of the risk management process.<P>

<center><IMG SRC="/tpg/food/xray/guide/xrayguide3.gif" alt="This flowchart is entitled Simplified Risk
Management Process For Device Safety"></center><P>

<i>1.4.1 Risk Analysis</i><P>

Risk analysis is the investigation of available information to identify hazards
and estimate risk. Risk analysis begins with hazard identification. Many tools
are available for identifying hazards and their cause such as fault tree analysis
(FTA) and, failure mode and effect analysis (FMEA). FTA is a technique that
begins with a potential consequence. Using deductive analysis, lower level fault
conditions that could cause the consequence are identified. FMEA is an inductive
technique by which the frequency and consequences of individual fault modes
related to product functions and components are systematically identified and
evaluated. The type of analysis tool that is used during any particular
development phase should be appropriate for that phase. Generally, deductive or
top-down analysis tools are used early in the design process while inductive or
bottoms-up tools are applied as the device design becomes more detailed. For
example, FTA can be used during conceptual design of the device for all possible
hazards including those from hardware, software, or use of the device.<P>

Risk estimation involves both the estimation of the likelihood of a hazard and
determination of the severity associated with a hazard. Because a hazard can have
more than one cause, estimating likelihood takes all causes into consideration.
Depending on the cause or causes, the method of estimation can be qualitative or
quantitative. Hazard severity is an assessment of the most credible worst case
mishap that could be caused by a hazard. Methods of severity assessment are
qualitative and employ categorization schemes.<P>

<i>1.4.2 Risk Reduction And Control</i><P>

The risk reduction and control activity involves the application of a hazard
control precedence sequence such as the following:<P>

<OL>
<LI>Design to eliminate or minimize hazard <P>
<LI>Provide safety mechanisms <P>
<LI>Provide warning mechanisms <P>
<LI>Control with labeling and training, i.e., the least reliable action <P>
<LI>Accept remaining hazards (Note: Justification and documentation may be
needed.)</UL><P>

The sequence is applied to the cause of each hazard in the order specified. The
preferred and most effective method for controlling the cause of a hazard is to
eliminate it or minimize it through redesign. If that is not possible, safety
mechanisms, such as isolation of a hazard by the use of physical barriers, might
be the next course of action. This procedure of risk control or reduction is
continued until the cause of each hazard has been eliminated or the risk
associated with each remaining hazard is reduced to an acceptable level. The
establishment of an acceptable level of risk may require justification.<P>

There are numerous sources of information available on risk management including
many textbooks on the subject. These sources can be used to acquire more detailed
information on principals and practices including the development and
implementation of risk management programs.<P>

<b>1.5 SENIOR MANAGEMENT</b><P>

Senior management establishes the context within which product design is
performed. It is their responsibility to: (1) decide how the design process is to
be managed and by whom, (2) ensure that adequate resources are available to carry
out the design process in the required time, and (3) ensure that internal
policies are established for issues affecting the design process.<P>

Selection of the project manager, who is responsible for control of the design
project, is a key responsibility. For large projects, senior management may also
establish the management structure for the project including defining the
authorities and responsibilities. If the project manager does not have
jurisdiction over manufacturing, senior management ensures that these functions
are integrated to the degree necessary for the project.<P>

Senior management ensures (1) that skills required for the project are available,
(2) that authorization is granted for training, hiring, and/or contracting for
missing skills, and (3) that required equipment and other resources necessary for
development of the manufacturing process are available.<P>

<UL>
<LI>assessing new product ideas,<P>
<LI>training and retraining of design managers and design staff <P>
<LI>use of external consultants<P>
<LI>subcontracting<P>
<LI>use of company experiential data</UL><P>

<b>1.6 QUALITY SYSTEM</b><P>

Quality system means the organizational structure, responsibilities, procedures,
and resources for implementing quality management (820.3 (v)). Authority for
establishing, implementing, and maintaining the quality system is delegated by
senior management to the manager with executive responsibility. The manager with
executive responsibility ensures that quality requirements for the project are
identified and understood by project management, and properly implemented. This
includes responsibility for establishing quality policies that impact the design
process.<P>

Example of topics for which policies may be appropriate are:<P>

<UL>
<LI>risk management<P>
<LI>device reliability<P>
<LI>device durability<P>
<LI>device maintainability<P>
<LI>device serviceability<P>
<LI>human factors engineering<P>
<LI>software engineering<P>
<LI>use of standards<P>
<LI>configuration management<P>
<LI>compliance with regulatory requirements<P>
<LI>device evaluation, including third party product certification/approval<P>
<LI>clinical evaluations<P>
<LI>the media to be used for the recording of the design information</UL><P>

For large or complex projects, quality system requirements may be in the form of
a project quality plan with defined objectives pertaining to key elements of
quality such as fitness for use, performance, safety, reliability, etc.<P>

<center><h3>2.0 DESIGN AND DEVELOPMENT PLANNING</h3><P>

<b>FDA 21 CFR 820.30 (b) &amp; ISO 9001 Subclause 4.4.2</b></center><P>

Design and development planning is needed to ensure that the design process is
appropriately controlled and that device quality objectives are met. Project
management, regardless of size and complexity, includes the identification of the
tasks to be undertaken and planning when tasks are to begin and end in order to
meet scheduling requirements, including completion of the project. It also
includes development of a list of project milestones, decision points, etc., with
required work products and required completion dates. This list is commonly
referred to as the master schedule. Therefore, to achieve these goals, the
project manager needs an effective method for organizing a network of
interrelated tasks and personnel in a manner consistent with the master schedule.
The method chosen and the detail will vary depending on the complexity of the
project and the level of risk associated with the device.<P>

Planning enables the project manager to have greater control of the design and
development process. Control is maintained by providing the project manager with
the ability to respond to unexpected problems. The design plan provides the
project manager with the capability to answer questions regarding timing of
project activities and evaluate the time and cost implications of resource
tradeoffs. It also provides a comparative reference for gauging progress and
detailing interrelationships between tasks.<P>

<b>2.1 PROJECT PLAN DEVELOPMENT</b><P>

The degree of difficulty in developing a plan is usually a function of the number
of activities or tasks, their sequence, their timing, and the complexity of the
device. For small projects, the plan may consist of only a simple flow diagram,
bar charts, or computer spreadsheets. For larger projects, there are a number of
tools that are used to develop plans. Two of the most commonly used are the
Program Evaluation and Review Technique (PERT) and the Critical Path Method
(CPM). They are two forms of activity network diagrams. Another project
management tool is the Gantt chart. Gantt charts are used to document the
schedule, tasks, and responsibilities necessary to complete a project. Another
important factor affecting planning is the uncertainty associated with complex
tasks being performed for the first time. Contingency planning tools are
available to assist the project manager in selecting alternatives that have the
least serious consequences for the project. The master schedule is developed in a
hierarchical manner listing the accomplishments required for each milestone,
event, decision point, etc., as well as the criteria necessary to demonstrate
achievement.<P>

Each of these methods are described in the literature. Software is available in
many forms for the PERT, CPM, and Gantt methods. When selecting these tools, care
should be taken to choose one that best fits the needs of the project. Some of
the software programs are capable of managing projects such as skyscraper
construction and may be far more complex than necessary.<P>

<i>2.1.1 Organizing Tasks</i><P>

When design tasks have been identified, the estimated completion time,
responsibility, and necessary resources for tasks are established and the order
in which tasks are performed is determined. Tasks are organized according to the
stages of the design process and are consistent with the master schedule. The
design plan establishes, to the extent possible, the time involved for each stage
or phase, the resources and personnel involved and the allocation of
responsibilities. The plan identifies the numbers and types of staff required at
the various stages of the design process, whether all these staff can be found
within the manufacturers' organization, whether new staff is necessary, or
external consultant staff are required. Staff are organized into an appropriate
structure that can be effectively managed.<P>

Tasks for all design process activities including verification and validation are
included. If any clinical evaluation is necessary, any special documentation
required to comply with regulatory procedures is referenced in the plan.
Applicable codes, standards, regulations and specifications are referenced.
Quality assurance practices such as the scheduling of design review meetings,
configuration management activities, documentation requirements, and
authorization requirements are included. The relationships between tasks are
presented in such a way that they are easily understood. Schedules for the
development and delivery of products and processes are mutually supportive. Tasks
on which others depend, tasks that are performed concurrently, and complex tasks
being performed for the first time are evident. The plan is known and understood
by all those involved in the design process.<P>

<i>2.1.2 Expansion And Evolution Of The Plan And Master Schedule</i><P>

Generally, the master schedule and design plan expand over the course of the
project. Unless a manufacturer has experience with the same type of device, the
plan initially consists of only an overview of the tasks, personnel, and
resources required for the project. The master schedule will be limited in scope
and detail as well. The plan and master schedule usually reflect the level of
detail required by project management to make necessary decisions, and provide
confidence in meeting initial schedule and performance objectives. The initial
plan is typically used to identify the skills required for the project, and thus,
identify the members of the design team. As information about the product design
becomes available, the master schedule and plan are expanded and refined.<P>

Eventually, activities are specified at a level of detail necessary for carrying
out the design process in a manner that permits verification that the device
design meets specifications.<P>

The master schedule and design plan also evolve. Changing conditions require that
the project manager continually assess project progress and make appropriate
modifications to the plan and schedule. Inexperience in estimating the time
needed to complete tasks, personnel turnover, unexpected design constraints, and
insufficient resources are examples of the many factors that cause the schedule
and plan to be modified. Modifications to the master schedule and design plan are
approved by the project manager.<P>

<b>2.2 RISK MANAGEMENT PLAN</b><P>

Development of a plan for identifying and controlling hazardous conditions
associated with the device is the responsibility of the project manager. The plan
is developed in accordance with quality system requirements. The plan identifies
tasks that are performed and the resources required for completing those tasks.
Risk management milestones are identified and a meeting schedule is prepared. The
plan includes staff training requirements, the risk assessment and risk
acceptance criteria, the hazard control criteria, the hazard analysis techniques
to be used, and the hazardous condition tracking system to be used for the
project. The estimated time for completing tasks are specified as well as the
order in which tasks are performed. Reviews and milestones are also listed on the
plan. The plan is reviewed for appropriateness, completeness, and traceability to
the design input safety requirements.<P>

The project manager is responsible for (1) integrating the risk management plan
into the master schedule and design plan, (2) providing adequate resources for
risk management tasks, and (3) assuring that the risk management plan is properly
implemented. In some companies, specific positions might be designated for risk
management activities. In other cases, risk management activities are conducted
by individuals as a normal part of their job as designers. In either case, the
project manager assures that the results from risk management activities are
reviewed, and milestones are reached.<P>

Implementation of the plan begins very early in the project. A preliminary hazard
analysis is performed to identify the hazards associated with device concept.
Other risk management tasks are performed concurrently with the design process
and are performed in accordance with the plan. Upon completion of all risk
analysis, risk reduction, and risk control activities, results are reviewed to
ensure that all hazardous conditions are within acceptable limits and that the
device is safe. The project manager assures that the acquired information is
incorporated into the device design.<P>

<center><h3>3.0 ORGANIZATIONAL AND TECHNICAL INTERFACES</h3><P>

<b>FDA 21 CFR 820.30(b) &amp; ISO 9001 Subclause 4.4.3</b></center><P>

When participation in the design process includes a variety of individuals and
functions, their interrelationships and interfaces (as well as the pertinent
responsibilities and authorities) are defined, documented, coordinated and
controlled. For example, quality assurance and manufacturing engineers coordinate
efforts to assure that component and assembly blue prints are not released until
the production process FMEA provides assurance that parts are producible without
defects.<P>

<b>3.1 CONTROL OF INTERFACES</b><P>

Many organizational functions contribute to the design process. These may
include:<P>

<UL>
<LI>research and development<P>
<LI>reliability engineering<P>
<LI>marketing<P>
<LI>purchasing<P>
<LI>quality assurance and quality management<P>
<LI>engineering<P>
<LI>regulatory affairs<P>
<LI>materials technology<P>
<LI>production /manufacturing<P>
<LI>service groups<P>
<LI>facilities management<P>
<LI>warehousing/ transportation/ logistics<P>
<LI>communications facilities<P>
<LI>information systems</UL><P>

It is the responsibility of project manager to ensure that organizational and
technical interfaces associated with the design process are properly controlled.
Job descriptions define the areas of responsibility for members of the design
team. For a large design team divided into a number of groups, the
responsibilities of each group is defined in writing. Where specialist staff are
supporting more than one group or have other conflicting responsibilities,
methods to resolve such conflicts are established.<P>

To function effectively the work groups, both internal and external,
establish:<P>

<UL>
<LI>what information should be received and transmitted<P>
<LI>identification of sending and receiving groups<P>
<LI>the purpose of the information transmittal<P>
<LI>identification of transmittal mechanisms<P>
<LI>document transmittal records to be maintained</UL><P>

As the design progresses, more information becomes available. The ways in which
such information is held, who has access to it, and how it is disseminated is
determined and documented by the project manager. Methods are established to
resolve conflicting positions between groups.<P>

The facilitation of organizational and technical interfaces is a classic example
of working and managing in a matrix organizational structure. There are many
business texts devoted to operations management with emphasis on management
techniques for matrix organizations. For a full description of these techniques,
the reader should study such texts.<P>

<b>3.2 STRUCTURAL BARRIERS</b><P>

It is for senior management to identify structural barriers in the company that
could impede the design process. The degree to which structural barriers are a
problem generally depends upon the company size and organization. Structural
barriers may not be a problem for small companies. However, they can be a
significant problem for larger, highly structured companies. In addition,
identifying those barriers can be a very difficult task. Barriers can be
cultural, technological, or environmental such as the following examples
illustrate: (1) fixed patterns of interaction between engineering and
manufacturing are inappropriate for the design process; (2) each functional
component within the company retains information in a format and manner useful
only to themselves; and (3) the physical separation of functional components,
departments, etc. creates problems with information exchange and meeting
arrangements.<P>

Senior management can control the adverse effects resulting from such barriers by
conveying to company managers (1) the importance of the project within the
context of the company strategies, (2) the commitment of resources to the
project, (3) the authorities and responsibilities of project management, (4) the
responsibilities of function managers in supporting the design process, and (5)
the methods to be used by project management when barriers are encountered.<P>

<center><h3>4.0 DESIGN INPUT</h3><P>

<b>FDA 21 CFR 820.30 (c) &amp; ISO 9001 Subclause 4.4.4</b></center><P>

The design input provides the foundation for product development. The objective
of the design input process is to establish and document the design input
requirements for the device. The design input document is as comprehensive and
precise as possible. It contains the information necessary to direct the
remainder of the design process. It includes design constraints, but does not
impose design solutions. <P>

A key perspective in developing the design input is the customer's. Design input
is largely determined by customer requirements. To this end, knowledge of
customer expectations, patterns of use, concerns for safety and performance is
critical. However, the customer's is not the only perspective. All factors
pertinent to the design of the product are addressed. Among others this includes:
(1) regulatory requirements; (2) design aspects and processes that may require
development and analysis, including prototype testing, to verify accuracy; and,
(3) all factors necessary to describe the device throughout the device life cycle
including manufacturing, support, maintenance, and disposal.<P>

<b>4.1 TYPES AND SOURCES OF INFORMATION</b><P>

Simply put, the design input process consists of the identification and
documentation of requirements, as well as confirmation through independent review
of the adequacy of those requirements. The following is a partial listing of the
type of information that should be acquired:<P>

Needs of the user/patient<P>

<UL>
<LI>Diagnostic and/or therapeutic requirements<P>
<LI>Clinical effectiveness requirements including user expectations<P>
<LI>Labeling requirements including operator guidance<P>
<LI>Human factors<P>
<LI>Safety including biological safety<P>
<LI>Training</UL><P>

Intended use requirements<P>
<UL>
<LI>Performance<P>
<LI>Functional<P>
<LI>Interface<P>
<LI>Environmental including EMC and device/system compatibility<P>
<LI>Reliability<P>
<LI>Maintainability, and reparability<P>
<LI>Storage and shelf life<P>
<LI>Materials including biocompatibility<P>
<LI>Regulatory (including GMP) requirements and standards<P>
<LI>Human factors<P>
<LI>Safety including biological safety<P>
<LI>Sterilization<P>
<LI>Standards or regulations</UL><P>

Other<P>
<UL>
<LI>Cost<P>
<LI>Technological viability<P>
<LI>Manufacturability including process compatibility<P>
<LI>Export requirements<P>
<LI>Packaging and shipping<P>
<LI>Business considerations<P>
<LI>Installation<P>
<LI>Legal issues</UL>
<P>
Market research is the principal mechanism for acquiring knowledge of customer
requirements. It is through market research that detailed information regarding
where l and how it will be used, who will use it, concerns for safety, etc. are
obtained. Therefore, l the focus of information gathering is outside of the
company. This is particularly true for those projects involving new device
development. The market research may involve the selection and application of
particular research methods, the use of prototyping, or other means to acquire
the needed information. The reader should refer to texts on marketing research
for determining customer requirements and validating those requirements. Market
research is a professional expertise of its own. Depending on the nature of the
project, professional expertise should be considered.<P>

Other information can come from a variety of sources. It might already exist such
as documentation from past projects and studies, company complaints, and
servicing  records, and standards. It may have to be acquired first-hand such as
through a consultation with an appropriately qualified practitioner on the
consideration that needs to be given to the anatomical and physiological
implications of the intended use of the device. Or, for a device intended for
home use or a device used in ambulances, an investigation might be conducted by
company engineers at selected sites to characterize the environment in which the
device will operate.<P>

<b>4.2 DESIGN INPUT DEVELOPMENT</b><P>

The magnitude of the effort required to develop the design input depends on the
reasons for initiating the project as well as the type of device. The effort is
typically not as great for projects to upgrade or modify existing devices as that
required for a new device. In either case, development of the design input
requirements is best accomplished as a broadbased cross-functional activity. The
design input team includes representatives from all departments that contribute
to the design process: marketing, medical affairs, finance, general management,
manufacturing, the engineering functions, etc.<P>

Control of the development process is achieved through (1) employment of an
appropriate multifunctional approach, (2) documentation, and (3) formal review.
Meetings are conducted to review each requirement for explicitness, review the
list of requirements for completeness, resolve differences, and identify missing
information. Missing information such as warranty data on similar devices is
acquired, analyzed, interpreted, and the requirements list is expanded. Upon
determination that differences are resolved and the design input requirements
list is as complete as possible, it is subjected to a formal review, often the
first formal design review for the project, using established criteria such as
that listed in Section 4.3. If possible, the review is conducted by a
cross-functional team comparable to the team that developed the design input.
Upon formal acceptance of the design input requirements document, it becomes part
of the device configuration and the Design History File.<P>

<i>Requirements Checklist</i><P>

Checklists are a valuable tool when conducting a formal review. The following
checklist is an example of one of that might be used to review the design input
requirements:<P>

<OL>
<LI>Each requirement must be precise.<P>

<LI>Customer requirements are written in language to accommodate needs of a
cross-functional team. They may contain technical terminology, but are written so
that team members can understand the content.<P>

<LI>The means of validation (see Section 8.0) are specified for each requirement,
i.e., the conformance assessment procedure, methods, and equipment.<P>

<LI>The requirements are as complete as possible. Confirmation is provided that
all external requirements imposed on the product have been taken into account.
Similarly, confirmation is provided that appropriate consideration has been given
to all realizable classes of operating conditions, both valid and invalid.<P>

<LI>To be determined (TBD) conditions, i.e., incomplete requirements, are
identified. The conditions creating the TBD condition are specified and as well
as what needs to be done to eliminate those conditions.<P>

<LI>The document includes a record of all resolutions of any incomplete,
ambiguous, or conflicting requirements.<P>

<LI>The document is prepared in a way that facilitates updates. For example,
requirements are organized in an appropriate manner, e.g., by importance,
necessity, etc., and the document has a table of contents, an index, and explicit
cross-referencing.<P>

<LI>The document includes indication of "when" and "what criteria" will cause the
document to be updated, and who has responsibility for updates.</OL><P>

<b>4.3 DEVICE SPECIFICATIONS</b><P>

The design input requirements and measures to prevent known faults on similar
devices are translated into the device specifications. The specifications define
the essential technical characteristics of the device. To the extent possible,
device specifications are written in technical language, e.g., engineering
terminology, with characteristics described in terms that are measurable. Where
an allowable variation in a characteristic is permitted, the specifications
include the acceptable ranges or limits of variation. Thus, specifications are
verifiable.<P>

The translation process provides both forward and backward traceability to ensure
that specifications have not inadvertently been added in the translation.
Techniques such as quality function deployment (QFD) might be used to assure that
the translation occurs in a systematic manner that provides traceability. QFD is
a methodology for ensuring that specifications are coupled with requirements. In
addition, the means of verification is provided for each specification. The
specifications and means of verification are reviewed for precision, accuracy,
and completeness. The specifications are added to the device configuration and
the Design History File.<P>

<center><h3>5.0 DESIGN OUTPUT</h3><P>

<b>FDA 21 CFR 820.30 (d) &amp; ISO 9001 Subclause 4.4.5</b></center><P>

Design output means the results of a design effort at each design phase and at
the end of the total design effort. The total finished design output consists of
the device, its packaging and labeling, and the associated specifications and
drawings. It includes the production and quality assurance specifications and
procedures. Described in other terms, the design output includes (1) the detailed
documentation covering all functional and performance characteristics of the
device, including those related to safety, and (2) the product and process
documents needed to produce the device and maintain it throughout its life
cycle.<P>

Design output is generated throughout the design process. Examples of the types
of documents that are produced are the following:<P>

<UL>
<LI>drawings<P>
<LI>test procedures<P>
<LI>performance test results<P>
<LI>specifications (including process and material specifications)<P>
<LI>work instructions<P>
<LI>software specifications and code<P>
<LI>quality assurance procedures<P>
<LI>installation and servicing procedures<P>
<LI>packaging and labeling specifications, including copies of approved labels<P>
<LI>methods and procedures</UL><P>

<b>5.1 USES OF DESIGN OUTPUT</b><P>

The design output is used for several different purposes such as the
following:<P>

<i>Documenting Conformance Of Output To Input</i><P>

Documentation confirming the conformance of design output to design input is
generated throughout the design process. For example, the device specifications
are reviewed for explicitness, accuracy, testability, safety, and traceability to
the design input requirements. The review is documented. Another example is
testing used to assess performance, safety, etc. at different stages of
development of the device. Test procedures, results, and assessments of those
results are documented as well as reviews of test procedures for accuracy,
completeness, and traceability. In totality, this documentation consists of all
design output generated by verification and validation activities.<P>

<i>Product And Process Documentation</i><P>

Some design outputs are used to generate other design output documents. For
example, design outputs are used to generate the product and process
documentation needed to produce the device and maintain it throughout its life
cycle.<P>

Such product documentation typically includes a parts list identifying all
purchased components. It includes materials specifications which specify, usually
by reference to standards, the characteristics of all materials needed to
manufacture the device and contains sufficient information for these materials to
be ordered by the purchasing department. It includes device packaging details,
examples of labels, and instructions for use, and instructions for the
installation and servicing of the device as well.<P>

The manufacturing process documentation that is generated defines how the device
will be produced. The documentation often includes a flow diagram showing the
sequence of operations performed in the manufacture of the device and work
instructions describing how each of the manufacturing operations is performed.
The work instructions identify the materials, components, tools and machines to
be used. They also describe the manufacturing operations and the test or
inspection procedures that show that the work has been properly done. The
documentation typically includes separate lists of the manufacturing equipment as
well as test and quality assurance inspection procedures.<P>

<i>Device History File (DHF) And Device Master Record (DMR)</i><P>

Design output provides the documentation used to compile files and records
required by regulation. The DHF documentation is compiled throughout the design
process. It includes or refers to the location of design documentation such as
the design input requirements, design verification results, design review
results, etc. The completed file provides a complete design history of the
finished device and demonstrates that the device design was developed, verified,
and validated in accordance with the approved design plan.<P>

The DHF contains information giving an overall picture of the design and
manufacture of the device such as block diagrams, outline drawings, flow
diagrams, etc., and can be maintained as a specific index file for the design
output. It includes identification of the next level of information and where it
can be found.<P>

The DMR is compiled in a similar manner. Once established, it is used and updated
throughout the full product life cycle. It contains device specifications,
production specifications, quality assurance procedures, packaging, and labeling.
It contains procedures for installation, maintenance, and servicing. Upon
completion, the DMR includes all of the detailed design documentation required
for production that is transferred to manufacturing.<P>

<i>Device Configuration</i><P>

During the design process, designers complete engineering drawings, flow
diagrams, source code, etc. These documents establish design criteria and are
required by others for further development of the device. For other designers to
use these documents, the documents are formally accepted, added to the device
configuration, and then released so that others may work with them.<P>

<b>5.2 CONTROL OF DESIGN OUTPUT</b><P>

Because of the number and types of documents that are generated as well as the
different ways in which they are organized and used, control of design output is
planned. The plan is implemented before design output is first generated. Key
components of the planning process are information and documentation flow
diagrams. They show graphically (1) where information and documentation is
generated, (2) where it is transmitted, (3) how it is used, and (3) where it is
stored.<P>

In general, the design output is organized and structured in a systematic manner
that facilitates accessibility, use, and updating of the documentation in a
manner that conforms with regulatory requirements and configuration management
procedures. The documentation incorporates means which provide traceability from
design outputs to the design input requirements. The documentation, including
copies of the latest version of the device configuration, is located where it is
used, e.g., engineering documents in the engineering department, purchasing
documents in the purchasing department, etc. It is complete and includes only the
latest version of each document. Obsolete documents are removed promptly and all
affected functions are notified. For records maintained for regulatory purposes,
documents are reviewed for adequacy prior to their being issued. Changes to
documents are documented, reviewed, and approved by the same function that
approved the original documents. The device configuration documentation system is
designed so that field problems can be traced to the date of engineering changes
and that all devices affected by the change can be identified.<P>

The documentation identification scheme provides means for individually
identifying each document that is consistent with (1) the various categories of
documents and (2) the manner in which they are stored. Care is taken in
establishing a document numbering system and in ensuring consistency in the use
of it throughout the documentation system. The system enables documents approved
and released for production to be distinguished from those not yet released.
Several texts are available on the subject of documentation control. The reader
is directed to these for a more comprehensive treatment of the subject.<P>

<center><h3>6.0 DESIGN REVIEW</h3><P>

<b>FDA 21 CFR 820.30 (e) &amp; ISO 9001 Subclause 4.4.6</b></center><P>

Design review refers to a proactive program of formal meetings that occur
throughout the design process. In general, design reviews are intended to (1)
provide a systematic assessment of the device and the associated designs for
production and support, (2) provide feedback to designers on existing or emerging
problems, (3) assess project progress, and (4) provide confirmation that the
project is ready to move on to the next stage of development. To meet these
goals, design reviews have both an internal and external focus. The internal
focus is on the feasibility of the design and the produceability of the design
with respect to manufacturing and support capabilities. The external focus is on
the user requirements, i.e., the device design is viewed from the perspective of
the user. The particular focus for any one design review meeting will vary
according to the stage of development of the device.<P>

<b>6.1 DESIGN REVIEW PROGRAM</b><P>

Control of the design review process is achieved by developing and implementing a
formal design review program consistent with quality system requirements.
Development of the program is the responsibility of the design review team. They
establish the meeting procedures, the meeting schedule, and variables checklists
that are appropriate for the stage of development. They also identify the
functions within the organization that should be represented at a meeting, e.g.,
for the design transfer meetings, they might require that all functions that
participated in the design be represented. The team also establishes procedures
for providing conditional acceptance of results. The evaluation criteria is
reviewed and updated as the design progresses.<P>

Formal reviews are planned in the master schedule and conducted at the end of
each phase and at important milestones in the design process. The following list
is an example of such a schedule. The number of meetings for any one phase
depends upon the complexity of the device.<P>

<b>Phase</b> (Number)<P>
<menu>
<b>Requirements Review (Design input)</b> (One to a few)<P>
<b>Functional Requirements Review</b> (One to a few)<P>
<b>Detailed Design Review #1</b> (Possibly several)<P>
<b>Detailed Design Review #2 (Post-verification)</b> (One to a few)<P>
<b>Design Transfer (Post-validation)</b> (One to several)</menu><P>

Prior to implementing the design review program, the team establishes
phase-specific criteria needed to demonstrate completion of a phase. They also
identify the supporting documentation required to make that assessment. In
preparation for each meeting, the documentation is assembled and reviewed.<P>

<b>6.2 DESIGN REVIEW TEAM</b><P>

The design review team plans, conducts, and records the design review meetings.
The multifunctional team is staffed by appropriately qualified personnel. The
team has at least one individual, assigned by management, who does not have
direct responsibility for design development. If possible, the other personnel on
the team are familiar with the details of the project but also not directly
involved in design development for the project. The competency of the
participants in the design reviews should be adequate to permit them to examine
designs and their implications.<P>

The team has sufficient authority to make decisions, provided that the design
remains within the overall constraints, such as:<P>

<UL>
<LI>to decide on and confirm the solution to be adopted<P>
<LI>to change the course of design<P>
<LI>to change to the- design input requirements<P>
<LI>to recommend additional research activity<P>
<LI>to conditionally accept results in accordance with established
procedures</UL><P>

<b>6.3 REVIEW PROCEDURES AND CHECKLISTS</b><P>

As previously stated, the nature of meetings changes as the design progresses.
During the initial stages, issues related to requirements and specifications
analysis will predominate. Next, the main function of the meetings is to review
the choice of solutions being offered by the design team. Then, issues such as
the choice of materials and the methods of manufacture become more important.
During the final stages, issues related to the verification of the design,
validation, and production predominate.<P>

However, all formal reviews are conducted in a similar manner. All formal
meetings are properly constituted with an agenda and recorded by minutes that
contain a dated action column. Material to be presented is distributed to other
participants in advance of the meeting so that it may be reviewed. The records
identify those present at the meeting and the decisions reached. Follow-up action
is monitored to assure that assignments are completed and all issues are properly
addressed.<P>

Finally, the following variables checklist is an example of one that might be
used in preparation for the formal review of design verification:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Do design outputs satisfy all design input requirements for the device
(including service)?<P>

<LI>Is the device design robust and process capable?<P>

<LI>Have risk management activities been performed to ensure that risk is within
acceptable levels?<P>

<LI>Do designs meet functional and operational requirements, that is, performance
and reliability objectives?<P>

<LI>Have appropriate materials and/or facilities been selected?<P>

<LI>Is there adequate compatibility of materials and components and/or service
elements?<P>

<LI>Is the design satisfactory for all anticipated environmental and load
conditions?<P>

<LI>Are components or service elements standardized and do they provide for
interchangeability, maintainability and replacement?<P>

<LI>Are plans for implementing the design, for example, purchasing, production,
installation, inspection and testing, technically feasible?<P>

<LI>Can the tolerance requirements consistently be met?<P>

<LI>Where computer software forms part of the product, or has been used in design
computations, modeling, or analyses, has the software (and its configuration
control) been appropriately validated, authorized, and verified?<P>

<LI>Have the inputs to such software, and the outputs, been appropriately
verified and documented?<P>

<LI>What are the assumptions made during the design process and what is their
validity?</UL><P>

<b>6.4 INFORMAL REVIEWS</b><P>

There is another type of review that occurs far more frequently and is an
integral part of the design process. Rather than being a component of a formal
program, these informal meetings occur as scheduled in project plans or on an
as-needed basis. The principal function of these meetings is usually to resolve a
problem or address issues in a specialty area. The meetings can be one-on-one,
few-on-few, etc. Usually, they are not multifunctional. They are an important and
necessary part of the development process. Those issues or problems that can be
addressed using informal meetings are resolved in that manner. As a result, many
important decisions, such as the selection of a design solution from among
alternatives presented, are made at informal meetings. Therefore, those decisions
and the rationale behind those decisions are recorded in the event that
unforeseen factors cause past design decisions to be reevaluated. However, all
decisions regarding problems or issues that will cause changes to specifications
or approved designs are made in the context of a formal, multifunctional design
review.<P>

<center><h3>7.0 DESIGN VERIFICATION</h3><P>

<b>FDA 21 CFR 820.30 (f) &amp; ISO 9001 Subclause 4.4.7</b></center><P>

Design verification is confirmation that design output meets design input
requirements (820.30(f)). Design verification has complementary global and local
meanings both of which apply to the design verification process. Globally, design
verification is the process by which conformance to design specifications is
confirmed and the question "did we design the device right" is answered. Locally,
verification is the process by which the output of a design activity is evaluated
to determine conformity with the input requirement for that activity. Therefore,
control of the design verification process is achieved by (1) ensuring that the
device specifications are verifiable and traceable to the design input
requirements, (2) planning and systematically verifying outputs of design
activities in a manner traceable to the design specifications, and (2) using the
formal design review process to determine if verification activities are
appropriate, consistent, complete, and traceable.<P>

<b>7.1 CONTROL OF DESIGN VERIFICATION</b><P>

Verification activities and tasks are conducted in every part of the design
process at all stages and levels of device design. The nature of verification
activities varies according the type of design output and the stage of the design
process. Verification activities include testing, inspection, analysis, review,
etc. Verification activities and tasks are planned. Planning usually includes
establishing the evaluation criteria, method of verification, and procedure to be
used. For example, one of the first verification activities may be a review of
the design specifications to ensure that they are complete, accurate, consistent,
verifiable, and traceable to the design input requirements. Design verification
activities and tasks include review of the results of FMEAs and FTAs and other
hazard analyses. Activities and tasks also include evaluation of the
appropriateness of design and process changes and the effectiveness of their
implementation. Whenever practical, verification activities and tasks are
performed by personnel other than those responsible for designing the work
product being evaluated.<P>

For large projects, a verification plan that relates verification activities and
tasks to the appropriate stage of development of the device may be necessary,
e.g., system-level verification activities may not be possible until prototype
development has been completed. The plan is reviewed for accuracy, completeness,
and to ensure that all activities are traceable to the design specifications.
Verification tasks are integrated into the project design and development plan.
Verification tasks are reviewed prior to beginning each new phase and changed
where necessary. Care is taken that, as the design progresses, verification
activities and tasks carried out at an early stage remain valid or are repeated
on the final design. The plan is used to convey to those conducting verification 
activities the importance of their activity within the entire verification
process.<P>

A major verification activity is the testing of the final device design.
Development of the  test plan usually begins during the design specifications
phase. The plan includes  performance, environmental, reliability, and safety
testing. Encountering conflicting  requirements, unforeseen design constraints,
changes in implementation, etc. can require  that the plan be changed. Therefore,
the test plan is revised and updated as the design  proceeds. The completed plan
includes detailed test procedures that take into account  worse-case operating
conditions. It includes acceptance criteria that is tied to the design 
specifications. Where criteria or procedures are based on standards, those
standards are  identified. Tools such as trace matrices are used to ensure that
all device specifications  have been accounted for and that testing is traceable
to the design specifications.<P>

Results generated from verification activities are analyzed and interpreted.
Correction of  any problem that is identified begins at the point in the design
corresponding to where the  problem originated. The results, analyses,
interpretations, as well as the identification of  individuals that performed
verifications are recorded and added to the Design History File  along with the
results of all other verification activities and tasks. <P>

Formal design reviews are an important part of the design verification process.
It is  during the formal design review process that determination of the adequacy
of the  verification activities is made while taking into account factors such as
conflicting design  requirements, unforeseen constraints, etc. Formal reviews are
also used to confirm  traceability of design outputs to the design
specifications. Therefore, the decisions made  during the review process are an
important part of the design process and are documented  in the design review
report prepared by the review team chairperson.<P>

<b>7.2 VERIFICATION TECHNIQUES</b><P>

Many different techniques can be used in the verification process. Analyses
including  failure analyses, alternative calculations, testing including animal
testing, auditing, design  reviews, demonstrations, and comparing a new design to
a proven design are examples of  verification techniques. (Auditing refers to any
independent examination of a design  output and not a quality audit.)<P>

Fault tree analyses (FTA), failure mode and effects (FMEA) analyses, and other
hazard  analysis techniques can be used as verification methods throughout the
design process.  The analysis techniques are applicable to more than verification
of conformance to safety  specifications, and can be used for process
verification as well.<P>

For most verification techniques, the verification procedures include evaluation
for both normal and unusual, e.g., out-of-range or invalid, operating conditions.
An example is the verification of software. As software design progresses, each
module is challenged by an independent team within the design group. Their task
is to examine the software under several extreme combinations of conditions
including testing that attempts to "defeat or fool" it.<P>

Most aspects of product design can be verified by in vitro testing, but some
medical devices may require animal and/or clinical testing. Such testing is only
undertaken (1) when it can be shown that there are aspects of the design that
cannot be verified by in vitro testing and (2) when in vitro testing has shown,
as far as possible, that the product is safe and satisfactory. Animal testing
precedes clinical testing and is be carried out against procedures which have
clear end points and which are designed to minimize animal suffering. The
procedures are reviewed prior to the initiation of testing to ensure that it is
possible to achieve the desired end points and that appropriate controls are in
place.<P>

When alternative calculations or comparison with a proven design are employed as
forms of design verification, the appropriateness of the alternative calculation
method and/or the proven design is reviewed in relation to the new
application.<P>

<center><h3>8.0 DESIGN VALIDATION</h3><P>

<b>FDA 21 CFR 820.30 (g) &amp; ISO 9001 Subclause 4.4.8</b></center><P>

Design validation means establishing by objective evidence that a device conforms
with user needs and intended uses (802.3 (z)(2)). The intent of design validation
is to go beyond the purely technical issues of verifying that the design output
meets the design input, and is intended to ensure that the device meets user
requirements. Conceptually, device validation is performed with respect to the
design input requirements and answers the question "did we design the right
device." However, in a manner similar to design verification, control of the
validation process is achieved by (1) planning for validation including the
development of procedures, evaluation criteria, etc., and (2) using the formal
review process to both evaluate the appropriateness of plans and review results
for completeness, accuracy, and traceability. If possible, design validation is
performed by an independent team familiar with the details of the project but not
directly involved in the design process.<P>

Planning for validation begins early in the design process. The performance
characteristics, features, etc. that are to be assessed are identified.
Acceptance, criteria should be established for each characteristic, feature, etc.
Worse case and unusual operating conditions are taken into account when
establishing the criteria. Where standards are the source of criteria, the
standards are specified. The characteristics, features, etc. and the acceptance
criteria are reviewed for appropriateness, completeness, as well as traceability
to the design input requirements.<P>

Design validation is performed under defined operating conditions on initial
production units, lots, batches, or their equivalents. Design validation can
include testing under actual or simulated use conditions. Therefore, before
procedures can be developed, the manner in which validation is to be performed,
and thus, the operating conditions for the method are identified. Assessments of
some characteristics, features, etc. might be performed under actual use
conditions while simulated conditions are used for others.<P>

Depending upon the type of device, procedures may have to be established for
several different assessment methods, e.g., clinical evaluations, safety
assessments, etc. Careful consideration is given to whom the user really is, the
operating instructions, and any restrictions on the use of the product. Careful
consideration is also given to the acceptance criteria as well as the capability
of an assessment method to produce the desired end points. All information
relevant to a procedure, such as the statistical methods to be used, is
specified. Where standards are the source of procedures, those standards are
specified.<P>

Evaluation of results is an important part of the validation process. Design
validation normally follows successful verification that the finished product
conforms to the device specifications. It forces a reconsideration of the design
input and whether user requirements were properly conveyed to the designers.
Problems identified during validation are corrected at the point in the design
process corresponding to where the problem originated. When validation has been
completed, the results are analyzed and interpreted. Conclusions are developed
and recorded. Methodology, results, analyses, interpretations, and conclusions
are evaluated as part of the formal design review process. The design validation
results, analyses, interpretations, etc. are documented in the Design History
File.<P>

<center><h3>9.0 DESIGN CHANGES</h3><P>

<b>FDA 21 CFR 820.30 (i) &amp; ISO 9001 Subclause 4.4.9</b></center><P>

Design changes occur throughout the design process. Often, assessing the impact
of changes on all aspects of the project can be very difficult. This is
particularly true for large projects involving multifunctional design teams.
Therefore, control of changes is achieved by establishing, applying, and
maintaining procedures for the identification, documentation, validation and
verification where appropriate, review, and approval of design changes before
their implementation (820.30(i)).<P>

Examples of changes that need to be controlled are:<P>

<UL>
<LI>new design criteria is added to the existing documentation as project
milestones are reached<P>
<LI>change in design inputs<P>
<LI>omissions or errors, e.g., due to calculation, material selection, etc.,
during the design phase have been identified afterwards<P>
<LI>manufacturing and/or installation difficulties are discovered after the
design phase<P>
<LI>the purchaser or subcontractor requests changes<P>
<LI>the function or performance of the device is to be improved<P>
<LI>safety, regulatory, or other requirements have been changed<P>
<LI>design verification or validation necessitates change</UL>
<P>

<b>9.1 CONFIGURATION MANAGEMENT</b><P>

In general, for any approved document, subsequent changes to that document are
approved by the same authority that approved the original design. In addition,
the request for a change is accompanied by an assessment of the total impact of
the change. However, for documentation that has been placed under configuration
control, changes to those documents are made in accordance with the established
configuration management plan.<P>

Configuration management refers to the documentation to be controlled, the
procedures for controlling it, and the responsibilities of those managing the
documentation, i.e., the configuration control board. It includes a system of
traceability including traceability of components, service manuals, procedures,
etc. that could be affected by a change. The controlled documents are
configuration items and collectively form the device configuration. Typically,
the device configuration includes specifications, design documents, test
documents, and all other deliverables including those documents required for
regulatory records. In other words, the configuration is the continually
increasing set of formally reviewed and accepted documentation that throughout
the project (1) establishes the current development status of the device, (2)
provides traceability to the design input requirements, and (3) serves as the
basis for further development. However, it is the responsibility of the project
manager to decide, in a manner consistent with the quality system requirements,
which documents are to be place under configuration control. Detailed
documentation flow diagrams are included in the plan.<P>

The configuration management plan is established during the design input
requirements phase. The procedures contained in the plan identify the documents
to be placed under configuration management and establish when, in their state of
development, they are placed under configuration control. For example, for some
projects, only documents that are completed and formally accepted are placed
under configuration management. For other projects, documents containing
to-be-determined conditions are placed under configuration control.<P>

All changes affecting the configuration are reviewed by the change control board.
The criteria for evaluating proposed changes is established in the quality
plan.<P>

The procedures for controlling change include methods for the following:<P>

<UL>
<LI>controlling the identification of development status<P>
<LI>requesting and approving changes<P>
<LI>ensuring that changes are properly integrated through formal change control
procedures<P>
<LI>obtaining approval to implement a change<P>
<LI>version identification, issue, and control</UL><P>

Change control procedures require the complete documentation of approved changes
and the communication of configuration changes to all who are affected. Design
changes are reviewed to determine whether they influence previously approved
design verification or validation results.<P>

<center><h3>10.0 DESIGN TRANSFER</h3><P>

<b>FDA 21 CFR 820.30 (h)</b></center><P>

The process of transferring knowledge about the device from the design team to
the manufacturing group, which will build the product, does not normally take
place at one time but preferably is carried on throughout the design process. The
knowledge may be transferred in the form of documentation, training and possibly
by the transfer of personnel.<P>

The transfer of a device design to production typically involves review and
approval of specifications, procedures, and critical product and process
characteristics established in the FMEAs, FTAs, and hazard analyses. Where
applicable, it includes confirmation of the adequacy of specifications, methods
and procedures through process validation, including the reliability and
durability testing of finished product under actual or simulated use
conditions.<P>

Incorporation of manufacturing and production personnel in the design review team
is an important element of design transfer. As each subsystem of the design is
completed, examples of that design element are manufactured under as near-normal
manufacturing conditions as possible by the manufacturing personnel under the
supervision and guidance of the designers. This enables any deficiencies in the
documentation to be identified as well as any practical difficulties in
constructing the device. At this stage, each subsystem is tested. The culmination
of this process is the construction of several complete examples of the finished
product which are those used for final device verification/validation or clinical
trials. However, only when the subsystem documentation and performance is
verified at the systems-level, is subsystem considered ready for release and the
Device Master Record completed.<P>

It may not be possible to determine the adequacy of full-scale manufacturing on
the basis of successfully building prototypes or models in a laboratory and
testing these prototypes or models. The engineering feasibility and production
feasibility may be different because the equipment, tools, personnel, operating
procedures, supervision and motivation could be different when a company scales
up for routine production. One way to ensure that distributed devices have the
quality attributes established during design, and that these are not adversely
affected by the production process, is to manufacture finished devices using the
approved specifications, the same materials and components, the same production
and assessment equipment, and the same methods and procedures that will be used
for routine production. In addition, manufacturing can use the opportunity to
develop screening methods for identifying manufacturing defects.<P>

Where appropriate, this may be accomplished by manufacturing "pilot runs" or
"first production runs. These devices, or samples from these runs, are then
qualified through testing under actual or simulated use conditions, and in the
environment, or simulated environment, in which the device is expected to be
used. The extent of the testing should be governed by the complexity and risk
associated with the device.<P>

<center><h3>11.0 CONCLUSIONS</h3></center><P>

The manner in which design controls are implemented by a device manufacturer is
affected by many factors such as scale of operation, device risks, and current
design practices. Virtually all device manufacturers employ activities and
techniques that are the same or similar to those described in this guidance,
e.g., project planning, design reviews, etc. Therefore, before implementing
design controls, manufacturers should evaluate their existing design process and
identify process deficiencies that could cause device nonconformance. Design
controls should then be implemented in a manner that is consistent with the
guidance, is best suited for their existing process, and addresses those
deficiencies. Finally, design controls are an interrelated set of activities and
techniques. Therefore, failure to implement "all" of the controls can be a cause
of device nonconformance. For example, a design process can include adequate
activities for planning, review, verification, validation, etc. However, failure
to properly develop the design input requirements can cause significant design
deficiencies that may not be detected until the design is validated.<P>

<hr>
<i>Editor's Note</i>: This draft document from CDRH has been reformatted. Original
document includes slightly different layout and numbered lines.<P>
</body> 



