<html> <head>
<title>Journal Issue Review: Nuclear Technology, January 1977</title>
</head>

<body background=/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif>
<center>
<table width=600><tr><td>
<center>
<h3>Journal Issue Review</h3>
<h1>Nuclear Technology, January 1977 (Volume ??, Number ??)</h1>
</center>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<b>TOPIC SENTENCE:</b> Eleven papers on Materials in High Level
Radioactive Waste Storage, part of the R&amp;D foundation for a real
disposal technology.  From the June 16, 1976 ANS-CNS meeting in
Toronto Canada. Nuclear Technology is published by American Nuclear
Society to publish review papers and unreported work of all phases of
applications of fundamental research to nuclear technology.

<hr>
<h3>List of Articles</h3>

<dl>
  <dt> <b>Materials Consideration In Radioactive Waste Storage</b>, pages 6-9
  <dd> <i>Warren K. Eister, U. S. Energy Research and Development
       Administration</i>
       <p>
  <dt> <b>Hanford Waste Encapsulation</b>, pages 10 - 15
  <dd> <i>R. R. Jackson, Atlantic Richfield Hanford Company</i>
       <p>
  <dt> <b>Stabilization And Storage Of Solidified High-Level
       Radioactive Wastes</b>, pages 16-24
  <dd> <i>J. R. Berreth, A. P. Hoskins, and J. A. Rindfleisch, Allied
       Chemical Corporation</i>
       <p>
  <dt> <b>Packaging Rocky Flats Waste</b>, pages 25 - 29
  <dd> <i>Charles E. Wickland,Rockwell International</i>
       <p>
  <dt> <b>Some Techniques For The Solidification Of Radioactive Wastes
       In Concrete</b>, pages 30 - 38
  <dd> <i>Peter Colombo and Robert M. Neilson Jr, BrookhavenNatioal
       Laboratory</i>
       <p>
  <dt> <b>Leach Behavior Of Hydrofracture Grout Incorporating
       Radioactive Wastes</b>, pages 39 - 52
  <dd> <iJ. G. Moore, H. W. Godbee, and A. H. Kibbey Oak Ridge
       National Laboratory></i>
       <p>
  <dt> <b>Packaging Of Tritium-Contaminated Liquid Waste</b>, page 53 - 59
  <dd> <i>E. A.  Mershad, W. W. Thomasson, J. J. Daubey of Monsanto
       Research Corporation</i>
       <p>
  <dt> <b>The Canadian Spent Fuel Storage Canister: Some Materials
       Aspects</b>, pages 60 - 71
  <dd> <i>Derek G. Boase, Tjalle T. Vandergraaf Whiteshell Nuclear
       Research Establishment</i>
       <p>
  <dt> <b>High-Level Waste Glass</b>, pages 72 - 87
  <dd> <i>John E. Mendel Battelle-Pacific Northwest Laboratory</i>
       <p>
  <dt> <b>High-Level Waste Glass: Field Leach Test</b>, pages 88 - 91 
  <dd> <i>W. F.  Merritt, Chalk River Nuclear Laboratory</i>
       <p>
  <dt> <b>High-Level Waste Ceramics: Materials Considerations, Process
       Simulations, And Product Characterization</b>, pages 92 - 105
  <dd> <i>Gregory J. McCarthy Pennsylvania State University</i>
</dl>
<hr>
<p>

<b>REVIEWER'S COMMENTS:</b> A basic set of tests upon which Yucca
Mountain disposal is based. Note particularly the "acid test" of
burying glassified waste directly in groundwater, and having so little
dissolved in relation to the relatively short time that the waste
would be radioactive!
<p>

<b>Journal Data:</b>
Nuclear Technology is published by the American Nuclear Society.<br>
Editor is William F. Vogelsang, Department of Nuclear Engineering and
Engineering Physics, University of Wisconsin, Madison WI 53706<br>

ANS Business Offices       (708) 352-6611  FAX(708) 352-6464<br>
555 North Kensington Avenue  La Grange Park ILL 60525 USA<br>
REPRINTS available from ANS Procurement Supervisor (708) 579-8233
FAX(708) 352-0499
<p>

<i>Reviewer:</i> Eugene N Cramer.  January 13, 1996
<p>

<font size=-2>KEYWORDS: Accidents, Burial, Chemistry, Concrete,
Conferences, Contamination, Detection, Dewatering, Fission Products,
Glass, Groundwater, High-Level Radioactive Waste, Hazardous Materials,
Hydrology, International, Low-Level Radioactive Waste, Materials,
Management &amp; Supervision; Minimization, Mixed Waste, Monitored
Retrieval Storage, Monitoring, Multipurpose Canisters, Nuclear Power
Plants, On-site LLW Storage, Packaging, Plutonium, Public Information
and Education, Radiation Exposure, Radioisotopes, Recordkeeping,
Recycling / Re-use, Reduction, Regulations, Research and Developement,
Risk Analysis, Standards, Field Test, Training, Transportation,
Uranium, U S Department of Energy, USDOE, Utilities, Vadose, WIPP,
Yucca Mountain.</font>

