<html> <head>
<title>Journal Article Review, High Level Waste Glass: Field Leach Test, Nuclear Technology, Jan. 1977</title>
</head>

<body background=/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif>
<center>
<table width=600><tr><td>
<center>
<h3>Journal Article Review</h3>
<h1>High-Level Waste Glass: Field Leach Test</h1>
<h3>Nuclear Technology, January 1977</h3>
</center>

<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<b>REVIEWERS SUMMARY:</b>Twenty-five blocks of glassified hi-level
waste were buried below the water table at Chalk River in 1958.  The
transit time would be some six half-lives of SR-90 for the 500 meters
to Perch Lake, by which time the SR-90 would be only 5 millicuries /
year to Perch Lake and thence to Ottawa River for a storage of wastes
from a 30,000 MWe nuclear industry.

<hr>

Nuclear Technology is published by American Nuclear Society to publish
review papers and unreported work of all phases of applications of
fundamental research to nuclear technology. The January 1977 issue
contains this article, one of a series of papers given at the June 16,
1976 ANS-CNS meeting in Toronto Canada. The articles are on Materials
in Waste Storage.:

<blockquote>
<b>HIGH-LEVEL WASTE GLASS: FIELD LEACH TEST</b>, pages 88 - 91<br>
<i>by W. F.  Merritt, Chalk River Nuclear Laboratory</i>
</blockquote>   

To study a worst case scenario, 25 blocks of hi-level waste glassified
in nepheline syenite were buried below the water table at Chalk River
in 1958.  Then in 1960, 25 other blocks were similarly buried, after
preparation from poorer glass. Groundwater past the blocks is 18
centimeters/day.  After some 10 years, leach rates of SR-90 were 3.5
microcuries per year.  For a storage of wastes from a 30,000 MWe
nuclear industry, the transit time for the 500 meters to Perch Lake
would be some six half-lives of SR-90, by which time the SR-90 would
be only 5 millicuries / year to Perch Lake and thence to Ottawa
River. Presently there are 50 millicuries / day of weapons testing
SR-90 passing CRNL in the Ottawa River.
<p>

<b>CONCLUSION:</b> Burial directly in the soil would be feasible for
permanent storage from a 30,000 MWe nuclear power industry.

<hr>

<b>REVIEWER'S COMMENTS:</b> Buried in old reports is the twenty year
R&amp;D basis for safe disposal of high level radioactive waste. Since
the 1982 Nuclear Waste Policy Act, most of the effort has gone into
the location and characterization of potential field locations for a
burial site.  Little new work has been more significant in showing the
relative ease of this safe disposal -- making this old work more
valuable as time progresses.
<p>

<b>Journal Data:</b>
Nuclear Technology is published by the American Nuclear Society.<br>
Editor is William F. Vogelsang, Department of Nuclear Engineering and
Engineering Physics, University of Wisconsin, Madison WI 53706<br>

ANS Business Offices       (708) 352-6611  FAX(708) 352-6464<br>
555 North Kensington Avenue  La Grange Park ILL 60525 USA<br>
REPRINTS available from ANS Procurement Supervisor (708) 579-8233
FAX(708) 352-0499
<p>

<i>Reviewer:</i> Eugene N Cramer.  January 13, 1996
<p>

<font size=-2>KEYWORDS: Accidents, Burial, Chemistry, Contamination,
Detection, Dewatering, Fission Products, Glass, Groundwater,
High-Level Radioactive Waste, Hazardous Materials, Hydrology,
International, Materials, Monitoring, Nuclear Power Plants, On-site
LLW Storage, Packaging, Plutonium, Public Information and Education,
Radiation Exposure, Radioisotopes, Regulations, Research and
Developement, Risk Analysis, Standards, Field Test, Training,
Transportation, Uranium, U S Department of Energy, USDOE, Utilities,
Vadose, WIPP, Yucca Mountain.</font>



</table>
<img src=/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif>
<!--#include virtual="/footer.html" -->
</center>
</body> </html>


