<html> <head>
<title>ANS/ENS 1996 INTERNATIONAL MEETING: Technical Sessions - Monday, November 11</title>
</head>

<body background=/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif>
<center>
<table width=600><tr><td>
<center>
<h3>ANS/ENS 1996 INTERNATIONAL MEETING</h3>
<h1>Technical Sessions - Monday, November 11</h1>
</center>
<a name="am"><p> <img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif"> <p></a>

<h3>8:30 a.m.</h3>
<dl>
  <dt> <b>ANS/ENS Plenary: The Global Benefits of Nuclear Technology</b><br>
     Session organizer: Donald Hoffman (EXCEL). All invited	
  <dd> This opening plenary session will complement the overall
       meeting theme, "The Global Benefits of Nuclear Technology:
       Improving the Quality of Life for the Present and Future
       Generations," and will address a number of the ways that
       nuclear technology improves the quality of life for present
       generations and is expected to improve the quality of life for
       future generations. These include its impact on medicine,
       manufacturing and industry, food and agriculture, and energy. A
       most prestigious group of high-level international and
       U.S. speakers from the medical, food and agriculture,
       industrial, political, academic, and energy fields will
       participate, including the presidents of the European Nuclear
       Society and the American Nuclear Society.
       <ul>
	 <li> Jacqueline DuPont (U.S. Department of Agriculture)
	 <li> Pierre Davres (EdF - France)
	 <li> Steven M. Larson (Sloan-Kettering Cancer Research Center)
	 <li> A. Jaumotte (AIB-Vincotte Nuclear - Belgium
       </ul>
</dl>
<p>

<a name="pm"><p> <img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif"> <p></a>
<h3>1:00 p.m.</h3>
<dl>
  <dt> <b>Waste Isolation Pilot Plant: Application for Compliance Certification-Panel</b><br>
       sponsored by fcwmd; Cosponsored by ESD. Session organizer: William W. Weston (Westinghouse, Carlsbad). All invited	
  <dd> Potential Panelists:

       <ul>
	 <li> Richard D. Anderson (SNL)
	 <li> Lokesh Chaturvedi (EEG)
	 <li> George E. Dials (DOE, Carlsbad)
	 <li> Charles Fairhurst (Univ. of Minnesota)
	 <li> Brian A. Howard (Westinghouse)
       </ul>
       <p>


  <dt> <b>Whistle-Blowers: What Are They Trying to Tell Us?-Panel</b><br>
       sponsored by PD. Session organizers: Barbara Newsom (ESC Learning), Mona Grimsley (Wolf Creek Nucl) All invited	
  <dd> Panel Session

       <ul>
	 <li> Three Types of Whistle-blowers, Billie Garde (Garde Law Offices)
	 <li> What Employee Concerns Programs Can Do, George Pliml (ComEd, Downers Grove)
	 <li> The Regulatory Perspective on Whistle-blowing, Edward Baker (NRC)
	 <li> The Ineffectiveness of Nuclear Whistle-blower Protection, Paul Blanch (Consultant)
	 <li> Protected Conduct and the Law, Jay M. Gutierrez (Morgan, Lewis and Bockius)
	 <li> Whistle-blowing in Other Industries, William G. Miossi (Winston &amp;Strawn)
	 <li> Developments in DOE Whistle-Blower Law, Don Meindertsma (Winston &amp;Strawn)
