<html> <head>
<title>Forms and CGI Templates for ANS Documents</title>
</head>

<body background=/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif>
<center>
<table width=600><tr><td>

<center><h1>Forms and CGI Scripts</h1></center>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

These collections of HTML forms and accompanying CGI scripts are
currently used to process ANS on-line applications.  Please read the
comment which accompanies each, since their usage is more complicated
than a standard HTML template.
<p>

Most ANS forms, particularly those involving payments, use a two step
process.  The data from the initial form is processed by a CGI script
and then a confirmation page [CGI-generated HTML] is shown.  On the
confirmation page, the user will see a concise summary of their
selections including an itemized and totalled bill.  By submitting
this information, the user receives a coded confirmation number and
the information is sent to ANS HQ.  Most forms use tables in their
construction (a virtual necessity), and therefore require slightly
more sophisticated browsers.  (It is probably possible to make this a
single script, but I haven't done it yet :) <p>

Most CGI scripts uses two common routines that check for a valid
looking e-mail address and ensure that mandatory information is
provided, respectively.  These two things are important given the ANS
HQ philosophy that they can follow up on missing or incorrect
information if they have enough contact information to do so.  If
either routine fails a complete error message page is shown indicating
which information is missing and suggesting that the user use the
"Back" button to correct missing or invalid information.
<p>

The currently used scheme for calculating a confirmation number is a
loosely encoded, non-random string created from some 4 letter code
word and the date and time stamp of the initial form submission.
Little need was seen for further development of this number since it
is more of a tracking number than a security number.
<p>

Finally, any form which allows direct credit card payment methods must
include a link to a warning that this is not a secure sever.  The
current message does point out that the risk is perhaps not significant
relative to giving a credit card to a waiter or giving the number over
the phone, but does allow the user to choose.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<dl>
  <dt> <b>Conference Registration</b>
  <dd> The form shown here was used for on-line conference
       registration for the 1996 ANS/ENS International Meeting.  Most
       meeting registration forms are separated in sections in this
       way, with there always being a section on each of:
       <table><tr>
       <td>
       <ul>
	 <li> personal data,
	 <li> conference fees,
	 <li> special publications options,
       </ul></td><td>
       <ul>
	 <li> special event tickets,
	 <li> professional development workshops, and
	 <li> payment options.
       </ul></td>
       </tr></table>

       In addition to changes which must be made in the appearance of
       the form for each new conference, changes must be made in the
       HTML form code to match the form data to the CGI script for
       changing special events, professional development workshops and
       special publications options.  This usually consists of slight
       changes to the form variable names and changes in the dollar
       values associated with each in the CGI script.
       <p>
       <ul>
	 <li> <a href="gen.reg.form.html">Generate your own form</a>
	 <li> <a href="wash.reg.html">Conference Registration Form</a>
	 <li> <a href="wash.pl">Initial Conference Registration Script</a>
	 <li> <a href="wash.confirm.pl">Conference Confirmation Script</a>
       </ul>
       
</dl>



</table>
