<html> <head>
<title>ANS HQ HTML Primer: Introduction</title>
</head>

<body background=/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif>
<center>
<table width=600><tr><td>
<center>
<h3>ANS HQ HTML Primer</h3>
<h1>INTRODUCTION</h1>
</center>
<img src=/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif>

<h3>What is the Internet?</h3>

The internet has been much in the news in the last few years, but what
is it?  The internet is really a large network of cables and
fiber-optics which criss-crosses the country and the globe connecting
computers to each other.  The internet allows the transfer of data in
many formats including e-mail, news, file transfer, and so on.  There
is a so-called "back-bone" around the country which carries most of
the information at the highest speeds.  There are branches off this
backbone, and further branches from these branches.  As a rule, each
branch carries less data than the trunk it branched from.

<h3>What is the World Wide Web?</h3>

A few years ago, some researcher at CERN in Switzerland decided that
there should be easier ways to share information on this powerful
network.  Basically, the technology for sharing information had not
kept pace with the capabilities of the network itself.  They developed
this concept of the World Wide Web [WWW] which is based on the concept
of hypertext, text which allows you to jump quickly between documents
and sections of documents.  Physically, the WWW is simply the
Internet, as described above.
<p>

What make it different between the WWW and the internet then?  The WWW
allows us to use this physical internet more efficiently, jumping
between documents which may be in completely different places around
the world, viewing images, listening to sounds, and so on.
<p>

While the WWW was originally based on hypertext, and the HyperText
Transfer Protocol (more on this below), most people now include most
of the possible communication methods on the internet in the
definition of the WWW.

<h3>Glossary</h3>

Since many of the terms may be new, I will introduce them at the
beginning rather than at the end, as in most references.  Most of
these definitions are not really important in terms of continuity.
Therefore, if you don't quite understand something, read on, hopefully
it will become more clear (or unnecessary :).

<dl>
  <dt> <b>HyperText Markup Language [HTML]</b>
  <dd> This is the basic formatting tool of the original WWW.  This
       markup language allows us to format the text we share on the
       WWW, much as a word processor allows us to format the text we
       share on paper.  There is one important difference: a markup
       language is designed to give basic typesetting suggestions
       which are then interpretted individually by the reader while a
       word processor gives final formatting rules.  More on this in
       the next chapter.
       <p>

       Markup languages in general are really quite simple.  "Tags"
       are added to a simple text document to give these typesetting
       suggestions.  In HTML a tag is enclosed in angle brackets,
       "&lt;tag&gt;", and most tags have a beginning and an end.  This
       concept will be quite familiar to people who work with other
       typesetting languages (eg. LaTeX) and with people who work
       often with the "Reveal Codes" mode of WordPerfect.  The next
       chapter will describe how to use the various tags of HTML to
       format a document.
       <p>
  <dt> <b>Protocol</b>
  <dd> A protocol is simply a method of exchanging information.  There
       are many protocols of various ages and sophistications.  All of
       you have used such a protocol if you have sent e-mail, browsed
       the web, or read news on-line.  Some of the protocols are:
       <p>

       <dl>
	 <dt> <i>HyperText Transfer Protocol [HTTP]:</i>
	 <dd> the basis of the WWW, this protocol allows the transfer
	      and interpretation of HTML and other documents.  It one
	      of the newest and most sophisticated protocols.
	 <dt> <i>File Transfer Protocol [FTP]:</i>
	 <dd> an older protocol which allows the simple transfer of
	      files in text or binary format.  This protocol is used
	      often by people wishing to share files and information
	      which is too big to send by e-mail.
	 <dt> <i>Simple Mail Transfer Protocol [SMTP]:</i>
	 <dd> this is the protocol used to send e-mail messages around
	      the internet.  You may never encounter this directly,
	      but somewhere in your system, there is a program
	      (server) which uses this protocol to send your messages
	      out the the internet and recieve others.
	 <dt> <i>Gopher:</i>
	 <dd> This protocol developed at the U of Minnesota was a
	      predecessor to HTTP and the WWW.  It allows people to
	      share files in a way similar to HTTP, but there is no
	      formatting and graphics.
	 <dt> <i>Network(?) News Transfer Protocol [NNTP]:</i>
	 <dd> This is the protocol used to spread electronic newsgroup
	      messages around the world.  If you read news on the
	      internet, it has probably been send, at some point, with
	      this protocol from where is began to where you read it.
       </dl>
       <p>
       
       Of these, the most important are probably HTTP and FTP, and
       less so Gopher.
       <p>
  <dt> <b>Server</b>
  <dd> The term server used to refer to two related things: the
       physical computer which is making information available with
       one of the above protocols and the software which is running on
       that computer to implement the protocol.
       <p>

       For example, the ANS Home page is made available on a 'server'
       (computer) called "www.ans.org" using an HTTP server (software)
       called APACHE.
       <p>

       In this case, the most important of these two is the physical
       computer meaing.  It is used in addresses given on the internet
       as URL's... see next definition.
       <p>
  <dt> <b>Uniform Resource Locator [URL]</b> (often pronounced like
       the name "Earl")
  <dd> This is the way that addresses are indicated on the WWW.
       Surely, by now, most have you have seen addresses like:

       <table border=1><tr>
       <td>http://www.ans.org/</td><td>(ANS WWW Server)</td>
       </tr><tr>
       <td>http://www.ans.org/membership/</td><td>(ANS WWW Server membership section)</td>
       </tr><tr>
       <td>http://www.ans.org/membership/form.html</td><td>(ANS On-line membership form)</td>
       </tr><tr>
       <td>http://www.nytimes.com/</td><td>(New York Times on-line)</td>
       </tr><tr>
       <td>http://www.7up.com/</td><td>(7up soft drink commerical home page)</td>
       </tr></table>

       in TV commericals, print ads, or email from people like me :).
       These are all examples of URL's.  You can probably already see
       the basic format of a URL:
       <p>

       <center><code>protocol://server/</code></center>
       <p>

       The above examples are all URL's for the HTTP protocol.  Other
       possibilities are:
       <p>
       
       <blockquote><blockquote>
       <code>
       ftp://ftp.cdrom.com/           (A shareware software archive)<br>
       gopher://gopher.wisc.edu/      (The UW-Madison Gopher server)
       </code>
       </blockquote></blockquote>

       Some other protocols use slightly different formats:
       <p>
       
       <blockquote><blockquote>
       <code>
       news:sci.energy		       (newsgroup about energy)<br>
       mailto:wilson@maple.fzk.de     (send mail to this author)
       </code>
       </blockquote></blockquote>

       There will be more info on URL's when we discuss how to link
       documents together.

</dl>
</table>
<img src=/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif>
