<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">

<CENTER><TABLE WIDTH="600" >
<TR>
<TD>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>ADVANCE PROGRAM &amp; MEETING REGISTRATION</H3>

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>ANS EXECUTIVE CONFERENCE</H1>

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER><I>Decommissioning and Spent Fuel Disposal</I></H1>

<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Red Lion Inn at the Quay, Vancouver, Washington<BR>
April 27-30, 1997</H3>

<P><IMG SRC="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" HEIGHT=3 WIDTH=600></P>

<CENTER><TABLE WIDTH="100%" >
<TR>
<TD>Dear Colleague:</TD>

<TD ALIGN=RIGHT>February, 1997</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>

<P>The American Nuclear Society is sponsoring an Executive Conference on
Decommissioning and Spent Fuel Disposal, April 27-30, 1997, in Vancouver,
Washington. The conference will address the comprehensive and cost-effective
approaches that have been applied to decommissioning and the disposition
of spent fuel. Dedicated scientists, engineers, technicians, and federal
and state regulators who have extensive knowledge in the planning and implementation
of decommissioning and spent fuel management programs are participating
in this conference to share their experiences.</P>

<P>The technical program will highlight such topics as resolving issues
associated with prompt decommissioning at the Trojan Nuclear Plant, and
Nuclear Energy Institute initiatives related to decommissioning and long-term
spent fuel management, as well as public perception of the decommissioning
and management of spent fuel at nuclear power facilities. Other topics
such as major activities and projects, and the options, challenges, and
solutions concerning decommissioning and the disposition of spent fuel
will also be addressed. The topics will include on-site and off-site low-level
radioactive waste and mixed-waste management and industry experience in
termination survey programs and decommissioning cost management systems.
As part of the conference, we will spend a day at the Trojan Nuclear Plant,
which is currently being decommissioned and whose spent fuel will be transferred
to an independent spent fuel storage installation on site. While Trojan
will be highlighted, lessons learned at other decommissioning plants, and
industry and regulatory views on emerging issues will be discussed. The
tour will be augmented with a technology fair at which several companies
will demonstrate decommissioning and spent fuel management technologies.
If your company wishes to participate in the technology fair, please contact
R. Jon Stouky at (910)316-0707 or (910)316-0550 (FAX), or e-mail at jstouky@aol.com.</P>

<P>The conference will be preceded by a visit to the world famous Astoria
Seafood Festival on Saturday and a no-host organized golf tournament on
Sunday. During the week, a visit to the famous Pendelton wool outlet store
and a tour of the Columbia River Gorge will give spouses/guests the opportunity
to take advantage of the fabulous prices at the outlet store and to have
lunch on the scenic Columbia River. </P>

<P>Please review the Advance Program. We believe that this conference will
be a great opportunity to learn what has been accomplished recently in
decommissioning and spent fuel disposal. We look forward to your participation
at this important conference. </P>

<TABLE WIDTH="100%" >
<TR>
<TD>Michael B. Lackey<BR>
General Chairman</TD>

<TD ALIGN=RIGHT>R. Jon Stouky<BR>
Technical Program Chairman</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>

