<html><head><title>Nuke News, 15/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 15/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.14.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"NRC Gives Perry Plant Good Marks on Safety"</b><br>
CLEVELAND PLAIN DEALER, 3/13/96, p. 3B</i><br>
Jim Nichols
<p>

Hubert J. Miller, chief of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission's Region
III office, gave the Perry nuclear power plant in Ohio an "upbeat
review," saying the plant appears to be reversing its "dismal record."
<p>

Miller: "What we're looking for at this point is continued, steady
improvement, and I think that's what we're seeing."  He said that a
detailed inspection during the plant's current refueling shutdown
"found no significant safety concerns" and inspectors are "pleased" by
the plant's maintenance program.
<p>

But Miller said the NRC would be "more vigilant" -- at Perry and
nationwide -- in the wake of a Time magazine article that portrayed
the NRC as "overly chummy" with the nuclear power industry and
"hostile" to whistleblowers.  He added, however, that if plant
operator Centerior Energy Corp. continues to improve the plant, it
should have "little cause for concern."
<p>

Last year Perry operated 900f the time, best in its ten- year
history.  Investigators also found that a "recurring problem" at Perry
- - leaking fuel rods -- are not linked to Perry's operations, but to
manufacturing flaws.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Anger Is Main Reaction at Hearing on NU's Troubled Nuclear Power Plants"</b><br>
HARTFORD COURANT, 3/14/96, p. A21</i><br>
Barbara A. Nagy
<p>

Most of the 125 people who showed up for the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission's hearing Wednesday in New London, CT were "angry," reports
the HARTFORD COURANT.  The NRC is holding the hearings because of
alleged mismanagement at Northeast Utilities' three-unit Millstone
nuclear power plants.
<p>

Last year a Millstone engineer told the NRC that for the last 20 years
NU has not followed its operating license in refueling Unit 1. The
unit is now offline for a detailed analysis to make sure all systems
and procedures conform to the license.  On January 31, the NRC put
Millstone on its "watch list" until the agency sees "considerable
progress" -- something that usually takes two or three years.
<p>

Wayne Lanning, director of the NRC's Millstone oversight team, said he
intends to have public hearings every other month to bring people up
to date, listen to comments and answer questions.  But Hartford
resident Bob Rutter said, "This kind of company and this kind of fox
guarding the henhouse cannot be tolerated."
<p>

Nine-year-old David Walker told the NRC staffers he was afraid the
plant would shut down, putting his father out of work and wasting
millions of dollars.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... Nuclear waste is accumulating at all five of Florida's nuclear 
power plants and at 104 plants nationwide, with no permanent solution 
in sight, the ST. PETERSBURG FL TIMES reported in a lengthy feature 
(3/11/96, p. 10, Robert Trigaux).


</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
