<html><head><title>Nuke News, 14/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 14/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.13.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... The Ukrainian government "understated" a "serious" incident last
November, when a worker at Chernobyl received radiation equivalent to
"one person working in the hall" for a year.  A spokesman for the
International Atomic Energy Agency in Vienna described the incident as
"no big deal" and praised Ukrainian officials for providing full
information (JOURNAL OF COMMERCE, 3/11/96, p. 5B, Reuters).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Wisconsin Debates Plan for Nuclear Fuel Storage"</b><br>
JOURNAL OF COMMERCE, 3/14/96, p. 7B</i><br>
Lee Hawkins Jr.
<p>

The controversy over Wisconsin Electric Power Co.'s plan to build a
series of concrete-lined casks to encase spent nuclear fuel rods on
the shores of Lake Michigan "came to a head this week."  Local
residents and environmentalists testified before the Michigan Public
Service Commission about the potential dangers of storing the waste at
the site.
<p>

The Point Beach plan was drawn up after the Energy Dept. failed to
meet deadlines to build a national storage site and take possession of
the utility's spent fuel.  Wepco officials tried to reassure residents
that the site would only be used as a temporary storage option, while
the federal government completes its storage plans.
<p>

But Marvin Resinikoff of Radioactive Waste Associates warned
regulators to be concerned about the possibility that the govern- ment
may never uphold its promises to store the waste.  Resin- ikoff: "It
is clear that the DOE no longer intends to take spent fuel from
nuclear reactors any time before 2015, or possibly 2025.  It may never
take the spent fuel from Point Beach at all."
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"UC Scientists See Almost No Chance of Nuclear Waste Megablast"</b><br>
SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE, 3/13/96</i><br>
David Perlman
<p>

"There is virtually no chance" that nuclear waste stored at the
proposed Yucca Mountain repository in Nevada could ever "explode
catastrophically," according to a study released yesterday by
researchers from the University of California at Berkeley.  The study
was done in response to a report last year by two Los Alamos National
Laboratory physicists which claimed that plutonium and uranium
containers stored at the site could eventually corrode, allowing waste
to accumulate and explode.
<p>

A nine-member UC team last summer developed detailed models of the
proposed repository and calculated the likelihood that waste might
escape from storage canisters and migrate through the mountain to
create "explosive masses."  The researchers concluded that "by the
time you accumulate the necessary plutonium for an explosion -- about
250 kilograms -- most of it has decayed." The $125,000 study is being
submitted to Los Alamos officials, who financed it.  It has also been
prepared for publication in the scientific journal Nuclear Technology.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Spent Nuclear Fuel Storage," Baton Rouge ADVOCATE, 3/11/96,
       p. 8B, Edward Lambremont, who writes in letter to the editor
       that the "technology for safe disposal has existed since the
       early 1960s.  Congress should "pass a bill co-sponsored by
       almost 200 members of the House of Representatives that
       requires the US Department of Energy to take spent fuel rods
       from nuclear plants beginning in 1998 and store them in a
       facility at the Nevada Test Site."
</ul>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Expert Says Nuclear Plant Was Mismanaged"</b><br>
DALLAS MORNING NEWS, 3/10/96</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

Joe Williams Jr., a former nuclear plant operator and Navy admiral,
testified last Friday that he would have shut down the South Texas
Project nuclear plant in late 1992 because "years of mismanagement"
had left it unsafe.  Williams is the second witness called by the city
of Austin in its lawsuit against Houston Lighting &amp; Power, which
operates the plant.
<p>

Austin, which owns 160f the plant, is seeking more than $115 million
to recover money it paid for repairs and replacement power during a
14-month period in which the plant was shut down by the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission.  In earlier testimony, a "former member" of the
NRC said that although the plant had received "good" and "superior"
performance ratings, it suffered from "numerous" maintenance and
management problems that made it unsafe.  HL&amp;P denies the
allegations.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Senate Panel Approves Interim Site in Nevada for Nuclear Waste" </b><br>
WALL STREET JOURNAL, 3/14/96, p. B2</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

The Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee yesterday voted 12-6
to send approve legislation that would send 120,000 metric tons of
spent nuclear fuel to a temporary storage site in Nevada and to speed
the development of the Ward Valley storage site in California.
<p>

The bill is similar to one passed by the House Commerce Committee last
summer.  It would allow for interim storage of the waste at Yucca
Mountain, NV, the planned site of the nation's permanent repository
for spent nuclear fuel.  However, the bill does not affect preparation
of the permanent site.
<p>

The bill calls for the Energy Dept. to start accepting waste for
temporary storage at Yucca Mountain by November 30, 1999, "provided
that the site has been approved by then for permanent storage.  In
addition, the bill would allow California to start developing the Ward
Valley site "after certain tests are conducted."  The Clinton
administration "has been reluctant" to approve the transfer of the
Ward Valley land to the state.
<p>

SEE ALSO: 
<ul>
  <li> "Energy News," CONGRESS DAILY, 3/13/96, Staff Report.
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Hanford Dump Studies Draw Fire -- States Draw Battle Lines"</b><br>
SEATTLE TIMES, 3/11/96, p. B1</i><br>
Danny Westneat
<p>

Oregon and Washington State officials have "not reacted well" to the
notion that the Dept. of Energy may bring plutonium or other
radioactive wastes across their states to the "sprawling," 560-square-
mile Hanford complex near the Tri-Cities.
<p>

Gov. Mike Lowry (D-WA) accused DOE of being not entirely "forthright"
with the public on plans to treat, store or dump wastes at Hanford,
which already has the most nuclear wastes in the U.S.  Michael
Grainey, speaking for Gov. John Kitzhaber (D-OR), said Oregon will not
stand for becoming the nation's "radioactive garbage dump."
<p>

Though DOE has identified Hanford as one of the top candidates for
treating and disposing of nuclear wastes from around the nation,
officials say no decisions have been made. DOE plans to have meetings
in Portland, Seattle and Richland in April to discuss the issue.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Loss of Nuclear Fuel Confirmed by Lithuania"</b><br>
NORTHERN NEW JERSEY RECORD, 3/10/96, p. a20</i><br>
Wire Reports
<p>

Lithuania's National Security Department has acknowledged that a
nuclear container that disappeared four years ago from the Ignalina
nuclear power plant was stolen.  A security official told the Interfax
news agency that a metal tube containing uranium was found 3 1/2 miles
from the plant Friday.
<p>

Plant managers in 1993 said the material had been "misplaced."
Lithuanian officials now say they know where part of the uranium was
stored and the identity of the thieves.


</td>
</tr>
</table>
