<html><head><title>Nuke News, 13/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 13/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.12.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"Permanent Closing Urged for Salem Nuclear Generators"</b><br>
PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER, 3/13/96, p. B3</i><br>
James O'Neill
<p>

Several "watchdog" groups yesterday "demanded" that the Public Service
Electric &amp; Gas Co. permanently shut down both its Salem 1 and
Salem 2 nuclear reactors because of cracks in their steam generator
tubes.  But PSE&amp;G said it did not intend to restart the either of
the reactors until they are proven safe. PSE&amp;G spokesman Neil
Brown accused the groups of employing "scare tactics" that are "not in
anyone's best interest."
<p>

The New Jersey Public Interest Research Group and the Washington-
based Nuclear Information and Resource Service said they are skeptical
about PSE&amp;G's ability to inspect and repair the units in a way
that will ensure no further cracks occur. But Victor Dricks of the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission said that PSE&amp;G is expected to
submit a plan of action once it completes inspections of the two
units.  Dricks: "If we thought the plant was unsafe, we wouldn't let
it open."
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Japan Restarts Advanced Water Reactor After Glitch"</b><br>
JOURNAL OF COMMERCE, 3/13/96, p. 4B</i><br>
Reuters
<p>

Japan yesterday resumed testing the world's first advanced boiling-
water reactor after shutting it down last month due to a problem with
its power system.  The reactor is expected to start producing
electricity today.
<p>

The 13.5 million kilowatt reactor is an improved version of the
conventional light-water reactor that industrial officials claim is
safer.  It was shut down manually on February 23 after power trouble
caused a pump to stop.  No radioactivity was found around the reactor.
<p>

But those troubles nearly coincided with an accident at Japan's
prototype fast-breeder reactor Monju, which fueled public fears of
nuclear power accidents.  Despite both mishaps, the Japanese
government has reiterated that it will not change its plans to
increase the country's use of nuclear power from 30% to 42% by 2010.
Monju, however, remains shut down.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Japan's Nuclear Reactor Develops Cracks in Gauge," WALL STREET
       JOURNAL, 3/13/96, p. A6, Staff Report, which reports that
       officials at the Monju reactor found new cracks in a gauge that
       monitors the temperature of sodium used to cool the reactor.
       Officials say more tests need to be done to determine if other
       gauges at the reactor could suffer similar cracks.
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

...  Rochester Gas &amp; Electric's 470-megawatt Robert E.  Ginna
nuclear power plant remained shut down for the third day Saturday
after a faulty monitoring device caused a non-emergency shutdown
(BUFFALO NEWS, "N- Plant Closed for a Third Day," 3/10/96, p.  A8,
Staff Report).
</td>
</tr>
</table>
