<html><head><title>Nuke News, 11/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 11/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.08.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>
<i><b>"Safety Deadline Set by Nuclear Agency for 2 Power Plants"</b><br>
NEW YORK TIMES, 3/9/96, p. A1</i><br>
Matthew Wald
<p>

"The Nuclear Regulatory Commission has given New England's largest
utility 30 days" to demonstrate that emergency safety systems at two
of its nuclear power plants in Connecticut comply with NRC rules, the
NEW YORK TIMES reports.
<p>

Northeast Utilities is "already under fire" for violating rules for
handling spent fuel rods at its Millstone 1 reactor near Waterford, CT
and now the NRC says it is concerned about several equipment problems
at Millstone 2 and 3 and the Connecticut Yankee plant in Haddam Neck.
The NRC ordered Millstone 2 to remain closed for now and said it was
sending about 20 inspectors to investigate the two plants' operations.
<p>

The agency's order is "a stinging rebuke" to Northeast Utilities and
"an embarrassment" to the NRC itself, which last month was the subject
of a TIME cover story about the commission's failure to enforce its
regulations.
<p>

<center><i>NOT UNUSUAL?</i></center>
<p>

Ted Feigenbaum, the utility's chief nuclear officer, "said none of the
problems was serious but ... collectively they undermined the
commission's confidence in plant safety." Feigenbaum said finding
minor problems was "not unexpected under the circumstances, when
you're starting to turn over rocks."
<p>

But Paul Blanch, a former NU engineer who claims he was "hounded out
of his job" for raising safety issues, said a close review "would find
much more," the TIMES reports.
<p>

Millstone 1 has been shut for weeks at a cost of $5-6 million a month,
mostly for replacement power.  At Millstone 2, the cost is $8-10
million, the TIMES reports.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "NRC Expands Investigation at Connecticut Nuclear Plant,"
       WASHINGTON POST, 3/9/96, p. A2, Gary Lee, which reports the NRC
       is conducting a review of spent-fuel cooling pools at all of
       the country's 109 reactors.  The POST reports that "Tom"
       Feigenbaum, identified as Northeast Utilities executive VP and
       CEO, cited "some problems with our license documentation."
  <li> "Nuclear Plants Are Safe, Northeast Utilities Says," NEW YORK
       TIMES, 3/10/96, p. 36, Andrew Revkin, which describes the NRC
       complaints as "a number of small discrepancies in records" at
       the Millstone reactors and reports there was no immediate risk
       to the public from the reactors.  The article reports that one
       of the industry's "most fervent champions of safety," S. David
       Freeman, considers the criticism of both the NRC and NU
       "overblown."  But "perhaps the most difficult challenge for the
       company ... is to rebuild shattered public confidence," Revkin
       reports.
  <li> "US Expanding Probe of N.E. Atom Utility," BOSTON GLOBE,
       3/10/96, p. 37, John Milne.
  <li> "NRC May Close Two Plants Owned by Northeast Utilities, Citing
       Safety," WALL STREET JOURNAL, 3/11/96, p. A16, Ross Kerber.
  <li> "Nuclear Watchdog Agency Probes Four New England Plants,"
       CHRISTIAN SCIENCE MONITOR, 3/11/96, p. 4, Peter Spotts.
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Appraisal Company Had Never Assessed a Nuclear Plant"</b><br>
HARTFORD COURANT, 3/7/96, p. B3</i><br>
Rosalinda DeJesus
<p>

A 1992 appraisal of the Connecticut Yankee nuclear power plant and the
credentials of the engineering firm that did the appraisal are "hot
issues" in a court case nearing its conclusion in the Middletown
Superior Court.
<p>

Pennsylvania-based Dean and Associates assessed the plant's fair
market value in 1992 at $840 million, "triggering" a lawsuit by owner
Northeast Utilities, which claimed the value was closer to $230
million. Then, in testimony two months ago in the "high- profile"
case, the engineering firm's owner, Steve Dean, "acknowledged
miscalculating" the 1992 appraisal and revised the figure to $485.7
million.  That had an "immediate impact" on the town of Haddam, which
now may have to raise property taxes to make up for the loss of
revenue from Connecticut Yankee.
<p>

<center><i>NO PRIOR EXPERIENCE?</i></center>
<p>

Former Selectman Michael Bromley said in an interview last week that
the accounting firm Arthur Andersen had recommended Dean and
Associates -- and the contract was awarded without competition -- even
though the firm had never assessed a nuclear plant.  Steve Dean is a
former engineer with the Nuclear Regulatory Commission and
Westinghouse. Bromley: We did not pick these people out of a hat."
<p>

The two sides in the case are scheduled to present closing arguments
today (Monday).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>



<i><b>"N-Plant Lands HL&amp;P, Austin in Court"</b><br>
HOUSTON CHRONICLE, 3/7/96, p. 23A</i><br>
George Flynn
<p>

In the opening of a trial in state District Court, attorneys for
Houston Lighting &amp; Power Co. and the city of Austin, TX last week
presented "opposite images" of the management of the Bay City nuclear
power plant.  Austin, a co-owner of the plant, is suing HL&amp;P for
$125 million in costs resulting from a 1993 shutdown of the plant.
<p>

Randy Wilson, an attorney for the city, said the plant's failure
"stemmed from HL&amp;P's rush to cut costs" too quickly. Wilson quoted
an HL&amp;P plant manager who said, "We tried to get 'cheap' before we
got good."  And he said HL&amp;P continued to postpone maintenance and
"slash training programs" in the face of "mounting outside criticism."
<p>

HL&amp;P attorney David Beck "accused Austin of indulging in
revisionist history and selective memory" about what really went on at
the plant.  He said Austin, as co-owner, sat on the management board
and "was aware of exactly what was going on."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


.....Environmental and nuclear watchdog groups last Friday said they would
ask New Jersey-based Public Service Electric &amp; Gas to permanently
close its Salem Nuclear Generating Station.  Equip- ment and
management problems have "plagued" the Salem 1 and Salem 2 reactors
over the years, and recently inspectors discovered cracks in the
reactors' steam generators (PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER, 3/9/96, p. D3,
Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>



<i><b>"Vanishing Act"</b><br>
ELECTRIC PERSPECTIVES, 3-4/96 issue, p. 4</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

A recent survey by the Washington International Energy Group (WEIG)
and Canadian Electrical Association reveals that most power industry
executives believe they will experience "massive consolidation,"
achieve universal retail access, and get more involved on the "other
side of the meter."
<p>

The "1996 Electric Industry Outlook" survey polled 3,557 senior
executives from electric utilities and independent power producers in
the US and Canada.  The survey found that only 42% believe their
company will be intact in ten years.  Forty-eight percent believe
their company will acquire or be acquired by another company, and 62%
think hostile takeovers will increase. Fifty-five percent said they
were currently involved in merger/acquisition discussions.
<p>

Executives were divided over the future of nuclear power. About 39%
said nuclear power can be competitive, while an equal percentage said
it cannot.  Only about 8% think there will be a resurgence of nuclear
power.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Le Bon Coal"</b><br>
RURAL ELECTRIFICATION, 3/6/96, p. 14</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

Southern France will soon boast "the world's largest clean coal power
plant."  State-owned Electricite de France commissioned the 250-
megawatt plant, which features a circulating-fluidized-bed boiler.
The power plant will be built by a consortium that includes ENDESA,
the Spanish power group.
<p>

"The project is a new step for the French utility," which currently
gets 800f its power from nuclear reactors.  If the plant is
successful, EDF hopes to use the technology in other countries, says
spokeswoman Sarah Berkey.
     
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
