<html><head><title>Nuke News, 8/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 8/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.07.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... Peco agreed it will not charge its customers for what it has spent
on replacement power -- an estimated $54 million -- while the Salem 
nuclear power plant is shut down (PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER, 3/8/96, p. 
C3, Staff Report).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Understanding Peco's Response"</b><br>
PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER, 3/8/96, p. C1</i><br>
B.J. Phillips, Column
<p>

Columnist B.J. Phillips notes a letter to the editor from Peco Energy
Co. CEO Joseph Paquette that was published in the PHILADELPHIA
INQUIRER and this space on Wednesday, in which Paquette said
"reforming the electricity industry ... would be a costly mistake. ...
I love his letter because it's a case study of how a special interest
protects its turf," Phillips writes.
<p>

Phillips dismisses Paquette's claims that the state would lose tax
revenues and that high electric rates in Pennsylvania do not hurt
industry because Peco's rates are competitive with those elsewhere in
the Northeast.  Phillips: "The Northeast, a.k.a. the Rust Belt, isn't
taking our jobs; the Southeast and Southwest are.  One hallmark of
these fast-growing states: cheap electricity."
<p>

But Paquette's greatest worry is recovering the cost of "those two
nuclear albatrosses" from ratepayers, so that investors do not have to
take the entire hit.  "Spoken like a man who knows he has captive
customers but not captive shareholders," Phillips notes, concluding,
"Deregulate 'em.  Now."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Next Stop for O'Leary: Capitol Hill"</b><br>
WASHINGTON POST, 3/8/96, p. A1</i><br>
Sharon Walsh
<p>

As the House Commerce Committee resumes hearings today on Energy
Secretary Hazel O'Leary's "lavish spending on official travel," her
critics "intend to broaden their attacks" and argue that O'Leary's
"disregard for spending has hurt department employees and programs."
<p>

"Resentment" among DOE employees "is building" after notices recently
went out telling them to expect more unpaid furloughs and no more
performance bonuses as part of the broader effort to avoid
layoffs. "With O'Leary now planning her next international trip to an
energy conference in Vienna, some employees grumble that the secretary
should find a way to take the budget hit herself."
<p>

The lengthy, detailed WASHINGTON POST article notes that "travel
extravagance" has been a "Washington trap" for many previous
officials. O'Leary and her supporters say the attacks are motivated by
partisan politics and disagreements over policy. But O'Leary "has been
criticized for not heeding an inspector general's recommendation that
she take no expensive foreign trips" until she has made accounting
changes in managing the DOE travel budget.
     

</td>
</tr>
</table>
