<html><head><title>Nuke News, 7/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 7/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.06.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... The Nuclear Regulatory Commission has scheduled an "informal 
public hearing" today to assess allegations that Northeast Utilities 
has violated the operating licenses of its nuclear power plants in 
Connecticut and New Hampshire. Whistleblower George Galatis says plant 
engineers have routinely overloaded waste-storage pools.  Another 
meeting this Friday will focus on cracks found in the steam generator 
pipes at the Millstone 1 plant (BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 3/7/96, 
Associated Press).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Tribe:  'No Deal' on Nuclear Storage"</b><br>
MINNEAPOLIS STAR-TRIBUNE, 3/6/96, p. B1</i><br>
Tom Meersman
<p>

Dealings between Northern States Power Co. and the Prairie Island
Dakota Tribe "dissolved into confusion and disagreement" on Tuesday
just hours after both parties said they had reached an agreement on
nuclear waste storage.  The tribe "surprised nearly everyone" by
announcing "there is no deal" until it receives land and compensation
in exchange for supporting changes in a 1994 state waste-storage law.
<p>

On Monday, NSP President and CEO Jim Howard and Tribal Chairman Curtis
Campbell met and issued a letter indicating they had agreed on a
"limited proposal" in which NSP would give the tribe $2 million in
cash and additional annual payments.  NSP would also win relief from a
provision requiring it to search for an alternative waste-storage site
in Goodhue County.  The utility currently stores waste in on-site
casks.
<p>

But the Howard-Campbell letter "omitted any mention of land," and the
tribe "apparently had a change of heart Tuesday." Tribal leaders
"acknowledged" the confusion they were creating but said the only
agreement so far is "an agreement in principle to continue working
together" on the legislation.
<p>

"The issue of land has bothered" Gov. Arne Carlson (R) and some
legislators who say the tribe may use the land to build another
casino.  The tribe says its main motive is to relocate residents who
no longer want to live adjacent to NSP's Red Wing nuclear power plant
and its on- site waste-disposal facility. Some observers questioned
whether there is enough time to enact any changes in the current
legislative session.
<p>

SEE ALSO:
<ul>
  <li> "Nuke Deal," MINNEAPOLIS STAR-TRIBUNE, 3/6/96, Editorial, which
       asserts the latest version of the legislation was "not all it
       could have been" but still "much better than none."  The
       editorial suggests the tribe use the cash it would receive to
       buy additional land.  Passage of the bill would bring numerous
       benefits and "offer Minnesotans a respite from toxic nuclear
       wrangling."
</ul>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
