<html><head><title>Nuke News, 6/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 6/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.05.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>
<i><b>"Caliente Asks Congress for Nuclear Waste Funds" </b><br>
LAS VEGAS REVIEW-JOURNAL, 3/1/96, p. 3B</i><br>
Tony Batt
<p>

Caliente, NV, Mayor Kevin Phillips asked the House Appropriations
Subcommittee on February 29 to restore oversight funding for Nevada
counties that want to review the government's nuclear waste studies at
Yucca Mountain.  Congress cut funding for the counties in the 1996
budget when "some lawmakers complained Nevada had used federal money
to oppose studies of Yucca Mountain as a permanent nuclear waste
repository." Phillips told the committee "...you've stopped the only
credible scientific oversight studies going on."
<p>

Also at the hearing were Sens. Richard Bryan (D-NV) and Harry Reid
(D-NV), who sought to fight any funding for temporary nuclear waste
storage in Nevada.  Congress is waiting to vote on a bill by Rep. Fred
Upton (R-MI) which would allow temporary nuclear waste storage in
Nevada, but the committee could still retain Nevada for interim
nuclear waste storage in this year's budget.  Reid: "Basically, we
were there to alert the committee not to try anything cute because
we'll be waiting for you."
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Austin, San Antonio Set for Legal Fight over Nuclear Plant" </b><br>
HOUSTON BUSINESS JOURNAL, 3/1/96</i><br>
Ann de Rouffignac
<p>

The city-owned utilities of Austin and San Antonio will face Houston
Light &amp; Power Co. in court this week over "costs and mismanagement" at
the South Texas Project nuclear power plant. The dispute is over who
should pay for replacement fuel and power during the plant's yearlong
outage that began in 1993.
<p>

Austin owns a 16hare of the plant, and San Antonio has a 28take.
Central Power &amp; Light of Corpus Christi owns 25.2%, but is not
taking part in the lawsuit.  HL&amp;P owns a 30.8hare and is the
plant's operator and manager.
<p>

Austin says HL&amp;P owes it "about $125 million," while San Antonio
is claiming "about $200 million."  Besides the claims for replacement
fuel and power costs, San Antonio says it shouldn't have to pay for
"certain operation and maintenance expenses that were incurred because
of poor management."
<p>

Between 1983 and 1989, Austin and HL&amp;P fought a "costly battle"
over construction cost overruns at the South Texas Project -- a case
that Austin ultimately lost.  But John Gooding, Austin's in-house
counsel, says, "We have a negligence cause of action instead of a
limited breach of contract case.  We think we'll present a strong case
that HL&amp;P didn't manage the nuclear plant to an accepted
standard."
<p>

HL&amp;P spokesman Graham Painter: "We don't believe they have a
case.... HL&amp;P has not indemnified other owners against unforeseen
things that have happened at the plant."
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
