<html><head><title>Nuke News, 5/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 5/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.04.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"Radioactive Release Contaminates 16 Maine Yankee Workers" </b><br>
BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 3/4/96</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

Sixteen workers at the Maine Yankee nuclear power plant were
"contaminated with low levels of radiation during a routine
maintenance project," the US Nuclear Regulatory Commission said.
<p>

An initial review by the NRC found the radiation release was "well
below regulatory limits," but it was still an "unusual situation,"
said NRC spokesman Victor Dricks.  The mechanics were trying to
install a cap on a tank when some radioactive gas was released.
<p>

Maine Yankee VP Graham Leitch said his company was "undertaking an
extensive review of why this occurred and what steps are necessary to
ensure it does not occur again."  The incident came just weeks after
Maine Yankee returned to service after extensive repairs to its steam
generator tubes.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Scientists Look into Nuclear-Waste Sorter" </b><br>
SALT LAKE TRIBUNE, 3/2/96, p. A3</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

Scientists at the Los Alamos National Laboratory are developing a
device that could be used to separate low-level waste from
uncontaminated waste.  Called a WAND -- Waste Acceptance for
Nonradioactive Disposal -- the detector screens "routine, low-density
trash" to see whether some of it could be disposed of at a
nonradioactive landfill.
<p>

The lab buries more than 85,000 cubic feet of low-level waste at its
Area G landfill each year, with disposal costs running about a $100 a
cubic feet and rising.  With WAND, the lab might be able to remove
much of the nonradioactive waste, "especially the 200r so that is
paper, cardboard or plastic," and dispose of it at a "normal landfill"
at about 25 cents a cubic foot.
<p>

The lab said WAND "still must prove its effectiveness in tests before
it can be put into use."
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Nuclear Sale"</b><br>
FINANCIAL TIMES, 3/4/96, p. 17</i><br>
Editorial
<p>

Negotiations over privatizing the UK's nuclear industry have "turned
into a standoff," according to the FINANCIAL TIMES.  The conflict
between the British government and British Energy -- the company
created for the sale -- centers on two issues: liabilities and debts.
<p>

The government "appears to have won" the first point, insisting that
all liabilities associated with running British Energy's eight power
stations should also be transferred to the new company.  But the issue
of debt levels remains "fiercely contested."
<p>

The FINANCIAL TIMES:  "Mr. Ian Lang, industry secretary, should 
continue to play tough on this point.  The government has been rightly 
criticized for privatizing many utilities with unnecessarily well- 
capitalized balance sheets, in order to smooth the sale.  Instead, 
initial debt should be set as high as expectations of cash flow will 
permit."
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... Public Service Electric &amp; Gas Co. and other utilities sued 
Westinghouse Electric Corp. in an attempt to recover at least $300 
million for allegedly defective steam generators at PSE&amp;G's Salem 
nuclear power plant (PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER, 3/5/96, p. C3, Staff 
Report).

</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
