<html><head><title>Nuke News, 4/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 4/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.01.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"Deal Apparently Reached in NSP Suit Over Nuclear Plant
Equipment"</b><br>
MINNEAPOLIS STAR TRIBUNE, 3/1/96, p. B1</i><br>
Tom Meersman
<p>

Northern States Power Co. and Westinghouse Electric Corp. have
"apparently achieved a breakthrough" in a multi-million- dollar
lawsuit over the Prairie Island nuclear plant just days before the
dispute was scheduled to go to trial.
<p>

Both parties declined to discuss details, and it is unclear whether
all of them have been worked out.  But the trial, which was scheduled
for court today (3/4), has been removed from the trial calendar.
<p>

NSP filed the suit in July 1993 on grounds that the equipment built
and installed by Westinghouse in the early 1970s was already wearing
out before its guaranteed 40-year lifespan.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Millstone Oversight an Embarrassment, Official Says"</b><br>
HARTFORD COURANT, 3/1/96, p. A6</i><br>
Barbara Nagy
<p>

A top Nuclear Regulatory Commission official said he is embarrassed
the NRC took 20 years to realize the Millstone 1 nuclear power plant
was being refueled improperly, and he acknowledged the agency has lost
public trust.
<p>

Speaking at a news conference on February 29, Thomas Martin, NRC's
Northeast regional administrator, said there is "no excuse" for the
oversight and the agency is investigating how the irregularities went
undetected.  The refueling practices at the plant owned by Northeast
Utilities became public last year after a series of problems.
<p>

Unit 1 has been off-line since November for detailed review of the
plant's systems and is not expected to operate again until mid-summer
at the earliest, Martin said.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Nuclear Plant's Value Melts Down"</b><br>
HARTFORD COURANT, 3/1/96, p. B1</i><br>
Rosalinda DeJesus
<p>

"Acknowledging a major miscalculation" in its assessment of the
Connecticut Yankee nuclear power plant, the town of Haddam has
released figures indicating its new assessment is about $840 million,
"millions below" the previous number.  The town's "grand list" of all
taxable property dropped by more than $280 million, the HARTFORD
COURANT reports.  "The change will almost certainly cause a rise in
local property taxes next year."
<p>

Northeast Utilities, the principal owner of Connecticut Yankee, sued
the town in 1992, saying its assessment of the plant was too
high. Northeast "insists" the value is about $230 million.  "People
affiliated with both sides" of the suit say "a settlement may be
drawing near." Closing arguments in the trial begin March 11 in
Middletown Superior Court.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>



<i><b>"Shut Nuclear Plant to Resume Operation"</b><br>
PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER, 3/2/96, p. B1</i><br>
Douglas Campbell
<p>

A team of eight federal inspectors on March 1 said New Jersey's Hope
Creek nuclear power plant is almost ready to resume generating
electricity.  The plant has been shut down since November when, during
a scheduled refueling, operators inadvertently reduced the flow of
cooling water to the reactor.
<p>

In a public meeting, the Nuclear Regulatory Commission told the
plant's owner, Public Service Electric &amp; Gas Co., that the utility
must report on three items before it can restart.  Citing declining
performance, the NRC decided to conduct an inspection of the Hope
Creek plant.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Volunteers Sought for Waste Site"</b><br>
PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER, 3/3/96</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

The Pennsylvania Dept. of Environmental Protection on March 1 issued a
plan to encourage communities across the state to consider hosting a
low-level radioactive waste storage site.
<p>

The plan, formulated by the DEP and contractor Chem-Nuclear Systems
Inc., offers municipalities information on what is involved in
becoming the site, and "provides a way for community leaders to
express interest in the project."  Pennsylvania agreed in 1985 to
build and operate a site to store waste generated there and in
Maryland, Delaware and West Virginia.
<p>

Officials hope to have the site open in about seven years. A five-
year technical evaluation of the state to find safe and suitable
locations was halted in July, when the DEP narrowed the focus of the
search to finding a volunteer.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"SCC Staff Report Criticizes Federal Waste-Fund Effort"</b><br>
VIRGINIAN-PILOT, 2/29/96, p. D1</i><br>
Dave Mayfield
<p>

"The federal government's expensive and time-consuming search" for a
place to store spent fuel from nuclear power plants "poses an
'economic threat to Virginia,'" according to a state Corporation
Commission staff report.
<p>

But the report stopped short of urging the commissioners to allow
Virginia utilities to discontinue collecting fees from their customers
to help pay for the waste-fund effort.
<p>

After spending $4.5 billion searching for a nuclear waste disposal
site, the DOE says it cannot open a site until 2010 -- 12 years later
than required by federal law.  Virginia ratepayers have paid $361
million toward the DOE waste fund and may have to pay another $400
million.  The SCC staff recommended against any action on the matter
until a multi-state lawsuit against DOE is resolved.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "End Nuclear 'Ripoff,' State Official Urges," MINNEAPOLIS STAR
       TRIBUNE, 3/1/96, p. B3, Associated Press, which reports that
       Minnesota Dept. of Public Service Commissioner Kris Sanda on
       February 29 testified to Congress that Minnesotans have paid
       more than $246.6 million for a nuclear waste site in what
       amounts to a "consumer ripoff."
</ul>
     
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
