<html><head><title>Nuke News, 1/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 1/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.02.28.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>
... As reported yesterday in "Daily Utility News," a power
failure in a key safety system shut down one of the two nuclear reactors at 
Baltimore Gas &amp; Electric's Calvert Cliffs nuclear power plant late 
Tuesday evening.  Emergency backup power kicked in and normal power was 
restored in three hours.  The unit is "likely to remain idle through 
the weekend" as company officials determine the cause of the power 
failure (WASHINGTON POST, 3/1/96, p. C4, Staff Report).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>  "O'Leary Backs Yucca Mtn."</b><br>
LAS VEGAS SUN, 3/1/96, p. 5A</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

"Saying there is an urgent need to dispose of tons of
surplus plutonium and uranium," Energy Secretary Hazel O'Leary on 
Wednesday reiterated support for a high-level nuclear waste 
repository at Yucca Mtn., NV.  Lacking a permanent disposal facility 
and facing perennial delays at the Yucca Mtn. site, many electric 
utilities have had to store such wastes at their own facilities.
<p>
     
The issue came up as O'Leary laid out a "draft programmatic 
environmental impact statement" outlining ways to manage the federal 
government's nuclear weapons stockpiles.  The Energy Dept. has 
postponed a decision on how to dispose of surplus plutonium and 
bomb-grade uranium from dismantled weapons.  But it said it has 
narrowed its options to three:
<ul>
  <li>  Use the material to power nuclear reactors;
  <li> "Immobilize" it in glass or ceramics, possibly along with other
       high-level wastes;
  <li> Bury it deep underground.
</ul>
A decision on the surplus nuclear materials is expected in June.<p>

SEE ALSO:
<ul>
  <li>US Proposes to Reduce Nuclear Arms Facilities," WALL STREET JOURNAL, 2/29/96, p. A20.<br>
  <li>"Plan for Managing Nuclear Arms Leaves a Tough Issue
       Unresolved," NEW YORK TIMES, 2/29/96, p. A18, Matthew Wald. <br>

  <li>"US to Make Nuclear Components," PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER,
       2/29/96, p. A4, H, Josef Hebert, Associated Press.<br>

  <li>"Downsizing at Nuclear Arms Facilities," WASHINGTON POST,
       2/29/96, p. A6, Gary Lee.<br>
       
  <li>"Department Releases Post-Cold-War Plans for Nuclear Weapons
       Complex, Plutonium Storage and Disposition," DEPT. OF ENERGY
       RELEASE, 2/28/96, Contact Barbara Wetherell, 202- 586-5806.
</ul>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
