<html><head><title>Nuke News, 28/2/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 28/2/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.02.23.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>
<i><b>"Maine Yankee Probes Said Costly But Vital; Nuclear Plant
Official Defends Multiple Investigations"</b><br>
BANGOR DAILY NEWS, 2/24/96 </i><br>
Bruce Kyle
<p>

Maine Yankee President Charles D. Frizzle told the Rockland, ME,
Rotary Club Friday that multiple investigations into an anonymous
allegation that Maine Yankee safety records are "enormously time-
consuming and expensive," but also "absolutely essential."
<p>

An anonymous letter sent to the Union of Concerned Scientists in
December charged that Maine Yankee has used a "flawed" computer code
to monitor its safety systems since 1984 and has "knowingly concealed"
its knowledge of the flaw from federal regulators.
<p>

The Nuclear Regulatory Commission is investigating the charge, with
its work monitored by the agency's Inspector General.  Maine Yankee
has conducted its own inquiry and hired a Pennsylvania law firm to
conduct an independent investigation.  Only Maine Yankee's internal
investigation is complete, finding no evidence of a flaw or
coverup. But Frizzle said he realizes federal officials will have the
"final word."
<p>

The plant shut down "early last year" for steam-generator repairs and
was supposed to go back on line in December.  The letter delayed
startup until January, when the NRC said the plant could run at 900f
full power until the investigation was complete.  Frizzle said the
month's delay cost Maine Yankee customers nearly $5 million for
purchased power, and the legal expenses so far stand at $900,000.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Nuclear Middlemen"</b><br>
NEW YORK TIMES, 2/28/96, p. A17</i><br>
Kenneth Timmerman, Op-Ed
<p>

The US Senate "is scheduled to hold hearings today on a dangerous new
treaty negotiated by the Clinton administration that would lift
longstanding controls on nuclear trade," writes Kenneth Timmerman,
director of the Middle East Data Project, a research group that tracks
nuclear proliferation.
<p>

The treaty grants the 15 members of Euratom, the European Union's
atomic energy agency, "the right to sell without our approval"
plutonium that they have extracted from spent US nuclear fuel, writes
Timmerman. Last November, President Clinton told Congress that the
treaty would help "insure a continuation and, I hope, growth of U.S.
civil nuclear exports to Euratom member states."
<p>

"The administration, it seems, is pushing exports with one hand while
trying to restrain nuclear proliferation with the other."  The treaty
"imposes trade controls on rogue states like Iran, but trusts our
allies to judge which nations will use nuclear materials only for
peaceful purposes."  Several European nations, including Germany,
France, Belgium, Italy and Austria "regularly do business with
would-be nuclear powers like Iran and Iraq," Timmerman concludes.
<p>

SEE ALSO:
<ul>
  <li> "The U.S. and Nuclear Technology in Europe," WASHINGTON TIMES,
       2/28/96, p. A21, an op-ed in which Alexander Haig, former
       secretary of state and NATO commander, calls the treaty "a
       cornerstone of the Atlantic Alliance's shared commitment to
       nuclear non- proliferation."
</ul>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"O'Leary Expresses an Interest in Staying at Energy After '96"</b><br>
WASHINGTON POST, 2/28/96, p. A17</i><br>
Reuters
<p>

Energy Secretary Hazel O'Leary indicated yesterday she would like to
stay on in her post if President Clinton is reelected. O'Leary,
speaking to a reporter after addressing a state energy officials
group, said efforts in Congress to cut the DOE's budget and
differences over energy policies made her "mad enough to say, 'yeah, I
need to stay here and finish it.'"  O'Leary said she also wants to
push for more sustainable energy programs and fight the proliferation
of weapons-grade nuclear material.
<p>

O'Leary dismissed the congressional investigation into her travel
expenditures as a "side show" and declined to comment further.  But
Rep. Joe Barton (R-TX), chairman of the House Commerce oversight and
investigations subcommittee, said Monday he plans to expand his
panel's probe.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
