<html><head><title>Nuke News, 23/2/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 23/2/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.02.22.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"Ex-NU Workers Refuse NRC Cooperation" </b><br>
BOSTON GLOBE, 2/22/96</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

Six former employees who have "blown the whistle on safety problems"
at the Millstone nuclear plant in Waterford, CT, are refusing to take
part in a federal investigation into their claims of harassment. Their
attorney, Ernest C. Hadley, said the Nuclear Regulatory Commission is
"mishandling the investigation" by revealing the workers' names to
Northeast Utilities.
<p>

Some of the workers have legal action against NU, and, said Hadley,
disclosing their names "could hurt their cases."  Giving their names
to the utility also makes it easier for NU to prepare responses to
allegations that "may surface" during the NRC review.  NRC spokeswoman
Diane Screni said that for the NRC to get both sides, the names had to
be disclosed to NU.  Hadley suggested turning the investigation over
to the NRC's inspector general, an independent arm of the agency.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "State Regulators to Review Nuclear Plant Management," BOSTON
       GLOBE, 2/22/96, Associated Press, which reports that
       Connecticut regulators have hired a consultant to review NU's
       management of its "troubled nuclear plants."
  <li> "Watchdog Group Questions Seabrook Safety After Uncovering
       Forged Documents," BOSTON GLOBE, 2/20/96, Associated Press,
       which reports that We The People Inc. wants the NRC to reopen
       its investigation into "forged engineering documents" at the
       NU-owned Seabrook nuclear plant in New Hampshire.  The NRC
       ruled earlier that the "forgeries did not affect safety" and
       took no action against Seabrook.
</ul>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Yankee Rowe"</b><br>
BOSTON GLOBE, 2/22/96</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

The Nuclear Regulatory Commission has rejected an antinuclear group's
request for more hearings into the dismantling of the 185- megawatt
Yankee Rowe nuclear plant, which closed in 1992 after 30 years of
operation.  After an earlier ruling by a federal appeals court, the
NRC ordered a halt to "major" work pending public hearings.
<p>

The Shelburne, MA-based Citizens Awareness Network contended hat more
work was being done than was allowed by the court. Plant officials
said they were doing only "minor work."  The NRC described the work as
"necessary to protect workers and the public" and said it included
"such things as the cleanup of a liquid decontamination pit."
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... Duke Power Co. denied a British official's statements that the 
company is considering buying the UK's nuclear energy plants 
(MINNEAPOLIS STAR-TRIBUNE, 2/22/96, p. D3, Associated Press

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... Peco Energy Co.'s Peach Bottom Unit 2 in York County, PA ranked 
second among the world's nuclear reactors for operating efficiency in 
1995, according to NUCLEONICS WEEK.  It ranked 16th in production. 
Peco's Limerick 2 unit in Montgomery County was 42nd in efficiency and 
47th in production.  General Public Utilities' Oyster Creek plant in 
Salem County ranked 37th in efficiency (PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER, 
2/23/96, p. C3, Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... South Korea and Japan will ask the European Union to contribute to 
the $4 billion project to develop safe nuclear power plants in North 
Korea.  Korea Electric Power is the main contractor for the project, 
and Japan is expected to provide "significant" financing.  But the US, 
which brokered the original deal, "has offered little financial 
support" (FINANCIAL TIMES, 2/23/96, p. 6, Peter Montagnon).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... China's Daya Bay nuclear power plant has experienced recent 
problems with three of its eight intermediate cooling pumps, "the 
latest in a series of glitches that have plagued the facility." But 
the problems have posed no safety concerns, according to an official 
with Hong Kong-based China Light & Power (WALL STREET JOURNAL, 
2/23/96, p. A7A, Erik Guyot).


</td>
</tr>
