<html><head><title>Nuke News, 22/2/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 22/2/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.02.21.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b></b><br>
</i><br>
<p>

<i><b>"Maine Yankee Will Rerack Its Spent-Fuel Assemblies Later
This year"</b><br>
BANGOR DAILY NEWS, 2/17/96</i><br>
Brian Swartz
<p>

With a federal repository for high-level radioactive waste not due to
open until 2010, engineers have begun a program to rerack the spent
fuel stored at the Maine Yankee nuclear power plant.  The project will
involve installing new racks in the 40- cubic-foot pool where the
spent fuel is now stored and trans- ferring the fuel, under water,
from the old racks to the new.
<p>

Maine Yankee's reactor core contains 217 fuel assemblies, each with
176 rods filled with uranium dioxide pellets.  The plant refuels every
18 months, when it replaces about a third of the used fuel assemblies.
The plant has been operating since 1972.  Reracking the plant's
spent-fuel pool will give Maine Yankee enough space to store spent
fuel until 2008.
<p>

The Department of Energy was supposed to open a repository in 1998,
says Maine Yankee's Bob Jordan.  DOE "examined various underground
repository sites before deciding to build one at Yucca Mountain in
Nevada."  About six years ago, Maine Yankee realized the "seriousness
of the delay" and decided to rerack its pool.  Reracking will be done
on an "accelerated schedule," 10 hours a day, six days a week,
beginning this spring.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Don't Move the Nuclear Waste," ST. LOUIS POST- DISPATCH,
       2/20/96, p. 10B, Editorial, which notes that St. Louis is a
       "logical transportation route" for moving spent fuel from
       commercial reactors to a storage site or repository in
       Nevada. Nuclear waste was shipped from Three Mile Island in
       Pennsylvania "right through" St.  Louis and "fortunately
       ... none spilled or leaked."  The government should delay
       moving "any waste anywhere until the problem of permanent
       storage has been solved."
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"US Utility Rejects Nuclear Sell-Off Claim"</b><br>
FINANCIAL TIMES, 2/22/96, p. 7</i><br>
David Lascelles, James Blitz and Richard Tomkins
<p>

Britain's nuclear privatization "was thrown into confusion" yesterday
when British Energy Minister Tim Eggar confirmed that he was
considering a "purchase approach" by the US utility Duke Power,
although Duke Power executives "flatly denied any interest."
<p>

Eggar said that a preliminary offer from Duke was being considered in
an effort to obtain the best value possible for the taxpayer.  But
Guynn Savage of North Carolina-based Duke Power "emphatically and
vehemently" denied that the utility has expressed any interest in
purchasing the UK nuclear units.
<p>

The confusion was traced to informal contracts between merchant
bankers working for the two parties.  The developments "cast the
sell-off in a new light by showing that the government is willing to
consider a private sale instead of the planned flotation."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Utilities to Spend $1.4 Billion on Power Plant Maintenance"</b><br>
ELECTRIC LIGHT &amp; POWER, 2/96 issue, p. 17</i><br>
Teresa Hansen
<p>

North American electric utilities have scheduled 795 power plant
maintenance projects valued at over $1.4 billion for the period
running from last October and ending April 1, 1998.
<p>

Approximately 300f the fossil-fuel plants in North America have
scheduled outages, while 870f all nuclear plants will shut down for
maintenance work.
<p>

Outages are conducted for reasons ranging from operations optimization
to government or insurance requirements, as well as for preventative
maintenance.  Based on interviews with utility contacts, conducted by
CSR Market Data Services, most voluntary outages are done to repair
components in the plant's turbine, generator or boiler/burner.
     


</td>
</tr>
