<html><head><title>Nuke News, 21/2/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 21/2/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.02.16.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"Commission Could Shut Down Part of Wisconsin Nuclear Power Plant"</b><br>
Minneapolis STAR TRIBUNE, 2/17/96, p. B1</i><br>
Tom Meersman
<p>

Wisconsin Electric Power Co.'s Point Beach nuclear power plant may be
forced into a partial shutdown this fall because of concerns over on-
site storage of radioactive waste and the condition of the plant's
aging steam generators.
<p>

Inspections last year showed that hundreds of tubes that carry hot,
radioactive water under high pressure are corroding faster than
officials had expected.  Cracks and other deterioration forced WEPCO
to obtain a special license amendment this year to continue operating
one of its steam generators.  And regulators who last February gave
WEPCO permission to store radioactive waste at Point Beach have been
required by a federal judge to reconsider.  Environmentalists had
appealed the approval of on-site storage.

<p>

<b><i>DECISION WILL HAVE RIPPLE EFFECT</i></b>
<p>

In April, Wisconsin's Public Service Commission will decide the future
of the Point Beach plant, and the decision may play into merger plans
between Northern States Power Co. and WEPCO. The two utilities plan to
merge at the end of this year and the future of the Point Beach plant
could have "financial repercussions."
<p>

But uncertainty about Point Beach's future does not threaten the
merger, according to Robert Link, WEPCO's VP of nuclear operations.
NPS officials declined to speculate on the matter.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Big Nuclear Agency Discussed"</b><br>
TORONTO GLOBE &amp; MAIL, 2/19/96, p. B1</i><br>
Martin Mittelstaedt
<p>

Ontario Hydro and the Canadian nuclear energy company Atomic Energy of
Canada Ltd. have had "a series of high-level meetings" to discuss
merging into a single company called Nuclear Canada.
<p>

The new company would be an unusual hybrid with joint federal and
Ontario ownership.  "With its huge size and more than $30 billion in
assets, it would become one of the most important corporations in the
world involved in producing and marketing nuclear energy."
<p>

While those involved stress that the talks have been only preliminary,
senior AECL officials have urged the Ontario government to consider
the possibility of a merger in weighing the future of Ontario Hydro.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Utility Deregulation Could Worsen Air Quality in East,Coalition Says" </b><br>
WASHINGTON POST, 2/21/96, p. A4</i><br>
Gary Lee
<p>

The impending deregulation of utilities is likely to worsen air
pollution along the East Coast, according to a coalition of
environmental groups and state officials.  The Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission this summer will issue its final rule allowing
power producers wider access to markets nationwide.
<p>

In all, deregulation could increase emissions of nitrogen oxide in the
Midwest by as much as 400,000 tons per year, according to an analysis
by the DC-based Center for Clean Air Policy.  It also predicted
increases in carbon-dioxide emissions and toxic pollutants such as
mercury.  Because of prevailing winds, the Northeast would receive the
brunt of the added pollution, the study said.
<p>

Under FERC's proposed rule, coal-fired power plants in the Midwest
that produce electricity at cheaper rates than their nuclear or oil-
burning competitors could boost output to sell power in regions where
rates are higher.  But by burning more coal, the plants would also
increase their emissions of nitrogen oxides, fine particulates and
other air pollutants, warned the CCAP's Executive Director Ned Helme:
"The increased production would inevitably bring more pollution."
<p>

<b><i>AEP:  A CASE IN POINT</i></b>
<p>

The center recently analyzed how deregulation would affect energy
production at American Electric Power, a major Midwest utility that
generates 830f its power from coal.  American Electric's plants
currently run at 70apacity.  The center predicts that if it raised
its capacity just 10%, the utility would emits tens of thousands more
tons of nitrogen oxides, a key contributor to urban smog.
<p>

<b><i>GROUPS OFFER MORE THAN JUST CRITICISM</i></b>
<p>

A coalition of environmental groups, Northeastern utilities and
consumer advocacy groups, such as Public Citizen and the Izaak Walton
League of America, is pushing FERC to add environmental restrictions
to the proposed rule.  They have offered a number of suggestions,
including requiring coal-burning plants to install more antipollution
technology or allowing utilities to offset increased emissions at some
plants with reductions from other plants in the region.
<p>

But a coalition of Midwestern utilities and other business groups
argue against changing the proposed rule on the grounds that
environmental problems should be handled by the US Environmental
Protection Agency, not FERC.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Ukraine's Energy Crisis Eases" </b><br>
FINANCIAL TIMES, 2/20/96, p. 2</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

Warmer temperatures and the resumption of coal shipments have eased
Ukraine's energy crisis slightly, although about 5,000 factories
remain closed and officials are still considering rationing each
region to just a few hours of electricity a day.
<p>

The crisis began last week when Russia took Ukraine off their shared
power grid.  Russians officials were afraid the grid might be damaged
by additional power demands from Ukraine, brought on by a coal strike
and record cold temperatures.  Miners went back to work last Friday,
allowing for coal shipments to resume.  Slightly warmer temperatures
are also helping.


</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
