<html><head><title>Nuke News, 16/2/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 16/2/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.02.14.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>EC INVESTIGATION OF NUKE PRIVATIZATION</b></i><br>
<p>

The European Commission's competition directorate last month sent a
letter to the UK Dept. of Trade and Industry seeking assurances that
the UK is not trying to use state aid to illegally "sweeten" pending
nuclear power privatization deals.
<p>

Several enviro and anti-nuclear groups charge that state- owned
Nuclear Electric is accelerating its payments on nuclear waste cleanup
bills to reduce the plants' enviro liabilities by $975 billion before
they are privatized.  DTI confirmed that it was talking with the EC,
but insisted they did not plan to use state aid in the sale.  One DTI
"official said the ministers were determined to transfer all relevant
cleanup costs to the private sector."
<p>

SEE ALSO:
<ul>
  <li> "Double Blow for Nuclear Sell-Off," LONDON GUARDIAN, 2/15/96,
       Simon Beavis and Chris Barrie, who report that BNFL "at the
       last minute" decided to withdraw a planned advertising campaign
       that was to "set out the merits" of underground disposal of
       nuclear wastes. A spokesman for Nirex, which is planning the
       site, denied the decision was influenced by the report's
       release.
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... As reported yesterday by the LOS ANGELES TIMES and EEI ONLINE, the
Clinton administration has called for more studies of the proposed
site for a low-level radioactive waste dump in Ward Valley, CA.  The
studies will delay construction "for at least a year" while soil and
seepage conditions are studied and a new environmental impact
statement is readied (NEW YORK TIMES, 2/16/96, p. A16, Kenneth Noble).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... The world's largest nuclear fuel reprocessing plant in Normandy,
France is contaminated by high levels of radioactive elements in the
soil, water and air, according to an "independent" study commissioned
by Greenpeace (FINANCIAL TIMES, 2/16/96, p. 2, AFP Service).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Maine Yankee Returning to Service"</b><br>
BOSTON GLOBE, 2/15/96</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

The Maine Yankee nuclear power plant began returning to service
Wednesday after a brief shutdown because of a problem in one of its
three steam generators.  Spokesman Marshall Murphy said the plant will
be reconnected to the regional power grid "in the next day or so."
<p>

Maine Yankee shut down automatically at about 10:30 p.m. Tuesday, when
high water levels were detected in the steam generator.  On Wednesday
afternoon, technicians replaced the control devices that caused the
problem.
<p>

The plant was brought back on line "just last month," after being
closed for a year to repair cracks in its steam generators. The $27
million repairs required inserting metal sleeves into each of the
plant's 17,000 steam generator tubes.
<p>

Murphy said the Tuesday shutdown had nothing to do with the earlier
repairs.  But Bill Linnell of the Committee for a Safe Energy Future
said, "This is more evidence that Maine Yankee, which is the eighth
oldest pressurized water reactor in the country, is experiencing more
aging problems."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Botched Nuclear Report a Study in Waste"</b><br>
USA TODAY, 2/16/96, p. 10A</i><br>
Editorial
<p>

"Imagine a pillar more than two miles thick, as high as Mount Everest
and glowing like a bug-zapper.  That's how much contaminated waste is
now lying around in the nation's vast nuclear weapons complex," writes
the editorial board at USA TODAY.  "Now imagine a column of dollar
bill 3.5 miles high, weighing 60 tons, and surrounded by a neon ribbon
flashing 'burn me ... burn me.'"  That stack would be the $59 million
the Energy Dept. spent to study how to dispose of its nuclear waste.
<p>

While the study was supposed to cost a fraction of that and be
completed in three years, it remains unfinished and is drawing
criticism from all quarters as useless.  But despite all its problems,
the "ill- starred study may have value after all.  It's a sobering
reminder of the scope of the cleanup task and of the perils of
underestimating it."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Storage of Nuclear Waste 'Unsatisfactory'"</b><br>
LONDON INDEPENDENT, 2/15/96</i><br>
Nicholas Schoon
<p>

Government regulators have strongly criticized some of British Nuclear
Fuel's methods for storing and disposing of nuclear waste at its
Sellafield nuclear reprocessing site and the nearby Drigg low-level
waste storage site.
<p>

A new study from the Nuclear Inspections Inspectorate and Her
Majesty's Inspectorate of Pollution released on Wednesday found "a
number of storage facilities to be less than satisfactory."  The
report made 15 specific recommendations, such as improving
recordkeeping of intermediate-level wastes, but said none of the
materials posed an immediate risk to the public. "The most damaging
part of the report consists of several photographs with captions
showing drums of plutonium contaminated waste stacked too high or in
an unstable position, or so exposed to the elements that they were
rusting."

</td>
</tr>
</table>
