<html><head><title>Nuke News, 14/2/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 14/2/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.02.12.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"Florida Power Plant Gets Time Off"</b><br>
ST. PETERSBURG TIMES, 2/9/96, p. 1</i><br>
Ian James<p>

Florida Power Corp. will shut down its Crystal River plant this month
for refueling and maintenance.  The Crystal River Plant, Florida's
most powerful, usually generates around 200f the Florida Power's
electricity.  FPC says it will be able to meet customer needs despite
the outage.
<p>

The scheduled refuelling, which comes once every two years, will begin
February 29 and last 47 days, costing St. Petersburg- based Florida
Power nearly $30 million.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Opponents Draw Line in Sand at Proposed Nuclear Dump Site" </b><br>
WASHINGTON POST, 2/12/96, p. A4</i><br>
William Claiborne
<p>


"A desolate, 1,000-acre tract of federal land in the Mojave Desert has
become Ground Zero for an explosive political battle over how to
dispose of the millions of cubic feet of low-level radioactive waste
that the United States produces each year," reports the WASHINGTON
POST.
<p>

The Ward Valley dump would be the first state-run repository under the
federal 1980 Low-Level Radioactive Waste Policy Act. That law made
regional state "compacts" responsible only for disposing of low-level
radioactive waste produced by industries and medical and research
institutions.
<p>

Although the struggle over Ward Valley has focused on such
environmental issues as water quality and endangered species habitat,
"the real conflict" boils down to whether low-level nuclear waste can
safely be stored in unlined underground trenches.  The argument has
taken on "added significance" due to the federal budget reconciliation
bill presently stalled in Congress.  It remains gridlocked partly over
an amendment sought by nuclear industry lobbyists that would transfer
ownership of the federally owned Ward Valley land to California,
allowing the repository's construction to go forward.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Cuba Hosts Tour of Nuclear Plant to Calm US Fears" </b><br>
ORLANDO SENTINEL, 2/9/96, p. A19</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

Cuban officials have guided a visiting US research group through the
unfinished Juragua nuclear power plant, "hoping to allay US fears of
'another Chernobyl' just 90 miles from Florida."  The group,
consisting of two retired admirals, two retired generals, and two
retired diplomats, on 2/8 said their visit to the plant was an
important step in the understanding of Cuba's nuclear plans.
<p>

The Juragua plant is not of the same design as Chernobyl, the
Ukrainian plant that caused the world's worst nuclear accident in
1986. "Cuba's plans, however, do envisage technology similar to that
used in a string of nuclear stations across the old Eastern bloc."
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... The Nuclear Regulatory Commission is proposing a $100,000 fine 
against Pennsylvania Power & Light Co. over an incident in which a 
supervisor punished a security officer who had reported personnel 
concerns to the NRC.  PP&L said it would accept the NRC's decision and 
had taken steps to prevent recurrence (PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER, 2/10/96, 
p. D3, Staff Report).

</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
