<html><head><title>Nuke News, 12/2/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 12/2/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.02.06.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"AEP Consolidates Nuclear Employees"</b><br>
PUBLIC UTILITIES FORTNIGHTLY, 2/1/96</i><br>
Lori Burkhart<p>

American Electric Power Co. plans to consolidate its Columbus, OH,
nuclear generation management and support staff with the nuclear staff
at its Donald C. Cook plant in Bridgeman, MI.  The relocation,
scheduled for summer 1996, affects about 250 employees.  About 50
positions will be cut.  Total employees in the AEP nuclear
organization will be reduced from about 1,300 to about 1,180, a 9.2%
cut.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>



<i><b>"Senate Panel OKs Nuclear Waste Bill" </b><br>
MINNEAPOLIS STAR-TRIBUNE, 2/9/96, p. B1</i><br>
Tom Meersman
<p>

A bill to allow increased nuclear waste storage at Minnesota's Prairie
Island nuclear power plant and to require Northern States Power Co. to
compensate a neighboring Indian tribe "passed its first test" on
Tuesday, as the Senate Jobs Committee approved it, 7-6.  The measure
would allow NSP to pack more spent fuel rods into storage pools at the
plant, a process called reracking, and end the search for an
alternative site for above-ground, waste-storage casks.  During debate
on the measure, Senate Democrats questioned the utility's credibility,
recalling that when NSP sought approval for the above-ground casks in
1994, it claimed reracking was "too risky for plant employees."
<p>

State Sen. Ellen Anderson (D): "Why are you telling us now that you
have to have authority to extend this plant and produce nuclear wastes
for 10 or 15 more years ... when you promised to us two years ago that
that would not happen?"  NSP officials said reracking was not an
option in 1994 because new racks could not have been installed without
shutting down the plant.  With storage now available in the casks,
enough room can be made in the pool for new racks, they said.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>INDIANS, ENVIROS UNHAPPY</b></i>
<p>

Curtis Campbell, president of the Mdewankanton Dakota Tribe Council,
urged legislators to support a provision requiring NSP to give the
tribe money and land over the next two decades as compensation for
having to live next to the waste storage site. And Michael Noble,
representing Minnesotans for an Energy- Efficient Economy, said the
new plan "undermines" a key part of the 1994 law, which required new
investments in wind, biomass and other "clean" energy projects.  The
bill now goes to the Senate Environment Committee, where a hearing is
scheduled for today (Friday).

</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
