<html><head><title>Nuke News, 6/2/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 6/2/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.02.05.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"A Very Sick Golden Goose"</b><br>
CLEVELAND PLAIN DEALER, 2/5/96, p. 8B</i><br>
Editorial
<p>


In the lead editorial of yesterday's CLEVELAND PLAIN DEALER, the
editors write that, "When Centerior Energy Corp. built those ghostly
silos in 1986 that mark the Perry nuclear power plant, some saw them
as the gates to Lake County's Magic Kingdom.  But the
happily-ever-after ending doesn't quite fit," as Centerior is now
asking regulators to slash plant's assessed value and its property
taxes.  That could mean that Lake County schools could lose about $2
million of the $2.3 million a year they now get in real estate taxes
from Perry.  The company also plans to ask the legislature for
personal property tax relief, the source of $20.7 million in school
tax revenue.
<p>

"Only a hermit would find" the company's moves surprising, the PLAIN
DEALER asserts.  The utility's "unreliable" nuclear generators have
never recouped their construction costs, and Centerior subsidiary
Cleveland Electric Illuminating Co. is "debt-ridden and uncompetitive.
... CEI and its regulators will probably reach some compromise"
eventually, but school officials are well advised to begin cutting
costs now, the editors conclude.


</td>
</tr>
</table>
