<html><head><title>Nuke News, 5/2/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 5/2/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.02.02.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"Concern Greets Millstone Scrutiny But Most Think 3 Plants on
Watch List are Not Hazardous"</b><br>
HARTFORD COURANT, 2/2/96, p. B9</i><br>
Anthony Giorgianni <p>

The Nuclear Regulatory Commission's announcement last week that it had
placed three Connecticut nuclear power plants on a safety "watch list"
drew concerned responses from local and state government officials.
<p>

NRC said that is was taking action because of five years of safety
violations at the three Millstone nuclear reactors in Waterford.  The
violations included procedural violations that in some cases
endangered plant workers; poor training of plant operators; delays in
fixing or reporting problems; and the harassment and intimidation of
employees who raised safety concerns.
<p>

One of the harshest official reactions came from state Attorney
General Richard Blumenthal, who said he would seek all necessary
remedies, including a shutdown of the plants, if they are found to be
unsafe.
<p>

But despite the listing, most sources expressed confidence that the
three Millstone nuclear power plants are safe.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Regulators Put Millstone Plants on 'Watch' List," HARTFORD
       COURANT, 2/1/96, p. A1, Daniel Jones and Anthony Giorianni.
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Virginia Power Eyes Military Sideline" </b><br>
WASHINGTON TIMES, 2/4/96, p. A12</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

Richmond-based Virginia Power last week told federal authorities it is
willing to consider using its commercial nuclear power reactors to
create tritium, a gas used to boost the explosive power of hydrogen
bombs.  Spokesman James Norvelle said the utility's interest in the
idea was "mild," but he noted that as the company faces growing
competition, "we're looking for ways to make some money -- safely."
<p>

Energy Secretary Hazel O'Leary first proposed the idea last October as
one option for replacing a DOE plant in South Carolina that produced
tritium until the late 1980s.  Virginia Power said it was among 17
other utilities that have expressed interest.
<p>

"Anti-nuclear groups say the idea breaches a long-guarded protection
against military use of civilian reactors."  But Jennifer Weeks of the
Union of Concerned Scientists said the option represented "the lesser
of evils" compared with building a new facility at the DOE's Savannah
River site.  Ms. Weeks also questioned whether a new source of tritium
is needed at all, since the government will be able to recycle enough
tritium from existing warheads to maintain the arsenal through 2011.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Power Authority's Indian Point Plant Still on Watch List"</b><br>
SYRACUSE POST-STANDARD, 2/1/96, p. B1</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

The New York Power Authority's Indian Point 3 nuclear power plant
remains on the Nuclear Regulatory Commission's "watch list" because it
failed to show sustained good performance, the NRC said on January 31.
<p>

The NYPA did not disagree and admitted that more work needs to be done
on the plant.  Indian Point 3 has been on the list since June 1993,
after it went out of service in February 1993 after a backup system
failed.
<p>

The plant has been in and out of service since then, but it will not
be restarted without approval from the NRC.

</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
