<html><head><title>Nuke News, 2/2/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 2/2/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.02.01.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"N-Reactor Overheats During Lunch Break"</b><br>
MIAMI HERALD, 2/1/96</i><br>
Associated Press<p>

While a nuclear power plant operator left his post to microwave his
lunch on January 22, pressure built up so much in a cooling unit that
alarms went off.  The operator at Florida Power &amp; Light's St. Lucie
Nuclear Power Plant has been suspended in the wake of the incident.
<p>

The operator failed to tell control-room colleagues that he
was adjusting the reactor coolant before he left to prepare his lunch.
<p>

Officials at the Nuclear Regulatory Commission office in Atlanta,
which is not expected to issue a full report on the incident for
several weeks, insist there was no danger to the public.  Beginning in
August, St. Lucie Unit 1 was out of service for 73 days "because of
personnel errors and mechanical problems," forcing the utility to
spend $16 million purchasing electricity from other sources to meet
its obligation.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Frozen Screen Halts Wolf Creek" </b><br>
KANSAS CITY STAR, 1/31/96, p. B1</i><br>
Martin Rosenberg
<p>

The Wolf Creek nuclear power plant near Burlington, KS was forced to
shut down on Tuesday after the water flow from an adjacent lake into
the plant was restricted by a frozen screen. When operators then tried
to slow the nuclear reaction in the core of the plant, some control
rods failed to fall into place, requiring the operators to dump boron
into reactor under emergency procedures.
<p>

Federal officials and plant managers said there was no threat to the
public from problems at the plant, which is owned by Kansas City Power
&amp; Light Co., Western Resources Inc. and the Kansas Electric Power
Cooperative, Inc.  The Nuclear Regulatory Commission is most concerned
about the failure of the control rods, an NRC official said.  The
plant will not generate power while repairs are made.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... The staff of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission recommended the
Watts Bar nuclear power plant near Knoxville, TN be allowed to move
toward producing electricity at full power by this spring.  But NRC
Chairwoman Shirley Jackson said she wanted to review the reactor's
record and complaints from local activists (ORLANDO SENTINEL, 2/1/96,
Staff Report).industrial customers

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... Philadelphia's Peco Energy Co. said it will shut down Unit 1 at
its Limerick nuclear power plant for three weeks starting today for
refueling and maintenance (PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER, 2/2/96, p.  C3,
Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Restructuring, Layoffs Continue in Electric Industry" </b><br>
ENGINEERING NEWS RECORD, 2/96 issue, p. 26</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

End-of-the year layoffs continue to make headlines across the nation,
and three energy organizations in the Northwest announced staff
reductions late in the year.
<p>

The Washington Public Power Supply System plans to cut about 100f
the work force at its Hanford nuclear reactor.  William Counsil,
Hanford plant managing director, said 130 workers over the next six
months will lose their job.  At the same time Supply System plans to
boost power production and efficiency in an effort to keep the Pacific
Northwest's only power reactor from being shut down.  Under the
cost-cutting plan, the Supply System hoped provide power to BPA at a
rate of 2.45 cents a kilowatt hour beginning on January 1 of this
year.
<p>

Two of the Northwest's investor owned utilities also announced job
layoffs attributable to increased competition. Idaho Power plans to
cut the work force in its retail services from 1,007 to 952 over the
next six months.  Idaho Power's retail unit currently has 79 positions
that are vacant or filled by temporary workers, therefore, no
full-time employees are expected to be laid off, according to Idaho
Power officials.<p>

PacifiCorp also recently announced that it will close all its customer
walk-in offices in both its Pacific Power and Utah Power divisions.
The closings will be completed by the end of 1996.  About 250
positions are expected to be eliminated.

</td>
</tr>
</table>
