<html><head><title>Nuke News, 1/2/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 1/2/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... Gilbert Associates Inc. of Reading, PA said it was closing 
United Energy Services, its nuclear-power consulting business 
(PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER, 2/1/96, p. D3, Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Nuclear Industry Faces Charges of Cutting Corners" </b><br>
WALL STREET JOURNAL, 2/1/96, p. B4</i><br>
Ross Kerber
<p>

Deregulation of the electric power industry "is posing a potent
challenge" to the nuclear power industry, the WALL STREET JOURNAL
reports, as pressure builds to cut costs without compromising safety.
Two recent "flaps" in New England "are bringing charges that power
companies are cutting corners on safety in ways that increase the
chance of radioactive accidents."
<p>

Yesterday, the Nuclear Regulatory Commission added Northeast
Utilities' Millstone 1 plant and two sister plants to its "watch
list," after a whistle blower alleged improper management of a cooling
system.  The Maine Yankee plant in Wiscasset, ME is operating below
full power while the NRC investigates "detailed" allegations by a
whistle blower there.  The plant's primary owner, Central Maine Power
Co., had closed it for much of 1995 to fix cracks in the steam
generator.
<p>

The whistle blower in Connecticut, George Galatis, says "a new
tightfistedness at Northeast contributed to management's unwillingness
to address the problem."  The company is currently trimming its
nuclear workforce from 3,000 to about 1,000 by 2000, and Galatis
charges that layoffs make other whistle blowers less likely to come
forward.  Ted Feigenbaum, the company's chief nuclear officer, says
Northeast will improve safety as it streamlines operations.  Central
Maine also argues that its plant's troubles had nothing to do with
restructuring.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<b><i>"NO EVIDENCE"</i></b>
<p>

"NRC officials say there is little evidence yet that reduced staffing
will lead to reduced safety."  A study several years ago found that
the Grand Gulf plant near Vicksburg, MS had a better safety record
than the Perry plant in Painesville, OH, which had twice as many
employees.
<p>

The article also quotes sources speculating that many nuclear power
plants will be forced to shut down in the coming years as deregulation
and cost concerns mount.
     
     

</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<table width=600>
  <tr>
    <td valign=middle><a href="/"><img src="/graphics/gifs/atom.t.gif"
