<html><head><title>Nuke News, 15/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 15/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.14.html">Previous Nuke News</a>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Internal Report Cites NRC Deficiencies"</b><br>
BANGOR DAILY NEWS, 5/13/96</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

Maine Yankee officials "say they welcome a government report" citing
"weakness" in one Nuclear Regulatory Commission staff review at the
plant, and "irregularities" in an NRC letter.  The report notes that
the plant itself did nothing wrong.
<p>

NRC Acting Inspector General Leo Norton wrote that the report "points
out the staff's inadequate documentation of significant
discussions/conversations with licensee personnel, as well as the
staff's failure to track licensee commitments made during those
discussion."  The report also found no "uniform policy" under which
NRC managers document or retain documentation of conversations with
plant managers.
<p>

A spokesman for Central Main Power Co., which partially owns the
facility, on May 11 said that the company views the report as an
intra- agency matter.



<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"US: Encourage Alternative Energy Sources"</b><br>
CHRISTIAN SCIENCE MONITOR, 5/14/96, p. 18</i><br>
Theodore Besmann, Letter to the Editor
<p>

In a letter to the editor of the CHRISTIAN SCIENCE MONITOR, an Oak
Ridge National Laboratory researcher states his opinion that the
recent "run-up in gasoline prices" and the "sharp public response" has
"reawakened awareness" of America's "dangerous dependence" on Middle
East oil.  He notes that "inexplicably," as oil imports have reached
an "all-time high, we are severely cutting the budget for research and
development in energy efficiency and alternative sources."  He
attributes this "confusion" to the lack of a US energy policy.
<p>

The nation needs a strategy to encourage investment in natural gas
use, advanced transportation technologies such as electric vehicles,
and alternative energy sources, he says.  But some members of Congress
want to "eliminate virtually all government funding for energy
technology programs, including a modestly funded design program that
shares costs with industry to develop advanced nuclear power plants."
<p>

The nation cannot depend on the energy industry, which he sees
"dominated by oil companies and the staid electric utilities," to
develop the "next generation" of energy-efficient equipment and
alternative energy sources.  Dr. Besmann calls on Congress and the
Pres. to "accept responsibility and demonstrate leadership."
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Invest in Renewable Energy," FINANCIAL TIMES, 5/1/5/96, p. 12,
       Peter Heilmann, who is director of Eco-Network International in
       London.  Heilmann expresses similar thoughts as Besmann, noting
       that if industrial countries invested the billions they're
       putting into nuclear energy into renewable energy instead, the
       world would "finally start receiving unlimited benefits from a
       source of energy that is inexhaustible."
</ul>


</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
