<html><head><title>Nuke News, 14/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 14/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.13.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... Commonwealth Edison on May 10 shut down its only operating nuclear
reactor at the Quad Cities nuclear power plant after high winds from a
possible tornado "ripped" metal wall panels from three buildings.
ComEd officials inspected the plant, and announced that no
radioactivity was released, and no employees were hurt (CHICAGO
SUN-TIMES, 5/11/96, p. 4, Brenda Rotzoll).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Hotter Nukes for Cooler Rates"</b><br>
BUSINESS WEEK, 5/20/96, p. 62</i><br>
Peter Coy
<p>

With competition increasing among electric utilities, some companies
are asking the Nuclear Regulatory Commission to allow nuclear power
plants to run hotter and operate longer.
<p>

A 1994 report by the Edison Electric Institute found that as of
January 1993, only 25% of US nuclear plants produced power more
cheaply than generators powered by natural gas, coal, and other energy
sources. Rather than sustain losses by shutting down, utilities want
to extract the maximum from their high-cost nuclear plants.
<p>

Turning up the rate of nuclear fission generates more electricity with
only a small increase in uranium fuel expenditure and some investment
in new equipment.  Utilities also want to run the plants 20 years past
their originally licensed 40-year life spans to improve their
economics.
<p>

As early as June, the NRC may receive an application from Northern
States Power Co. to raise the thermal output of its 25-year-old
Monticello, MN plant by 6.3% above its designed maximum of 1,670
megawatts.  The request will mark the first time a utility has asked
for an increase at a plant already operating at its design limit.
<p>

The NRC has "looked favorably" on power increases for plants that were
originally licensed to operate at less than their design
capacity. Increases within design limits have been granted to 36 of
the nation's 110 reactors, with more requests pending.
<p>

Critics charge operating plants above design limits and extending
useful lives may lead to higher accident risks.  "For regulators, the
issue comes down to this: a certain increase in cheap megawatts vs. a
best-estimate increase in risk."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Utility-Competition Decision Is Upheld in New Hampshire"</b><br>
WALL STREET JOURNAL, 5/14/96, p. B5</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

"The New Hampshire Supreme Court upheld a ruling by state regulators
that could allow electric utilities to compete in each other's service
territory."  Public Service Co. of New Hampshire had claimed the NH
Public Utilities Commission was wrong to order it to allow competitors
to use its transmission lines.
<p>

Separately, the state legislature is considering a plan to speed
retail competition in the state's power market, and a pilot program is
set to begin next week.  Concord-based Freedom Energy Co. said it
would file plans today that would allow it to begin selling
electricity in PSNH territory.
<p>

PSNH President William Frain said the ruling left unresolved several
issues, including "who should pay for expensive nuclear- power plants
whose cost the utility is now guaranteed to recover from ratepayers."


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"A Nuclear Power Boost?"</b><br>
DALLAS MORNING NEWS, 5/13/96, p. 7D</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

Nobel Prize-winning physicist Carlo Rubbia, at a recent meeting of the
American Physical Society in Indianapolis, unveiled the latest
energy-generation calculations for his theoretical "Energy Amplifier."
<p>

Rubbia first proposed the idea of generating electricity from nuclear
fission through the use of a small particle accelerator in 1993. His
recent announcement claims that the process would generate more than
50 times the energy needed to run the particle accelerator.
<p>

Rubbia says his approach would be safer than conventional nuclear
power plants because it does not rely on a "critical" nuclear chain
reaction.  Also, most of its radioactive wastes could be reused as
fuel, along with waste from other plants.  It only produces a small
amount of plutonium and employs thorium -- an abundant chemical -- as
a fuel source.  Rubbia says the process could also be used to split
water into hydrogen and oxygen.


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... The Dept. of Energy yesterday announced it will allow 41 countries
to ship 20 metric tons of spent nuclear fuel to the United States for
storage and disposal (WASHINGTON POST, 5/14/96, p. A13, Gary Lee).


</td>
</tr>
</table>
