<html><head><title>Nuke News, 13/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 13/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.10.html">Previous Nuke News</a>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Putting a Charge Back Into Driving"</b><br>
NEWSWEEK, 5/20/96 issue, p. 66</i><br>
Adam Rogers and Sharon Begley
<p>

Another debate about EVs "is their environmental benefit -- or lack
thereof."  The nation's auto fleet is already being replaced with
newer, cleaner models.  And Richard Tempchin of the Edison Electric
Institute "admits:" "You need a substantial number of EVs to make a
dent in smog-causing emissions."
<p>

"Another criticism" is that EVs merely transfer pollution from the
auto tailpipe to the powerplant smokestack.  But according to the
Electric Power Research Institute, a gasoline- powered car in New
England emits six times more smog precursors than the power plant
supplying electricity for an EV.  In areas where plants run on natural
gas or nuclear power, pollution from EVs could be as little as 1% of
gasoline cars, says Roland Hwang of the Union of Concerned Scientists.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Industry Gets Serious About Electric Cars," WASHINGTON TIMES,
       5/10/96, p. E13, "Auto Weekend" Section, Mike Anson, who test-
       drove a Honda EV and found it "impressive."  Anson writes that
       "everything is ready for electric vehicles except for one thing
       -- batteries" that can provide the convenience and performance
       consumers are accustomed to.  But he nonetheless concludes that
       EVs will find a place in America's transportation system.
</ul>



<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Power Struggle:  Deregulation Sparks Marketing Battle"</b><br>
WALL STREET JOURNAL, 5/13/96, p. B1</i><br>
Ross Kerber and Benjamin Holden
<p>

"With the kind of intensity normally used to hawk corn chips or
compact cars, companies are starting to woo customers in New Hampshire
for one of New England's hottest commodities -- electrical power," the
WALL STREET JOURNAL reports.  In a retail- wheeling experiment seen as
a national case study, about 17,000 customers will be able to choose
their power supplier beginning May 28.  The state's "dominant"
utility, Public Service of New Hampshire, is facing about 29
competitors, and consumers can expect "a confusing array of products."
<p>

So far, pitches have included "pledges never to rely on nuclear fuel,
discounts for conservation" and free insulation and energy- management
services.  "Even Jacqueline Lake Killgore, an attorney who has worked
on deregulation issues, finds the campaign confusing," having to
choose from among several very different packages.
<p>

The "deregulation bandwagon leaves many issues unsettled," the JOURNAL
reports.  For example, PSNH's rates are the highest in the nation
partly because rates cover some costly nuclear facilities and mandates
requiring the utility to buy power from alternative suppliers. PSNH
has appealed to the public with ads "meant to raise doubts about
reform."  The utility also hints it may sue to block the program "if
it determines the new competitive environment will be unfair."
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Enron Offers Switch to Electric Customers in NH," OMAHA
       WORLD-HERALD, 5/10/96, p. 24, Associated Press, which quotes
       George McCluskey, project manager for the NH Public Utilities
       Commission: "It really comes down to price and where the power
       comes from. ...  Some customers just want price, even though
       they may get it from a nuclear plant.  Some want clean power,
       no fossil fuels."
</ul>



<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"NRC Finds Signs Maine Yankee Plant Hid Faults in Nuclear-Safety Program"</b><br>
WALL STREET JOURNAL, 5/13/96, p. A4</i><br>
Ross Kerber
<p>

In the "latest in a string of adverse findings" related to New England
nuclear power plants, the US Nuclear Regulatory Commission on May 10
issued a report finding "significant indications" that operators of
the Maine Yankee plant in Wiscasset, ME hid problems in a safety-
related computer program from the NRC.  The NRC report supported the
allegations of an anonymous whistleblower who wrote to state officials
with criticisms of the plant in December.
<p>

The report, issued by the NRC's top internal review officer, Leo
Norton, also found NRC inspectors relied too much on the plant
operators to ensure safety at Maine Yankee.  A separate NRC
investigation is underway into the conduct of Maine Yankee's owners.
Norton's report will be included in that probe.
<p>

Central Maine Power Co. owns 38% of Maine Yankee, and New England
Electric System and Northeast Utilities each hold a 20% stake in the
plant.  A Maine Yankee spokeswoman said executives wouldn't comment
until they could review the report in detail.
<p>

Some nuclear activists said the latest NRC report supports charges
that the commission is "too cozy with those it oversees."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"City to Pay Electric Debt with Nuke Settlement"</b><br>
AUSTIN AMERICAN-STATESMAN, 5/10/96, p. B1</i><br>
Diana Dworin
<p>

Last Thursday, the Austin City Council voted 6-0 to use the money it
won in a legal settlement with Houston Lighting &amp; Power Co. to
reduce the municipal utility's debt.
<p>

The city had sued HL&amp;P, claiming $120 million in replacement power
costs caused by a 14-month shutdown of the South Texas Project nuclear
power plant in 1993 and 1994.  But last month, as the jury "seemed to
deadlock," the city settled for $20 million.
<p>

Some council members initially suggested using the money for the
city's operating expenses.  But Mayor Bruce Todd said reducing the
debt was "critical" to getting the utility ready for greater
competition in case the state legislature deregulates the power
industry.


</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
