<html><head><title>Nuke News, 10/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 10/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.07.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... The Tennessee Valley Authority's Watts Bar nuclear power plant
Unit 1 reached full power for the first time on Wednesday, producing
1,170 megawatts of electricity (TVA PRESS RELEASE, 5/9/96, Contact:
Tom Tohill, 423-365-3033).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... The International Maritime Organization recently decided not to
classify coal as a hazardous cargo when shipped in bulk (JOURNAL OF
COMMERCE, 5/10/96, p. 12B, Tim Sansbury).


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"TVA Moves on Bellefonte Conversion; Natural Gas, Coal in Competition as Fuel"</b><br>
COAL WEEK, 5/6/96, p. 4</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

The Tennessee Valley Authority is considering converting its
unfinished Bellefonte nuclear plant to a combined-cycle plant using
either coal, gasified coal, or natural gas as the primary fuel.  The
utility, which is preparing an EIS and 18-24 month engineering and
financial study to "evaluate development and operating alternatives,"
will hold a public hearing on 5/16/96 to receive comments on possible
environmental impacts of fossil fuel use at the plant.  Registration
for the meeting will begin at 6 p.m. at the Scottsboro High School in
Scottsboro, AL; and TVA will include comments in the draft EIS set for
public review in 2/97.  The final EIS on fossil fuel use at Bellefonte
is planned for release in 10/97.  Written comments may be submitted
before 5/31/96 to Greg Askew, TVA, 400 West Summit Dr., Knoxville TN
37902 or by e-mail to gaskew@mhs-tva.attmail.com.
<p>

Since TVA "could still complete Bellefonte as a nuclear power plant,
either alone or with a partner," and since the nuclear EIS was part of
the original construction permit, the May meeting "will not address"
the nuclear option.


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Radiation Expert to Eyeball Seabrook"</b><br>
BOSTON HERALD, 5/9/96, p. 5</i><br>
David Talbot
<p>

The Nuclear Regulatory Commission on May 8 announced that it is
sending a radiation expert to the Seabrook nuclear power plant in New
Hampshire to investigate events which took place on November 29, 1995.
On that date, "unprecedented" levels of radiation were detected in
towns near the plant, after the facility released high levels of
radiation from a vent stack.  The NRC dismissed Seabrook as a possible
source of the excess radiation.
<p>

But Jim Muckerheide of the MA emergency management office said the
move indicates that the NRC is not confident in its own initial
investigation.  Muckerheide and the MA Attorney General's office claim
that Seabrook and the NRC have never documented the plant's non-
involvement in the incident.
<p>

So far, no one has been able to explain where the above-average levels
of radiation originated, although Seabrook officials claim that "no
abnormal radiation levels" were found at the plant.
<p>

"Seabrook spokesman Rob Williams said the plant will cooperate when
NRC radiation specialist Jason Jang arrives for a two-day probe May
29."


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"High-Level Waste"</b><br>
DETROIT NEWS, 5/8/96, p. A12</i><br>
Editorial
<p>

"At last it has surfaced -- the one aspect of American life the
Clinton administration has no interest in controlling.  The president
is promising to veto legislation that finally would force the federal
government to centralize storage of high-level nuclear waste," the
editorial page editors of the DETROIT NEWS write.  The editorial notes
the federal gov't has applied more than $5.8 billion of its $11
billion nuclear waste trust fund to deficit reduction -- "waste,
considering Washington's profligate habits" -- and a permanent
repository is not expected to be completed before 2011.  "Shuttered
reactors would make the environmental lobby very happy," but
"windmills and solar panels are incapable of replacing the 20% of the
nation's electricity generated by nuclear power."
<p>

The Clinton admin. wants a permanent storage site chosen at the same
time an interim site is chosen, and it wants the EPA to be in on the
environmental impact statement.  "But this would only guarantee that a
storage facility would never get sited."
<p>

The editorial notes Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole (R-KS) "has been
pretty nervous" about bringing the bill to the floor, but it's "long
past time" for such action, the editors assert.  It is "incumbent on
the House and Senate to approve the bill by margins wide enough to
override" the president's anticipated veto, the editorial concludes.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "S. 1271 Is a Good Move for the Environment," another placement
       of the Nuclear Energy Institute's near-full- page ad, which
       calls the nuclear-waste policy bill pending in the US Senate "a
       good move for the environment" (WALL STREET JOURNAL, 5/10/96,
       p. A5B).
</ul>


</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
