<html><head><title>Nuke News, 7/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 7/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.06.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... Purchases of replacement power stemming from the shutdown of the 
Millstone nuclear power complex will cost Northeast Utilities about 
$25 million a month while the reactors are out of service, the company 
announced yesterday (BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 5/7/96, Associated Press). 
The company also said it would provide reports to the Nuclear 
Regulatory Commission documenting the safety of the three Millstone 
reactors in July, September and the fourth quarter, respectively.  The 
company had previously said the reports would be done by August (WALL 
STREET JOURNAL, 5/7/96, p. A10, Staff Report).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... A Minnesota district judge has dismissed a lawsuit against 
Northern States Power Co., clearing the utility to build a nuclear 
waste storage facility near Frontenac, MN.  The lawsuit claimed that 
NSP's search for a separate storage area in Goodhue County, MN 
violated the state's Environmental Rights Act (MINNEAPOLIS 
STAR-TRIBUNE, 5/4/96, p. B3, Tom Meersman).


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Harshbarger Asks Fed Probe of Seabrook"</b><br>
BOSTON HERALD, 5/4/96, p. 5</i><br>
David Talbot
<p>

The attorney general for Massachusetts has requested a federal
investigation into New Hampshire's Seabrook Nuclear Power Plant, and
the events which took place on November 29, 1995 when the plant
released high levels of radiation from a vent stack.
<p>

Higher-than-normal levels of radiation were detected on November 29,
1995 in West Newbury, Amesbury and Newburyport in MA.  Assistant
Attorney General James Milkey wrote to the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission asking why it ruled out the Seabrook plant as a possible
cause of the Massachusetts radiation in November.
<p>

The NRC, Northeast Utilities -- which owns the Seabrook plant -- and
the MA Health Dept. have not been able to determine another source for
the radiation in MA, even though Jim Martin of NU has said that the
utility and the NRC have already "thoroughly investigated" the issue.
<p>

Milkey: "We would at least expect they would be interested in tracking
down what happened.  There may be a perfectly good explanation -- we
just haven't heard it yet."


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Volunteers Sought:  Communities Interested in Being Host to N-Waste Site Can Drive Hard Bargain"</b><br>
HARRISBURG PATRIOT, 5/3/96, p. A </i><br>
Editorial
<p>

The administration of Gov. Tom Ridge (R) of Pennsylvania, in search of
a community to host a low-level-radioactive waste repository, is
holding a series of "open houses" starting in Chambersburg on 5/7/96.
The HARRISBURG PATRIOT commends the effort, even though it "ultimately
may prove futile." Finding a community willing to accept the
radioactive effluvium from nuclear plants, hospitals, research
facilities and industry "surely is preferable" to imposing it on a
community "arbitrarily selected."  The 1988 PA enabling law, "crafted
to allow for maximum flexibility," puts a willing community in an
"extraordinarily powerful position" to negotiate a favorable contract,
"both in terms of safeguards and economic benefits."  Minimum benefits
include two full-time inspectors; payment of property taxes of
individuals living within two miles of the facility; training and
equipping of local police, fire, and emergency services; and annual
payments--to be negotiated--to the municipality.  Although "none of
this is to suggest" that hosting a nuclear waste storage area is
"without risk," the "genie is out of the bottle," and "there is no
choice" but to store this material in the safest possible way and be
prepared to generously reward those communities willing to assume the
burden.



<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Dole Said to Promise Action on Yucca Mt. Storage Site"</b><br>
CONGRESS DAILY, 5/6/96</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

Senate Majority Ldr. Robert Dole (R-KS) has reportedly promised
"early" floor consideration of a bill to locate an interim nuclear-
waste-storage facility near Yucca Mt., NV, an industry source told
CONGRESS DAILY.  In a meeting with Sens. Frank Murkowski (R-AK) and
Larry Craig (R-ID), Dole said the Senate will consider Craig's
nuclear- waste-storage bill "the week before or after the scheduled
Memorial Day recess."
<p>

Nevada's senators are "threatening a filibuster."  An aide to Sen.
Richard Bryan (D-NV) questioned the wisdom of forcing nuclear waste on
Nevada during an election year.  Rep. John Ensign (R-NV) said last
month that Dole told him the bill would not come to the floor.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Delays on Dump Site for Nuclear Fuel Put Pressure on
       Illinois," CHICAGO SUN-TIMES, 5/6/96, p. 18, Lynn Sweet, which
       reports the nuclear-waste-storage debate "has enormous
       implications for Illinois, which has the most nuclear reactors
       of any state."  John Maxson, a lobbyist for Commonwealth
       Edison, said: "This is our No. 1 priority. ... There is nothing
       else more important than this we are talking to Congress
       about."  Illinois's senators are inclined to support the Bryan
       bill, the CHICAGO SUN-TIMES reports.
  <li> "S. 1271 Is a Good Move for the Environment," WASHINGTON POST,
       5/7/96, p. A16, a near-full-page ad by the Nuclear Energy
       Institute calling for support of the Craig bill.
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Report Sees Rate War Hurting Power Supply"</b><br>
BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 5/7/96</i><br>
Scott Allen
<p>

Greater competition in the electric power industry "could force the
early shutdown of as many as seven of New England's eight nuclear
power plants," according to a new study done by Resource Insight for
Massachusetts Attorney General Scott Harshbarger.  In fact, the
Pilgrim plant in Plymouth, MA and Millstone I and II in Waterford, CT
"are likely to lose so much money ... that they should be closed now,"
the report said.
<p>

Utility officials said it's too early to make such speculations since
no state has finalized the details of the transition to competitive
power markets and because nuclear plant managers are cutting costs to
prepare for competition.  Managers at both Millstone and Pilgrim have
cut hundreds of jobs, the BOSTON GLOBE reports.  Environmentalists are
worried, however, that such cutbacks could spur safety problems.
<p>

If nuclear plants are shut down, "it could force major changes" in the
regional economy, the GLOBE notes.  Nuclear reactors account for 26%
of the region's power supply.  Massachusetts Electric could benefit,
the study finds, because it operates so many inexpensive hydroelectric
dams.


</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
