<html><head><title>Nuke News, 6/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 6/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.03.html">Previous Nuke News</a>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"HL&amp;P Officials Upbeat Over Nuclear Plant Deal"</b><br>
HOUSTON CHRONICLE, 5/2/96, p. 1A</i><br>
Jerry Urban and George Flynn
<p>

Houston Lighting and Power Co. on May 1 offered to pay the city of
Austin, TX $20 million in an out-of-court settlement which ends a two-
year-old, $120 million lawsuit over HL&amp;P's management of the
2,500- megawatt South Texas Project.  The suit was meant to recover
losses from a year-long outage of HL&amp;P's plant in 1993, when
Austin was forced to replace lost energy.
<p>

The settlement could "open the door" for the implementation of an
independent management company to operate the Bay City nuclear plant
in Matagorda County -- a not-so-uncommon practice in the nuclear
industry. HL&amp;P general counsel Hugh Kelly said that it would cost
HL&amp;P less than $1 million to transfer operations to an independent
management company.
<p>

Central Power and Light, which owns 25.2% of the plant, has openly
supported the idea of an independent manager, and Kelly said that
HL&amp;P is "very confident" that the city of San Antonio will also
support the plan.  San Antonio is suing HL&amp;P for $150 million for
costs associated with the 1993 shutdown.

<center><h3>DEADLOCKED JURY?</h3></center>

Austin agreed to the settlement because the jury appeared to be
deadlocked on the case.  Austin spent about $12 million on legal fees
and wanted to avoid the cost of another trial.  Jury foreman Charles
Moore said the settlement roughly parallels the verdict toward which
the jury was aiming.
<p>

Moore added that the jury was quite critical of the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission's role in the operations and oversight of the project.  NRC
spokesman Breck Henderson said the commission's will see that the
plant is run safely under any new management.
<p>

Analysts say the settlement should not significantly affect HL&amp;P
because settlements generally clear away any uncertainties.
HL&amp;P's Kelly agreed: "This settlement will have a very beneficial
effect.  The litigation has been very demoralizing to all involved.
We will now have a cooperative joint direction."
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Nuke Plant Snakebit Even Before it Started," HOUSTON
       CHRONICLE, 5/2/96, p. 16A, Carlos Byars, which chronicles the
       history of troubles at the Bay City plant from 1973 to this
       week's settlement.
  <li> "Settlement Well Handled," AUSTIN AMERICAN- STATESMAN, 5/3/96,
       p. A12, Editorial, which notes that the settlement was handled
       "the way it should have been: in the open."  It suggests that
       the money from the settlement should be used to reduce the
       utility's debt.
  <li> "A $20 Million Nuclear Hit," BUSINESS WEEK, 5/13/96 issue,
       p. 54, Thane Peterson.
</ul>



<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Vermont Utility:  Shutdown Prevents Cut-Rate Program"</b><br>
BOSTON GLOBE, 5/5/96, p. 56</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

Vermont's Green Mountain Power Corp. has withdrawn its proposal for
"an experimental program of cut-rate electricity sales," fearing
summer power shortages due to the shutdown of the Millstone nuclear
power plant in Connecticut.
<p>

"With the recent unplanned outages of the nuclear plants and new
information about potentially tight capacity this summer, the
assumptions underlying our price test suddenly have changed," said
Steve Terry, vice president of GMP.
<p>

The company notified the VT Public Service Board of its decision on
Friday.



<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"NRC Looks at Forcing TVA to Create Reactor-Closing Fund"</b><br>
NASHVILLE TENNESSEAN, 5/2/96, p. 4B</i><br>
Aassociated Press, Duncan Mansfield
<p>

The Nuclear Regulatory Commission is being urged by its inspector
general's office to require the Tennessee Valley Authority -- "the
largest US public power producer" -- to maintain a separate fund to
pay for decommissioning obsolete nuclear power plants.
<p>

Currently, TVA must only present a "statement of intent" that it will
pay for decommissioning its three nuclear facilities in southeast
Tennessee and north Alabama.  It is exempted from the rule that
applies to investor-owned utilities because it is a federal
corporation.
<p>

The TVA actually set up its own decommissioning fund in 1977, but
without NRC regulations to stop the TVA from doing so, the utility
depleted the fund in 1993, relying on the assumption that the federal
government would pay for the TVA if the utility weren't able to do so
by itself.
<p>

Stephen Smith of Tennessee Valley Energy Reform Coalition in
Knoxville: "If TVA gets into a financial crunch, they will liquidate
this fund again.  I guarantee it."
<p>

The inspector general's report said the decommissioning requirements
the NRC set for TVA may not be sufficient.  But NRC inspector general
spokesman Bill McDowell "conceded [on April 30] the amount TVA
has set aside is 'within the realm of reasonableness' of what will be
required."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... The WALL STREET JOURNAL again publishes a near-full-page ad by the
Nuclear Energy Institute, calling for support of S. 1271, a nuclear-
waste policy bill (5/6/96, p. B7F).


</td>
</tr>
