<html><head><title>Nuke News, 3/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 3/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.02.html">Previous Nuke News</a>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Morale Problems Emerge as Plant Continues to Cut Jobs"</b><br>
RALEIGH NEWS AND OBSERVER, 4/30/96, p. B1</i><br>
Jay Price
<p>

"With another straight-A report card from the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission," one would expect the workers at Carolina Power &amp;
Light's Shearon Harris nuclear power plant to "be whistling like the
Seven Dwarfs."  But the Raleigh-based utility has a morale problem
stemming from continuing layoffs.
<p>

This summer, CP&amp;L plans to cut 200 jobs from its nuclear group,
after cutting 100 positions in the group in August 1994 and 150
workers throughout the company in 1995.  "Company officials say
downsizing is part of a continuous program to become more efficient in
the face of rising competitive pressures."  Both CP&amp;L and the NRC
say the layoffs do not threaten the plant's "integrity."  Yet the next
round of job cuts "raises the nebulous question of how much cutting
can be done without compromising the safety margin," the RALEIGH NEWS
AND OBSERVER reports.
<p>

"The stakes are high for CP&amp;L."  A study released last year found
CP&amp;L is among the utilities "most vulnerable" in a competitive
market due to high rates and fixed costs.  The article continues by
reviewing layoffs and associated safety concerns at nuclear utilities
nationwide.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Nuclear Plant Gets High Marks for Safety," RALEIGH NEWS AND
       OBSERVER, 4/25/96, p. B3, Staff Report, which notes the NRC
       gave the Shearon Harris plant "top ratings" for plant
       operations, maintenance, engineering and plant support.
  <li> "Hydro Delays Pickering Station Restart," TORONTO GLOBE AND
       MAIL, 5/2/96, p. A4, Staff Report, which notes the utility will
       extend a two-week shutdown of the Pickering nuclear power plant
       for another week to perform additional maintenance work.  The
       outage is costing the utility about C$1.2 million a day.
</ul>
       
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... The Nuclear Energy Institute's full-page ad touting S. 1271, a
Senate nuclear waste policy bill, appeared today in the WALL STREET
JOURNAL (5/3/96, p. A7A).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... State Sen. Gary Suhadolnik (R) withdrew an amendment to the OH
low-level radioactive waste disposal law, this week.  His amendment,
attached to a "noncontroversial" landfill bill, would have allowed
more staff and multiple contractors to locate, build, and operate a
"dump" to store low-level radioactive waste from OH and five other
Midwest states for 20 years beginning in 2005.  Suhadolnik will "seek
another vehicle" to amend the law that permits only one contractor.
(Cleveland PLAIN DEALER, 5/2/96, p. 5B, T.C. Brown).


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... A letter to the editor of the JOURNAL OF COMMERCE from Frank
Bruce, a former associate director of the Oak Ridge National
Laboratory, argues governments already possess "an easy instrument"
for addressing global warming concerns: the power to approve or deny
power plants' permits to operate.  Bruce encourages support for
renewing nuclear plant licenses while shutting down coal-fired plants
(5/3/96, p. 6A).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... French firefighters are distributing iodine pills to thousands of
people who live near nuclear power plants as an possible antidote in
the event of widespread radiation poisoning.  But "it only made some
people more nervous" (RALEIGH NEWS AND OBSERVER, 4/27/96, p. A13,
Associated Press).


</td>
</tr>
