<html><head><title>Nuke News, 2/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 2/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.01.html">Previous Nuke News</a>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Westinghouse Settles Nuclear Plant Complaints" </b><br>
JOURNAL OF COMMERCE, 5/2/96, p. 7B</i><br>
Knight-Ridder Financial Wire Report
<p>

"Westinghouse Electric Corp. [yesterday] said it reached 'an amicable
settlement' with Portland General Electric and PacifiCorp over a
lawsuit involving steam generators supplied by Westinghouse to the
Trojan nuclear power plant."
<p>

Portland General operates the Trojan nuclear plant and had closed in
1993 "after several years of extensive steam-generator repairs."
Portland General filed suit against Westinghouse in February 1993.
Before yesterday, Westinghouse had already reached a settlement with
the city of Eugene Water and Electric Board, which also owns a stake
in Trojan.
<p>

Westinghouse reached a settlement last week in a similar suit
involving Northern States Power in Minnesota.  Westinghouse still has
two steam-generator suits outstanding; one with Chicago-based
Commonwealth Edison and the other with Newark, NJ- based Public
Service Electric &amp; Gas.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Westinghouse Settles a Lawsuit," WALL STREET JOURNAL, 
       5/2/96, p. B2, Staff Report.
  <li> "Westinghouse Says Heads of Two Units Will Leave Company," WALL
       STREET JOURNAL, 5/2/96, p. B12, Staff Report, which notes the
       heads of its Government &amp; Environmental Services unit,
       James Moore, and of its Energy Systems unit, Nathaniel Woodson,
       will leave the company.  "Neither man was forced out," a
       spokeswoman said.  "Analysts said their departures signal an
       increased emphasis on profitability" as the company considers
       selling its Industry and Technology Group.  Francis Harvey was
       named acting president of the units.
</ul>


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Former Nuclear Facility Resumes Electricity Production"</b><br>
COLORADO SPRINGS GAZETTE-TELEGRAPH ONLINE, 5/2/96</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

A former nuclear power plant in Platteville, CO resumed operations on
Tuesday as a 130-megawatt natural-gas-fired unit.  The Fort St.  Vrain
plant was operated as a nuclear facility for 10 years, until August
1989, when Public Service Co. of Colorado decided to make the fuel
switch.
<p>

The first phase of construction was completed last month; the company
plans to produce 471 megawatts from the plant by May 1999.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Large-Scale Protests May Be in Past, but the [Nuclear] Industry Faces Tough Times"</b><br>
NORFOLK VIRGINIAN-PILOT AND LEDGER-STAR, 4/28/96, p. D1</i><br>
Scott Harper
<p>

Virginia Power executives say their nuclear power plants are "totally
different" from the Chernobyl plant which exploded 10 years ago last
Friday.  In one of two lengthy features that ran in this paper last
Sunday, the reporter recalls the industry's most notable troubles with
nuclear plants, and the subsequent "soul-searching" investigations and
safety upgrades.
<p>

The article also notes that of the 84 reactors that have been shut
down worldwide, the average life span was 17 years -- far less than
the average 40-year lifespan predicted.
<p>

Environmental protests have lessened, but that is largely because no
new plants have been commissioned in years.  Today, environmental
concerns center on nuclear waste, the reporter concludes, recapping
the undecided status of the US nuclear-waste policy debate.
<p>

SEE ALSO:
<ul>
  <li> "Will Nuclear Regain Its Power?  Va. Power Shook a Troubled
       History," NORFOLK VIRGINIAN-PILOT AND LEDGER-STAR, 4/28/96,
       p. D1, Dave Mayfield, another lengthy analysis of the
       industry's challenges.  The article recalls the 1986 accident
       at VP's Surry nuclear power plant, which led to the deaths of
       four workers burned by leaking hot water.  This week, Virginia
       Power has begun a 37-day refueling outage which -- if all goes
       well -- should contribute to the company's overall effort to
       control costs over the next several years.
  <li> "Nuclear Industry in US Expects a Renaissance," SEATTLE TIMES,
       4/26/96, p. A3, Gannett News Service.  In another Chernobyl-
       related analysis, the SEATTLE TIMES notes most of America's
       nuclear plants are taking one of two routes: "replacing vital
       parts" -- especially steam-generators -- or shutting down due
       to unfavorable economics.
  <li> section below.
</ul>



<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Search for Nuclear Waste Site"</b><br>
SEATTLE POST-INTELLIGENCER, 4/29/96, p. A3</i><br>
Holly Yeager
<p>

The U.S. Senate is set to consider a bill that would "tilt the odds
even further" toward making Yucca Mountain in the NV desert the
permanent storage site for the nation's high-level nuclear waste.
Legislation, crafted by Sen. Larry Craig (R-ID), would authorize a
temporary storage facility a few miles from Yucca Mountain ready to
accept materials from commercial power plants by 1/31/99. It also
would accept spent fuel from Navy nuclear subs, now stored at the
Idaho National Engineering Lab.  Critics argue that making Yucca
Mountain the temporary site will make it the "de facto permanent"
site; since it is "unlikely" that "dangerous waste" would be reshipped
out of NV.
<p>

The problem is that 26 of the nation's 110 nuclear reactors will fill
up their on-site storage space for spent fuel by 1998; and by 2010 --
the earliest date for a permanent facility -- 80 reactors will run out
of space.  The POST-INTELLIGENCER quotes Leigh Ann Marshall,
spokesperson for the Nuclear Energy Institute, the industry's
Washington-based trade assn., as stating that, without quick action,
the electric utilities are "either going to have to shut down or ask
their ratepayers to pay to build additional on-site storage
facilities."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... A state bill to "raid" nuclear power plant taxes is being
"blasted" by critics in St. Charles Parish, site of the Waterford 3
nuclear plant.  They contend that sharing the plant's tax revenue with
the state and other parishes would set a "dangerous precedent" and
destroy "incentives" for local governments to accept "controversial"
industries.  The bill also targets Entergy Corp.'s River Bend nuclear
plant in West Feliciana Parish, set to join the tax rolls next year
(NEW ORLEANS TIMES-PICAYUNE, 5/1/96, p. B3, Rhonda Bell).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... A "small" heavy-water leak was reported at the Point Lepreau 
nuclear power plant in New Brunswick, Canada.  A tube inside one of 
the reactor's four boilers is leaking more than two pounds of heavy 
water an hour, a rate officials called "minor" and no threat to the 
public (BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 5/1/96, Associated Press).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... Blaming reduced federal funding, Atomic Energy of Canada Ltd. will 
cut more than 200 jobs and $27 million in research over the next 12 
months.  Most cuts will be at the Chalk River facilities northwest of 
Ottawa, but some job losses are expected at labs in Whiteshell, Man. 
and the neutrino observatory in Sudbury, Ont. (TORONTO GLOBE &amp; MAIL, 
5/1/96, B4).


</td>
</tr>
