<html><head><title>Nuke News, 1/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 1/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.30.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... A "mysterious cloud of radiation" that passed through three
northern MA towns near the Seabrook Nuclear Power Plant last year
prompted local leaders and a state senator to call for closer scrutiny
of the NH reactor. Seabrook officials, who concede releasing "some
radiation into the air that night," insist the amount was "smaller
than even naturally occurring levels" and say the reported material
must have come from another source. (BOSTON HERALD, 4/29/96, Mark
Mueller).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... The OH Low-Level Radioactive Waste Facility Development Authority 
may have to eliminate the western half of the state, known to gas and 
oil drillers as "the Big Lime," from consideration as a site for a 
radioactive waste disposal center. The problem is cracks that form in 
the bedrock in much of that region that could leak radioactive 
material into groundwater (COLUMBUS DISPATCH, 4/27/96, p. 1C).
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Nuclear Waste: Just Passing Through," ATLANTA JOURNAL-
       CONSTITUTION, 4/25/96, Joan King, Op-Ed, in which the author,
       an activist from Sautee, GA, alerts readers that the move to
       begin nuclear waste shipments is about to come to a floor vote
       in the US Senate. Pointing out that GA is a rail and highway
       crossroads, she asks, "Are we really ready for this?"
</ul>


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Northeast Utilities Update Frustrates NRC Officials" </b><br>
BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 5/1/96</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

"Northeast Utilities' plans to improve safety and efficiency at its
troubled Millstone nuclear power complex failed to impress Nuclear
Regulatory Commission officials" at a public hearing yesterday.
<p>

Ted Feigenbaum, the utility's executive VP and chief nuclear officer,
outlined a "wide-ranging" plan addressing "improved performance,
corrective actions, management training and employee morale."  But
both Wayne Lanning, director of the NRC's oversight team at Millstone,
and NRC branch chief Jack Durr indicated they weren't convinced.
Lanning: "We don't want another plan.  What we want is results."  Durr
told a reporter: "I can't really say we've made any progress in
improving station performance. ... I feel like we've really lost
ground."
<p>

"But there has been some good news for NU," the AP reports.  The NRC
has said it may allow the Millstone 3 reactor to restart before
August, lessening the threat of power shortages this summer.


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Nuclear Plant Stops Because Water Drops" </b><br>
ASBURY PARK [NJ] PRESS ONLINE, 5/1/96</i><br>
Ralph Ortega
<p>

Managers of the Oyster Creek, NJ nuclear power plant are trying to
determine exactly what caused an automatic shutdown at 2:55 a.m. on
Tuesday morning.  The reactor shut itself down while powering up
"because of a low water level reading in the core," a plant spokesman
said.  It wasn't known why the water level was low, but investigators
suspect plant operators did not switch open a set of valves that fills
the reactor core with water.
<p>

The spokesman said no equipment failure was detected, and there was
enough water inside the reactor to prevent overheating.  The US
Nuclear Regulatory Commission was notified, and since there was no
safety risk, plant officials expected to restart the reactor last
night.


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Forces Marshaled Against Nuclear Waste Bill"</b><br>
LAS VEGAS SUN, 4/30/96, p. 9</i><br>
Mary Manning
<p>

Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole (R-KS) has not yet scheduled a vote on
the Nuclear Waste Policy Act, the LAS VEGAS SUN reports.  The bill,
originally set for Senate consideration today, would allow
construction of an interim nuclear-waste storage facility at the
Nevada Test Site near Yucca Mountain, NV, the site of a proposed a
long-term repository.
<p>

Dole spokesman Jeremy Wallison on 4/29 said the bill might come up
later, "but not this week."  The legislation could be attached to a
1997 budget package later in the year, but nuclear industry leaders,
government officials and lawmakers were not encouraged.  President
Clinton has threatened to veto the bill.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Nuclear Hot Potato," Minneapolis STAR TRIBUNE, 4/30/96,
       p. A12, Editorial, which says the "Senate legislation sensibly
       proposes developing an interim storage facility at the
       government's nuclear bomb test facility in Nevada.
       <p>
       
       ... Unfortunately, the bill requires that the government take
       title to the waste as soon as it is transferred to the interim
       site.  That means that if long-term storage costs go up --
       which they almost certainly will -- the taxpayer takes the hit.
       That's the wrong target."
  <li> "Congress Has Over 110 Good Reasons to Store Nuclear Waste in 1
       Place," WASHINGTON POST, 5/1/96, p. A8, another appearance of
       the Nuclear Energy Institute's large advertisement backing the
       Senate nuclear-waste bill.
</ul>
     


</td>
</tr>
</table>
