<html><head><title>Nuke News, 30/4/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 30/4/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.29.html">Previous Nuke News</a>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Millstone Shutdown Could Crimp Competition in New Hampshire"</b><br>
BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 4/30/96</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

"Rising wholesale electricity prices" may force the New Hampshire
Public Utilities Commission to revise the retail- wheeling pilot
program set to begin in that state on May 28.  Rising prices may be
due to the shutdown of Northeast Utilities' Millstone nuclear power
plant in Connecticut, the Associated Press reports.
<p>

To salvage the program, the PUC may have to raise the "assumed market
price," or the price at which it expects customers to be able to buy
electricity on the open market.  Under current plans, residential
customers automatically get a 10% discount as an incentive to
participate in the pilot, but the discount will be less if they pay a
price higher than the assumed market price.  If the discount becomes
too small, "customers might not want to bother choosing from as many
as 20 competing suppliers."  High wholesale prices might also affect
which suppliers are willing to compete, the AP reports.
<p>

Although the PUC discussed the issue on Monday, no decision has been
made, an official said.  The commission may soon hold hearings on the
issue.


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Residents Say They Don't Trust Nuclear Officials"</b><br>
BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 4/30/96</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

Residents near the Maine Yankee nuclear power plant in Wiscasset, ME
told federal regulators "they are worried" about the plant's safety
and they "don't trust plant officials or regulators to protect them
from radiation."  About 350 people attended a meeting with officials
of Maine Yankee and the US Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
<p>

Maine Yankee managers presented an analysis that shows the recently
repaired cooling system works correctly.  If the NRC agrees -- in a
process that is expected to last two to three months -- the plant will
be allowed to return to full power for the first time since January
1995.
<p>

Maine Gov. Angus King (I) said Monday the state has hired Purdue U. 
nuclear engineering Professor Victor Ransom to review Maine Yankee's 
analysis of the cooling system.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... About 20 peaceful anti-nuclear protestors were arrested on 
Saturday outside the Tennessee Valley Authority's Watts Bar nuclear 
power plant, which has been delayed for years by safety hazards and 
management troubles (GREENPEACE PRESS RELEASE, 4/27/96, Contact Stacey 
Fenn, 415-602-9564).

</td>
</tr>
