<html><head><title>Nuke News, 29/4/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 29/4/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.26.html">Previous Nuke News</a>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"N.E. Utilities Warn of Summer Power Shortages" </b><br>
BOSTON GLOBE, 4/26/96, p. B6</i><br>
Jerry Ackerman
<p>

New England's electric utilities are warning that the region faces
"brownouts" in many areas and periodic blackouts in parts of
Connecticut, due to the shutdown of three Northeast Utilities nuclear
power plants in Connecticut.  Utility officials said that with a hot
summer and a possible fourth shut down of an NU plant, rolling
brownouts and even blackouts may be necessary.
<p>

Some public officials said the warning letters sent by the New England
Power Pool may be efforts to hasten the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission's investigations into some area plants.  The review of NU's
Millstone 3 could be finished by June, but those for 1 and 2 could
take until August.
<p>

State regulators have responded by telling utilities to take
extraordinary measures to combat possible shortages, such as
increasing the power capacity of transmission lines and leasing
emergency generators.
<p>

Even though NU has vowed not to pass on the cost of finding alternate
energy sources to customers, other utilities in the region might have
to raise their rates.  Jeffrey Tranen of New England Electric System
-- the region's second largest utility -- said the situation may push
the spot price of power under emergency conditions to triple the
normal level.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Protestors Rally to Mark Chernobyl Anniversary," BOSTON GLOBE
       ONLINE, 4/29/96, Associated Press, which reports that about 85
       people marched to the Millstone complex on Saturday to mark the
       10th anniversary of the Chernobyl nuclear power accident in the
       Ukraine.  The protestors raised safety concerns about the
       Millstone complex.
</ul>


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Fears About WPPSS Bonds Are Revived" </b><br>
WALL STREET JOURNAL, 4/29/96, p. C1</i><br>
Fred Vogelstein
<p>

"Just when many in the Northwest thought they finally had lived down
the tortured legacy of the giant bond default known as Whoops, it is
rearing its head again."  A nuclear power plant owned by the
Washington Public Power Supply System (WPPSS) defaulted on its $2.25
billion debt in 1983, spawning 12 years of litigation over the
municipal bonds.  But now, as policy makers seek to restructure the
federally owned Bonneville Power Administration, "no one can seem to
get around the fact the BPA is the ultimate backer" of the WPPSS
bonds, whose annual debt service of nearly $500 million a year
consumes about 20% of BPA's annual expenses.
<p>

The BPA "may have an easier time adjusting" to power industry
restructuring because "political considerations" may drive decisions
and the agency "remains one of the cheapest power producers in the
country." Yet BPA "has been fighting for its life" against lower-cost
gas-fired power plants, and it is under pressure to spend more to
protect endangered salmon species.
<p>

"Few anticipate another WPPS default, but a ratings downgrade is a
possibility," the WALL STREET JOURNAL reports.
<p>

Meanwhile, a 20-member committee representing the utility's various
constituencies, backed by the region's governors, is preparing a list
of options by July 15 for BPA restructuring, with a report to the
governors by Labor Day and to Congress by December 1.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... Full-page ads in both the WASHINGTON POST and WASHINGTON TIMES 
proclaim, "Congress has over 110 good reasons to store nuclear waste 
in 1 place."  The Nuclear Energy Institute ad features a map showing 
110 nuclear power plants spread across the US, concluding:  "Better to 
put nuclear waste at one central facility in a remote desert area [the 
Nevada Test Site] -- not at nuclear power plant sites and defense 
facilities all across the country."  The ad urges support for Senate 
bill #1271 (WASHINGTON POST, 4/29/96, p. A14).

</td>
</tr>
