<html><head><title>Nuke News, 26/4/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 26/4/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.25.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

Gov. Bill Weld (R) showed that he received several thousand dollars
from out-of-state utilities including Atlanta- based Southern Company,
Southern California Edison, Alabama Power and Georgia Power.  Nuclear
industry companies ICF Kaiser Engineers and CH2M Hill Companies gave
$2,000 each (BOSTON HERALD, 4/25/96, p. 1, Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... The leaders of China and Russia met in Beijing yesterday and
signed a number of accords, including deals to cooperate in nuclear
power and accelerate negotiations for the sale of nearly $3 billion in
power-generation and fuel-processing facilities to China over the next
decade (LOS ANGELES TIMES [Washington Edition], 4/26/96, p. A2,
Rone Tempest and Carol Williams).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Westinghouse, NSP Settle Suit Over Equipment"</b><br>
MINNEAPOLIS STAR-TRIBUNE, 4/25/96, p. D1</i><br>
Tom Meersman and Susan Peterson
<p>

Minneapolis-based Northern States Power Co. and Westinghouse Electric
Corp. agreed on April 23 to settle a "major" lawsuit out of
court. Neither company disclosed the terms of the settlement, but
previous deals between Westinghouse and other utilities have involved
cash and discounted services.
<p>

The lawsuit concerned some "prematurely aging equipment" at the
Prairie Island nuclear power plant.
     

</td>
</tr>
