<html><head><title>Nuke News, 24/4/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 24/4/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.23.html">Previous Nuke News</a>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Northeast Utilities, Despite Ills, Shows Lots of Energy"</b><br>
WALL STREET JOURNAL, 4/24/96, p. B4</i><br>
Ross Kerber
<p>

Despite troubles at its Millstone nuclear power complex, CT- based
Northeast Utilities is "leading the charge into the era of utility
deregulation," the WALL STREET JOURNAL reports in its "Corporate
Focus" column.  Frank Sabatino, Northeast's vice president for
wholesale power sales, said the utility closed 14 new contracts in
1995 and is getting ready to complete six more.  The utility is also
competing for customers in New Hampshire's retail-wheeling pilot
project.  And it has applied for permission to export power to Quebec.
<p>

"In part, Northeast's push for new customers is a bet" by its CEO,
Bernard Fox, that the US Nuclear Regulatory Commission will let the
company restart the Millstone reactors within a few months.  If that
happens, "the wholesale contracts that Northeast has negotiated will
keep it in the game."  But if the shutdown continues beyond early
1997, NU's replacement power bills will mount, "further complicating
its problems."  The company expects to provide documents to the NRC by
the end of August to allow a restart.
<p>

"Analysts said the lack of Millstone's power would become a
company-threatening problem only if two of the three reactors ...
remain off-line for a year or more."  The company's management also
has other defenders.  Despite a whistleblowers' charges that managers
ignored safety guidelines and deceived the NRC, Millstone engineer
Michael Ahearn told a public hearing that he has found managers "very
receptive" to concerns he has raised in the past.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Utility Launches Ad Campaign to Counter Bad Publicity About
       Millstone," BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 4/24/96, Associated Press,
       which notes the utility will start running ads today in
       newspapers and on radio stations featuring workers talking
       about the importance they and the company place on safety.  The
       ads also invite citizens to take guided tours of the Millstone
       complex.
  <li> "Lawmakers Grill Utility Officials About Nuclear Safety,
       Costs," BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 4/23/96, Associated Press, which
       reports that community activists and a Northeast Utilities
       whistleblower testified before the CT General Assembly's Energy
       and Technology Committee on April 22, and called for the
       company's top officials to resign.  "Little new light was shed
       on the problems of the embattled company," but CEO Fox said the
       company expects to spend $30 million a month for replacement
       power.
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Seabrook Declared Well-Operated" </b><br>
AP/BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 4/23/96</i><br>
Wire Report
<p>

On April 22, the US Nuclear Regulatory Commission and Seabrook nuclear
power plant officials released the results of a February inspection of
the New Hampshire plant, concluding it is "a well-operated facility"
with no major safety issues.
<p>

The NRC did have some negative observations, including reported
problems with the plant's corrective measures, difficulties with
equipment and personnel errors.
<p>

The NRC also announced it be inspecting Seabrook less often, which
brought "immediate condemnation" from the Seacoast Anti- Pollution
League.  Spokeswoman Jane Doughty criticized the move as
"irresponsible and indefensible in the context of a technology that
has the potential to endanger the lives ... of thousands of people."


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Nuclear Shutdown Stirs Questions"</b><br>
TORONTO GLOBE &amp; MAIL, 4/23/96, p. A6</i><br>
Martin Mittelstaedt
<p>

Ontario Environment Minister Brenda Elliott "expressed concern" over
safety problems that forced the shutdown of Ontario Hydro's Pickering
nuclear plant this past weekend, but said that the utility's prompt
decision-making was "reassuring."
<p>

Opposition leaders on April 22 asked Elliott to persuade Ontario Hydro
to disclose internal peer reviews of utility operations.  The reviews
are thought to be "critical of safety standards" at Ontario Hydro, but
are not being released for "public relations and financial reasons."
<p>

Elliott also gave a "cautious endorsement" to provincial utilities
that want to use plutonium from the US Dept. of Energy as fuel for
nuclear reactors.  Elliott: "It's certainly something I think that the
province wants to consider," but she also wants "public input on how
the citizens of the province feel about it."


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... County supervisors in Los Angeles and San Diego took opposite 
sides yesterday on the issue of siting a low-level radioactive waste 
facility in Ward Valley, CA.  L.A. County supervisors voted 3-2 to 
oppose the dump site based on fears that it could contaminate the 
county's water supply from the Colorado River.  But San Diego 
supervisors voted 4-0 in favor of the site (LOS ANGELES TIMES 
[Washington Edition], 4/24/96, Jeffrey Rabin).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... Virginia Power will "speed up the schedule for restructuring its 
nuclear operations because of signs of mounting stress on employees -- 
including the second fatal heart attack among workers at the North 
Anna nuclear plant" on Saturday.  A deadline for "re-engineering" the 
unit has been moved up from September to June (RICHMOND 
TIMES-DISPATCH, 4/24/96, p. C1, Michael Martz).

</td>
</tr>
</table>
