<html><head><title>Nuke News, 23/4/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 23/4/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.22.html">Previous Nuke News</a>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... Sen. Rod Grams's (R-MN) attack on the Dept. of Energy in a 4/9
WALL STREET JOURNAL op-ed "rehashes arguments that were explored and
dropped in the Reagan era and again last year," writes a DOE official.
Dismantling the agency would result in no clear savings for taxpayers,
setbacks in nuclear-waste cleanup, and other problems, writes Carmen
MacDougall, DOE deputy asst. sec'y for communications (WALL STREET
JOURNAL, 4/23/96, p. A23).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... Rochester Gas &amp; Electric recorded a nuclear power industry first
by hoisting a steam generator through the top of a working plant.  At
the Ginna Nuclear Power Station in Ontario, NY, the nation's largest
mobile crane lifted a 63-foot-long generator through a hole cut with
jackhammers in the 3-foot-thick containment dome.  A second generator
will be removed in the same way, and both will be stored as low-level
radioactive waste in a concrete building 300 yards from the plant
(SYRACUSE POST- STANDARD, 4/19/96, p. B2, Associated Press).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... An amendment to a law mandating that Ohio accept low-level
radioactive waste from five other Midwest states for as many as 20
years is under a threat of being blocked by Ohio state Sen. Dennis
Kucinich (D).  The bill would allow the Low Level Radioactive Waste
Authority to hire additional staff and multiple contractors to build
and operate a proposed dump (CLEVELAND PLAIN-DEALER, 4/19/96, p. 5B,
T.C. Brown).


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Supreme Court Backs TMI Accident Lawsuits"</b><br>
PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER, 4/23/96, p. A8</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

The US Supreme Court yesterday declined to hear the nuclear power
industry's appeal seeking to block more than 2,000 individuals who
claim they were injured by radiation from the 1979 Three Mile Island
accident from receiving punitive damages under Pennsylvania law.
<p>

The plaintiffs can now seek punitive and compensatory damages, opening
the door to possible multi-million dollar awards.  A group of 10 test
cases is scheduled to go to trial in June and will consider whether
the 3/79 "partial meltdown" at Three Mile Island caused the alleged
injuries and whether damages should be awarded.
<p>

About 1,000 people with injuries or their survivors have suits pending
against Metropolitan Edison, General Public Utilities Corp.  and other
companies involved with the plant.
<p>

A federal appeals court in Philadelphia last year ruled that
individuals injured by the accident could try to recover punitive
damages under state law.  It rejected the defendants' argument that
such claims were barred under amendments adopted by Congress in 1988
to the Price-Anderson Act, which governs the nation's nuclear power
industry.
<p>

The PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER also noted the story in its "Business
Briefs" section on p. C3 of today's issue.
<p>

SEE ALSO: 
<ul>
  <li> "Path Cleared for Lawsuits in TMI Accident," USA TODAY,
       4/23/96, p. 3A, Tony Mauro.
  <li> "High Court to Decide Whether Antibias law Covers Ex- Workers,"
       WALL STREET JOURNAL, 4/23/96, p. B6, Paul barrett, which
       includes a TMI subhead.
</ul>




<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Pickering Stills All Eight Reactors"</b><br>
TORONTO GLOBE &amp; MAIL, 4/22/96, p. A1</i><br>
Michael Grange
<p>

All eight reactors at Ontario Hydro's Pickering nuclear generating
plant were shut down this past weekend due to a "flaw" in the plant's
secondary safety system.  Spokesmen for Hydro and the Atomic Energy
Control Board said on April 21 that the problem did not compromise
public safety.
<p>

The shutdown "punctuates a difficult stretch" for Canada's largest
nuclear energy facility.  Sixteen months ago, Pickering nuclear
station A was shut down due to a broken pipe.  Eight months ago, Hydro
was ordered to improve safety practices or face penalties.  Last week,
radioactive heavy water from one of Pickering's reactors leaked into
Lake Ontario.
<p>

The reactors -- which provide about 20% of Hydro's electrical
generating capacity -- may be decommissioned for eight to 10 days.
However, a Pickering spokesman said some of the reactors may be
operational by April 24 or 25.

</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
