<html><head><title>Nuke News, 22/4/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 22/4/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.19.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"NU Violations Were Intentional, Lawyer Says"</b><br>
HARTFORD COURANT, 4/19/96, p. F2</i><br>
Barbara Nagy
<p>

"The Nuclear Regulatory Commission has determined that Northeast
Utilities intentionally violated the conditions of its operating
license for the Millstone 1 nuclear power plant" in Waterford, CT,
according to Massachusetts lawyer Ernest Hadley, who is representing
whistleblower George Galatis.
<p>

Hadley said that the NRC has found that NU willfully refueled Unit 1
incorrectly.  After Galatis reported the refueling problem to the NRC
last year, the agency put all three Millstone units on its "watch
list" and ordered them to stay closed indefinitely.
<p>

"NRC spokesman Victor Dricks wouldn't confirm Hadley's version of the
refueling report, and said it's unlikely that the full document will
ever be made public."  If the report contains allegations of willful
wrongdoing, the NRC will take its findings to the Justice Department
for possible criminal prosecution.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Uneasiness, But Not Panic, Spreads Among Neighbors of Troubled
       Nuclear Power Complex," BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 4/21/96, which
       reports that residents living near the Millstone nuclear power
       complex are troubled by the performance of the reactors.
  <li> "Northeast Utilities May Face NRC Penalties," BOSTON GLOBE,
       4/19/96, p. 91, Bloomberg.
</ul>


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Testimony Ends Nuke Suit"</b><br>
AUSTIN AMERICAN-STATESMAN, 4/19/96, p. B4</i><br>
Matt Schwartz
<p>

After seven weeks of testimony and evidence, a Harris County, TX jury
is set to hear final arguments today in the City of Austin's $120
million lawsuit against Houston Lighting &amp; Power Co.  Austin is
suing HL&amp;P for negligence, claiming its mismanagement of the South
Texas Project nuclear power plant led to a 14-month shutdown that cost
the city millions for replacement power.
<p>

HL&amp;P rested its case on April 18 with the testimony of a
University of Texas professor who told the jury the city suffered no
damages during the shutdown for repairs in 1993 and 1994 because the
extra operating and maintenance costs were reasonable.  Witness Martin
Baughman said that because STP would have been shutdown for much of
the same period for equipment repairs, the amount of time the plant
was closed for regulatory reasons was a reasonable burden of owning a
nuclear facility. Baughman estimated that even if the city did suffer,
the damages were "at most" only $8.7 million.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Russia Struggles in Long Race to Prevent an Atomic Theft"</b><br>
NEW YORK TIMES, 4/20/96, p. 1</i><br>
Michael Gordon
<p>

"Two years after the first reports that nuclear material had been
smuggled out of the former Soviet Union," the US and Russia are
"already collaborating" on a program to help safeguard Russia's
nuclear materials, reports the NEW YORK TIMES in a lengthy, front-page
article.
<p>

While progress is slow, officials are making steady progress in
setting up security systems for the vast store of nuclear material
scattered at sites across the former Soviet Union.
<p>

"So far there is no evidence that nuclear materials have been acquired
by would-be nuclear powers of terrorist groups."  But many experts
believe that it is only a matter of time until a serious incident
occurs, and say that money and efforts to guard against theft needs to
be doubled.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"One Big Dump"</b><br>
ECONOMIST, 4/20/96, p. 22</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

Three main obstacles that have raised concerns have yet to be resolved
by the "army of scientists and technicians at Yucca Mountain," the
potential dump site for the nation's worst nuclear waste.  Energy
Dept. officials will determine by the end of the decade whether the
site in south-western Nevada will safely contain nuclear waste
produced by the US's 100-plus commercial nuclear reactors and its
armed forces.
<p>

Scientists remained concerned about a potential volcanic eruption --
the region has a history of volcanic activity.  They are also worried
about the proximity of the area to a fault line which may cause
earthquakes.  But their "chief concern" is water.  When the containers
containing the nuclear waste begin to decompose, the surrounding rock
should stop any penetration to the surface.  But the movement of water
"could let radionuclides past this natural barrier."

</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
