<html><head><title>Nuke News, 19/4/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 19/4/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.18.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien announced on April 17 that
his country is contemplating building as many as four additional
reactors at the site of the recently opened Cernavoda nuclear plant in
Romania, which has been plagued with soaring cost overruns and
scandalous allegations (TORONTO GLOBE &amp; MAIL, 4/18/96, p. A14,
Geoffrey York).

<p> <img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif"> <p>

... Pres. Clinton arrived in Russia for a summit with Pres. Yeltsin
and leaders of eight nations "to boost East-West cooperation in
reducing the risk of nuclear accidents" (WALL STREET JOURNAL, 4/19/96,
p. A1, Staff Report).

<p> <img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif"> <p>

<i><b>"Northern States Says Talks With Apaches on Spent Fuel Falter"</b><br>
WALL STREET JOURNAL, 4/19/96, p. B5</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

Minneapolis-based Northern States Power Co. said yesterday it had
suspended its negotiations with the Mescalero Apache tribe over a
possible storage site for spent nuclear fuel on tribal land in New
Mexico.
<p>

"Like other utilities with nuclear plants," NSP currently stores spent
fuel on-site in facilities that are rapidly approaching capacity. The
federal government's plans to construct interim and permanent storage
sites have been delayed "repeatedly."
<p>

NSP, representing a consortium of 11 electric utilities, said the
group will now open talks with other potential hosts.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Mescaleros Close Negotiations for Nuclear Storage Site,"
       COLORADO SPRINGS GAZETTE-TELEGRAPH ONLINE, 4/19/96, Associated
       Press, which notes tribal leaders "haven't given up on a
       nuclear storage project."  NSP's Scott Northard praised the
       "courage" of tribal leaders in "tackling this national
       challenge" and said, "We're parting on good terms."  But some
       tribal members and the New Mexico congressional delegation had
       opposed the concept of storing nuclear waste "amid an upscale
       mountain resort area, surrounded by trout lakes and streams,
       pine trees and ski slopes."
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Utility's Plans at Nuclear Plant OK'd"</b><br>
MILWAUKEE JOURNAL SENTINEL, 4/17/96, p. 1D</i><br>
Lee Bergquist
<p>

The Wisconsin Public Service Commission on April 16 voted 3-0 to allow
Wisconsin Electric Power Co. to replace two steam generators at the
Point Beach nuclear power plant at a cost of $94 million.  WEPCO said
the decision ensures that the plant will stay in operation well into
the next century.
<p>

Without the ruling, WEPCO would have been forced to close the plant --
which provides 300f the utility's electricity -- and find a
replacement energy source.  WEPCO said it hopes to have the generators
replaced by the end of this year.  The PSC also decided to allow WEPCO
to continue storing spent nuclear fuel rods in concrete and steel
casks outside the utility's plants in Manitowoc County because storage
space at the Point Beach plant is running out.
<p>

David Merritt, executive director of the Madison-based public interest
group Citizens' Utility Board: "The three PSC commissioners once again
turned their backs on everybody but Wisconsin Electric."  Merritt said
his group was strongly considering a lawsuit to block the project.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Deregulation Spurs Edison to Sell 2 Coal-Fired Plants"</b><br>
CHICAGO TRIBUNE, 4/18/96, p. 1</i><br>
David Young
<p>

As reported here yesterday, Chicago's Commonwealth Edison Co.
announced Wednesday it will sell two of its power plants to
independent electricity producers for a total of $250.2 million.  The
plants, located in Hammond, IN and Kincaid, IL, will be sold to
Southern Electric International and Dominion Energy Inc.,
respectively.  Both buyers agreed to modernize the plants within two
years.
<p>

The sale provides Commonwealth with cash to pay down its debt, much of
which is carried on its 12 nuclear plants.  Commonwealth said it will
buy back power from the facilities for the next 15 years.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... The Tennessee Valley Authority's Watts Bar Nuclear Plant was
stalled on April 17 as workers tried to determine what caused a valve
to cut off steam power to the main turbine, shutting down the reactor
(ATLANTA CONSTITUTION, 4/18/96, p. E9, Gerrie Ferris).
     


</td>
</tr>
</table>
