<html><head><title>Nuke News, 18/4/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 18/4/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.17.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... Canada's prime minister Jean Chretien yesterday opened Romania's 
first nuclear plant, the only one in the former Eastern bloc built 
with Western technology.  The Cernavoda plant was built by Atomic 
Energy of Canada along with Ansaldo of Italy and Renel, Romania's 
state electricity company (FINANCIAL TIMES, 4/17/96, p. 5, Virginia 
Marsh).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>



<i><b>"Northeast Utilities, Workers Violated Procedures at Nuclear Plant, NRC Says"</b><br>
WALL STREET JOURNAL, 4/18/96, p. A4</i><br>
Ross Kerber
<p>

The US Nuclear Regulatory Commission has concluded that employees at
Connecticut-based Northeast Utilities operated the Millstone nuclear
power plant improperly, and "willfully" filed "misleading" reports to
the NRC about the plant.
<p>

The findings were first described publicly by Ernest Hadley, an
attorney for NU engineer George Galatis, who filed the allegations of
"corporate misconduct" last year.  An unidentified NRC official
confirmed to the WALL STREET JOURNAL that Mr. Hadley's description of
the findings was accurate.
<p>

An NRC probe found that NU employees "knew they were violating the
company's operating guidelines when they moved the entire fuel core of
the Millstone 1 reactor into its cooling pools in one step," instead
of in stages.  Investigators also concluded the company "knowingly
filed false documents about the procedure to the agency."
<p>

The NRC is now considering whether to impose fines or seek criminal
charges against the utility.  An NU spokesman said the company had not
seen the NRC report and had no comment.
     
     


</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
