<html><head><title>Nuke News, 17/4/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 17/4/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.16.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"NRC To Reconsider Funding Rules Due To Restructuring" </b><br>
PUBLIC UTILITIES WEEKLY, 4/12/96, p.1</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

In an effort to show changes brought about by the restructuring and
deregulation of the electric industry, the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission is contemplating amending its regulations on nuclear-plant
decommissioning and funding.  The NRC will take comments until June 24
before proposing a rule.
<p>

Current regulations allow utilities more flexibility than non- utility
licensees in providing financial security.  The NRC wonders whether a
nuclear power licensee would have to forfeit a regulated rate base to
offset the unfunded balance of decommissioning expenses.
<p>

NRC is considering requiring licensees to: (1) guarantee they can
finance the full decommissioning cost if they are no longer assured a
source of income; and (2) provide periodic progress reports on their
decommissioning funds.
<p>

NRC is contemplating allowing licensees to receive credit for a
positive, real rate return on decommissioning funds while the plant is
"maintained in a condition that allows radioactivity on site to
decay." NRC will also decide whether federal government licensees
should continue to be allowed to use statements of intent to meet
decommissioning financial assurance requirements.


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Energy Targeted in Senate Proposal"</b><br>
WASHINGTON TIMES, 4/17/96,p. A6</i><br>
Ruth Larson
<p>

Sen. Rod Grams (R-MN) yesterday introduced a bill to abolish the US
Dept. of Energy and transfer its functions to other agencies within
three years.  Noting Pres. Clinton's remark that "the era of big
government is over," Grams said, "What better way to carry out this
pledge than to start dismantling an agency with no mission, no purpose
and no legitimate future?"  <p>

Grams's bill would shift DOE's cleanup of nuclear-weapons- related
sites, its power marketing administrations (PMAs) and its national
labs to the Pentagon, while transferring basic energy research and the
Energy Information Administration to the Interior Dept.  Grams said
his bill would save between $19-23 billion over five years.  <p>

The Energy Dept. "ridiculed" Grams's proposal in a statement: "There
they go again.  A few extremists who have run out of issues ...  are
now recycling an old, failed idea. ... Democrats and reasonable
Republicans agree -- it's a dumb idea."  Grams acknowledged his bill
had little chance of passage this year "but said it was important to
get the process started."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... Maintenance and refueling kept Public Service Electric &amp; Gas Co.'s
nuclear power plants in New Jersey idle in the first quarter, reducing
earnings by 8 cents per share (PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER, 4/17/95, p. C2,
Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... The Nuclear Regulatory Commission on April 15 began a two- week
safety review into Northeast Utilities' Haddam Neck nuclear power
plant. This comes on the heels of the NRC's shutdown of all three
nuclear reactors at NU's Millstone 1 nuclear plant, and charges of
harassment of company whistleblowers (BOSTON GLOBE, 4/15/96, p. 1,
Scott Allen).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... Supporters of California's proposed Ward Valley nuclear waste
dump, including Rep. Don Young (R-AK), say that improper trash
handling at a "Spring Gathering" of environmentalists last week, and
an ongoing encampment at the site, pose a threat to the endangered
desert tortoise. Young demanded that environmental studies be made to
determine the camp's effects on the ecology of the region (WASHINGTON
POST, 4/16/96, p. A3, Staff Report).


</td>
</tr>
</table>
