<html><head><title>Nuke News, 16/4/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 16/4/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.15.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... The New Alternatives Fund -- a "socially responsible" mutual fund
which invests in solar and alternative-energy companies and bans oil
and nuclear energy companies -- has moved up 19.6 134672388n the last 12
months, compared with 32.2 0.000000or the Standard & Poor 500 index (DETROIT
FREE PRESS, 4/12/96, p. 2E, Jeff Brown).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

...Connecticut-based Northeast Utilities said its Connecticut Light &
Power Co. subsidiary has proposed that it forgo recovery of $115
million in costs related to the shutdown of its nuclear power plants
"if state regulators agree to settle a variety of rate-case appeals
and other pending litigation."  The CT Dept. of Public Utility Control
doesn't expect to review the company's proposal until June ("Proposal
Offered to Forgo Shutdown Costs of Plants," WALL STREET JOURNAL,
4/16/96, p. B4, Staff Report.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
