<html><head><title>Nuke News, 15/4/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 15/4/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.12.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... The state of Texas is suing the US EPA, claiming that radiation
from a planned nuclear waste dump in New Mexico could seep across the
state line (DALLAS MORNING NEWS, 4/12/96, p. 40A, Staff Report).


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Nuclear Waste"</b><br>
MINNEAPOLIS STAR-TRIBUNE, 4/12/96, p. A24</i><br>
Editorial
<p>

"Failure to find a solution to the political mess at Prairie Island,
Minnesota, is one of the most toxic outcomes of the past legislative
session," says the MINNEAPOLIS STAR TRIBUNE.
<p>

Instead of working towards positive solutions, "a discredited and
costly search for a second radioactive-waste storage site in Goodhue
County was allowed to continue another year, draining state coffers,
picking ratepayers' pockets and wasting valuable political energy and
capital."  Two deals between Northern States Power Co. and the tribe
have fallen apart.
<p>

Ratepayers lose because the expensive search process must now
continue.  "Tribal leaders should recognize" that an end to the "good
faith" effort required of NSP to seek an alternative storage site
could cost them dearly, the TRIBUNE says.  "When the legislature
convenes next January, an agreement had better be in hand to end this
wasteful struggle."
     

</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
