<html><head><title>Nuke News, 12/04/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 12/04/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.11.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"WEAPONS MAY FUEL REACTORS"</b><br>
PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER, 4/12/96, P. B1,</i><br>
Mark Jaffe
<p>

Philadelphia's Peco Energy Co. is "one of a handful of utilities" that
is "exploring the possibility" of using fuel made from decommissioned
nuclear warheads to generate electricity at its nuclear power plants.
"But because the plutonium could be removed and used to make nuclear
weapons, the fuel might become a target for terrorists," critics like
Greenpeace contend.
<p>

The US Dept. of Energy is considering three ways to dispose of 42 tons
of weapons-grade plutonium: encasing it in glass or ceramics and
storing it; burying it deep underground; or using it as reactor fuel.
The DOE would have to build a factory to produce the fuel, known as
mixed oxide or MOX.  "One of the reasons DOE is considering the MOX
fuel" is that it would destroy the weapons-grade plutonium.
<p>

Peco spokesman William Jones said, "It is just something we're
expressed interest in, if the DOE picks up the cost and there is a net
benefit for our customers."  Jones recalled the "no lose" situation
when Peco took slightly used fuel from the Shoreham nuclear power
plant on Long Island, getting $70 million in "free fuel" for just $50
million in transportation costs.
<p>

Scott Peters, a spokesman for the Nuclear Energy Institute: "The
industry probably feels that dismantling weapons and taking plutonium
and burning it up reduces risks to world peace.  If it makes economic
sense."
<p>

The DOE will review public comments on the issue this spring and
settle on a plan "later this year."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"PERRY RUNNING AGAIN AFTER FIXES, REFUELING"</b><br>
CLEVELAND PLAIN-DEALER, 4/11/96, P. 3B,</i><br>
Jim Nichols
<p>

The Perry nuclear power plant, which is operated by the Cleveland
Electric Illuminating Co., a subsidiary of Centerior Energy Corp., is
"up and running again," after a brief refueling and repair shutdown.
Officials said technicians cleared up virtually all 2,800 slated
repairs and tests for the plant, many of which were ordered under an
agreement between Centerior and the Federal Nuclear Regulatory
Commission.
<p>

Operators replaced 280 bundles of uranium-filled fuel rods, including
one rod which was found to be leaking radioactive gas into the
reactor, prompting fears that the plant's cooling system could be
contaminated.  Officials said that radioactivity did not end up
exposing workers.  The plant began test runs on April 10 and is
scheduled to return to full power by today.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"JUDGE RULES AGAINST PGE PROFIT ON TROJAN"</b><br>
PORTLAND OREGONIAN, 4/9/96, P. B11,</i><br>
Bill Mackenzie
<p>

A Marion County Circuit Court judge ruled on April 5 that Portland
General Electric can't earn a profit on its stranded investment in the
Trojan nuclear power plant in Rainier, which closed in January 1993.
However, PGE said it will appeal the ruling, and according to Roxanne
Bailey of PGE, "there's already a pretty good track record
that it will turn out in our favor."
<p>

After Trojan closed, PGE asked the Oregon Public Utility Commission to
decide how to handle the recovery of the company's remaining
undepreciated investment in the plant and whether the company could
earn an additional return on it.  The commission, another Marion
County circuit Court judge and the state attorney general all have
supported PGE's right to receive a return on its investment through
rate increases.
<p>

Friday's decision allows PGE to recover its investment, but not to
earn a profit on it.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"NIMO FACES NRC INQUIRY"</b><br>
SYRACUSE POST-STANDARD, 4/9/96, P. A9,</i><br>
Mary Jo Hill
<p>

The US Nuclear Regulatory Commission today will question Niagara
Mohawk Power Corp. about steps it took to correct a problem with an
incorrectly-sized bolt that was installed on a pressure relief panel
years ago at the Nine Mile Point 1 nuclear plant.  The meeting does
not mean that a violation took place or that punishment will ensue,
according to an NRC statement.  The NRC just wants to know why it took
almost a year and a half to correct the problem, said Barry Norris of
the NRC.
<p>

Niagara Mohawk maintains that the faulty bolts would have come off
before "meaningful damage" could be caused to the building where they
were housed.  Norris said that the bolts were excessively large, and
would have let pressure behind the panels build up beyond normal
levels before blowing off.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"CHANGING FACE OF NUCLEAR POWER"</b><br>
JOURNAL OF COMMERCE, 4/12/96, P. 7A,</i><br>
Arthur Gottschalk, OP-ED
<p>

As the 10th anniversary of the Chernobyl nuclear power plant explosion
approaches next week, an international conference in Vienna is
examining the resulting human health problems "which continue to
rise," and a special meeting of the G-7 industrial nations is being
convened to consider what to do about the 15 Chernobyl-style reactors
still operating in Russia, Ukraine, and Lithuania.
<p>

But while those discussions proceed, JOURNAL OF COMMERCE reporter
Arthur Gottschalk says "an even more fundamental question remains ...
: What to do with the thousands of tons of high-level radioactive
waste produced by the 432 reactors now operating in 30 countries."
Those plants produce 230f the world's electricity, but by 2015, they
will have produced 220,000 metric tons of "deadly" spent fuel that
will remain "highly dangerous to living things for at least 10,000
years." None of the countries that operate nuclear reactors has found
"the definitive answer" to this problem, Gottschalk writes.
<p>

The columnist then reviews the disposal debate in the US, noting the
slow development the Yucca Mountain long-term storage facility and the
1998 deadline for DOE to take spent fuel from utilities for interim
storage.  If the US can complete the Yucca Mountain project, the US
would be the first to address the long-term storage issue, which would
be "only fitting for the first nation to develop nuclear power in the
first place."  With 132 new nuclear plants on the drawing boards or
under construction around the world, "it's time to get serious about
solving the nuclear industry's most pressing problem," Gottschalk
concludes.


</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
