<html><head><title>Nuke News, 11/4/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 11/4/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.10.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"Row Over Death Toll From Worst Nuclear Disaster"</b><br>
London Independent, 4/10/96, P. 8,</i><br>
Adrian Bridge
<p>

"Ten years after Chernobyl, international experts are gathering this
week in Vienna to take stock of the scientific, medical and social
impact of the world's worst nuclear disaster."  About 700 delegates
are attending the meeting, which is sponsored by the International
Atomic Energy Agency, European Commission and the World Health
Organization.  Special panels focus on public perception of the
accident, as well as its enviro, economic and political impacts.
<p>

Ukrainian Prime Minister Yevhen Marchuck on Tuesday told attendees
that his country "still has not gotten adequate financial support to
solve this problem."  Under a deal signed in December 1995, Ukraine
agreed to shut the plant by 2000 in return for billions of dollars in
aid from the "Group of 7" industrial nations.  "Last week, the G-7
upped its offer to $3.1 billion in an apparent effort to accelerate
the shutdown."  The issue seems likely to come up at the upcoming G-7
summit in Moscow on April 19-20.  The Ukraine has previously asked for
$4 billion in aid.
<p>

Ukrainian officials say 125,000 Ukrainians died as a direct result of
the accident, with tens of thousands more made ill from radiation.
Western experts dispute that, saying the number of deaths attributable
to the accident could be as low as 45.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Reactor Explosion 'Could Never Happen Again,'" LONDON
       INDEPENDENT, 4/10/96, p. 8, Christopher Bellamy, which reports
       that in London, the chairman of the World Assn. Of Nuclear
       Operators, Remy Carle, told a meeting of association members
       that the Chernobyl nuclear disaster "as it happened in 1986,
       cannot happen again."  Improvements to the RMBK reactor design
       and the growth of a Western-style "safety culture" have made it
       "impossible" for a similar accident to occur, he said.
</ul>
<p>

</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<table width=600>
  <tr>
    <td valign=middle><a href="/"><img src="/graphics/gifs/atom.t.gif"
