<html><head><title>Nuke News, 10/4/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 10/4/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.09.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>
<i><b>STUDY:  MANY NUCLEAR PLANTS UNSAFE"</b><br>
LAS VEGAS SUN, 4/9/96,</i><br>
Mary Manning
<p>

"Promises of an energy paradise driven by atomic power had no
engineering foundation," according to a report released yesterday by
the MD-based Institute for Energy and Environmental Research, an
industry critic.  An "exhaustive" review of archival material shows
"nuclear power was born of compromises on safety questions, government
subsidies" and decisions by General Electric and Westinghouse to take
"huge losses" on initial orders, the LAS VEGAS SUN reports.  Records
show "industry and government leaders clearly understood that nuclear
power would be expensive and difficult to develop."
<p>

The study also concludes that there are no private insurers likely to
cover nuclear power accidents on the scale of the 1986 Chernobyl
accident in the Ukraine.  The report also claims nuclear safety issues
cannot be resolved fast enough to allow it to contribute to reducing
greenhouse gas emissions.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"FEDERAL COURT UPHOLDS MOST OF YANKEE ROWE DEAL"</b><br>
BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 4/9/96,</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

The Yankee Atomic Electric Co. is entitled to recover all of its
investment in the Yankee Rowe nuclear power plant, a federal court
ruled on Tuesday.  The US Court of Appeals upheld most of a Federal
Energy Regulatory Commission ruling that allowed Yankee to recover
costs of construction, operation and closure from ratepayers.  The
FERC decision had been challenged by the town of Norwood, MA.
<p>

Yankee Rowe was shut down in 1991 due to safety concerns.  The costs
of decommissioning the plant are estimated at $368.3 million.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"SUBSCRIBERS WON'T PAY FOR NUCLEAR SHUTDOWN AT NORTHEAST UTILITIES"</b><br>
WALL STREET JOURNAL, 4/10/96, p. A13,</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

Connecticut-based Northeast Utilities does not expect ratepayers to
help pay the costs of its nuclear-plant shutdowns and is instead
considering charges against earnings.  Northeast has said replacement
power may cost about $130 million before the three reactors at its
Millstone power plant are reopened.  The company earned $282.4 million
last year.  The reactors were idled recently by the utility and the US
Nuclear Regulatory Commission due to safety concerns.  In a letter to
state lawmakers, CEO Bernard Fox said NU wouldn't be able to recover
costs in areas where it "failed to meet industry standards."  Fox also
raised the prospect of NRC financial penalties that wouldn't be
recoverable in rates.  He said the CT Dept. of Public Utilities is
auditing NU's nuclear operations to determine which, if any, costs can
be passed on to ratepayers.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Hearing on NU Attracts Both Sides of Nuclear Power Issue,"
       HARTFORD COURANT, 4/9/96, p. A7, Barbara Nagy, which reports
       the US Nuclear Regulatory Commission held a public hearing in
       Waterford, CT on Monday to discuss whether Northeast Utilities
       knowingly violated NRC rules when it refueled its three
       Millstone nuclear power reactors.
       <p>

       The crowd of about 250 people "seemed to be split evenly
       between Millstone employees, who turned out to support NU
       management, and anti-nuclear power activists, who said the
       problems at the plants prove nuclear power is not safe."
       <p>
       
       The commission said it would use the public comments in
       evaluating whether to suspend or revoke NU's licenses to
       operate several nuclear reactors.
       <p>
  <li> "Plant Closings Send NU Stock to 10-Year Low," HARTFORD
       COURANT, 4/9/96, p. 1A, Dan Haar.
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"JUDGE TO REVIEW PLANT APPRAISAL"</b><br>
HARTFORD COURANT, 4/9/96,</i><br>
Rosalinda DeJesus
<p>

A state judge is now deciding how to appraise the value of the
Connecticut Yankee nuclear power plant, which is operated in the town
of Haddam by Northeast Utilities.  NU sued the town in 1992, saying it
was overassessed from 1991 to 1994.  "Since the case went to trial
this winter, both sides have acknowledged mistakes in their
assessments of the power plant."  The plant's value was originally
assessed by the town at $840 million, but NU insists the value is $235
million.  The town in 1995 revised its assessment to $423 million in a
move that caused local property tax revenues to plummet.
<p>

"Both sides do agree on one point -- that the plant will operate until
2007 and then shut down," the HARTFORD COURANT reports.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"AN AGENCY THAT'S GOT TO GO"</b><br>
WALL STREET JOURNAL, 4/9/96, p. A19,</i><br>
Sen. Rod Grams (R-MN), Op-Ed
<p>

Almost 20 years after the US Dept. of Energy was created to deal with
a perceived energy crisis, the agency has become "a bureaucracy
without equal ... without a focused mission," writes Sen. Rod Grams
(R- MN), a member of the Senate Energy and Natural Resources Cmte.
For example, much of the agency's budget goes toward overseeing the
nation's nuclear waste.  But "unfortunately, the waste problem -- one
of the DOE's primary missions -- has become its primary failure,"
Grams writes.
<p>

Twenty-six nuclear power plants nationwide will run out of storage
space for spent nuclear fuel by 1998, the year DOE is required by law
to begin storing such wastes at an interim facility.  The DOE has had
14 years to prepare such a site but none has even been selected, "and
a permanent storage facility is no more than a pipe dream."
Meanwhile, electric ratepayers have paid $11 billion into a trust fund
for the permanent facility, with "little progress" to show for it.
<p>

Concerning the DOE's other missions, "we have little but pork" to show
for its alternative-energy research; energy conservation is less
important since oil, coal and natural gas reserves have all increased;
and energy imports are up.  And the agency is mired in management
problems.  "Americans are no longer willing to foot the bill for a
bloated, cumbersome agency that has outlived its usefulness," Grams
concludes.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... The US Nuclear Regulatory Commission "wants to know why it took
Niagara Mohawk Power Corp. more than a year to replace the wrong-size
bolts on panels" at the Nine Mile Point 1 nuclear power plant.  NRC
and utility officials will meet on Friday to discuss four "apparent
violations," an NRC spokeswoman said (NEW YORK TIMES, 4/10/96, p. B4,
Associated Press).


</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
