<html><head><title>Nuke News, 9/4/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 9/4/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.05.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"NRC IS THREATENING TO REVOKE LICENSE FOR NORTHEAST UTILITIES' NUCLEAR REACTOR"</b><br>
WALL STREET JOURNAL, 4/8/96, p. A12B</i><br>
Ross Kerber
<p>

Northeast Utilities yesterday was required to prove to the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission that its Connecticut Yankee plant in Haddam
Neck, CT is safe to operate.  "Otherwise, the agency may order that
plant off- line."
<p>

Northeast Utilities has been plagued with problems at a number of its
nuclear power plants around New England.  The NRC recently ordered
three reactors at its Waterford, CT-based Millstone nuclear power
station closed, pending a safety investigation.
<p>

Analysts say NU's nuclear "woes" could hurt the company financially.
Stephen Mahoney, pres. of the Boston-based energy and utilities
consulting company Devonrue Ltd.: "They've been spending at a heavy
clip on Millstone Units 1 and 2, and at this pace it's going to start
adding up."
<p>

NU officials estimate that the cost of replacement power could run as
high as $9 million per month.  But Dan Scotto, a utilities analyst at
New York-based Bear, Stearns &amp; Co., said that the costs of replacement
power could be as much as $30 million to $50 million more than NU's
estimates.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Rating Agency Gives Northeast Utilities Warning on Credit,"
       NEW YORK TIMES, 4/9/96, p. B2, George Judson.  The US Nuclear
       Regulatory Commission's "scrutiny" of Northeast Utilities'
       Millstone nuclear power plant has prompted Standard &amp; Poor's to
       put NU on the rating service's watch list.  Raymond Leung, an
       S&amp;P analyst, said the cost of replacement power and repairs to
       the Millstone reactors "is slowing the company's repayment of
       debt" and further unanticipated costs "could result in a credit
       downgrading."
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"STUCK FUEL RODS SAFELY DISLODGED" </b><br>
WASHINGTON POST, 4/8/96, p. A4</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

Workers on Sunday "carefully dislodged" a 1,500-pound bundle of
uranium fuel rods from the bottom of the reactor core at the Palo
Verde Nuclear Generating Station in Phoenix, AZ without releasing any
radiation.
<p>

The procedure was conducted under 50 feet of water using equipment
attached to a long pole and operated by workers on a bridge above.
The reactor has be down since the problem was discovered during a
routine refueling operation on March 16.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "News Briefs," CHRISTIAN SCIENCE MONITOR, 4/9/96, p. 2, Staff
       Report.
  <li> "Repair is Completed Safely at Nuclear Plant," BALTIMORE
       SUN, 4/8/96, p. 2A, Staff Report.
  <li> "In the News," WALL STREET JOURNAL, 4/8/96, p. A1, Staff
       Report.
  <li> "Fuel Bundle Dislodged Safely at Ariz. Plant," USA
       TODAY, 4/8/96, p. 4A, Staff Report.
  <li> "Removal of Stuck Fuel at Nuclear Plant Delayed," DALLAS
       MORNING NEWS, 4/6/96, p. 30A, Associated Press.
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"UTILITIES STOCKS HIT HARD BY SURGE IN INTEREST RATES IN FIRST QUARTER"</b><br>
BALTIMORE SUN, 4/7/96, p. 5E</i><br>
New York Times News Service
<p>
     
"Hit by the same surge in interest rates that briefly sent the stock
market reeling," utility funds were among the "poorest- performing"
mutual funds in the first quarter of 1996.  Analysts fear that another
increase could further hurt the sector.  Utilities are sensitive to
changes in interest rates because they borrow heavily to finance their
operations, and "because their yields compete with bonds on yield."
<p>

Although utility funds finished the quarter "virtually where they
started in part due to other holdings that provided a buffer,
"disappointed" investors continue to pull money out of the funds.  And
"in a sign of just how out of favor the category is," the Dreyfus
Corp.  announced that it would liquidate its 5- year-old Edison
Electric Index Fund this month.
<p>

Standard &amp; Poor's Jane Collin: "This industry is changing rapidly,
and lots of opportunities are opening up for electric utilities, but
there's no question about it -- they still follow interest rates, and
when rates go up, stock prices fall."
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Safe Widow and Orphan Utility Stocks May Be History," 
       LOS ANGELES TIMES, 4/7/96, p. D1, Tom Petruno.
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"FPL REORGANIZING, MAY CUT 120 JOBS" </b><br>
MIAMI HERALD, 4/6/96, p. 8B</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

Florida Power &amp; Light is reorganizing its nuclear division.  The
move was prompted by "several mishaps" last year at its St. Lucie
nuclear plant.  FPL, the state's largest utility, is carrying out a
three-month review of its nuclear operations and estimates that as
many as 120 jobs could be eliminated.
<p>

Last November, FPL was fined $50,000 by the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission for having "inoperable" equipment and failing to conduct
proper testing at its St. Lucie plant.  Last week the NRC fined the
utility another $50,000 for violating federal safety rules at St.
Lucie in January.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> ORLANDO SENTINEL, 4/6/96, p. B8, Staff Report.
</ul>
     

</td>
</tr>
</table>
