<html><head><title>Nuke News, 5/4/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 5/4/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.04.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"THE NUCLEAR STOCKPILE AMERICA NEEDS"</b><br>
NEW YORK TIMES, 4/5/96, p. A27</i><br>
Peter Crane, Op-ed
<p>

The stockpiling of potassium iodide -- "a cheap and effective drug
that protects the thyroid from exposure to radioactivity" -- is
"standard practice" in most industrial nations, but not the United
States, writes Peter Crane, a lawyer with the US Nuclear Regulatory
Commission.  After initially favoring creation of regional stockpiles,
the Federal Emergency Management Agency and NRC dropped the idea in
1985, saying stockpiles are not needed because nuclear accidents are
rare and thyroid disease is "easy" to treat.
<p>

In the latest chapter of the debate, the NRC in 1994 considered
whether to purchase stockpiles and distribute them to the states.
"But representatives of the nuclear power industry contended any
change in policy could affect 'public confidence in the technology.'"
The commission failed, on a 2-2 tie vote, to approve the new policy.
<p>

Noting the rash of thyroid cancer in children and adults near the
damaged Chernobyl reactor in Ukraine, Crane concludes: "If the day
ever comes that American children suffer" because of inaction on this
issue, "what will officials say to their parents?"

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"U.S. CITES 3D REACTOR FOR FLAWS IN ITS DESIGN"</b><br>
NEW YORK TIMES, 4/5/96, p. B6</i><br>
Matthew Wald
<p>

The US Nuclear Regulatory Commission said yesterday it had found
design flaws at the Millstone 3 nuclear power plant in Waterford, CT,
"less than a month after it ordered the other two Millstone plants to
stay shut until their safety could be assured."  The NRC "said the
problems were so serious that it had asked the plant's owner,
Northeast Utilities, to give it information to determine whether" the
plant's license should be revoked or modified.  All three plants were
put on the agency's "watch list" on January 31.
<p>

Millstone 3 is already off-line for "routine" maintenance, but the
commission's order "essentially prevents the utility from reopening
the plant until it addresses 'substantial questions'" about its
operations.
<p>

Company spokesman Anthony Castagno said, "We're really confident that
Millstone 3's analysis will move along more quickly than either
Millstone 1 or 2."  Castagno said the company could get along without
the three plants for a few weeks, "but that it could run into trouble"
by summer, when air conditioners begin to boost demand for
electricity. The plant's problems involve backup cooling pumps and
electronic devices that transmit information from the containment
building to the control room.
     

</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
