<html><head><title>Nuke News, 3/4/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 3/4/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.04.02.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... Uranium prices have more than doubled in the last year due a
worldwide increase in the use of nuclear power and depressed Russian
output.  The price of one pound of yellowcake, which is refined into
uranium, went from $7.25 in March 1995 to $15.50 today (JOURNAL OF
COMMERCE, 4/3/96, p. 5B, Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... Vermont Electric Cooperative filed for bankruptcy protection,
falling victim to debts from nuclear power projects that were never
built (USA TODAY, 4/2/96, p. 11A, Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... Japan's "long-cherished dream of generating a steady supply of 
electricity from plutonium" won't die, despite cost overruns, a 
reactor accident, and plenty of local and international criticism, the 
WALL STREET JOURNAL reports in a lengthy feature (4/3/96, p. A11, 
David Hamilton).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Palo Verde Fuel-Removal Try Set"</b><br>
JOURNAL OF COMMERCE, 4/3/96, p. 7B</i><br>
Walter Berry
<p>

Nuclear energy experts are trying to figure out how to remove a
1,500-pound uranium "fuel bundle" stuck in a reactor at the Palo Verde
Nuclear Generating Station without damaging one or more of its 236
fuel rods.

<p>

A damaged fuel rod could potentially release radioactive iodine,
krypton and xenon gas into the containment building and drop spent
uranium fuel pellets into the bottom of the reactor.  If such an
accident were to occur, it would require a costly cleanup that could
lead to an increase in electricity rates for the plant's four million
customers across four states.
<p>

The problem was discovered on March 22 when one of 241 fuel bundles
could not be lifted out of the reactor during a routine refueling
operation.  Six Nuclear Regulatory Commission inspectors and 50 plant
officials have been working round-the- clock on the problem since
Sunday.  The experts plan to use remote-controlled hydraulic jacks to
push up the bundle and lower a sling-like metal structure over it.  A
pair of hooks would then be used to secure and hoist the bundle.
<p>

Arizona Public Service Co. partly owns and operates the $9.3 billion
reactor, located 55 miles west of Phoenix.  Other stake- holders
include El Paso Electric Co., Southern California Edison and the
Public Service Co. of New Mexico.  SEE ALSO: "Nuclear Problem," USA
TODAY, 4/3/96, p. 3A, Staff Report.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Hope Creek Nuclear Plant is Restarted" </b><br>
PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER, 4/3/96, p. B2</i><br>
Douglas Campbell
<p>

The Hope Creek nuclear power plant is back at "full throttle" after a
four-month hiatus, and the "troubled" Salem 2 reactor "will return to
service in August, a month earlier than planned."
<p>

Public Service Electric &amp; Gas Co. said it is considering its
options on a third plant, Salem 1, which has "microscopic cracks" in
its steam-generator system.  Replacing the steam generator could take
until 1997 and cost about $150 million, said company spokesman Neil
Brown.
<p>

At Hope Creek, air vents that had been installed backward -- which in
an emergency could have allowed radioactive air to escape -- were
turned around, and the unit returned to full power on March 25.
<p>

All three plants "have been idled by various mechanical and safety
problems 32 times in the last three years."  Salem 1 has produced no
power since May 1995 and Salem 2 since June 1995.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"In A-Plants' Backyard in Connecticut, Trust Ebbs" </b><br>
NEW YORK TIMES, 4/3/96, p. A1</i><br>
George Judson
<p>

Allegations that operators at Northeast Utilities' Millstone reactors
"skimped on safety to cut costs" are forcing local residents in
Waterford and East Lyme, CT to reexamine their comfort level
concerning nuclear power.
<p>

Confidence in the Millstone reactors remains high, but it is
increasingly "based on faith in the friends and neighbors who work"
there, rather than trust in Northeast Utilities or the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission.  David Cini, First Selectman of East Lyme: "I
know people at Millstone, and I believe that the hundreds of people
who work there all want to be safe."
<p>

But safety questions have impacted local perceptions.  Waterford First
Selectman Tony Sheridan: "It's not a panic, but there is a concern
that wasn't here a year ago.  Most people are generous with their
trust, but once you lose it, it's lost."  For instance, the Citizens
Regulatory Commission, a local watchdog group, has already begun to
question the feasibility of evacuation plans and the plants'
protection from such disasters as earthquakes and hurricanes.

<b><center>FIRST SIGHTINGS OF A TRUST DIVIDE</center></b>

This kind of "stark divide" between those who are alarmed and those
who feel reassured "is typical" when people confront risks from
radiation and other invisible threats to health, sociologists say.
Kai Erikson of Yale U.: "Having invested a great deal of faith in one
institution ... and having come to feel that they haven't been treated
fairly by it, people begin to have questions about almost
everything. The whole world seems less reliable." 4/2).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Regulators Probe Cooper Plant For Possible Safety Violations"</b><br>
OMAHA WORLD-HERALD, 3/30/96, p. 13</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

The Nuclear Regulatory Commission said on March 29 that it was looking
into further apparent safety violations discovered in February at the
Cooper Nuclear Station in Brownville, Nebraska.  One of the alleged
violations involves a "blowout panel" which is supposed to protect the
reactor containment building in case of a main steam-line rupture,
said NRC spokesman Mark Hammond.  In 1985, the blowout panels were
reinforced with fiberglass -- meant to stop air leaks -- but possibly
prevented the panels from working properly.
<p>

Noreen Thomas, spokeswoman for the Nebraska Public Power District,
which owns the plant, disagreed with the NRC, saying that the
equipment would have performed "as it was designed."
<p>

The station was shut down from April 1994 to early 1995 due to safety
violations involving the plant's emergency diesel generators.
However, the NRC last August issued a performance report indicating
that improvements at the plant had been made.


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"The Benefits of Nuclear Power"</b><br>
ST. LOUIS POST-DISPATCH, 4/1/96</i><br>
Stanford Levin, Op-Ed
<p>

The author, a professor of economics at Southern Illinois University
and former commissioner of the Illinois Commerce Commission, notes
that in the emerging competitive power market, "nuclear power will be
one of the least expensive sources of electricity."  And "as a nation,
we cannot afford to rule out any economic options for producing
electricity."
<p>

Levin reviews the cost competitiveness of nuclear versus coal and
renewable energy sources, and notes many plants are performing at
"remarkable" levels of output and efficiency.
<p>

An "important area for cost reduction is the regulatory process,"
Levin writes.  Current NRC regulations are overly prescriptive,
unprioritized and focused on "processes and procedures instead of
results."  In contrast, a performance-based system giving plant
operators "basic" requirements and flexibility in deciding how to meet
them, "promises substantial cost savings."
<p>

"Despite the continuing nuclear-waste disposal problem, which Congress
and the administration have so far not addressed,... we can make
progress with a pragmatic policy.  Economics, not ideology, should
guide our planning, Levin concludes.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Don't Spread Radioactive Waste," ST. LOUIS POST- DISPATCH,
       4/1/96, Don Fitz, which is accompanied by an image of the
       radioactive-hazard symbol and a skull and crossbones.  Fitz,
       editor a book about dioxin and a member of the Missouri Green
       Party, argues against a DOE proposal to truck high-level
       nuclear waste through the Midwest to a final burial site in
       Nevada.  Fitz argues the process would be unsafe in many ways,
       and concludes not only that nuclear waste "should be left where
       it is," but also that "all" nuclear power plants should be shut
       down.
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"O'Leary Outlines Yucca Timetable"</b><br>
LAS VEGAS REVIEW-JOURNAL, 3/30/96, p. 3A</i><br>
Tony Batt
<p>

Energy Sec'y Hazel O'Leary on March 29 told the House Appropriations
Energy and Water Subcommittee that the government will not know before
1998 whether it can safely store nuclear waste at Yucca Mountain in
Nevada.  This follows an earlier meeting between the House panel and
the Energy Dept.'s Daniel Dreyfus in which Dreyfus said that he is
confident Yucca Mountain will be found viable in 1998 as a nuclear
repository.
<p>

Subcommittee chairman Rep. John Myers (R-IN) "reminded O'Leary that
Congress has a responsibility to nuclear power utilities 'that you
once represented' to take possession of the waste by 1998."  O'Leary
responded, saying it would be shortsighted to move legislation for an
interim storage facility before the Energy Dept. makes its finding in
1998.  "Such a move might answer the needs of a few utilities that
have run out of storage space, she said, but it would risk the
development of a permanent repository for all utilities."

</td>
</tr>
</table>
