<html><head><title>Nuke News, 2/4/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 2/4/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.29.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"NRC Charges Maine Yankee With Three Safety Violations"</b><br>
BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 4/2/96</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

Officials at the Maine Yankee nuclear power plant in Wiscasset, ME are
"focusing on improving employee safety" since the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission charged them with three violations last month.  Radioactive
gas was released on February 29, exposing 16 workers to radiation
"well below federal limits." But the accident was "another failure" of
personnel to follow prescribed work methods, the NRC said.
<p>

A Maine Yankee spokeswoman said a new job-hazard training program is
underway at the plant, and an employee review board has been convened
to seek other ways to improve safety measures. Plant officials will
report to NRC staff at a meeting in Philadelphia on April 25.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"High Hanford Radiation Exposure Cut"</b><br>
SEATTLE POST-INTELLIGENCER, 3/29/96, p. C10</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

Relatively high levels of radiation exposure have decreased 670ver
three years at the Washington Public Power Supply System, due in part
to a shift in the way "hot spots" at the plant's No. 2 reactor are
cleaned, according to plant radiation protection manager John Albers.
In 1993, plant workers received a monthly average of 21.5 rems of
radiation.  Early this year, that figure was down to 7.3 rems.
<p>

WPPSS improved the exposure problem by having employees cast lead
shields to fit around leaking pipes and valves, cutting down their
radiation exposure time.  No worker's health was threatened by the
exposure levels, but the Nuclear Regulatory Commission saw it as a
sign of a "sloppily run" plant.  "Now, worker exposure is taken into
account when decisions are made as to what will be cleaned and what
will be left alone."
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"NRC Dismisses Allegations Against Entergy"</b><br>
SATURDAY STATE TIMES/MORNING ADVOCATE, 3/30/96, p. 3B</i><br>
James Minton
<p>

The US Nuclear Regulatory Commission last week dismissed allegations
that Entergy Operations Inc. retaliated against an employee
"whistle-blower" working at the River Bend nuclear power plant in
Louisiana.  The decision by the NRC's regional office runs counter to
conclusions of the NRC's Office of Investigation announced in December
1995.  NRC regional administrator L.J. Callan said that the staff
reached their decision after consulting with the director of the
Office of Investigation.
<p>

The NRC's initial concern was that the employee's job performance
ranking was inconsistent with earlier evaluations.  However, EOI
representatives met with NRC regional officials in February to present
their case, and convinced the NRC staff that the company would have
taken the same action against the employee even if he had not raised
safety concerns.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Plutonium Eyed for Power Plants"</b><br>
TORONTO GLOBE &amp; MAIL, 4/1/96, p. A1</i><br>
Jeff Sallot
<p>

"The Canadian government is backing a plan to use plutonium from
surplus warheads as a fuel in nuclear power reactors," according to
federal sources.  Prime Minister Jean Chretien will politically
support the proposal later this month when he meets with US President
Bill Clinton, Russian President Boris Yeltsin and others at a nuclear
safety summit in Moscow, "senior government sources" said.
<p>

No final decisions are expected at the summit.  Many plans to use
plutonium -- including one to use Ontario Hydro's Bruce A reactor --
face several political struggles in Canada and abroad.
<p>

The "ailing" nuclear industry in Canada "strongly supports" the
proposal, believing that it would showcase their technology. If the
plan is approved, several reactors could receive a much- needed boost,
including the Bruce A reactor, which has not been in use because
Ontario Hydro has excess generating capacity.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... Officials at the Palo Verde Nuclear Generating Station in 
Arizona -- the largest nuclear power plant in the nation -- are 
"trying to figure out" how to remove fuel rods that are stuck in the 
reactor without releasing radioactive gas.  No radiation has been 
released since the problem was discovered on March 22 (DALLAS MORNING 
NEWS, 4/1/96, p. 22A, Associated Press).  The problem is also reported 
in this morning's USA TODAY (p. 3A, Staff Report) and CHRISTIAN 
SCIENCE MONITOR (p. 2, Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... Northeast Utilities said CEO Bernard Fox's pay will be cut 
$82,000 unless the company's Millstone nuclear plants improve their 
safety records (USA TODAY, 4/1/96, p. 12A, Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... Six workers at Virginia Power's North Anna nuclear plant 
suffered heart problems during recent refueling of the company's 
reactors, raising concerns about stress on workers from 72-hour 
workweeks (RICHMOND TIMES-DISPATCH, 3/30/96, p. A1, Michael Martz).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
... Florida Power &amp; Light Co. has agreed to pay a $50,000 fine
for allegedly violating a federal safety requirement at the St. Lucie 
nuclear power plant on Hutchinson Island.  The event did not 
compromise plant safety, but NRC spokesman Roger Hannah said the 
incident suggested a lack of attention to detail by plant operators 
(FT. LAUDERDALE SUN-SENTINEL, 3/30/96, p. 20A, Warren Richey).

</td>
</tr>
</table>
