<html><head><title>Nuke News, 29/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 29/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.28.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

.. "There is no direct link" between radiation and the "high" rate of 
infant leukemia near the Sellafield nuclear power plant in England, a 
government panel said yesterday (FINANCIAL TIMES, 3/29/96, p. 9, James 
Harding).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Austin Ends Testimony in Nuke Trial With Expert" </b><br>
AUSTIN AMERICAN-STATESMAN, 3/26/96, p. B6</i><br>
Matt Schwartz
<p>

The city of Austin, TX on March 25 rested its case against Houston
Lighting &amp; Power with the testimony of Bart Withers, a former
manager of the Wolf Creek nuclear power plant and former head of the
Institute of Nuclear Power Operations.  The city is suing HL&amp;P for
negligence, charging the utility's mismanagement of its South Texas
Project nuclear plant led to a 14-month shutdown in 1993 and costs to
Austin totaling $120 million.
<p>

Basing his claims on documents from the Nuclear Regulatory Commission,
HL&amp;P, and INPO, Withers testified that HL&amp;P had mismanaged the
South Texas Project in 1990, 1991 and 1992, and that it "repeatedly
failed to fix things it had promised to correct."
<p>

HL&amp;P lawyer David Beck accused Withers himself of mismanaging the
Wolf Creek plant he once worked for, citing NRC ratings for Wolf Creek
below those of HL&amp;P.  Withers admitted under questioning that NRC
reports tend to focus on problems rather than compliments, and that
selectively chosen INPO standards could indict "even a well-run
plant."
<p>

But Withers later pointed to HL&amp;P documents in which managers 
state that the utility must repair its reputation with the NRC.
     

</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
