<html><head><title>Nuke News, 28/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 28/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.27.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"Conflicts Flare Up Amid Rush to Adjourn; Dispute Over Money Ties Up Bill to Solve Nuclear Waste Issue"</b><br>
MINNEAPOLIS STAR-TRIBUNE, 3/27/96, p. B1</i><br>
Robert Whereatt
<p>

A proposal in the Minnesota legislature to halt the search for a new
nuclear-waste disposal site and compensate Indians living next to the
existing site "melted down" on Tuesday after lawmakers decided to
force Northern States Power Co. to foot $10 million of the total cost.
<p>

Under a previous agreement, NSP had agreed to pay the Prairie Island
Dakota tribe $2 million as compensation for living next to an
above-ground storage site for spent nuclear fuel. Sen. Steven Novak
(D), the bill sponsor, then proposed having the state contribute $8
million. But after some lawmakers questioned why the state should pick
up the larger share of the costs, the language was changed to require
a $10 million contribution from NSP, leading NSP Vice President Tom
Micheletti to say: "The package now does not make any sense to
us."
<p>

In response to the controversy, Senate Enviroment Committee Chairman
Bob Lessard (D) said he will not raise the issue again in the
session's final days, "dashing hopes that this emotional environmental
issue will be resolved this year."  Novak said the proposal was "all
but dead."  A 1994 mandate requiring the state and NSP to locate an
alternative site will remain on the books.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Public Service Decommissions Plant; Fort St. Vrain First to Complete Removal of Radioactive Material"</b><br>
DENVER ROCKY MOUNTAIN NEWS, 3/23/96, p. 49A</i><br>
John Rebchook
<p>

Colorado's Public Service Co., the state's largest gas and electric
utility, announced on March 22 that it is the first utility in the
nation to physically decommission a long-term operating, commercial-
sized nuclear power plant.  Most of the removal of low-level
radioactive material was completed in February, and the final release
survey should be completed in August, allowing the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission to release PSC from its nuclear operating license by the
end of the year.
<p>

PSC's vice president, A. Clegg Crawford: "This marks a significant
milestone, not just for Public Service Co. of Colorado, but for the
entire nuclear industry.  We have shown the world that a nuclear power
plant can be successfully decommissioned, both from a technical and
financial standpoint."
<p>

The Fort St. Vrain plant will be repowered to use natural gas and will
generate electricity beginning in May.  PSC spokesman Mark Stutz said
that the company may be able to serve as a consultant or technical
expert to some 119 other nuclear reactors that face shutdown in the
next decade or two.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... Duke Engineering and Services Inc., a subsidiary of Charlotte, NC- 
based Duke Power Co., will buy the nuclear engineering and services 
businesses of California-based Vectra technologies for $27.5 million 
in cash (NEW YORK TIMES, 3/28/96, p. D4, Bloomberg Business News).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... A group of utility companies has filed a plan to resolve Cajun 
Electric Power Cooperative's bankruptcy and cut electricity bills for 
1 million customers in Louisiana by up to 25%. Southwestern Electric 
Power Co.  Under the plan, SWEPCO would buy Cajun's coal- and 
natural-gas- fired power plants, but not cajun's 30hare of the 
River bend nuclear power plant (BATON ROUGE STATE TIMES/MORNING 
ADVOCATE, 3/23/96, p. 1A, Randy McClain).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... The Fort McDermitt Paiute-Shoshone Indian Tribe in Nevada has 
dropped its efforts to host a temporary nuclear-waste-storage facility 
(LAS VEGAS REVIEW-JOURNAL, 3/23/96, p. 4B, Associated Press).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... South China's Guangdong province hopes to put 8-10 more nuclear 
reactors on-line by 2010, officials announced yesterday (JOURNAL OF 
COMMERCE, 3/28/96, p. 7B, Benjamin Kang Lim).


</td>
</tr>
