<html><head><title>Nuke News, 26/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 26/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.25.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... The Canadian federal government on March 21 proposed a Nuclear
Safety and Control Act, which would raise penalties for violations
from C$10,000 to C$1 million, force utilities to cover decommissioning
costs, and rename the Atomic Energy Control Board as the Canadian
Nuclear Safety Commission.  The commission would be authorized to
order nuclear plants to correct hazardous situations and bear any
related costs (TORONTO GLOBE &amp; MAIL, 3/22/96, p. B2, Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... The British government yesterday pledged $352 million of public
money to help pay the costs of decommissioning nuclear power plants
after privatization.  The move "reversed" the government's previous
stand and "is understood to have salvaged" the privatization plan
(FINANCIAL TIMES, 3/26/96, p. 9, Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Former Federal Regulators on NU Payroll"</b><br>
HARTFORD COURANT, 3/25/96, p. 1</i><br>
Mike McIntire
<p>

Northeast Utilities has "tapped" several former federal regulators to
help the company as it "grapple's" with problems at its nuclear
plants."  Most recently, former US Nuclear Regulatory Commission
member E. Gail DePlanque was asked to join NU's board. NU Chairman
Bernard Fox said that DePlanque was hired because the company wanted
another nuclear energy expert.  Other ex-regulators who have been
hired by NU include: -- Thomas Murley, a retired NRC director of
nuclear reactor regulation.  Murley was paid $63,000 in 1994 for
"outside services," and works as a consultant for other utilities;
<ul>
  <li> James Partlow, a retired NRC director of reactor inspection and
       safeguards.  Partlow was hired to investigate safety concerns
       raised by a Millstone power station whistleblower.  Partlow
       died in 1995; and
       <p>

  <li> James Curtiss, a retired NRC commissioner.  The Washington-
       based law firm of Winston &amp; Strawn -- which represented NU
       in a 1991 NRC investigation -- hired Curtiss as a partner after
       his retirement in June 1993.
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"N-Plant Concerns Navajos"</b><br>
TUCSON DAILY STAR, 3/24/96</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

"Residents of the Navajo Reservation expressed concern that tribe
officials were considering allowing a nuclear power plant and waste
storage site to be built on their land."  Navajo Nation Vice President
Thomas Atcitty said that Navajo officials are currently educating
themselves on the issue of nuclear energy and have not committed to
either project.
<p>

Navajo Nation Council Delegate Eula Yazzie: "It sure isn't going to be
in my area, I can tell you that."  Another delegate, Freddie Howard:
"I don't think there is a need for nuclear power.  I think the area is
saturated with power - there's four power plants surrounding the
reservation."
     


</td>
</tr>
</table>
