<html><head><title>Nuke News, 25/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 25/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.22.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... Public Service Co. of Colorado announced that it completed the 
decommissioning work at its nuclear power plant, the Fort St. Vrain 
Generating Station, for less than the $189 million that had been 
budgeted.  The utility said it plans to complete the final site survey 
of the plant and the surrounding areas for possible contamination by 
August (WALL STREET JOURNAL, 3/25/96, p.B9, Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Bill Seeks Choice of Power Provider"</b><br>
CLEVELAND PLAIN DEALER, 3/22/96, C1</i><br>
Vindu Goel
<p>

Ohio state Rep. Ronald Amstutz introduced a bill on 3/21 to allow Ohio
consumers, who pay some of the highest electric rates in the nation,
to choose their electricity supplier.  About a dozen key lawmakers
have co-sponsored the bill.  But Amstutz does not expect the bill to
pass this session.
<p>

"Essentially, the bill would repeal the exclusive rights electric
utilities such as Cleveland Electric Illuminating Co. and Ohio Edison
now have to serve a particular area."  The hope is that companies will
be forced to compete for customers and thus lower their prices.
<p>

Obstacles to the deregulation process include the state property- tax
system, which supports schools through electricity taxes, and possible
stranded costs from several multibillion- dollar nuclear-power
investments made by some companies.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"In Tenn., Latest Nuclear Power Plant Epitomizes Industry's Rise and Fall"</b><br>
PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER, 3/24/96, p. A3</i><br>
Jeffrey Fleishman
<p>

The story of the Watts Bar power plant "is the story of the nuclear
industry."  After 23 years of troubles, the Tennessee Valley
Authority's Watts Bar nuclear reactor, the nation's last nuclear
plant, this spring will begin operating at full speed. But the plant
still faces attacks from employees and scientists "who contend the
plant is too dangerous to open."
<p>

Critics say that with the construction costs of Watts Bar adding up to
$6.8 billion -- 1,600% the original estimation of $370 million -- the
plant will never compensate for its overruns. TVA, which has been a
mainstay for the nuclear industry, faces a threatened future because
of the tremendous debts it has created investing in nuclear projects.
And scientists and economists argue that it is TVA's ratepayers who
will pay for investments like the Watts Bar.



</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
