<html><head><title>Nuke News, 22/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 22/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.21.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"Hearing to Probe BGE Labor Practices"</b><br>
BALTIMORE SUN, 3/22/96, p. C1</i><br>
Kevin McQuaid
<p>

"The National Labor Relations Board has lodged a complaint against
Baltimore Gas &amp; Electric Co. and intends to hold a hearing" on
charges brought by the union attempting to organize BGE's employees.
The action responds to the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers' claims that BGE is "harassing" employees engaged in union
activities at its nuclear power plants.  Some employees were "fired,
demoted or feared company reprisals" for being involved in union
organizing, according to the union.
<p>

Kathleen Nolan, a BGE spokeswoman, said the utility "welcomes" the
hearing.  Nolan: "We don't believe there is any merit to these
charges. This is a common union tactic, and we're not going to be
intimidated by it."
<p>

The new developments "mark the latest in heightening tensions between
the utility and the union," which also represents 2,700 employees of
Potomac Electric Power Co., with whom BGE plans to merge.  BGE has
always been nonunion and "hopes employees will reject union
representation."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Legislators Want Answers From Northeast Utilities Boss"</b><br>
AP/BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 3/21/96</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

Leaders of the Connecticut House Energy and Public Utilities Committee
sent a letter this week to the president of Northeast Utilities,
Bernard Fox, inviting him to appear before the panel and explain NU's
policy regarding whistleblowers and replacement power costs due to
shutdowns at the Millstone nuclear power complex.
<p>

Among the questions in the letter, the reps asked what specific
remedies were being taken to "repair the damage that has been done to
NU's credibility."  Also: "To your knowledge, has there ever been an
attempt to mislead public officials, regulators, your employees, your
employers regarding the operation of NU's nuclear facilities?"
<p>

"NU spokesman Anthony Castagno said Fox will respond to the committee
members' questions and also will appear at the panel's convenience."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"CMP Shareholders to Vote on Selling Maine Yankee"</b><br>
BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 3/20/96</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

Central Maine Power Co. shareholders will vote in May on whether the
company should divest itself from the Maine Yankee nuclear power
plant, which was shut down last year for major repairs.  William
Linnell, an anti-nuclear activist and sponsor of the resolution, says
the company should drop all investments in Maine Yankee by the end of
1996, "citing high maintenance costs and dangers of nuclear power."
Linnell: "Maine Yankee's best days are gone.  CMP shareholders would
be wise to dump this plant now."
<p>

But CMP spokesman Mark Ishkanian said the motion is "ill- considered"
and "unlikely" to pass.
<p>

Last spring, company officials discovered extensive cracks in the
plant's stem generator tubes, requiring a shutdown and a "massive,"
$30 million repair project.  The Nuclear Regulatory Commission has
allowed the plant to return to 900f full power while it investigates
remaining safety issues.
<p>

CMP's Ishkanian said, "Maine Yankee is a very beneficial resource for
us, and while it was down most of 1995, it is back and running.  If
its past reliability was any measure of the future, it will be a
significant contributor."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Utilities Deregulation Would Be a Bigger Ripoff Than the S&amp;Ls"</b><br>
MINNEAPOLIS STAR TRIBUNE, 3/21/96, p. A22</i><br>
Molly Ivins
<p>

Nationally syndicated columnist Molly Ivins criticized Sen. J.
Bennett Johnston's (D-LA) bill to "preempt state experiments in
utility deregulation."  She wrote that although some states
wish to pursue wholesale competition in the electric industry, the
Johnston bill would require all states to opt for retail competition,
which is what big industrial power users such as Dow Chemical or
General Motors want. "They want to be able to go around the utilities
and directly to generators of electricity and cut themselves the best
deal they can."
<p>

Ivins also criticized the Johnston bill for allowing utilities to
recover 1000f their stranded assets.  Companies that invested in
costly projects such as the South Texas Nuclear Project would "get to
project stranded costs out over the entire projected life of
the plant and get paid for that too. Presto!  The largest public
bailout of a private industry in history."
<p>

Matthew Freedman of the Public Citizen consumer organization Critical
Mass Energy Project, contemplated the scope of "this rip-off," saying:
"It is just major.  Major.  Major."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>



<i><b>"Panel Finds No Reason to Rush Storage Site Construction"</b><br>
S.F. EXAMINER/CHRONICLE Online, 3/20/96</i><br>
H. Josef Herbert, Associated Press
<p>

There is no scientific or safety reason to immediately build a
centralized spent-nuclear-fuel storage facility, the Nuclear Waste
Technical Review Board said on Wednesday.  The 11-member board,
created by Congress in 1987 to advise lawmakers and the Energy
Department on nuclear waste issues, said there likely will not be a
"serious crunch" for centralized storage until 2010, when reactors are
expected to begin shutting down in high numbers.
<p>

The board's report said the government should concentrate on
determining the suitability of the Yucca Mountain, NV site for a
permanent underground waste repository and then consider building a
temporary storage facility to serve interim needs.  Many nuclear plan
operators say they're running out of storage space for waste, but the
report "concluded that the situation is not nearly as urgent as the
nuclear industry suggests."
<p>

The nuclear industry criticized the board's findings and said the
panel had "strayed from its mandate" of providing scientific
evaluations and improperly was "becoming an advocate of policy instead
a defender of science."  Scott Northard of Northern States Power Co.
said a large- scale central facility for spent fuel needs to be
available "as soon as possible" to avoid some nuclear plants being
forced to shut down ahead of schedule.


</td>
</tr>
</table>
