<html><head><title>Nuke News, 21/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 21/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.20.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"Low-Level Nuclear Waste Facility Safe, Say Experts"</b><br>
ASBURY PARK NJ PRESS, 3/19/96</i><br>
Neil A. Sheehan
<p>

A low-level radioactive waste storage facility proposed for New Jersey
would pose "no more of a health risk than calling the Rocky Mountains
home," according to Arthur Upton, a professor of environmental and
community medicine at the University of Medicine and Dentistry of New
Jersey.  Upton's remarks came Monday at a conference sponsored by the
League of Women Voters, the League of Municipalities and Rutgers
University.
<p>

He said that residents near the facility would receive an added dose
of 25 millirems a year, which he said was an "acceptable risk."  But
people living in the Rockies already receive that much more from the
cosmic radiation from living at a higher elevation.
<p>

For the past year and a half, New Jersey has been trying to "entice" a
town into hosting a $100 million facility for storing the 17
tractor-trailer loads of low-level waste produced each year in the
state.  The state is willing to offer up to $3 million a year, plus
"several other incentives," but so far response has been "tepid."  New
Jersey currently exports its waste to Barnwell County, SC.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>



<i><b>"NU Starts Millstone Cleanup"</b><br>
HARTFORD COURANT, 3/19/96, p. F1</i><br>
Barbara A. Nagy
<p>

Northeast Utilities this week will begin cleaning up a radioactive-
waste storage area at its Millstone 1 nuclear power plant.  The
company the cleanup will exceed federal standards by installing a new
processing system that will reduce the plant's liquid radioactive
waste by two- thirds, according to Deborah Beauchamp, a company
spokeswoman.
<p>

Last week NU disclosed that rusting pipes in the plant have been
neglected for 10 or 15 years, and that several holding tanks were
leaking about 1.5 quarts a day of radioactive waste.  The federal
Nuclear Regulatory Commission is investigating, and the company
expects to be fined.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Budget Briefing"</b><br>
CONGRESS DAILY, 3/19/96, p. 3</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

Under Pres. Clinton's proposed budget for FY '97, which was released
on Tuesday, the Department of Energy would receive $16.3 billion,
"roughly the same as the current year funding."  Energy Secretary
Hazel O'Leary "touted the budget proposal as a $3 billion cut from FY
'93 levels and attributed it to better management of the department
under the Clinton administration."
<p>

The proposal would cut DOE's defense environmental management by 5% to
$5.4 billion.  Energy supply research would be increased by 5.3%,
general research by 2.7% and energy conservation research by 33%.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Minnick Wants New INEL Mission"</b><br>
Blackfoot ID MORNING NEWS, 3/13/96, p. A1</i><br>
Brian Lee
<p>

Idaho Democratic candidate Walt Minnick, who is seeking the US Senate
seat held by Republican Larry Craig, on March 13 said Congress should
make a new mission for the Idaho National Engineering Laboratory by
using it to pursue a new generation of nuclear power plants.
<p>

Minnick, the former CEO of the giant wood-products company TJ
International, suggested the Energy Dept. have INEL' nuclear
scientists develop a new reactor.  Minnick said he believes that
natural resources are finite and that nuclear energy is the best
alternative for cheap power.  While Minnick said he would push for a
nuclear energy project at INEL if elected to the Senate, he has
previously come out strongly against the storage of nuclear waste at
the site and has criticized ID Gov. Phil Batt's (R) agreement with the
DOE to store waste there.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>



<i><b>"Industry Funds Global-Warming Skeptics"</b><br>
WASHINGTON POST, 3/20/96, p. A8</i><br>
Gary Lee
<p>

The Washington, DC-based environmental group Ozone Action yesterday
charged that three researchers who are "outspoken critics" of the
scientific evidence that suggests that global warming is occurring
have received hundreds of thousands of dollars from the petroleum and
coal industries.  one of the scientists also receives regular funding
from the oil-rich government of Kuwait.
<p>

The researchers -- Arizona State University's Robert Balling,
University of Virginia's Patrick Michaels and Sherwood Idso of
Phoenix, AZ -- are frequently called to testify before congressional
panels and other public groups.  They have publicly asserted that if
global warming is occurring, it is caused by natural factors, not
human activity as many believe.

<center><h3>HOW MUCH AND FROM WHO?</h3></center>

Balling reportedly received up to $311,000 from the oil and coal
industries, as well as the Kuwaiti government.  A large portion of his
funding came from AZ-based Cyprus Minerals Co., an organization of
various petroleum and coal companies.  UVA's Michaels received about
$150,000 from such interests, including the Western Fuels Assn., "an
umbrella industry organization." Both men were invited two weeks ago
the "make their case" the House Science Committee, which wants to cut
federal funding for climate change research by 40%.
<p>

Idso, a physicist who works closely with Balling, "has received an
undisclosed amount of funding from oil, gas and utility sources,
according to Ozone Action."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... A temperature-resistant "super plastic" developed by the National 
Aeronautics and Space Administration will be used to coat metal and 
concrete pipes and other components of the Surry and North Anna 
nuclear power plants in Virginia, NASA said on Monday.  Virginia Power 
will provide the funding (RICHMOND TIMES- DISPATCH, 3/19/96, p. B4).


</td>
</tr>
