<html><head><title>Nuke News, 20/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 20/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.19.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... Eleven executives of PECO Energy Inc. sold nearly 200,000 shares 
earlier last month, "just before the company's stock price began 
sliding from its 52-week high.  A spokesman for the utility said the 
stock sales were all option-related and had "absolutely nothing" to do 
with the company's troubled Salem nuclear reactors (WALL STREET 
JOURNAL, 3/20/96, p. C15, Bridget O'Brian).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... "Workers violated radiation-control rules by removing contaminated 
tools from limited-access areas at Pennsylvania Power &amp; Light Co.'s 
Susquehanna nuclear power plant, the company said" (PHILADELPHIA 
INQUIRER, 3/20/96, p. C3, Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Was Therapy Used to Punish Nuclear Workers"</b><br>
WALL STREET JOURNAL, 3/20/96, p. B1</i><br>
Ross Kerber
<p>

"In a growing number of instances, nuclear workers say they are being
pressured to undergo psychological evaluations after raising safety
concerns," reports the WALL STREET JOURNAL.  In a growing number of
cases, workers get normal performance reviews "until they start
raising concerns.  "And management needs a way to discredit them,"
says Lynne Bernabei, a Washington attorney who has represented workers
in several harassment cases.
<p>

Psychological testing of nuclear-plant workers has become routine in
1990 and 1992 when the Nuclear Regulatory Commission instituted new
rules to address drug abuse and other behavioral problems.  They
required plant operators to monitor employees closely and offer
assistance programs when needed.
<p>

<center><b>CASES IN QUESTION</b></center>
<p>

Glenda Kay Miller, a security engineer at the Tennessee Valley
Authority's Browns Ferry nuclear plant, filed a complaint with the US
Labor Dept.  She was sent to company psychologists for questioning the
reliability of a proposed employee- identification system and last
August was fired on the grounds that she was unfit for duty.
<p>

Elsewhere, Labor Secretary Robert Rieich in January ordered Florida
Power &amp; Light Co. to rehire engineer Richard Robainas who said he
was fired after refusing to undergo a psychological evaluation.
Robainas had questioned the reliability of reactor pressure-monitoring
equipment at FPL's Turkey Point plant.  And the NRC is currently
investigating allegations that Northeast Utilities has routinely
harassed workers criticizing safety procedures, including sending them
to therapy and counseling. Robainas: "In certain societies, psychiatry
is used to curb dissent.  I think that's what is occurring here."
<p>

<center><b>CAN ANYTHING BE DONE?</b></center>
<p>

NRC officials say they are aware of allegations that utilities are
using the rules to harass whistle-blowers, but says it is difficult to
prove.  Officials also say that their top priority is investigating
the safety concerns raised; "accusations of improper referrals to
psychologists take less precedence."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>



<i><b>"Options for Managing N-Site to Be Outlined Tuesday"</b><br>
BUFFALO NEWS, 3/16/96, p. C5</i><br>
Bob Buyer
<p>

The Energy Dept. and West Valley Nuclear Service Co., a Westinghouse
subsidiary, planned to release on March 19 a draft environmental
impact statement on the cleanup of the 200-acre West Valley
Demonstration Project in New York.  The document is based on 40
volumes of data collected since 1980 and compiled by Reston, VA-based
Scientific Applications International Corp.
<p>

The environmental study was initiated when members of the West Valley
Coalition, a "citizens group," went to federal court and got the
government and Nuclear Service Co., the prime contractor in the
cleanup, to agree to do the study.  The West Valley properties are
jointly owned by DOE and the NY State Energy Research and Development
Authority.  The study looks at options for cleaning up the facilities
left behind when the former Nuclear Fuels Services Co. "abandoned" its
commercial fuel reprocessing business, leaving "600,000 gallons of
radioactive waste and radioactive buildings and ground."
<p>

Alternatives spelled out in the study range from doing nothing to
"scooping up the entire area and hauling the materials away."
Additional cleanup costs could go "as high as $8.3 billion."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Bataan Plant to Be Converted"</b><br>
FINANCIAL TIMES, 3/19/96</i><br>
Edward Luce
<p>

The Philippine government announced Monday that it would take
international bids on converting the "controversial" Bataan nuclear
power plant to a gas-fired station, ten years after the plant was
"moth- balled for safety reasons."  The decision came five months
after the government "struck" a $100 million out-of- court settlement
with Westinghouse, which allegedly overcharged the Philippines for the
$2.1 billion plant on a fault line.

</td>
