<html><head><title>Nuke News, 19/3/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 19/3/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.03.18.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"EIA:  Less Nuclear Power, Lower Fuel Prices"</b><br>
ELECTRIC PERSPECTIVES, 3-4/96, p. 5</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

Nuclear power generation will decrease 32% by 2015 and fuel prices
will drop less sharply than previously predicted, according to the
Energy Information Administration's "Annual Energy Outlook 1996.
<p>

EIA's forecast assumes that about 400f the current nuclear
generation capacity will retire by 3015 as plants reach the end of
their 40-year operating life.  The resulting 32-percent reduction in
the use of nuclear power between 1994 and 2015 was not evident in
earlier projections, as most of the retirements would occur after the
previous forecast horizon of 2010.  EIA predicts that coal and natural
gas use will rise to increase to fill the gap and meet expanding
electricity demand.
<p>

The group expects lower prices for natural gas and coal than in prior
forecasts, mostly because of higher resource estimates, technology
improvements and productivity gains.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Conditions in Millstone Rooms May Bring Fine"</b><br>
HARTFORD COURANT, 3/15/96, p. A1</i><br>
Barbara Nagy and Michael McIntire
<p>

A radioactive waste storage area at Northeast Utilities' troubled
Millstone 1 nuclear power plant "is in such poor condition that a tank
is leaking and pipes are rusting."  The situation could earn NU "a
substantial fine, according to" NU chairman Bernard Fox.
<p>

The utility is now using robots to examine the condition of three
small, isolated rooms where waste is stored.  NU said no workers were
exposed to radiation and there is no threat to public health.
<p>

The condition of the rooms have degraded over the last 15 years,
according to NU spokeswoman Deborah Beauchamp.  But she added that the
utility's new management team is committed to decontaminating the
rooms. Beauchamp: "The new management will not tolerate
operation of our facilities in this way. They're taking ownership of
these issues. There's absolutely no excuse for that area to be in the
condition it was in."
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Boston Edison May Sell Plants"</b><br>
BOSTON GLOBE, 3/15/96, p. 35</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

Boston Edison may sell two of its three power plants, leaving it with
just one nuclear power station and several smaller plants.  While none
of the sales are expected in the near future, Boston Edison spokesman
Michael Monahan said the utility has been approached by two companies
interested in its New Boston facility in South Boston and its Mystic
plant in Everett.
<p>

The sell-off is an effort by Boston Edison to streamline and become
more competitive as deregulation of the electric utility industry
comes to Massachusetts.  The utility has reportedly been talking to
Houston- based American National Power and Trigen- Boston Energy Corp.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Prairie Island Indian Community Wants a Solution on Nuclear Waste Storage"</b><br>
MINNEAPOLIS STAR TRIBUNE, 3/15/96, p. A25</i><br>
Curtis Campbell Sr., Op-Ed
<p>

Curtis Campbell Sr., chairman of the Prairie Island Indian Community,
writes that "time may run out" on Minnesota's 1996 legislative session
before the "serious problem" of nuclear waste storage at Northern
States Power's Prairie Island nuclear power plant is solved.  His
tribe is supporting a bill that would provide "fair compensation" to
the tribe and end NSP's search for an "alternative storage site" in
Goodhue County, MN.
<p>

Though NSP ratepayers have paid more than $240 million for developing
a federal storage site, the waste remains at Prairie Island. Taxpayers
could pay as much as $64 million to move the waste to an alternative
site -- a process that "even state lawmakers are calling a joke."
<p>

The state Environmental Quality Board wants to end the search for new
sites and leave the waste at Prairie Island.  But Campbell says that,
without an agreement with NSP, his tribe will not allow that to happen
and will take legal action if necessary.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Prairie Island: Last Chance for Tribe to Cut a Deal,"
       MINNEAPOLIS STAR TRIBUNE, 3/17/96, p. A28, Editorial, which
       notes that "there is still time for a solution ... but Prairie
       Island tribal members must wise up.  If they fail to reach an
       agreement this legislative session, much more than two years of
       hot air will have been wasted.  They may lose their chance to
       gain any compensation at all."
</ul>


</td>
</tr>
</table>
