<td>

<i><b>"Fired Reactor Workers Say They Prevented Disaster"</b><br>
ST. PETERSBURG TIMES, 3/14/96, p. 1B</i><br>
Ian James
<p>

Control-room workers at Florida Power Corp.'s Crystal River nuclear
plant found a problem in a main safety system in September 1994 that
they say could have "led to a disaster."  The company promptly
corrected the problem but, according to the workers, "wasn't exactly
grateful."
<p>

Last August the company disciplined six employees who worked that
shift, charging that they "performed unauthorized tests." Two
supervisors were fired, and four workers were reprimanded or "stripped
of their nuclear operators' licenses."
<p>

Former shift supervisor David Fields, who was fired, and two other
workers filed a complaint with the US Labor Dept. last month with
claimed they had performed a "routine procedure" and were being
"penalized for identifying the problem."  Florida Power declined
comment because the Labor Dept. and the Nuclear Regulatory Commission
are investigating the issue.
<p>

According to workers, the problem began in April 1993, when plant
managers ordered them to add more hydrogen to a main safety system.
The workers "worried" that adding to much hydrogen could burn up a
crucial pump and, if backup systems were down, could leave the reactor
core exposed.  So they decided to "see for themselves" with a
procedure they called "safe and routine."  The company said that
though public safety had not been at risk, the operators had
intentionally subjected safety equipment to high pressure levels that
made alarms go off.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Anger Is Main Reaction at Hearing on NU's Troubled Nuclear Power Plants"</b><br>
HARTFORD COURANT, 3/14/96, p. A21</i><br>
Barbara A. Nagy
<p>

Most of the 125 people who showed up for last Wednesday's hearing on
Northeast Utilities' "troubled" reactors were there "because they were
angry."  One woman "near tears" said, "This is terrifying.  We live in
these communities."
<p>

The Nuclear Regulatory Commission held the hearing because of concerns
about NU's three-unit Millstone nuclear plant.  The commission put
Millstone on its "watch list" on January 31 because of the plant's
eight-year history of "safety and management problems" -- problems
that "culminated" last year when a Millstone engineer told the NRC
that Unit 1 had not been refueled according to procedures for 20
years.
<p>

The NRC requires "substantial progress" before removing the plant from
the list, a process that "usually" takes two or three years.  But Bob
Rutter of Hartford said, "This kind of company and this kind of fox
guarding the chicken coop cannot be tolerated."  Wayne Lanning,
director of the NRC's Millstone oversight team, said he plans to hold
public hearings every other month to keep people informed and listen
to comments.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"TMI Cited for Two Violations"</b><br>
YORK PA DAILY RECORD, 3/14/96, p. A2</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

The Nuclear Regulatory Commission has issued two citations to GPU
Nuclear, which operates the Three Mile Island nuclear plant.  The
first violation concerned GPU's failure to modify some pipe supports
that its own engineers recommended in 1990. The other was for
miscalculating the pipe stress and "failing to establish through
analysis the adequacy of the pipe supports."
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>




<i><b>"Senate Plan Targets Nevada Test Site; A Proposal to Keep
Nuclear Waste on an Interim Basis in Nevada Ignores Out-of- State
Alternatives"</b><br>
LAS VEGAS REVIEW-JOURNAL, 3/13/96, p. 1A</i><br>
Tony Batt
<p>

The Senate is "following the lead of the House" with legislation that
"targets" the Nevada Test Site for interim storage of nuclear waste
and eliminates other possibilities, reports the LAS VEGAS REVIEW-
JOURNAL.  The bill was expected to "pass easily" on Wednesday because
one of its authors is panel chairman Sen. Frank Murkowski (R-AK).
<p>

The Senate bill, introduced by Sen. Larry Craig (R-ID), "mirrors" a
bill introduced in the House by Rep. Fred Upton (R- MI).  Upton's bill
is "stalled" because lawmakers have "balked" at removing federal
budget restrictions for temporary storage and permanent disposal.  The
Senate bill would maintain budget restrictions, but shift the priority
to storage.
<p>

The Senate bill also calls for shipping the waste across Nevada in
"heavy-haul trucks," while the House bills calls for building a
railroad.  The House bill requires DOE to begin storage by January 31,
1998.  The Senate bill directs DOE to take title to the waste by 1998,
but gives DOE until January 31, 1999, to begin storage at the test
site.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Clinton Reaffirms Dump Opposition," LAS VEGAS REVIEW- JOURNAL,
       3/12/96, p. 4B, Staff Report, which quotes Gov. Bob Miller (D-
       NV): "President Clinton told me he would do nothing to hurt
       Nevada, especially on the issue of nuclear waste.  He is
       the only occupant of the Oval Office ever to take Nevada's side
       on keeping nuclear waste out of our state."
</ul>


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Nunn Urges More Aid to Curb Illicit Nuclear Sales"</b><br>
ATLANTA JOURNAL/CONSTITUTION, 3/14/96, p. A10</i><br>
Andrew J. Glass
<p>

While Congress is prepared to spend billion for a new missile system,
it is "balking" at spending far smaller sums in the former Soviet
Union to deny nuclear weapons to "rogue countries and terrorists,"
Sen. Sam Nunn (D-GA) said Wednesday.
<p>

Nunn spoke in response to a General Accounting Office report that
linked lax controls over former Soviet weapons to seven nuclear thefts
and the threat of a nuclear black market.  Though the report found no
"direct evidence" of such a market, it did find "poor security at many
storage sites for weapons-grade plutonium and enriched uranium."
<p>

Congress has voted to spend $1.8 billion over the last five years to
help dismantle Soviet weapons and safeguard materials, and a "quasi-
private program" has been set up to buy uranium for reprocessing in US
plants.
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Russians Develop Floating Station for Nuclear Power"</b><br>
PORTLAND OREGONIAN, 3/14/96, p. A4</i><br>
Wire Reports
<p>

Russia plans to put a floating nuclear power plant into operation in
the Far East in five years, according to Alexander Polushkin, head of
the Malaya Energetika company.  The plant will consist of two small
reactors aboard a barge in the East Siberian Sea.  The reactors will
be delivered ready to operate, but every 13 years must be towed about
2,500 miles -- one way -- for repair and refueling.  "Russia's nuclear
power industry has raised safety concerns in the United States and
other countries."
     

