<html><head><title>Nuke News, 31/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 31/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.29.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... The WASHINGTON POST reports "a new job has been created at the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission"; Edward Baker of the enforcement staff
was named "agency allegations adviser."  "And people who make
allegations no longer are called whistleblowers"; they are "allegers"
(5/31/96, p. B1, Cindy Skrzycki).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... China plans to construct fewer small, coal-fired power plants in
the next five years "in a bid to improve its energy sector and dismal
air quality."  At a conference this week attended by more than 500
public and private officials, a planning minister said China would
focus on large clean-coal, nuclear and hydroelectric plants in central
and western regions (WASHINGTON TIMES, 5/31/96, p. A14, United Press
Intl.).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Explosion Rocks Nuclear Waste Silo at Point Beach Nuclear Plant"</b><br>
CITIZENS' UTILITY BOARD RELEASE, 5/29/96</i><br>
Contact:  David Merritt (608) 251-3322
<p>


The first radioactive waste storage "explosion" at a US nuclear plant
occurred at 2:45 am on 5/28 inside a nuclear waste silo at Wisconsin
Electric Power Company's Point Beach nuclear power plant.  Following
the accident, the state's first above- ground nuclear waste dump was
closed for the second time in five months.  "DAILY UTILITY NEWS" has
found little newspaper coverage of the event (see below).
<p>

According to the Nuclear Regulatory Commission's initial report, an 
unidentified gas ignited inside a cask fully loaded with spent fuel 
rods as it was being welded shut, causing the explosion.  There were 
no injuries and no radioactivity was released.
<p>

Each 18-foot-high cask is loaded with 14 tons of radioactive waste,
including 170 pounds of plutonium, and each loaded silo contains the
"equivalent radioactivity of 240 Hiroshima-type explosions."  Federal
guidelines require the waste to be "kept safe" for 10,000 years.
<p>

In 12/95, a Dane County Circuit Court judge had shut down the
facility, ruling that the Public Service Commission's environmental
impact statement was "fatally flawed" because it did not consider how
long waste may need to be stored in WI and didn't "evaluate economic
energy alternatives."  On 5/20/96, the PSC issued a new order
reopening the dump, and one week later the explosion occurred.
<p>

David Merritt, executive director of Citizens' Utility Board, said
"It's time for WEPCO to stop experimenting with nuclear waste on Lake
Michigan."  CUB will ask for an immediate PSC investigation and an
order reversing the reopening; the group also "will likely" file a
lawsuit challenging that order.
<p>

SEE ALSO: 
<ul>
  <li> "Fire Closes Wisconsin Nuclear Waste Site," MINNEAPOLIS STAR
       TRIBUNE, 5/30/96, p. 2B, Associated Press, which notes the
       Point Beach Plant is scheduled to be taken over by Minnesota's
       Northern States Power Co. within a year as part of a merger
       with Wisconsin Electric.
  <li> "Gas Ignites as Fuel Cask at Nuclear Power Plant About to Be
       Welded Shut," FISHWRAP [SAN FRANCISCO NEWSPAPERS ONLINE],
       5/29/96, Associated Press, which quotes WEPCO spokesman Rick
       James as saying the incident was a "gas burn" that lasted a
       couple of seconds.  Workers managing the process by remote
       control were not in danger, James said.
</ul>     
     


</td>
</tr>
</table>
