<html><head><title>Nuke News, 29/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 29/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.28.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... The British government said yesterday it would sell stock in the 
state-owned nuclear power generator, British Energy PLC, in July 
Barclays de Zoete Wedd, the investment bank managing the transaction, 
said details of the offering would be published in early June (NEW 
YORK TIMES, 5/29/96, p. D4, Dow Jones).




<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"It Turns Out Power Isn't Always Sexy"</b><br>
BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 5/24/96</i><br>
Chris Reidy
<p>

With deregulation advancing in the electric utility industry,
companies are trying to figure out how to convince consumers that "our
electricity is better than their electricity."
<p>

In California, one supplier touts the "socially responsible kilowatt,"
promising power will not be generated by a nuclear reactor or a plant
with a poor environmental record.  In New Hampshire, companies in a
competition pilot program are wooing customers with "spruce seedlings,
free showerheads -- even $50 checks."
<p>

"Already, the kilowatt battle reminds some observers of the marketing
wars waged by long-distance companies," the BOSTON GLOBE reports.  New
Hampshire's airwaves "crackle" with TV ads for competing power
suppliers.  So far, established players like Public Service of New
Hampshire and New England Electric have been more restrained, favoring
newspaper ads and educational material included with bills.  Boston
Edison is "considering escalating its campaign," aiming to invest
Edison with a "meaningful personality" and help it "brand the
kilowatt."
     

</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<table width=600>
  <tr>
    <td valign=middle><a href="/"><img src="/graphics/gifs/atom.t.gif"
