<html><head><title>Nuke News, 28/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 28/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.24.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<i><b>"Research for Reactor Nobody Wants"</b><br>
WASHINGTON POST, 5/28/96, p. A9</i><br>
Guy Gugliotta
<p>

Over the next few months, Rep. Mark Foley (R-FL) will try to kill
federal subsidies for private research on the Advanced Light Water
Reactor, which is billed as providing "a new generation" of better
performing nuclear power plants.  "Except nobody in the United States
wants one," writes Guy Gugliotta in the WASHINGTON POST, noting a
recent poll of utility execs indicating most would never again order a
new nuclear power plant.
<p>

But "the nuclear industry is not going to roll over," the POST
reports.  Nuclear Energy Institute spokesman Steve Unglesbee: "In the
next decade, the balance of power demand will shift ... because of
aging and environmental concerns."  Despite nuclear's declining cost-
competitiveness versus coal, natural gas and even wind power,
Unglesbeee says, "We think nuclear will be a contender."
<p>

Since the 1992 Energy Policy Act authorized five years of funding,
beginning in 1993, ALWR backers say the FY '97 request of $30.3
million "simply fulfills" the pledge made in the act.  But Foley
argues that the three firms receiving the money -- General Electric,
Westinghouse and Asea Brown Boveri's Combustion Engineering unit --
"don't need the help of the federal government."


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Agency Discovers Refueling Errors at 14 Nuclear Power Plants"</b><br>
NEW YORK TIMES, 5/26/96, p. 17</i><br>
Matthew Wald
<p>

The Nuclear Regulatory Commission has issued a public report finding
that refueling errors at Millstone 1 Plant in Waterford, CT, were
common at 14 other reactors around the country, which all have "moved
to correct" the problem.
<p>

The Millstone Plant had been removing all of its nuclear fuel
assemblies during refueling, instead of the designated one-third, and
storing them in a spent fuel pool.  Too many assemblies in the pool,
especially ones recently removed from a reactor, "theoretically" could
generate enough heat to boil away the cooling water, "raising the
possibility" that the fuel would melt down and release radioactivity
into the atmosphere.
<p>

Employees at Northeast Utilities, which operates the plant, 
reported the spent-fuel storage problem to the NRC, which then 
surveyed the 110 commercial reactors in the US and found the following 
ones committing the same error:
<ul>
  <li> Cooper in Brownville, NE (owned by NE Public Power District);
  <li> McGuire 1 and 2 in Cowans Ford Dam, SC, and Oconee 1, 2, and 3
       in Lake Keowee, SC, (Duke Power Co.);
  <li> North Anna 1 and 2 in Mineral, VA (owned mainly by Virginia
       Electric and Power Co.);
  <li> South Texas 1 and 2 in Matagorda County (Houston Lighting and
       Power Co., mainly);
  <li> Summer in Jenkinsville, SC (SC Electric and Gas Co.,mainly);
  <li> Turkey Point 3 and 4 near Miami, FL (Florida Power and Light
       Co.); and
  <li> Alvin W. Vobtle, in Waynesboro, GA (Georgia Power Co., mainly).
</ul>
<p>

NRC staff said all of the utilities involved had pledged to study
their fuel pools and, if they are overheating, to change storage
practices.  The safety of spent-fuel pools "has become a bigger issue
in the last few years because the Energy Dept. has not found a
permanent repository for the wastes."
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Power Plants' Woes Bode Ill for the Summer," NEW YORK TIMES,
       5/27/96, p. 22, Associated Press, which quotes a spokesman for
       the New England Power Pool saying that if NU's Connecticut
       Yankee nuclear plant goes off-line for regulatory scrutiny, it
       could cause "more severe" regional power shortages than those
       experienced last week.
  <li> "Have You Heard?," HARTFORD COURANT, 5/24/96, p. F1, Staff
       Report, which reports that despite Northeast Utilities's recent
       problems, it made BUSINESS ETHICS magazine's first-ever list of
       the 100 best corporate citizens in its May- June issue, ranking
       at No. 81.  The magazine considered factors such as employee
       ownership, profitability, the presence of women and minorities
       on boards, ethics codes and other social factors.
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"NRC Lowers Pilgrim Rating"</b><br>
BOSTON GLOBE, 5/25/96, p. 25</i><br>
Scott Allen
<p>

A "pattern of mistakes" at Boston Edison's Pilgrim nuclear power plant
prompted the Nuclear Regulatory Commission on Friday to downgrade the
plant's safety ratings "for the first time in eight years."  The
report -- which comes as the utility is cutting the plant's work force
-- found that workers had mistakenly shipped radioactive wastes to a
laundry and a battery- recycling center.  Also, workers at the plant
were exposed to "unusually high levels" of radioactivity, bucking an
industry trend toward reduced exposures.
<p>

"Pilgrim officials, who just completed a record 319-day run of the
plant without stopping for repairs, said they were disappointed."
Edison Senior VP E. Thomas Boulette said, "We cannot be satisfied with
'good' performance," adding the company would do whatever it takes to
earn "superior" ratings in all areas.  The NRC had "steadily improved"
its ratings of Pilgrim since the mid-1980s, when it was considered one
of the five worst-run plants in the country.  In 1994, it was one of
the nation's two best-run plants.
<p>

The downbeat report comes as the electric-utility industry braces for
greater competition, "putting intense pressure on plant managers to
reduce costs."  "But nuclear power, with its potential for
environmental damage," will face "special scrutiny" during the
transition, the BOSTON GLOBE reports.


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Back on Line, Reactor Aims at Full Power"</b><br>
ARKANSAS DEMOCRAT-GAZETTE, 5/26/96, p. 1B</i><br>
Staff and Wire Services
<p>

The Arkansas Nuclear One power plant in Russellville, AR, owned by
Entergy Corp., "eased" back on line Saturday after being shut down
since May 19.  Entergy officials said a piece of monitoring equipment
had "wrongly indicated" that the reactor's cooling-pump speed had
dropped. The reading caused an automatic shutdown of the reactor.  The
pump in question supplies water to the plant's steam-generator system.
<p>

A five-man team from the Nuclear Regulatory Commission, which
investigated the shutdown and reviewed the plant's systems, found
problems in electronic equipment installed last year that led to the
"erroneous reading."  After the shutdown, one of 16 safety valves
designed to close automatically stuck open.  Entergy officials said
both problems have been corrected.
<p>

The NRC team, which left the site on Friday, will issue a final report
in three weeks, and the NRC will hold a public meeting in the
Russellville area to discuss the findings.  Although the NRC has fined
the plant $545,000 for nine separate violations since 1984, it has
received superior and good ratings in recent years.
<p>

SEE ALSO: 
<ul>
  <li> "Reactor Restarted After Lapse," ARKANSAS DEMOCRAT- GAZETTE,
       5/25/96, p. D1, and "Shutdown Sends Special Team to Nuclear
       One," ARKANSAS DEMOCRAT-GAZETTE, 5/24/96, p. A1, Andrew Moreau,
       which noted that state and federal officials monitoring the
       problems found "no threat to public safety" during the
       shutdown.
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Fire Torches Idle Browns Ferry Nuke Plant Tower"</b><br>
MEMPHIS COMMERCIAL APPEAL, 5/24/96, p. A17</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

An idled cooling tower at the Browns Ferry Nuclear Plant on May 23 was
"destroyed by flames" in "the latest of a string of fires that has
plagued the plant for two decades."
<p>

Tennessee Valley Authority officials said that no one was hurt by the
early morning fire and there was no radiation threat.  Plant spokesman
Terry Johnson said the public was not notified because the fire
occurred outside the plant.  The plant's two reactors were not
affected by the fire.
<p>

Browns Ferry, located on the Tennessee River about 100 miles north of
Birmingham, AL, has been the site of at least three fires since 1975,
including one that was considered at the time the nation's worst
nuclear accident.
<p>

Stephen Smith of the Knoxville-based Tennessee Valley Energy Reform
Coalition, a regional watchdog group, said that a full investigation
is needed because of Browns Ferry's history of fires.  About the fire,
Smith said it "doesn't surprise me."
<p>

TVA spokeswoman Barbara Martocci said an investigation would be
undertaken immediately.

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Fire at Troubled TVA Nuclear Plant," MINNEAPOLIS STAR-
       TRIBUNE, 5/24/96, p. A4, Staff Report.
  <li> "In Alabama, Fire Hits Nuclear Plant," BOSTON GLOBE, 5/25/96,
       Associated Press.
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... The Nine Mile Point 1 nuclear power plant in upstate New York was
restarted on May 23 after a problem with a feed-water valve was
corrected, according to a spokesman for Niagara Mohawk Power Corp.,
which operates the plant (SYRACUSE POST-STANDARD, 5/24/96, p. B1,
Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... General Electric has won a contract to supply two nuclear reactors
and related equipment for Taiwan's fourth nuclear power plant,
according to the state-run Taiwan Power Company (NEW YORK TIMES,
5/27/96, p. 30, Reuters).  Taiwan's Parliament voted last week to urge
the Cabinet to scrap the project, but the Cabinet has decided to
proceed anyway (FINANCIAL TIMES, 5/28/96, p. 5, Laura Tyson).


</td>
</tr>
</table>
