<html><head><title>Nuke News, 24/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 24/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.23.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... Leaders of Sweden's political parties yesterday opened talks on
how to decommission the country's 12 nuclear power plants by 2010, as
first endorsed in a 1980 national referendum (FINANCIAL TIMES,
5/24/96, p. 2, Hugh Carnegy).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... Taiwan's state electricity utility today opens bidding for two nuclear
reactors and related equipment for the country's fourth nuclear power
plant.  The three qualified bidders are Westinghouse, Combustion
Engineering and General Electric (FINANCIAL TIMES, 5/24/96, p. 6, Laura
Tyson).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... An idle cooling tower at the Browns Ferry nuclear power plant in
Athens, AL was destroyed by fire yesterday, marking the fourth fire at the
site since 1975.  No one was injured, and the fire posed no radiation risk
(FISHWRAP [SAN FRANCISCO NEWSPAPERS ONLINE], 5/23/96, Associated
Press).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... Officials from the US Nuclear Regulatory Commission and the Bureau of
Indian Affairs were scheduled to meet yesterday with members of Minnesota's
Prairie Island Indian community to discuss concerns about Northern States
Power Co.'s nuclear power plant and waste-disposal plans (MINNEAPOLIS
STAR-TRIBUNE, 5/23/96, p. B3, Associated Press).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... In a GREENSBORO NC NEWS &amp; RECORD op-ed, Thomas Elleman, a professor
emeritus of the nuclear engineering dept. at North Carolina State U., urges
support for the proposed Nuclear Waste Policy Act now pending in Congress.
It would be "tragic," he writes, "if extreme environmentalists succeeded in
using the waste problem to abolish nuclear power."  And the nuclear
industry has the ability to handle waste safely, he writes (5/19/96,
p. F3).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<i><b>"Edison's Competition Plan:  A 'Fortress' Balance Sheet"</b><br>
CHICAGO SUN-TRIBUNE, 5/23/96, p. 47</i><br>
Francine Knowles
<p>

Top executives of Chicago's Unicom Corp., the parent of Commonwealth
Edison, told shareholders Wednesday the company is preparing for utility
industry competition by creating a "fortress balance sheet."  In response
to critics of the firm's stance -- Unicom has proposed delaying full-scale
competition until -- Chairman James O'Connor said: "We don't intend to be
brought into the competitive arena kicking and screaming.  We will embrace
competition because we're convinced that we can win in the
... marketplace."  ...  Some shareholders said "things aren't as bright as
the company claims," blasting the utility's falling stock price and
multi-million- dollar executive salaries.  O'Connor said the downturn
resulted from the company's decision to invest $70 million in improvements
at its nuclear plants.


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"A Fiscal Meltdown"</b><br>
FISHWRAP SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE ONLINE, 5/22/96</i><br>
Jonathan Marshall
<p>

San Francisco-based Pacific Gas &amp; Electric has filed a restructuring plan
with the CA Public Utilities Commission in which the utility would speed
the depreciation of its Diablo Canyon nuclear power plant in order to
maintain its competitiveness.
<p>

PG&amp;E wants to write off the remaining $3.8 billion book value on its
plant 15 years ahead of its initial target date of 2016.  By doing so, it
would be able to lower its electricity rates while still showing a profit.
Chris Warner of PG&amp;E: "Our goal is to get Diablo in a position where it
will operate for many years and continue being an economic benefit to the
county."
<p>

However, the county of San Luis Obispo, where Diablo is located, is voicing
strong protests, saying that the plan violates "moral" and "legal"
commitments PG&amp;E made to the community.  The county stands to lose
nearly $10 million a year from lower property tax revenues under the plan.
<p>

James Boothe, an aide to PUC Commissioner Daniel Fessler, said the
commission likely will not stop the restructuring process because of one
county's woes.  Unless restructuring advances, Boothe said, Californians
will never enjoy lower rates.



<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"We Shouldn't Export Nuclear Waste"</b><br>
MINNEAPOLIS STAR TRIBUNE, 5/18/96, p. 23A</i><br>
David Morris, John Bailey, Institute for Local Self-Reliance
<p>

"We have yet to discover a safe way to deal with the radioactive wastes
generated from nuclear power plants," write David Morris and John Bailey in
the MINNEAPOLIS STAR TRIBUNE.
<p>

Yet, they assert that measures such as the proposed Yucca Mountain
radioactive waste repository which would "force Nevada to become the
nation's radioactive waste dump," are not the answer.  Instead, the pair
argue that states should take responsibility for their own wastes, and not
"whine about how the federal government has done us wrong."
<p>

They advocate a "major engineering upgrade" in dry cask design for wastes
to allow for 100 year or greater storage capacity.  They also suggest
finding a community in Minnesota that would serve as a storage site, "for
the right price."  Finally, they assert that nuclear power must be phased
out in the state.  Although that move would end up raising electricity
rates, that is the "modest" price "we pay for having made an irresponsible
decision."

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"End Corporate Welfare for Nuclear Reactors"</b><br>
SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE, 5/20/96, p. A18</i><br>
Editorial
<p>

No US electric utility has ordered a new nuclear reactor in years, and a
recent survey of utility execs found there is "little hope" for industry
expansion.  "So why are taxpayers still being asked to fork over hundreds
of millions of dollars to mature, highly profitable companies" like General
Electric and Westinghouse "to develop new nuclear power reactors?"  The SAN
FRANCISCO CHRONICLE editorial page editors suggest that the Dept. of
Energy's Advanced Light Water Reactor program be ended.
<p>

"Except for the reactor's export potential, it's hard to see" how the
program can be justified, the CHRONICLE writes.  But federal law says the
subsidies are for development of reactors to be built and operated in the
US.  And even if there is a lucrative export market, there's "no reasons"
why major companies couldn't finance their own R&amp;D programs.  The
subsidy should be allowed to expire in September, the editorial concludes.


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"A Day of Reckoning for NU"</b><br>
HARTFORD COURANT, 5/21/96, p. A16</i><br>
Editorial
<p>

Amid this week's heavy coverage by the HARTFORD COURANT of Northeast
Utilities' nuclear power woes, the paper's editorial page opined,
"Stockholders, neighbors and customers ... have good reason to be outraged"
at the decisions taken by management in recent years.  "Facing increasing
competition and financial pressures, NU's leaders decided one way to cut
costs was to meet only minimum safety standards and do repairs on the
cheap. ... The consequences have been disastrous," with NU's Millstone
nuclear power plant closed by the NRC, federal investigations looking into
alleged mistreatment of whistleblowers and the company's stock price
plummeting.
<p>

Current managers bear "much of the blame," but former Chairman William
Ellis and the NRC "must be held to account, too," the COURANT concludes.


</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
