<html><head><title>Nuke News, 23/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 23/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.22.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

..."Heat Leads to Power Shortage," HARTFORD COURANT, 5/22/96, p. 1A,
Dan Haar, which recaps Connecticut-based Northeast Utilities' efforts
this week to cope with power shortages stemming from the hot weather
and its temporarily closed nuclear plants.



<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Shareholders Confront NU Chairman"</b><br>
HARTFORD COURANT, 5/22/96, p. 1A</i><br>
Barbara Nagy
<p>

"Saying Northeast Utilities is in 'real trouble,' Chairman Bernard
M. Fox apologized to shareholders Tuesday but rejected angry demands
from some of them that he and other top officials step down."  "The
company will recover," Fox said, "because of the good people who work
here and the many people who want to see it recover."
<p>

The shareholders' meeting drew 850 people, "more than any other" in
the company's 30-year history.  Investors, many of them retired CT
residents, voiced their anger about NU's plunging stock price, which
ended Tuesday at $14.75, its lowest level in more than ten years.  The
company currently is struggling with federal investigations of alleged
mismanagement at its Millstone and Connecticut Yankee nuclear power
plants.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Northeast Utilities Vows Turnaround," BOSTON GLOBE, 
       5/22/96, p. 34, Jerry Ackerman.
</ul>



<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Telephone Signals to Run Home Appliances"</b><br>
CHICAGO TRIBUNE, 5/22/96, p. B1</i><br>
David Young
<p>

Chicago-based Commonwealth Edison Co. next fall plans to begin testing
a program which will allow the utility to manage residents' major home
appliances over the phone.
<p>

ComEd will work with telephone company Ameritech Corp. to offer the
service free of charge to as many as 2,000 Chicago-area homes.  The
pilot program would allow the utility to remotely run customers'
furnaces, water heaters, refrigerators and other appliances in order
to take advantage of lower off-peak rates.
<p>

The program is part of Edison's strategy to better prepare for
increased competition brought on by industry deregulation.  ComEd
charges higher rates than neighboring utilities because of its
reliance on nuclear power, and has been "under pressure" to cut rates.
Last year, company officials announced the home management system as
part of their plan for deregulation and a rate freeze.


</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
