<html><head><title>Nuke News, 22/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 22/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.21.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... A federal court in Florida ordered St. Petersburg-based Florida
Power Corp. to pay $88,000 in back wages to a former engineer at its
Crystal River nuclear power plant.  The engineer had alleged he was
laid off due to age discrimination during a general downsizing in
1994.  The utility hasn't decided whether to appeal the decision (ST.
PETERSBURG TIMES, 5/18/96, p. 1E, Robert Trigaux).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Emergency Measures Invoked by Utilities on Eastern Seaboard"</b><br>
WALL STREET JOURNAL, 5/22/96, p. A3</i><br>
Ross Kerber and Jonathan Auerbach
<p>

Electric utilities in the Northeast cut off power to many customers
and urged others to use less as a "freakish" May heat wave caught many
utilities "offguard."  "The moves could presage a summer of possible
rising prices and power outages in the Northeast, where a sizable
portion of generating capacity has been idled by federally ordered
nuclear-plant shutdowns. "
<p>

Connecticut-based Northeast Utilities, New Jersey's Public Service
Enterprise Group and Pennsylvania's PP&amp;L Resources reduced or cut
off service to hundreds of commercial, industrial and residential
customers. The New England Power Pool shaved voltage to Connecticut
customers by 5%, while Consolidated Edison of New York dropped voltage
by 8% and cut power to 115,000 residents.
<p>

Yesterday's load in New England went as high as 18,000 megawatts,
compared to the seasonal average of 15,000 megawatts.
<p>

Many power plants in the region were offline for maintenance.
Mechanical troubles caused by thunderstorms also added to the day's
difficulties "and can be rectified in short order."  But given that
none of the three shuttered nuclear reactors owned by NU is expected
to restart until August, analysts predicted higher prices for
electricity and a much more active wholesale spot market.



<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"5 in Waste Compact Ordered to Try Again For a Settlement"</b><br>
OMAHA WORLD-HERALD, 5/17/96, p. 22</i><br>
Paul Hammel
<p>

A US District Court judge ordered Nebraska and a five-state compact to
meet "one last time" to hammer out a settlement over the withholding
of federal funds to build a low-level radioactive waste storage
facility near Butte, NE.  Judge David Piester ordered the parties to
meet on May 23 to work out an agreement.
<p>

The five-state compact's Facility Review Committee has argued that
Nebraska has been careless and slow with the license review process
for the waste site.  The state argues that the compact's insistence on
enforcing a schedule for completion of the state's license review is
"impractical."
<p>

The compact commission is in charge of developing a disposal site for
low-level radioactive waste from Nebraska, Oklahoma, Kansas, Arkansas
and Louisiana.  "The vast majority of such waste comes from nuclear
power plants," and power plant operators such as the Omaha Public
Power District and Nebraska Public Power District are primarily
financing the project.
     


</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<table width=600>
  <tr>
    <td valign=middle><a href="/"><img src="/graphics/gifs/atom.t.gif"
