<html><head><title>Nuke News, 21/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 21/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.20.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

..."Nuclear Plant Has Role in Merger Competition," JOURNAL OF
COMMERCE, 5/21/96, p. 7B, Staff Report, which notes Western and KCPL
already share one large asset -- the Wolf Creek nuclear power plant in
Burlington, KS.




<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"NRC is Questioning Assurances on Plant of Northeast Utilities"</b><br>
WALL STREET JOURNAL, 5/21/96, p. B9</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

The Nuclear Regulatory Commission "questioned safety assurances" given
by the managers of the Connecticut Yankee nuclear power plant in
Haddam Neck, CT, "raising the chances that the plant could be shut
down."  In a letter last Friday to Northeast Utilities, the main
equity holder in the plant, the NRC said findings by a team of its
inspectors "call into question" Northeast's contention that safety
issues at the plant were "minor."
<p>

Northeast is also owner of the Millstone nuclear power plant in
Waterford, CT, which is currently shut down for intense NRC scrutiny.
<p>

Separately, NU said its No. 2 nuclear officer, Fred Dacimo, left the
company for unspecified reasons.
<p>

"The mounting troubles ... came as Northeast prepared for what is
expected to be a contentious shareholders' meeting today" in Stamford,
CT.  The utility's stock has plunged 41% this year, the WALL STREET
JOURNAL reports.


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Northeast Utilities: A Fall from Grace"</b><br>
HARTFORD COURANT, 5/19/96 and 5/20/96, p. A1</i><br>
Michael Remez and Mike McIntire
<p>

In a two-part series based on its own 3-month investigation, the
COURANT examines the sagging fortunes of Northeast Utilities, whose
stock price has "plunged" from $25 a share to $15.25.  Part One, "Down
a Dangerous Path at NU: Cutting Costs, Corners," the COURANT says the
US Nuclear Regulatory Commission decision of 1/96 to add the Millstone
plants to its watch list "could have come much sooner."  The NRC gave
the Millstone units, once "model" nuclear power plants, more "waivers
from license requirements" than any other plant.
<p>

The article includes a "Troubled Times at Millstone" timeline that
traces troubles back to 4/86 when the last Millstone plant went on
line, $3 billion over budget.  The nuclear operation has been "in
turmoil" ever since as "cost containment trumped safety" in
preparation for deregulated competition.
<p>

Part Two, "Whistle-blowers: NU's Most Vexing Issue," begins with the
premise that the three Millstone reactors in Waterford, CT, are shut
down "indefinitely" because of problems identified "in large measure"
by its own employees.  The reporters find "several recurring themes"
in the NU treatment of whistle- blowers: a "tendency" to refer
"troublesome" employees for psychological counseling or to pay them
cash settlements to leave the co. and, "in some instances, to keep
quiet."
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "NE Utilities Executives on Hot Seat," BOSTON HERALD, 5/20/96,
       p. 21, in which reporter Tony Munroe says "a root canal
       probably sounds better" to NU executives than the "grilling
       they are likely to get" at the annual shareholders meeting on
       5/21.
</ul>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... Yankee Atomic Electric Co., which operates the Yankee Rowe nuclear
power plant in Rowe, MA, said it has commissioned design work on a
$15- 20 million interim nuclear-waste-storage facility.  The project
may not go forward if Congress approves an interim national facility
in Nevada (WALL STREET JOURNAL, 5/21/96, p. B4, Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
... The NRC on Friday proposed to fine Commonwealth Edison of Chicago 
$100,000 over safety issues at its Braidwood plant in Illinois.  
Edison spokesman Gary Wald said the problems cited have "little" 
safety significance "individually ... but taken collectively they 
address a trend we need to address" (CHICAGO SUN-TIMES, 5/18/96, p. 6, 
Basil Talbott).


</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
