<html><head><title>Nuke News, 20/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 20/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.17.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... Five new nuclear power plants have come on line around the world
since 1994 and a mothballed plant in Armenia is back on line, bringing
the total number to 438, according to the International Atomic Energy
Agency (WASHINGTON TIMES, 5/20/96, p. A12, Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... In its latest performance report, the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission on May 16 gave Houston Lighting &amp; Power's South Texas
Project nuclear plant "good" and "superior" marks.  The NRC evaluated
the plant's operations, maintenance, engineering and plant support.
It received "superior" in maintenance and plant support and "good" in
operations and engineering (AUSTIN AMERICAN-STATESMAN, 5/17/96, p. B2,
Staff Report).


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Beware of Nuke Costs, Some Watchdogs Say"</b><br>
SYRACUSE POST-STANDARD, 5/17/96, p. D1</i><br>
Mary Jo Hill
<p>

The New York Public Service Commission's decision on May 16 to move
the state's electric utility industry to competition "means power
plants will have to compete, and this could spell trouble for nuclear
reactors, some interest groups believe."
<p>

Ashok Gupta of the Natural Resources Defense Council said that
uneconomical power plants won't be operating in the future.  Nuclear
plants will be "high on the problem list" because of high fixed costs.
NRDC believes that if reactors can't compete, they should be shut
down.
<p>

Niagara Mohawk Power Corp. owns two nuclear power plants in Oswego
County, NY while the New York Power Authority runs a third.  The three
reactors can "barely compete" now, according to James Riccio of the
consumer group Critical Mass Energy Project.  Riccio: "This is going
to be a weeding out process."
<p>

Gupta believes one-quarter to one-third of the nuclear plants in the
US will not be able to compete, even though regulators may be able to
shield them from competition.  However, Consumer Protection Board
spokesman Steven LaFever felt that by allowing competition, the PSC
almost guaranteed that the price of electricity in the long-term will
decline.  LaFever: "We're very happy."
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "PSC's Decision Gives a Lift to NiMo Stock," SYRACUSE
       POST-STANDARD, 5/17/96, p. D1, Mike Fish and Bob Niedt, which
       notes that Niagara Mohawk's stock "rose slightly" on May 16
       following the announcement by the PSC.  The company's stock has
       been upgraded recently in anticipation of the commission's
       announcement.
</ul>


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"TVA Devises Payment Plan for Shutting Down Reactors"</b><br>
NASHVILLE TENNESSEAN, 5/16/96, p. 6B</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

The Tennessee Valley Authority's board on 5/16 approved a plan to pay
for closing the agency's nuclear plants in the next century.  TVA
directors also approved a $123 million contribution to the
decommissioning fund, bringing it to about $400 million.
<p>

"TVA has come under fire about the fund recently because the agency
depleted the fund in 1993 to take advantage of a $163 million
investment profit."  The new contribution should restore the fund to
the 1993 level.  TVA assumes the fund will grow through investments
and be able to cover the $4 billion estimated cost of closing down
TVA's six reactors, beginning about 2016.
<p>

Federal law requires every US utility company to maintain a fund for
decommissioning nuclear plants.  "TVA, the nation's largest public
power producer, is the exception to the rule," but it has still
maintained a decommissioning fund since 1977.
     
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<table width=600>
  <tr>
    <td valign=middle><a href="/"><img src="/graphics/gifs/atom.t.gif"
