<html><head><title>Nuke News, 17/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 17/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.16.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

..."New Concept for Nuclear Power," SYRACUSE POST-STANDARD, 5/15/96,
p. C1, Mary Jo Hill, which reports that Niagara Mohawk is depending on
the deregulation of the electric industry to help it avoid bankruptcy.
Facing higher costs and lower-than-expected earnings, NiMo has said it
may have to file for bankruptcy if the PSC doesn't approve
PowerChoice.



<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"San Antonio Nuke Settlement 10 Times Austin's 'Victory'" </b><br>
AUSTIN AMERICAN-STATESMAN, 5/15/96, p. A1</i><br>
Diana Dworin and Ben Wear
<p>

Last month, Austin city leaders accepted a $20 million settlement to
end a lawsuit over "alleged mismanagement" of the South Texas Project
nuclear power plant by Houston Lighting &amp; Power; now they're
having second thoughts since the City of San Antonio may come out 10
times better in its settlement with HL&amp;P over the same plant.  San
Antonio's publicly owned utility, City Public Services, has
"tentatively" accepted a settlement valued at $225 million with $75
million in cash and $150 million in reduced operating costs.
<p>

The Austin settlement involved only mismanagement, since the city
already had taken HL&amp;P to court in 1989 to dispute cost overruns
in constructing the $6 billion plant, winning a verdict but receiving
no damages from the jury.  In contrast, the San Antonio agreement,
still subject to final approval by the utility board, "puts to rest" a
lawsuit over mismanagement that led to a 14-month shutdown and a
construction dispute.  Austin owns only a 16% share of the STP plant,
while San Antonio owns a 28% stake.  Austin City Council members,
nettled by the larger settlement, point out that City Public Services,
originally a partner in the Austin lawsuit, pulled out just before the
trial started, announcing that it had reached a settlement, the terms
of which only now have become public.


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Oversight at Yankee"</b><br>
BANGOR DAILY NEWS, 5/15/96</i><br>
Editorial
<p>

Maine Gov. Angus King (I) "properly" hired an outside consultant last
month to review a proposal by the Maine Yankee nuclear power plant to
return to full power, but the BANGOR DAILY NEWS says he should expand
the investigation.  An NRC report, issued last week, also suggested
widening the review.
<p>

Victor Ransom, head of the nuclear engineering program at Purdue Univ., 
is reviewing a computer program submitted by plant officials to the 
Nuclear Regulatory Commission to justify a return to full power. Maine 
Yankee, an older plant that recently went through the "world's largest 
re-sleeving job" to repair cracked tubes in its steam generator, was 
held to 90% power after an anonymous letter criticized the computer 
model that predicts what would happen during a loss-of-coolant 
accident. Although an NRC internal review showed the letter writer was 
"generally correct" in charging lax oversight, the newspaper said this 
did not mean charges of "willful negligence" against Maine Yankee 
officials "also were on target."
<p>

Calling for an "outside expert" to review practices going back to 1989
when NRC admitted "to dozing off," the editorial said the reason no
nuclear power plants have been built in the US in a generation is that
"a measurable and loud portion" of the public does not trust them to
be safe.  The state should have assurances that even during the time
of lax oversight, Maine Yankee was operating well within safety
limits.


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Beasley:  SC Ready to Sue Feds Over Nuclear Waste"</b><br>
ROCK HILL [SC] HERALD, 5/15/96, p. 10A</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

South Carolina will once again sue the US DOE over the shipment of
spent foreign nuclear fuel to the Savannah River Site nuclear weapons
complex, said Gov. David Beasley (R) on May 14.
<p>

During the next 13 years, as many as 300 fuel shipments will enter the
port of Charleston, and be taken by truck or rail to the SRS, about
125 miles away.  The DOE argues that the US must take back the fuel it
sold to foreign research reactors, to protect against the spread of
the weapons-grade material.
<p>

Beasley said the government did not perform the proper environmental
reviews and might end up leaving the waste in SC because the DOE
doesn't have a credible, long-term storage plan.  The government's
proposed permanent repository at Yucca Mountain, NV is "far from"
completed.  SC's Attorney General will file suit before June 1.


</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
