<html><head><title>Nuke News, 16/5/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 16/5/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.15.html">Previous Nuke News</a>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"NU Calling Its Older Plants To Active Duty"</b><br>
HARTFORD COURANT, 5/15/96, p. 1F</i><br>
Barbara A. Nagy
<p>

"With Northeast Utilities's much larger and more efficient Millstone
nuclear reactors off line indefinitely in Waterford," about a half
dozen smaller and older power plants around Connecticut are "gearing
up" to meet peak summer demand.
<p>

NU's three Millstone reactors are on the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission's "watch list" of troubled facilities, and are off line
while the utility works to prove they are operating safely.
<p>

Meanwhile, the utility is spending $25 million to reactivate old
plants, working feverishly to bring in alternative power and ready
transmission lines by July 1 -- the company's self-imposed deadline
for preparing for summer heat waves.
<p>

NU is bringing two retired fossil-fuel plants in Middletown and
Bridgeport Harbor back on line, and leasing five General Electric Co.
40-megawatt power generators.  The utility has also asked Pratt amp;
Whitney to generate and sell excess power to it this summer, and is
working with the state to obtain emergency permits and waivers for all
the work.
<p>

Robert Gunderson, manager of the recommissioned Devon station, pointed
all out the activity at the plant to a HARTFORD COURANT reporter.
Gunderson: "A week ago Friday, there was nothing here.  ... It's an
incredible effort."
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "NU Readies for Summer Service," BOSTON GLOBE ONLINE, 5/16/96,
       Associated Press, upon which the COURANT story is based.
</ul>



<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"Questions Surround Financial Status of Waste-Site Firm"</b><br>
OMAHA WORLD-HERALD, 5/13/96, p. 11</i><br>
Julie Anderson
<p>

An official of American Ecology Corp. -- the parent company of a firm
developing a radioactive-waste storage site in Nebraska -- said the
company is in a "difficult position" financially and is negotiating
with shareholders for more cash to complete the waste-storage project.
<p>

An AEC spokesman said the company needs an infusion of "multimillions"
in cash to "address liabilities" the firm discovered in dealings with
two subsidiaries acquired in 1994.  The company is expected to post a
$33 million write-down of values associated with the two companies.
<p>

Rich Paton, vice president of AEC and its subsidiary US Ecology, said
his companies are in no danger of bankruptcy.  Paton also said AEC's
financial troubles would not stop it from obtaining a
construction-financing loan to build the low-level radioactive waste
site for Nebraska and four other states.
<p>

However, Gregory Hayden of the University of Nebraska-Lincoln, who
sits on a five-state compact commission which oversees the AEC
project, said that several factors indicate that the company may be in
worse shape than previously thought.
<p>

The issue is significant for Nebraska utilities because there is a
possibility that electric ratepayers may get "stuck with the bill" if
AEC can't complete the facility.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Nelson: Firm's Problems Are Cause For Concern," OMAHA
       WORLD-HERALD, 5/13/96, p. 13, which quotes NE Gov. Ben Nelson
       (D) as saying: "It's questionable whether you want a company in
       financial difficulty to build a site that is going to be
       managed for hundreds of years.  You can't help but worry."
</ul>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<i><b>"How the French Get Power"</b><br>
THE ECONOMIST, 5/11/96 Issue, p. 62</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

Electricite de France, Europe's largest electricity company, has "long
championed" nuclear power, which "may prove to be its downfall," says
THE ECONOMIST.  European Union energy ministers met on 5/7 to plan
industry deregulation, but EDF is "doing everything" it can to
preserve its "near-monopoly."  Even though the utility has made
nuclear power a symbol of national pride, its profits are "meager"
compared with those of many privatized electricity firms.
<p>

By standardizing reactor design, the utility has kept nuclear power
costs "relatively low;" French electricity prices are "much lower"
than Germany's.  Since completing most of the "current generation" of
reactors in France, the utility has "exported its expertise" to China,
Eastern Europe, Spain and Argentina.  But decommissioning French
reactors is another matter, and critics contend that EDF may have
underestimated the sum needed.  If full decommissioning costs were
included in electricity prices, it would be "more expensive," they
say. Storage of high-level radioactive waste is another "looming"
problem.
<p>

But EDF "worries most" about Europe-wide electricity deregulation.  If
the utility beghan to lose its reputation as a creator of jobs and if
its financiers began to demand market- oriented accounting, "the whole
structure could collapse," THE ECONOMIST concludes.
<p>

SEE ALSO:  
<ul>
  <li> "Short Circuit," THE ECONOMIST, 5/11/96 issue, p. 63, Staff
       Report, which describes the divisions among European
       governments over industry deregulation.  EU businesses pay
       about 50% more for electricity than their American
       counterparts.
</ul>

</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
