<html><head><title>Nuke News, 4/6/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 4/6/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.06.03.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>
 
<i><b>"U.S. Seeking to Strengthen Nuclear Agency" </b><br>
NEW YORK TIMES, 6/4/96, p. A11</i><br>
Raymond Bonner
<p>

A US-backed plan to strengthen the powers of the International Atomic
Energy Agency "has run into determined resistance, not from rogue
states bent on acquiring nuclear arsenals, but from two allies --
Germany and Japan -- that fear a new burden on their flourishing
nuclear power industries."
<p>

The NEW YORK TIMES reports from Vienna that a majority of nations seem
to support a stronger IAEA.  The agency's proposed new powers would
enable it to make more thorough inspections and require "more detailed
reports" from operators of nuclear power plants, especially about the
imports and exports of nuclear- weapons related material.  The
government cites continuing concerns about the nuclear ambitions of
countries like Iraq and North Korea.
<p>

But a "senior German diplomat" said the expanded powers being sought
for the agency would give its inspectors "more legal rights to search
private property than a German police officer has."  And he said
owners of private nuclear plants are opposed to filing more reports
and having more inspectors.
<p>

Makoto Yamanaka, a senior Japanese diplomat, said the burden of
nuclear inspections is already greater on japan than most countries
becuase of its large nuclear industry.  The US representative to the
UN in Vienna conceded that Germany and Japan would face greater
burdens under the proposal.  But he said, "The enormous benefits to
global security from deterring, or at least detecting, a future Saddam
Hussein, overwhelm the modest burdens involved."




<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Nuclear Watchdog Agency Shows Signs of Bite" </b><br>
CHRISTIAN SCIENCE MONITOR, 6/4/96, p. 1</i><br>
Peter Spotts
<p>

The US Nuclear Regulatory Commission "has worked relatively well over
the years," judging by the safety record of the US nuclear power
industry.  But a review of NRC documents, as well as conversations
with inspectors and "industry insiders" suggests the agency "may
indeed have problems," reports the CHRISTIAN SCIENCE MONITOR in a
lengthy, page-one feature with photos and a map of "Nuclear Plants to
Watch."  Critics say there is even "a growing danger of another
serious nuclear accident."
<p>

Among several problems, the MONITOR's investigation identified 
these:
<ul>
  <li> NRC inspectors may be "too willing to take a utility's word"
       that it is addressing problems; 
  <li> "Higher-level" NRC officials "sometimes downgrade the severity
       of safety problems" discovered by inspectors "without giving
       reasons for the change";
  <li> NRC inspectors who press safety issues "have been subjected to
       harassment and intimidation by their supervisors."
</ul>
<p>

"What critics find particularly troubling" is that the demoralized
NRC's problems come as the industry prepares to deal with uncertainty
stemming from deregulation of power markets and aging facilities.
Industry consultant David Lochbaum even compares the situation today
to that of NASA and the space industry at the time of the 1986
Challenger accident.
<p>

"Utility executives acknowledge the challenges ahead," the MONITOR
reports.  "But they dismiss concerns that plants are being pushed
beyond safe limits" and point to statistics that show all of the
industry's safety trends are heading in the right direction.
<p>

The article continues with references to specific performance issues
at Entergy's nuclear plants in the South and the Wolf Creek plant in
Kansas.  The map shows the location of US nuclear plants with four on
the NRC's "Watch List" highlighted: Dresden in Illinois, Browns Ferry
in Alabama, Indian Point in New York and Millstone in Connecticut.



<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Point Beach Nuclear Plant Update"</b><br>
WISCONSIN ELECTRIC PRESS RELEASE, 5/31/96 Contact:</i><br>
Mary carpenter, 414-221-4444
<p>

Wisconsin Electric and a six-member team from the US Nuclear
Regulatory Commission are reviewing the circumstances that led to the
ignition of hydrogen gas during welding on a spent-fuel storage
container at Point Beach nuclear plant on 5/28.
<p>

In a press release last week, the Citizens Utility Board group
characterized the incident as an "explosion" at the Point Beach
nuclear- waste storage facility.  But the utility says the gas burn
"produced enough force to move the shield lid slightly while the lid
was being mechanically welded to the container."  No radiation was
released during the incident, the utility says.
<p>

Wisconsin Electric VP Bob Link said spent-fuel assemblies had been
removed from the container and inspected, and no damage was found,
demonstrating a "high level of safety" built into the containers and
the process for loading them.
<p>

The NRC team, which will be on-site until the end of the week, will 
prepare a findings report, and the utility will not resume loading 
until it can identify the source of the hydrogen and take corrective 
measures.


</td>
</tr>
