<html><head><title>Nuke News, 3/6/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 3/6/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.05.31.html">Previous Nuke News</a>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

... The Nuclear Regulatory Commission held a public meeting on May 31
to discuss the findings of a special inspection team that was sent to
investigate a shutdown last week at Arkansas Nuclear One (ARKANSAS
DEMOCRAT-GAZETTE, 5/31/96, p. D2, Staff Report).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... The Nebraska Public Power District has agreed to pay a $50,000
fine for a violation of fedreral safety regulations at the Cooper
nuclear power plant.  The penalty stems from an improper repair to a
backup system 10 years ago (OMAHA WORLD- HERALD, 5/30/96, p. 15, Toni
Heinzl).


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"N.Y. and New England May Run Short of Power"</b><br>
PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER, 6/1/96, p. D1</i><br>
Sue Fernandez
<p>

A recent study undertaken by the North American Electric Reliability
Council, an industry-financed research group, found that New England
and New York are "in greatest danger of voltage reductions and other
power-supply disruptions" this summer.  But barring sudden storms,
extreme heat or technical breakdowns, the rest of the nation most
likely will not experience those types of disruptions.
<p>

On average, the US is carrying a power reserve equal to 25% of the
average use for June through September.  But New England is down to a
reserve of about 12%, mostly because of the shutdown of the Millstone
nuclear power plant in Connecticut.  The PHILADELPHIA INQUIRER writes
that while Millstone's closing most directly affects New England, it
may have repercussions on the entire Northeast.
<p>

In the Southeast, the Olympic Games being held in Atlanta are expected
to increase regional power demand in July by 600 megawatts, but
Georgia Power Co. officials say they are have prepared to meet the
extra demand.  Georgia Power vice president William Archer: "Georgia
Power's strategy ... will be a combination of buy, borrow and save."
<p>

SEE ALSO: 
<ul>
  <li> "State Hoping to Get Power From Region: Utility Officials
       Seeking to Avoid Blackouts," HARTFORD COURANT, 5/30/96, p.  F1,
       Susan Kinsman, which examines the contingency power plans being
       undertaken by Connecticut utilities in preparation for a
       power-scarce summer.
</ul>


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Closing of Nuclear Plants Opposed Despite Problems"</b><br>
HARTFORD COURANT, 5/30/96, p. A3</i><br>
Mike McIntire and Michael Remez
<p>

"Despite nagging concerns about safety at Connecticut's nuclear power
plants, a majority of state residents surveyed do not want the plants
closed if it means paying higher electric bills," reports the HARTFORD
COURANT.
<p>

The telephone poll of 500 randomly selected adults, conducted May 10
to May 18 by the Institute for Social Inquiry at the U. of
Connecticut, surveyed residents on their attitudes concerning several
issues related to the nuclear industry, including those related to
Northeast Utilities' Millstone Nuclear Power Complex in Waterford,
CT. The survey's authors found that most people's perceptions of
nuclear safety are complicated -- "and sometimes contradictory."
<p>

Forty-nine percent of the survey's participants said they see the
problems at Millstone as mostly technical in nature, while only 25%
thought they were "real safety problems."  Also, 79% of respondents
said they didn't worry very much about the possibility of a major
accident at a nuclear plant.
<p>

On the other hand, 49% of survey participants said they think a
serious nuclear accident is a "real possibility" in the state, and 58%
would be very concerned to live near a nuclear plant -- as opposed to
47% who would fear neighboring a maximum- security prison.
<p>

Northeast Utilities said the findings are consistent with what the
company has discovered in its own polling.  The Courant/Connecticut
poll has a margin of error of plus or minus five percentage points.
<p>

SEE ALSO: 
<ul>
  <li> "Moody's Lowers Ratings on NU Securities," HARTFORD COURANT,
       5/30/96, p. A3, Staff Report, which writes that Moody's
       Investors Service, "as expected, has lowered its ratings on
       $2.3 billion worth of securities issued by Northeast Utilities
       and its subsidiaries," following a similar downgrade on May 28
       by Standard &amp; Poor.
  <li> "NU Effort During Fire Criticized in Cheshire," HARTFORD
       COURANT, 5/30/96, p. A3, Marisa Colon, which notes that the
       Fire Chief in Cheshire, CT has filed a complaint against NU
       charging that the utility's delay in turning off power to a
       house which caught fire on April 10 endangered the lives of
       residents of the house and of the firefighters.
</ul>


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Maine Yankee to Get Review"</b><br>
BANGOR DAILY NEWS, 5/31/96</i><br>
Associated Press
<p>

The Nuclear Regulatory Commission on May 30 announced that an
independent team will take a comprehensive look at operations at Maine
Yankee nuclear power plant in Wiscasset, ME.  The probe will follow up
an earlier review that was described as weak and inadequate.
<p>

The Independent Safety Assessment team will evaluate the licensing and
operational safety performance at the plant, develop a work plan by
June 9 and should submit a report in about 16 weeks.
<p>

A spokeswoman for the utility could not be immediately reached for
comment.


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Panel Kills Proposal to Split Plant Taxes"</b><br>
BATON ROUGE ADVOCATE, 5/30/96, p. 7A</i><br>
Marsha Shuler
<p>

The Louisiana Senate Revenue and Fiscal Affairs Committee on May 29
defeated a proposed constitutional amendment which would have spread
tax revenues from nuclear powerplants among the state's 46 parishes
whose residents get electricity from the Entergy-Louisiana Power and
Light facilities.
<p>

The Senate panel agreed with bill opponents such as St. Charles
parish, who said that it was unfair to take the taxes away from
parishes that agreed to house nuclear plants at a time when the idea
was looked upon unfavorably.
<p>

Jefferson Parish Council President Aaron Broussard, who pushed for the
defeated tax distribution plan said the public will notice the change
when they see their utility bills start to climb in July to make up
for the taxes to be paid to St. Charles.





<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"Off Base"</b><br>
NEWSWEEK, 6/3/96 Issue, p. A3</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

"Even interim solutions to the disposal of nuclear waste are plagued
by political wrangling," NEWSWEEK reports.
<p>

The nuclear-power industry is pushing for legislation in Congress to
allow shipments of nuclear waste across Nevada for temporary storage
at Yucca Mountain.  The Nuclear Waste Policy Act would establish two
interim storage facilities near Yucca Mtn. -- the proposed permanent
storage site -- for spent fuel from civilian and military reactors.
<p>

But an "unlikely" alliance, including the "anti-nuke" lobby, Nevada
and the US Air Force is opposing the act.  Planned waste shipment
routes run through the training range at Nellis Air Force Base, and
USAF officials warn that any interruption in flights over the area
could threaten national security.  Bob Loux of Nevada's nuclear waste
office: "Fighter bombers with live ordnance and nuclear waste spells
conflict in my mind."
<p>

Senate floor action is expected on the Nuclear Waste Policy Act later
this summer.


</td>
</tr>
</table>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
