<html><head><title>Nuke News, 5/6/96</title></head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<h1>Nuke News for 5/6/96</h1>
<h3>distributed by Charles Sayles</h3>
<a href="96.06.04.html">Previous Nuke News</a>

<table width=600>
<tr>
<td>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"DOE Employees in Pro-Nuclear Alliance Tread Narrow Legal Line"</b><br>
ELECTRIC POWER ALERT, 5/8/96, p. 17</i><br>
Staff Report
<p>

"The emergence of an aggressively pro-nuclear coalition of utilities,
trade associations and directors of five Dept. of Energy laboratories
is unleashing grave concern among scientists and environmentalists as
to the legality of government officials lobbying Congress," ELECTRIC
POWER ALERT reports.
<p>

Called the "Eagle Alliance," the coalition is pushing "a bold new
movement to revitalize nuclear science and technology in America."
The group had planned a meeting for May and already has a brochure
with a membership list and a set of objectives.  The participants list
"reads like a Who's Who of the nuclear community," including officials
from the Nuclear Energy Institute, the Tennessee Valley Authority,
Edison Electric Institute and national lab directors from Los Alamos,
Oak Ridge, Brookhaven, Argonne and DOE's Idaho Operations.
<p>

The alliance is backing a "broad range" of objectives to promote
nuclear technologies, including support for more nuclear power plants.
And the group is embracing a "panoply" of tactics such as securing
"pro- nuclear planks in major political parties for the 1996
elections" and making "persuasive contact via senior nuclear personnel
to every incumbent and candidate for 1996 congressional and
gubernatorial offices in the nation."
<p>

Sources with the group Public Citizen and the Nevada Nuclear Waste
Task Force believe the officials overstep legal boundaries by
participating in lobbying activities.  Georgetown University law
professor Paul Rothstein said it is illegal to use the name of the
agency if employees are "putting forth a personal view that has not
been put forth by the agency."
<p>

But a DOE spokesman said upon reviewing the Eagle Alliance brochure,
only one official on the list is actually a DOE employee.


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<i><b>"War Over Waterford"</b><br>
NEW ORLEANS TIMES-PICAYUNE, 6/3/96, p. 6B</i><br>
Editorial
<p>

St. Charles Parish officials won the "first skirmish" in their fight
to "hang on to" property tax revenue from the Waterford 3 nuclear
power plant after a state Senate committee defeated a bill to divide
tax revenue from the plant among the parishes it serves.  But Bill
sponsor Sen. John Hainkel (R) of New Orleans said he has not given up;
and Jefferson Parish, which stood to gain $4.7 million from the law,
has hired a company to help it get the revenue.
<p>

Share-the-wealth proponents argue that Waterford 3 building costs and
St. Charles Parish taxes will be borne by all Entergy customers and so
have named it "taxation without representation."
<p>

The TIMES-PICAYUNE found more compelling the argument of St.  Charles
officials who countered that no other parishes were willing to accept
the risk of having a nuclear power plant within their
boundaries. St. Charles has had to contend with wastes from the plant
and demands on parish services, such as an 800- student surge in its
public schools.

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


... The US NRC has proposed a $100,000 fine against a unit of CT-based
Northeast Utilities over the layoff of a technician after he raised
safety concerns.  The technician, Adam McNiece, worked for a
contractor, Bartlett Nuclear of Plymouth, MA.  Citing his privacy, the
NRC declined to discuss the outcome of a probe into the safety issues
he raised (WALL STREET JOURNAL, 6/5/96, p. B8, Staff Report).

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

... The US NRC cited a unit of Atlanta-based The Southern Co. for
unfair retaliation in the firing of two managers who raised safety
concerns at the Vogtle nuclear power plant in Georgia.  Georgia Power
called the action "disappointing" and said it would continue several
legal challenges.  The NRC did not fine Georgia Power, saying the
five- year statute of limitations had expired (WALL STREET JOURNAL,
6/5/96, p. C2, Staff Report).
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

...  "Weighed down" by nuclear power investments, Illinois Power Co.'s
debt load comes to 85% of stock value, according to Moody's Investors
Service, which still put $1.8 billion in IP securities under review
for a possible ratings upgrade.  The Decatur-based utility, a unit of
Illinova Corp., has cut costs in recent months, but production costs
remain above average in the region (CHICAGO TRIBUNE, 5/31/96, p. 3,
Staff Report).


</td>
</tr>
