<html> <head>
<title>Nuclear News: October 1996</title>
</head>

<body background=/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif>
<center>
<table width=600>
<tr>
<td colspan=2 align=center>
    <h1><img src="graphics/nn.logo.gif" alt="Nuclear News"></h1>
  </td>
</tr><tr>
<td align=center><h4>October 1996</h4></td><td align=center><h4>Volume 39, No. 11</h4></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=2>

<center><i><a href="back.issues.html">(On-line information about
issues after April 1996 is available)</a></i></center>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<img src="graphics/oct.96.jpg" alt="Nuclear News
cover, October 96" align="right" width=295>

<center><h3>SPECIAL SECTION</h3></center>
<i><b>Plant Maintenance</b></i>, p. 25

<dl>
<dt> <b>The first outage at Sizewell B</b>
<dd> <i>by Simon Rippon</i>, p. 26
</dl>

<dl>
<dt> <b>Best practices in maintenance</b>
<dd> <i>by Rick Michal</i>, p. 29
</dl>

<dl>
<dt> <b>Gannon: Maintenance at Brunswick</b>
<dd> <i>Interview by Rick Michal</i>, p. 32
</dl>

<dl>
<dt> <b>A reactor core barrel lift at Byron</b>
<dd> <i>by Rick Michal</i>, p. 34
</dl>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=300 height=3>
<p>

<center><h3>POWER</h3></center>

Brunswick survives hurricane in good shape. Diaz, McGaffigan are new NRC 
commissioners. Point Beach performance issues draw reviews from WEPCO and NRC. 
Missing wire extends Maine Yankee modification outage. PSE&amp;G hopes retraining 
will cure Salem maintenance ills. AIT reviews multiple incidents at Haddam 
Neck. Five NRC fines proposed. <b>page 17</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=600 height=3>
<p>

<center><h3>INTERNATIONAL</h3></center>

Chooz-B1 supplies first electricity to French, Belgian grids. EBRD and EU to 
assess Chernobyl closure plan. Consultant study boosts Indonesia nuclear plant. 
Record outage at Cofrentes. Privatization prospectus for AEA Technology issued. 
Iranian government sues Siemens over Bushehr plant. <b>page 36</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=600 height=3>
<p>

<center><h3>WASTE MANAGEMENT</h3></center>

NAS committee supports phased cleanup of Hanford tank waste. GAO report on WIPP 
indicates possible late facility opening. NRC and GA ask ASLB to sign 
settlement agreement. German court decides Gorleben store is legal. Taipower 
looking for storage site for plant LLW. Business developments. <b>page 38</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=600 height=3>
<p>

<center><h3>INDUSTRY</h3></center>

Acquisitions, agreements, new firms and facilities. News about contracts. 
Companies meet ISO 9001 quality control standard. <b>page 43</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=600 height=3>
<p>

<center><h3>FUEL</h3></center>

Uranium fuel plant fire probably ignited by acid/base mixture. NFS cited for 
violations that led to duct fire. NRC and OSHA coordinate GDP worker 
protection. NRC extends licenses for trouble-free mills. <b>page 47</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=600 height=3>
<p>

<center><h3>STANDARDS</h3></center>

New ANS standards available for purchase. <b>page 53</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=600 height=3>
<p>

<center><h3>ANS NEWS</h3></center>

Activities of the ANS Public Information Committee. Three "Wise" students. New 
members. ANS organization listings. <b>page 62</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=600 height=3>
<p>

