<center><h3>FEATURE ARTICLES</h3></center>

<dl>
<dt> <b>Improved tech specs: An industry/NRC effort</b>
<dd> <i>by Rick Michal</i>, p. 23
</dl>

<dl>
<dt> <b>Talking to the old-timers pays off</b>
<dd> <i>by Mike Owen and Jim McNeil</i>, p. 30
</dl>

<dl>
<dt> <b>Carle: An international nuclear leader</b>
<dd> <i>interview by Simon Rippon</i>, p. 36
</dl>

<center><h3>LIST OF SCHEDULED OUTAGES AT U.S. NUCLEAR POWER PLANTS, p. 25</h3></center>

<center><h3>INDEX TO 1996 <i>NUCLEAR NEWS</i> CONTENTS, p. 14</h3></center>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=300 height=3>
<p>

<center><h3>POWER</h3></center>

Connecticut Yankee votes for premature shutdown. Advanced reactors set
to meet base load expansion. Moody's says nuclear plants face tough
competitive road. Study finds oversupply of new engineers
vs. jobs. The NRC gets a new EDO management group. Generic Letter
clarifies steam generator shipping. <b>page 19</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>OPERATIONS</h3></center>

Improved tech specs: An industry/NRC effort. (See also Meeting Notice
on p. 67 for the Seventh Topical Meeting on Robotics and Remote
Systems, April 27-May 1, 1997, in Augusta, Ga.) <b>page 23</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>INTERNATIONAL</h3></center>

Chinese Candu contract signed for Qinshan site. Chernobyl-1 shut down;
Unit 2 may restart in 1997. Superphenix produces power at 90
percent. South Korean parliament revises Atomic Energy Law. Russia
sets agreement to help with Bulgarian VVER-440s. Level 2 incidents at
nuclear plants in the Netherlands and Sweden. <b>page 33</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>MEETINGS</h3></center>

Report on the 1996 ANS/ENS International Meeting. <b>page 40</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>WASTE MANAGEMENT</h3></center>

DOE sets policy, selects Oak Ridge as lead site. NRC amends HLW
repository regulations. <b>page 45</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>INDUSTRY</h3></center>

Westinghouse to separate industrial, broadcasting units. New ventures,
recent acquisitions. ASNT introduces new NDT examination/certification
program. Contracts go to FTI, Holtec, Biach, R.O.V. <b>page 46</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>ISOTOPES AND RADIATION</h3></center>

DOE announces plans to produce Mo-99 at Sandia. Committee to write
guide to reliable radionuclide sampling. <b>page 48</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>ANS NEWS</h3></center>

Board considers new approaches, approves budget. New group to focus on
accelerator technology. ANS executive director resigns. Awards
presented at Washington meeting. President's column. Tsoulfanidis to
succeed Vogelsang as <i>NT</i> editor. Science workshop is a
success. Local section meeting planned. Midwest student
conference. Young physicist is an ANS grandson. New members. <b>page
61</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

