<html> <head>
<title>Nuclear News: February 1997</title>
</head>

<body background=/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif>
<center>
<table width=600>
<tr>
<td colspan=2 align=center>
    <h1><img src="graphics/nn.logo.gif" alt="Nuclear News"></h1>
  </td>
</tr><tr>
<td align=center><h4>February 1997</h4></td><td align=center><h4>Volume 40, Number 2</h4></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=2>

<center><i><a href="back.issues.html">(On-line information about
issues after April 1996 is available)</a></i></center>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<img src="graphics/feb.97.jpg" alt="Nuclear News
cover, February 97" align="right" width=295>

<center><h3>SPECIAL SECTION: COMPUTER APPLICATIONS</h3></center>

<dl>
<dt> <b>EdF: Using CAD for design and more</b>
<dd> <i>by Simon Rippon</i>, p. 26
</dl>

<dl>
<dt> <b>Computerizing procedures and work orders</b>
<dd> <i>by Terry Dexter</i>, p. 33
</dl>

<dl>
<dt> <b>Software use in a regulated industry</b>
<dd> <i>by Morgan D. Libby</i>, p. 36
</dl>

<dl>
<dt> <b>Hartzog: Information systems at Turkey Point</b>
<dd> <i>interview by Rick Michal</i>, p. 39
</dl>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=300 height=3>
<p>

<center><h3>POWER</h3></center>

Entergy, Maine Yankee sign management services pact.  Maine
Yankee to remain shut down until NRC gives restart OK.  President
Clinton names Federico Pena Secretary of Energy.  NRC to oversee
safety at DOE nuclear sites.  Consumers Power changes name to
Consumers Energy.  Inspectors criticize ComEd's LaSalle, Dresden
plants.  Pantex plant, others, candidates for MOX fuel
fabrication.  Annealing demonstration suspended, funds cut from
federal budget.  First steam generator shipped to Salem-1 under
new DOT category.  Toluene spill at Indian Point-2 prompts
unusual event and evacuation. <b>page 19</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>BOOK REVIEW</h3></center>

<dl>
<dt> <b><i>Power Deficit,</i> by Frank L. Kelly</b>
<dd> <i>review by Brian K. Hajek</i>, p. 24
</dl>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>INTERNATIONAL</h3></center>

Spanish electric utility industry, government sign market
liberalization protocol.  U.K.'s Hunterston B, Hinkley Point B
each okayed for 10 more years of operation.  BNFL plans cleanup
and refurbishment at Sellafield.  Turkish utility invites bids
for nuclear power plant.  China willing to add second nuclear
unit at Pakistan's Chasnupp site.  Belarus interested in a first
nuclear power station.  Government of Philippines looking for
prospective new sites for nuclear power plants.  Big bang
experiment to proceed upon completion of CERN's Large Hadron
Collider.  Restart of Ukraine's Chernobyl-2 proposed for late
1997.  More protocols signed for North Korean PWR project. 
VVER-440/213 replica in Hungary ready for maintenance training. 
World Council of Nuclear Workers plans second marathon. <b>page
41</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>WASTE MANAGEMENT</h3></center>

DOE notifies utilities of delay in acceptance of commercial spent
nuclear fuel.  Dreyful resigns as head of OCRWM.  Last of Finnish
spent fuel sent to Russia.  Costs of policing waste shipments
drive Germany's Lower Saxony government to court. LANL scientists
say that probability of giant explosion at underground repository
does not exist.  Taipower selects five candidate LLW sites. 
Germany's ERAM marks 25 years of operation. <b>page 45</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>INDUSTRY</h3></center>

BW/IP acquires Anchor/Darling; other business developments.  GSE,
ABB CENO, GAI-Tronics, others sign contracts. <b>page 48</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>APPLICATIONS</h3></center>

Duke Power shares plant information through software program.
<b>page 50</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>ANS NEWS</h3></center>

What has ANS done for you?  President's Column.  Hajek named
interim ANS Executive Director.  New Accelerator Applications
Technical Group moves ahead.  Landis receives Henry DeWolf Smyth
Award at Washington meeting.  Hollensteiner retires from ANS
headquarters.  New ANS members.  Washington race report. <b>page
68</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>DEPARTMENTS</h3></center>

<table width=60%>
<tr>
<td>Advertising Index/FAXLink</td><td align=right>56</td>
