<title>Nuclear News: April 1996</title>
</head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<table width=600>
<tr>
  <td colspan=2 align=center>
    <h1><img src="graphics/nn.logo.gif" alt="Nuclear News"></h1>
  </td>
</tr><tr>
<td align=center><h4>April 1996</h4></td><td align=center><h4>Volume 39/NO. 5</h4></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=2>
<center><i><a href="back.issues.html">(On-line information about
issues after April 1996 is available)</a></i></center>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<img src="graphics/apr.96.jpg" alt="Nuclear News
cover, April 96" align="right" width=295>
<center><h3>FEATURE ARTICLES</h3></center>
<dl>
  <dt> <b>Reactor engineering: Supporting plant operations</b>
  <dd> <i>by Rick Michal</i>, pg 22
       <p>
  <dt> <b>Chernobyl today: A tour of the site</b>
  <dd> <i>by Simon Rippon</i>, pg 30
       <p>
  <dt> <b>Princeton lab deputy director reflects on the fate of the
       fusion program</b>
  <dd> <i>article and interview by Allen Zeyher</i>, pg 51
</dl>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=300 height=3>
<p>

<center><h3>POWER</h3></center>
SG analysis delays Salem-1 restart indefinitely. Hydropower stops
WNP-2 run short of plant record. HPS: Low-dose effects may be
nonexistent. Focus on Finance.  NRC, others examine sticking control
rods. ACRS says NRC and industry should move faster on ECCS
strainers. Watts Bar-1 startup works through a few routine
problems. Mecatiss passes UL tests; FPC awaits NRC approval., <b>pg
17</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=300 height=3>
<p>

<center><h3>OPERATIONS</h3></center>

Support of plant operations by reactor engineering at Davis-
Besse. Reactor engineering at Three Mile Island-1. (See also Calls for
Papers on p. 74 for the 2nd International Topical Meeting on Advanced
Reactor Safety, ARS '97, June 1-4, 1997, in Orlando, Fla., and on
p. 75 for the ANS Seventh Topical Meeting on Robotics and Remote
Systems, April 27-May 1, 1997, in Augusta, Ga. <b>pg 22</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>INTERNATIONAL</h3></center>

U.K. parliamentary committee says privatization okay. Lord Marshall of
Goring dies. Record generation statistics in France and Japan. Minor
hitch in ABWR commissioning. New Australian government to change
uranium policy. French-South African laser enrichment agreement
signed. Belarus Nuclear Society founded. A tour of the Chernobyl
site. Photo feature on Chernobyl today. NEA report about Chernobyl ten
years on.<b>pg 27</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>WASTE MANAGEMENT</h3></center>

DOE issues RFP for Hanford tank waste solidification. Court orders
document search at Hanford. Downsizing proposed for production
facilities. OU study on impacts of Barnwell site closure. La Manche
repository closure cleared in court. National labs involved in waste
handling innovations. Business developments. <b>pg 40</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>MEETINGS</h3></center>
Report on Waste Management '96 in Tucson, Ariz.<b>pg 46</b>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>RESEARCH</h3></center>

