  </td>
</tr><tr>
<td align=center><h4>May 1996</h4></td><td align=center><h4>Volume 39/NO. 6</h4></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=2>
<center><i><a href="back.issues.html">(On-line information about
issues after April 1996 is available)</a></i></center>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<img src="graphics/apr.96.jpg" alt="Nuclear News
cover, April 96" align="right" width=295>
<center><h3>SPECIAL SECTION: COMPETITIVE NUCLEAR POWER (p. 31)</h3></center>
<dl>
  <dt> <b>FERC and deregulation of electric energy sales</b>
  <dd> <i>by Elizabeth A. Moler</i>, p. 32
       <p>
  <dt> <b>California's move from integrated monopolies to competitive
       generation: Smooth transition, not shock therapy</b>
  <dd> <i>by Daniel W. Fessler</i>, p. 36
       <p>
  <dt> <b>Retail competition: An absence of proof</b>
  <dd> <i>by Joseph F. Paquette</i>, Jr., p. 40
</dl>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=300 height=3>
<p>

<center><h3>FEATURE ARTICLE</h3></center>
<dl>
  <dt> <b>U.S. capacity factors: Crowding the ceiling</b>
  <dd> <i>by E. Michael Blake</i>, p. 24
</dl>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=300 height=3>
<p>

<center><h3>POWER</h3></center>

Fort St. Vrain decom project involves new tools, communication.  Stuck
fuel assembly freed at Palo Verde-2. Salem restart moved up; Hope
Creek back in service. IP-3 restart under way. Annealing demonstration
at Marble Hill. YAEC wins double victory for decommissioning
effort. Industry organizations appoint new managers. WPPSS to sell
WNP-1 and -3 assets., <b>pg 16</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


<center><h3>OPERATIONS</h3></center>

Performance indicators show nuclear industry continues
improvement. DOE's Argonne opens new R&amp;D center for reactor
safety. U.S. capacity factors improve. (See also Call for Papers on
p. 67 for the Sixth ANS Topical Meeting on Emergency Preparedness and
Response, April 22-25, 1997, in San Francisco, Calif.), <b>pg 20</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>INTERNATIONAL</h3></center>

Infection found likely cause of U.K. leukemia cases. U.K. nuclear power
plants are ready for privatization. One Guangdong outage helps to end
another. India's third reprocessing plant opened at Kalpakkam. Antinuclear
groups planned actions over Easter in Germany. International Comment.
Technical opinion issued on Chernobyl source term. Zaporozhye-6 increases
power to 90 percent. IPSN and GRS report Eastern Europe progress and
concerns., <b>pg 42</b>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>INDUSTRY</h3></center>

Westinghouse to close Pensacola assembly plant. Companies form alliances;
new facilities; acquisitions. News about contracts.-- page 46
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>WASTE MANAGEMENT</h3></center>

EPA issues criteria for standards compliance for WIPP. Hanford management
contract RFP elicits three proposals. Texas LLW disposal site gets
environmental, safety okay. Reprocessing waste to be vitrified at Germany's
Karlsruhe. Lower Saxony loses Gorleben cases., <b>pg 49</b>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>ISOTOPES AND RADIATION</h3></center>

Mn-53 decay pinpoints thaw in early solar system. German scientists create
a new heavyweight atom. New radiation regulations have improved protection
of human research subjects., <b>pg 51</b>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>ANS NEWS</h3></center>

ANS launches Web site; Internet uses grow. An appeal to Congress.
President's column: ANS representation in France. Study: The next 50 years
of nuclear energy. ANS backs naming element 106 seaborgium. Idaho exhibit
shows the atom. Bob Lacy scholarship fund. New ANS members., <b>pg 62</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>


