<title>Nuclear News: July 1996</title>
</head>

<body background="/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif">
<center>
<table width=600>
<tr>
  <td colspan=2 align=center>
    <h1><img src="graphics/nn.logo.gif" alt="Nuclear News"></h1>
  </td>
</tr><tr>
<td align=center><h4>July 1996</h4></td><td align=center><h4>Volume 39, No. 8</h4></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=2>
<center><i><a href="back.issues.html">(On-line information about
issues after April 1996 is available)</a></i></center>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<img src="graphics/jul.96.jpg" alt="Nuclear News
cover, July 96" align="right" width=295>
<center><h3>FEATURE ARTICLES</h3></center>
<dl>
  <dt> <b>A Miller's Tale: Profile of new ANS President Don Miller</b>
  <dd> <i>by Rick Michal</i>, p. 3

  <dt> <b>The sodium leak at Monju in perspective</b>
  <dd> <i>by John Lambert</i>, p. 38
</dl>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=300 height=3>
<p>
<center><h3>LIST OF SCHEDULED OUTAGES AT U.S. NUCLEAR POWER
PLANTS <i>(p.&nbsp;27)</i> </h3></center>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=300 height=3>
<p>
<center><h3>POWER</h3></center>

NRC requests modifications for ECCS strainers. Reactor trip and steam
generator boil-off draws inspection team to ANO-1. Dresden improves as
ComEd aims for sustained performance at the nuclear plant. Millstone
not alone in full-core offload problem. Independent Safety Assessment
team to review safety performance at Maine Yankee; law firm finds no
misconduct. Decom funding plan at TVA to add $123 million this
year. Watts Bar-1 begins commercial operation. Cause of cooling tower
fire at Browns Ferry is unknown. Grumbly named undersecretary, Alm in
charge of EM, at DOE; NRC changes managers, <b>page
19</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<center><h3>OPERATIONS</h3></center>

NPIC&amp;HMIT'96: A report on the American Nuclear Society International
Topical Meeting on Nuclear Plant Instrumentation, Control, and
Human-Interface Technologies, <b>page 24</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<center><h3>INTERNATIONAL</h3></center>

Taipower chooses GE ABWR for fourth plant. Overview of German nuclear
industry released. The SBWR concept lives on in Germany. Loan
agreements signed for Mochovce completion. Construction begun at
Qinshan-2 and -3 in June. British Energy shares up for sale to the
public. Nuclear privatization progresses in Argentina. IGSCC found in
pipework welds at Barseback-1. No money for new fuel at
Chernobyl-1. Kozloduy-1 outage moved up for metallurgical
testing. Radiation Council urges adoption of ICRP-60. International
Comment. International peer review set for WIPP site, <b>page 36</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<center><h3>WASTE MANAGEMENT</h3></center>

Point Beach: NRC looks into cask welding incident. Spent fuel
treatment demonstration to proceed at ANL-W. NWTRB's 1995 summary
report notes Yucca Mountain progress. Proposed NRC rule on LLW
jurisdiction withdrawn. Yankee proceeds with onsite storage design;
other business developments, <b>page 41</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<center><h3>INDUSTRY</h3></center>

Eagle Alliance sets course, elects officers, opens office. VECTRA,
DE&S deal final; other acquisitions. Firms get work in Europe, Taiwan,
China; other pacts. Companies meet ISO 9002 quality control
standard, <b>page 44</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<center><h3>FUEL</h3></center>

USEC okayed to increase Paducah enrichment level. ASLB vindicates LES
on CEC safety issues, <b>page 47</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<center><h3>ISOTOPES AND RADIATION</h3></center>

National Atomic Museum looks to preserve nuclear history, <b>page 52</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<center><h3>STANDARDS</h3></center>

Newly published standards available from ANS, <b>page 55</b>


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<center><h3>ANS NEWS</h3></center>

The PEP honor roll. President's column. ANS elects 11 new
Fellows. Michigan Section recognizes nuclear professional. Penn State
Student Branch hosts speakers. 1996 ANS scholarship recipients. New
ANS members, <b>page 59</b>


<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<center><h3>DEPARTMENTS</h3>

