<title>Nuclear News: August 1996</title>
</head>

<body background=/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif>
<center>
<table width=600>
<tr>
<td colspan=2 align=center>
    <h1><img src="graphics/nn.logo.gif" alt="Nuclear News"></h1>
  </td>
</tr><tr>
<td align=center><h4>August 1996</h4></td><td align=center><h4>Volume 39, No. 9</h4></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=2>

<center><i><a href="back.issues.html">(On-line information about
issues after April 1996 is available)</a></i></center>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<img src="graphics/aug.96.jpg" alt="Nuclear News
cover, August 96" align="right" width=295>
<center><h3>FEATURE ARTICLES</h3></center>
<dl>
  <dt> <b>Disposition of weapons-grade plutonium in commercial light-water reactors</b>
  <dd> <i>by William F. Naughton</i>, p. 24
</dl>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=300 height=3>
<p>
<center><h3>SPECIAL SECTION</h3></center>
<i><b>Second Annual Nuclear News Vendor/Contractor Profile Section</b></i>, p. 27

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=300 height=3>
<p>

<center><h3>POWER</h3></center>

Browns Ferry removed from NRC watch list; Millstone status
changed. Nuclear stations operate through Western outage. Sealant in
intake tunnel forces LaSalle shutdown. Turbine vibrations force
Fermi-2 power reduction. Brief Cooper shutdown allows removal of
leaking fuel. NRC answers OIG report on handling Maine Yankee. <b>page
19</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=300 height=3>
<p>

<center><h3>OPERATIONS</h3></center>

Disposition of weapons-grade plutonium in commercial light-water
reactors.  <b>page 24</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>INTERNATIONAL</h3></center>

EU agrees on directive to open electricity market. Uranium Red Book
cites increased consumption and cost. Russian regulatory authority
gives go-ahead for VVER-640. U.K.'s Sizewell B has a good first
year. Calder Hall and Chapelcross plants keep on going. Expert
commission endorses France's Superphenix demo program. Russia ships
new fuel to Chernobyl. Japan Atomic Power Company to close
Tokai-1. China announces plans for experimental fast reactor. Backfit
to allow 40-year operation of Germany's Obrigheim. Biblis A scheduled
for August restart. Meeting on cutting the cost of nuclear power
generation.  <b>page 70</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>MEETINGS</h3></center>

1996 ANS Annual Meeting: The sustainability of nuclear power. Embedded
topical: New directions in fusion research.  <b>page 75</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>INDUSTRY</h3></center>

Agreements, restructuring, new facilities, acquisitions. BGE gets
contract extension; new pacts.  <b>page 80</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>WASTE MANAGEMENT</h3></center>

AIT issues Point Beach report; NRC asks for information. M4
commissions second waste facility; waste management-related
contracts. The 1996 WERC Environmental Design Contest.  <b>page 82</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>ANS NEWS</h3></center>

Miller, Goldberg, Wright: 1996-97 officers. Awards presented at Reno
meeting. President's column. A tribute to Raymond D. Maxson,
1898-1996. New members.  <b>page 97</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>
<center><h3>DEPARTMENTS</h3>

