<html> <head>
<title>Nuclear News: September 1996</title>
</head>

<body background=/graphics/gifs/logo.bkgrnd.gif>
<center>
<table width=600>
<tr>
<td colspan=2 align=center>
    <h1><img src="graphics/nn.logo.gif" alt="Nuclear News"></h1>
  </td>
</tr><tr>
<td align=center><h4>September 1996</h4></td><td align=center><h4>Volume 39, No. 10</h4></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=2>

<center><i><a href="back.issues.html">(On-line information about
issues after April 1996 is available)</a></i></center>
<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<img src="graphics/sep.96.jpg" alt="Nuclear News
cover, September 96" align="right" width=295>
<center><h3>FEATURE ARTICLES</h3></center>
<dl>
<dt> <b>Innovators of the nuclear industry: Four stories</b>
<dd> <i>by Rick Michal</i>, p. 20
</dl>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=300 height=3>
<p>

<center><h3>POWER</h3></center>

Entergy to manage NYPA plants. Marble Hill annealing demo shows stresses within limits. NRC to require third-party review before Millstone restart. Inspectors find flaws in several plant processes at Connecticut Yankee. Niagara Mohawk buyout would reduce high-priced liability. AIT faults ComEd control for strainer fouling at LaSalle. Susquehanna back on line after false turbine vibration signal. <b>page 19</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif" width=300 height=3>
<p>

<center><h3>OPERATIONS</h3></center>

Four nuclear utilities singled out for innovative contributions toward improving efficiency and productivity: computer-based PRA at San Onofre, reducing refueling outage duration at PECO, the URSULA reactor vessel examination system, and document management at V.C. Summer. (See also Call for Papers, insert opposite p. 60, for the ANS 1997 Annual Meeting, June 1-5, 1997, in Orlando, Fla.) <b>page 20</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>INTERNATIONAL</h3></center>

Safety convention to be in force by October. IAEA reports safeguards implementation in 1995. WHO protocol outlines second-phase Chernobyl projects. International Comment. Japanese town votes "no" to new nuclear plant. Nonpayment for electricity elicits Russian plant, worker protests. Seismic restraints tightened at EdF's nuclear plants. Successful fuel melt experiment done at Phebus. Radiation incident and fatal accident on same day at Almaraz. Industrial source radiation incident occurs in Iran. German Social Democrats offer new consensus talks. Two mishaps on same day at Ukraine's Khmel'nitskiy. <b>page 29</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>RESEARCH</h3></center>

New UC San Diego lab studies plasma boundary. <b>page 33</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>WASTE MANAGEMENT</h3></center>

Senate passes S. 1936; White House promises veto. DOE awards contracts worth $11 billion. NAC/Voest-Alpine sign cask pact; contract news. Special commission sets French repository closure plans. Empty cask completes test run to Gorleben. <b>page 34</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>APPLICATIONS</h3></center>

Maine Yankee rehabilitates service water pipeline. <b>page 37</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>EDUCATION</h3></center>

Nuclear workforce, school enrollment decline. <b>page 38</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>INDUSTRY</h3></center>

Acquisitions, restructures, new facilities, relocations. News about contracts. <b>page 39</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>ANS NEWS</h3></center>

Board discusses finances, new ventures, other issues in Reno. President's column. Nuclear engineering educators tour French facilities. Reno run. New members. <b>page 56</b>

<p>
<img src="/graphics/gifs/stripe.gif">
<p>

<center><h3>DEPARTMENTS</h3>

